const VAULT = {"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots": {"key": "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots", "category": "Eras", "name": "Pre-2005 Roots", "tags": ["era", "roots"], "links": ["Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy", "Concepts/Retroclones", "People/Ron Edwards", "Games/Burning Wheel", "People/Luke Crane", "Games/Dogs in the Vineyard", "People/Vincent Baker", "Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory", "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing", "People/Matt Finch", "People/Ron Edwards", "People/Vincent Baker", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "crossover", "summary": "The foundations of everything that follows. Two threads run in parallel through this period: the classic D&D tradition (Gygax, Arneson, and the editions that followed) and the indie design conversation coalescing around The Forge. The OGL, published in 2000, is the legal hinge on which the entire post-2005 landscape turns.", "html": "<h1>Pre-2005 — Roots & Catalysts</h1>\n<p>#era #roots</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>The foundations of everything that follows. Two threads run in parallel through this period: the <strong>classic D&D tradition</strong> (Gygax, Arneson, and the editions that followed) and the <strong>indie design conversation</strong> coalescing around The Forge. The OGL, published in 2000, is the legal hinge on which the entire post-2005 landscape turns.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Classic D&D Tradition</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>1974</strong> — Original D&D published by Gygax & Arneson (TSR). Three \"little brown books.\"</li>\n<li><strong>1977</strong> — Basic D&D (Holmes edition); AD&D begins publication</li>\n<li><strong>1981</strong> — B/X D&D (Moldvay/Cook) — the edition many OSR designers consider the sweet spot</li>\n<li><strong>1983</strong> — BECMI D&D (Mentzer) — Rules Cyclopedia follows in 1991</li>\n<li><strong>1989</strong> — AD&D 2nd Edition</li>\n<li><strong>2000</strong> — D&D 3rd Edition (WotC, after acquiring TSR in 1997); OGL published</li>\n<li><strong>2003</strong> — D&D 3.5 revision</li>\n</ul>\nThe B/X and AD&D 1e editions are the primary targets of the retroclone movement. Understanding <em>why</em> these editions felt different is the entry point into OSR philosophy.\n<p>See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy\">OSR Play Philosophy</a>, <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Retroclones\">Retroclones</a></p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Forge & Indie Theory</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>~2000–2001</strong> — The Forge forum founded by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Ron Edwards\">Ron Edwards</a></li>\n<li><strong>2001</strong> — <em>Sorcerer</em> published; GNS theory developed</li>\n<li><strong>2002</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Burning Wheel\">Burning Wheel</a> published by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Luke Crane\">Luke Crane</a></li>\n<li><strong>2004</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dogs in the Vineyard\">Dogs in the Vineyard</a> by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a></li>\n</ul>\nThe Forge was an online forum that became the intellectual center of indie TTRPG design. Its GNS theory — Gamist, Narrativist, Simulationist — was a contested but enormously influential attempt to categorize modes of play and design failure.\n<p>See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory\">The Forge & GNS Theory</a></p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Critical Hinge: The OGL (2000)</h2>\n<p>When WotC published D&D 3e, they released core mechanics under the <strong>Open Game License</strong> — a legal instrument allowing third parties to publish compatible material. The OGL covered mechanics (uncopyrightable) but not expression (text, art, product identity).</p>\n<p>A small number of legally-minded hobbyists realized this created the opening for retroclones: write new text expressing old mechanics, release under OGL, achieve functional compatibility with beloved older editions.</p>\n<p>See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">The OGL & Open Licensing</a></p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What to Read / Play from This Period</h2>\n<ul><li><em>A Quick Primer for Old School Gaming</em> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a> (free; articulates what changed)</li>\n<li><em>Sorcerer</em> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Ron Edwards\">Ron Edwards</a> (Forge-era design at its most focused)</li>\n<li><em>Dogs in the Vineyard</em> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a> (pre-PbtA story games high watermark)</li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>Next Era</h2>"}, "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity": {"key": "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity", "category": "Eras", "name": "2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity", "tags": ["era"], "links": ["Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence", "Games/Troika", "Games/Mothership", "Games/Mork Borg", "Games/Old-School Essentials", "People/Gavin Norman", "Games/Blades in the Dark", "People/John Harper", "Games/Spire The City Must Fall", "People/Grant Howitt", "People/Christopher Taylor", "Games/Dream Askew", "People/Avery Alder", "Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard", "People/Grant Howitt", "People/Matthew Mercer", "People/Matt Colville", "Games/Hyperborea", "Games/Dolmenwood", "Games/Spire The City Must Fall"], "lineage": "crossover", "summary": "The richest period of cross-pollination. All three lineages are producing strong work simultaneously. Blades in the Dark creates the FitD family. The OSR's second wave produces distinctly aesthetic, art-forward games. The UK indie scene emerges with its own voice. The actual play boom peaks. This is the era your games come from.", "html": "<h1>2017–2020 — Synthesis & Maturity</h1>\n<p>#era</p>\n<p>← <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>The richest period of cross-pollination. All three lineages are producing strong work simultaneously. Blades in the Dark creates the FitD family. The OSR's second wave produces distinctly aesthetic, art-forward games. The UK indie scene emerges with its own voice. The actual play boom peaks. This is the era your games come from.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>OSR Thread</h2>\n<h3>The Second Wave</h3>\n<ul><li><strong>2017</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Troika\">Troika!</a> — weird science fantasy with varied character backgrounds</li>\n<li><strong>2017</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mothership\">Mothership</a> — sci-fi horror in zine format; high production value</li>\n<li><strong>2019</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mork Borg\">Mörk Borg</a> — death metal aesthetic; art-forward design</li>\n</ul>  - Wins ENnie Gold for Best Game and Product of the Year\n<ul><li><strong>2019</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Old-School Essentials\">Old-School Essentials</a> by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Gavin Norman\">Gavin Norman</a></li>\n</ul>  - B/X reformatted for clarity; becomes dominant neo-trad platform\n  - Separates rules from setting; modular design\n<h3>OSR Character in This Period</h3>\n<ul><li>Aesthetic ambition increases dramatically</li>\n<li>Clear split between \"OSR proper\" (strict retroclone sensibility) and \"post-OSR\" (OSR-informed but experimental)</li>\n<li>itch.io becomes major distribution platform</li>\n<li>Zine Fest culture influences production format</li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>Story Games Thread</h2>\n<h3>Forged in the Dark</h3>\n<ul><li><strong>2017</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Blades in the Dark\">Blades in the Dark</a> by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a></li>\n</ul>  - Introduces: position and effect, flashbacks as resource, clocks as pacing tool\n  - Crew-level meta-game; between-score downtime\n  - FitD license enables family of games\n<ul><li><strong>2018</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\">Spire: The City Must Fall</a> by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a> & <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Christopher Taylor\">Christopher Taylor</a></li>\n</ul>  - FitD-adjacent; explicitly political; dark elf revolutionaries ⭐ <em>you've played this</em>\n<ul><li><strong>2018</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dream Askew\">Dream Askew</a> by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a></li>\n</ul>  - GM-less PbtA; innovative resource system\n<h3>UK Indie Scene Emerges</h3>\n<ul><li>Rowan, Rook and Decard (<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard\">RR&D</a>) establish distinctive voice</li>\n<li>British design sensibility: literary, political, high-concept</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a>'s one-page games (especially Honey Heist) circulate widely</li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>Mainstream Thread</h2>\n<h3>Actual Play Peak</h3>\n<ul><li>Critical Role moves to its own channel (2019); becomes media company</li>\n<li>Acquisitions: Critical Role Kickstarter raises $11M in 24 hours (2019 animated series)</li>\n<li>Actual play becomes primary vector for new player acquisition</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matthew Mercer\">Matthew Mercer</a> defines public expectations of GM performance</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>DMs Guild & Third-Party Boom</h3>\n<ul><li>DMs Guild enables D&D-adjacent publishing</li>\n<li>Large wave of 5e third-party products (Kobold Press, MCDM, others)</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Colville\">Matt Colville</a>'s <em>Running the Game</em> YouTube series reaches hundreds of thousands</li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>Your Games in Context</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Year</td><td>Where It Sits</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Hyperborea\\</td><td>Hyperborea\">td><td>Hyperborea</a></td><td>2012 (3e 2022)</td><td>OSR first wave; Sword & Sorcery</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dolmenwood\\</td><td>Dolmenwood\">td><td>Dolmenwood</a></td><td>2024 (developed here)</td><td>Neo-trad; OSE platform</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\\</td><td>Spire\">td><td>Spire</a></td><td>2018</td><td>FitD-adjacent; UK indie</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\\</td><td>Brindlewood Bay\">td><td>Brindlewood Bay</a></td><td>2020</td><td>PbtA mystery; next era</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>All four sit at or near the synthesis moment when OSR craft, story games design theory, and indie aesthetic ambition were in direct conversation.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What to Read / Play from This Period</h2>\n<ul><li><em>Blades in the Dark</em> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a> (essential FitD text)</li>\n<li><em>Old-School Essentials</em> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Gavin Norman\">Gavin Norman</a> (best entry to neo-trad)</li>\n<li><em>Mörk Borg</em> — Tøgersen & Nohr (even just as a design object)</li>\n<li><em>Heart: The City Beneath</em> — Howitt & Taylor (Spire's dungeon companion)</li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>Next Era</h2>"}, "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence": {"key": "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence", "category": "Eras", "name": "2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence", "tags": ["era"], "links": ["Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years", "Games/Lamentations of the Flame Princess", "People/James Raggi", "Games/Dungeon Crawl Classics", "Games/Hyperborea", "People/Jeff Talanian", "Games/Into the Odd", "Games/DD 5th Edition", "People/Mike Mearls", "People/Jeremy Crawford", "People/Matthew Mercer", "Games/Dungeon World", "People/Sage LaTorra", "People/Adam Koebel", "Games/Monsterhearts", "People/Avery Alder", "Games/The Quiet Year", "People/Avery Alder", "People/James Raggi", "People/Sage LaTorra"], "lineage": "crossover", "summary": "The three lineages develop in parallel and begin to cross-pollinate. The OSR gets weirder and more aesthetically ambitious. PbtA explodes into a family of dozens of games. D&D 5th edition launches the biggest mainstream revival in the hobby's history. Kickstarter transforms how games are funded and distributed. Critical Role begins (2015).", "html": "<h1>2011–2016 — Explosion & Divergence</h1>\n<p>#era</p>\n<p>← <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>The three lineages develop in parallel and begin to cross-pollinate. The OSR gets weirder and more aesthetically ambitious. PbtA explodes into a family of dozens of games. D&D 5th edition launches the biggest mainstream revival in the hobby's history. Kickstarter transforms how games are funded and distributed. Critical Role begins (2015).</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>OSR Thread</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>2010</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Lamentations of the Flame Princess\">Lamentations of the Flame Princess</a> by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/James Raggi\">James Raggi</a></li>\n</ul>  - Pushes OSR in weird, transgressive, literary direction\n  - High production values; distinctive aesthetic\n  - Commissions notable adventures from outside designers\n<ul><li><strong>2012</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dungeon Crawl Classics\">Dungeon Crawl Classics</a> by Goodman Games</li>\n</ul>  - Pulp fantasy; funnel mechanic (0-level characters)\n  - Highly distinctive dice system\n<ul><li><strong>2012</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Hyperborea\">Hyperborea</a> (ASSH) by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeff Talanian\">Jeff Talanian</a></li>\n</ul>  - Sword & Sorcery OSR; Clark Ashton Smith influence ⭐ <em>you've played this</em>\n<ul><li><strong>2014</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Into the Odd\">Into the Odd</a> by Chris McDowall</li>\n</ul>  - Rules-light; eliminates to-hit rolls entirely\n  - Influential on later minimalist OSR design\n<h3>OSR Publishing Matures</h3>\n<ul><li>Adventure modules become a significant market</li>\n<li>LotFP, Goodman Games, others establish professional publishing operations</li>\n<li>OSR blog culture at its peak (Grognardia, dozens of others)</li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>Mainstream Thread</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>2012</strong> — D&D Next open playtest begins (largest TTRPG playtest in history)</li>\n<li><strong>2014</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 5th Edition\">D&D 5th Edition</a> published</li>\n</ul>  - Design goal: appeal to everyone (3e fans, 4e fans, old-school fans)\n  - Hugely successful; becomes dominant game in the hobby\n  - <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Mike Mearls\">Mike Mearls</a> and <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeremy Crawford\">Jeremy Crawford</a> as primary architects\n<ul><li><strong>2014</strong> — DMs Guild and OGL ecosystem begins to develop</li>\n<li><strong>2015</strong> — Critical Role launches on Geek & Sundry</li>\n</ul>  - <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matthew Mercer\">Matthew Mercer</a> as GM\n  - Begins fundamentally reshaping hobby demographics\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Story Games Thread</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>2010–2012</strong> — PbtA explosion following Apocalypse World</li>\n</ul>  - <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dungeon World\">Dungeon World</a> (2012) — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Sage LaTorra\">LaTorra</a>, <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Adam Koebel\">Koebel</a>\n  - <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Monsterhearts\">Monsterhearts</a> (2012) — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a>\n  - Dozens of PbtA games circulate in zine/PDF format\n<ul><li><strong>2013</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Quiet Year\">The Quiet Year</a> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a></li>\n</ul>  - Map-making community game; establishes new design genre\n<ul><li><strong>The Forge closes</strong> (2012) — end of an era for indie theory</li>\n</ul>  - Community disperses to G+, blogs, later Discord\n<ul><li>Dungeon World wins multiple ENnie Awards; PbtA enters mainstream awareness</li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>Cross-Pollination in This Period</h2>\n<ul><li>D&D 5e's success creates a large audience — some of whom discover OSR and indie games</li>\n<li>PbtA's accessibility introduces story games to D&D-adjacent players (via Dungeon World especially)</li>\n<li>Kickstarter enables small publishers to fund ambitious projects across all lineages</li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>What to Read / Play from This Period</h2>\n<ul><li><em>Lamentations of the Flame Princess</em> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/James Raggi\">James Raggi</a> (read the Rules & Magic book)</li>\n<li><em>Dungeon World</em> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Sage LaTorra\">LaTorra</a>, <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Adam Koebel\">Koebel</a> (free SRD online)</li>\n<li><em>Monsterhearts 2</em> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a></li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>Next Era</h2>"}, "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years": {"key": "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years", "category": "Eras", "name": "2005-2010 The Catalyst Years", "tags": ["era"], "links": ["Eras/Pre-2005 Roots", "Games/OSRIC", "People/Matt Finch", "People/Stuart Marshall", "Games/Basic Fantasy RPG", "People/Chris Gonnerman", "Games/Labyrinth Lord", "People/Daniel Proctor", "Games/Swords and Wizardry", "People/Matt Finch", "Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "People/James Maliszewski", "Games/DD 4th Edition", "Games/Pathfinder 1e", "Publishers/Paizo", "Games/Dogs in the Vineyard", "People/Vincent Baker", "Games/Lady Blackbird", "People/John Harper", "Games/Apocalypse World"], "lineage": "crossover", "summary": "The most consequential five years in recent TTRPG history. The retroclone movement creates the legal and creative infrastructure of the OSR. D&D 4th edition alienates a significant portion of the fanbase, catalyzing both the OSR and the story games scene simultaneously. Apocalypse World is written (published 2010). The hobby will never fully re-consolidate.", "html": "<h1>2005–2010 — The Catalyst Years</h1>\n<p>#era</p>\n<p>← <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005 Roots</a></p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>The most consequential five years in recent TTRPG history. The retroclone movement creates the legal and creative infrastructure of the OSR. D&D 4th edition alienates a significant portion of the fanbase, catalyzing both the OSR and the story games scene simultaneously. Apocalypse World is written (published 2010). The hobby will never fully re-consolidate.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>OSR Thread</h2>\n<h3>The Retroclone Wave</h3>\n<ul><li><strong>2006</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/OSRIC\">OSRIC</a> published by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a> & <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Stuart Marshall\">Stuart Marshall</a></li>\n</ul>  - First major retroclone; legal infrastructure for the movement\n  - Targets AD&D 1st edition\n<ul><li><strong>2006</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Basic Fantasy RPG\">Basic Fantasy RPG</a> by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris Gonnerman\">Chris Gonnerman</a></li>\n</ul>  - B/X target; establishes free/open-access ethos\n<ul><li><strong>2007</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Labyrinth Lord\">Labyrinth Lord</a> by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Daniel Proctor\">Daniel Proctor</a></li>\n</ul>  - Becomes dominant OSR publishing platform\n<ul><li><strong>2008</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Swords and Wizardry\">Swords & Wizardry</a> by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a></li>\n</ul>  - Targets original 1974 D&D\n  - <em>A Quick Primer for Old School Gaming</em> published alongside — key philosophical text\n<h3>The Catalyst</h3>\n<ul><li><strong>2008</strong> — D&D 4th Edition published → <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/D&D Edition Wars\">see Edition Wars</a></li>\n</ul>  - Many players experience it as a radical departure\n  - Drives a wave of new players to retroclones\n  - OSR goes from hobbyist curiosity to genuine movement\n<h3>The OSR Finds Its Voice</h3>\n<ul><li><strong>2008</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/James Maliszewski\">James Maliszewski</a> launches <em>Grognardia</em> blog</li>\n</ul>  - Becomes movement's critical and historical center of gravity\n<ul><li>OSR blog culture explodes: dozens of blogs articulating old-school philosophy</li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>Mainstream Thread</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>2008</strong> — D&D 4th Edition published (<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 4th Edition\">D&D 4e</a>)</li>\n</ul>  - WotC releases new GSL (Game System License) replacing OGL — more restrictive\n  - Divisive reception; tactically strong, aesthetically polarizing\n<ul><li><strong>2009</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 1e\">Pathfinder 1e</a> published by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Paizo\">Paizo</a></li>\n</ul>  - Built on D&D 3.5 OGL; marketed as \"D&D 3.75\"\n  - Becomes #1 selling TTRPG, outselling D&D for several years\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Story Games Thread</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>2004–2009</strong> — Forge-era indie games develop and circulate</li>\n</ul>  - <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dogs in the Vineyard\">Dogs in the Vineyard</a> (2004) — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a>\n  - Various shorter Forge games: Shock, The Mountain Witch, In a Wicked Age\n<ul><li><strong>2009</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Lady Blackbird\">Lady Blackbird</a> by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a> published (free)</li>\n</ul>  - Ultra-condensed; anticipates later design efficiency\n<ul><li><strong>2010</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Apocalypse World\">Apocalypse World</a> published by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a> & <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Meguey Baker\">Meguey Baker</a></li>\n</ul>  - Introduces Moves as design concept\n  - The PbtA family begins here\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key Tensions of This Period</h2>\n<p>1. <strong>What is D&D for?</strong> — 4e forced an answer nobody agreed on 2. <strong>Can you legally republish old mechanics?</strong> — Retroclones proved you could 3. <strong>What makes old-school play distinctive?</strong> — OSR blogs began to articulate this explicitly 4. <strong>Is narrative design compatible with genre play?</strong> — Story games designers wrestling with this</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What to Read / Play from This Period</h2>\n<ul><li><em>A Quick Primer for Old School Gaming</em> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a> (free, ~10 pages)</li>\n<li><em>Labyrinth Lord</em> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Daniel Proctor\">Daniel Proctor</a> (free PDF; play some B/X)</li>\n<li><em>Apocalypse World</em> 2nd ed — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a> (read the GM chapter especially)</li>\n<li>Grognardia blog archives — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/James Maliszewski\">James Maliszewski</a></li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>Next Era</h2>"}, "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape": {"key": "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape", "category": "Eras", "name": "2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape", "tags": ["era", "current"], "links": ["Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity", "Games/Dolmenwood", "Publishers/Exalted Funeral", "Games/Brindlewood Bay", "Games/Heart The City Beneath", "Games/Wanderhome", "Games/The Between", "Games/Starforged", "Games/Pathfinder 2e", "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023", "Games/Vaesen", "Games/The One Ring 2e", "Games/Draw Steel", "Games/Daggerheart", "People/Jeremy Crawford", "People/Chris Perkins", "People/Gavin Norman", "People/Jason Cordova", "People/Jay Dragon", "People/Shawn Tomkin"], "lineage": "crossover", "summary": "The pandemic accelerates online play and broadens the audience. The 2023 OGL crisis shatters mainstream consolidation around D&D and permanently decentralizes the ecosystem. OSR publishing reaches its most mature and prolific state. The indie scene diversifies into cozy, solo, and GM-less play. Pathfinder 2e becomes the primary mainstream D&D alternative. The crossover space grows significantly. A", "html": "<h1>2021–Present — The Post-OGL Landscape</h1>\n<p>#era #current</p>\n<p>← <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>The pandemic accelerates online play and broadens the audience. The 2023 OGL crisis shatters mainstream consolidation around D&D and permanently decentralizes the ecosystem. OSR publishing reaches its most mature and prolific state. The indie scene diversifies into cozy, solo, and GM-less play. Pathfinder 2e becomes the primary mainstream D&D alternative. The crossover space grows significantly. And in 2025, D&D's primary architects leave WotC to join Daggerheart's publisher.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>OSR Thread</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>2022</strong> — Hyperborea 3rd Edition; Dolmenwood developed through Patreon releases</li>\n<li><strong>2024</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dolmenwood\">Dolmenwood</a> boxed set (Kickstarter $1.1M+); the neo-trad OSR's flagship</li>\n<li>Zine explosion continues; itch.io TTRPG section vast and diverse</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Exalted Funeral\">Exalted Funeral</a> (Cristin & Matt Kelley) as primary curatorial retailer</li>\n<li><em>Knock!</em> magazine (Éric Nieudan & Olivier Revenu) as flagship anthology</li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>Story Games Thread</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>2020</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\">Brindlewood Bay</a> (Cordova) — Conspiracy mechanic; mystery solutions collaboratively authored ⭐ <em>you GM this</em></li>\n<li><strong>2021</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Heart The City Beneath\">Heart: The City Beneath</a> (Howitt & Taylor)</li>\n<li><strong>2021</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Wanderhome\">Wanderhome</a> (Dragon) — cozy wave reaches full expression</li>\n<li><strong>2022</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Between\">The Between</a> (Cordova) · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Starforged\">Ironsworn: Starforged</a> (Tomkin)</li>\n<li>Solo TTRPG market expands dramatically during pandemic years</li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>Mainstream Thread</h2>\n<h3>OGL Crisis (2023)</h3>\n<ul><li>January 2023 — OGL 1.1 draft leaks; massive community backlash</li>\n<li>WotC retreats; 5e SRD placed under Creative Commons</li>\n<li>Paizo develops ORC License; <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 2e\">Pathfinder 2e</a> sees major sales spike</li>\n<li>Multiple actual play shows move away from D&D 5e</li>\n<li>See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OGL Crisis 2023\">OGL Crisis 2023</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Crossover Space Grows</h3>\n<ul><li><strong>2021</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Vaesen\">Vaesen</a> (Free League / Hintze)</li>\n<li><strong>2022</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The One Ring 2e\">The One Ring 2e</a> (Free League / Nepitello)</li>\n<li><strong>2024</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Draw Steel\">Draw Steel</a> (MCDM / Colville) — $4.7M Kickstarter</li>\n<li><strong>2024</strong> — D&D 2024 revision (One D&D)</li>\n<li><strong>2025</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Daggerheart\">Daggerheart</a> Core Rulebook released (May 2025)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>The 2025 Talent Shift</h3>\n<ul><li><strong>April 2025</strong> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeremy Crawford\">Jeremy Crawford</a> and <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris Perkins\">Chris Perkins</a> depart WotC (28 and 18 years respectively)</li>\n<li><strong>June 2025</strong> — Announced as Game Director (Crawford) and Creative Director (Perkins) at Darrington Press</li>\n<li>Together: 46 combined years of D&D design experience now working on Daggerheart expansions</li>\n<li><strong>Gen Con 2025</strong> — Multiple Daggerheart expansions announced: Crawford (new setting), Perkins (adventure), Keith Baker & Jenn Ellis (new world)</li>\n<li>Daggerheart Kickstarter for play accessories announced for September 2025</li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>The Decentralized Present</h2>\n<p>The post-OGL landscape has no single dominant game or community hub in the way 5e dominated 2014–2022. Instead: <ul><li>OSR: prolific, aesthetically diverse, itch.io-distributed</li> <li>Story games: mature ecosystem, strong convention presence</li> <li>Mainstream: fragmented between D&D 2024, Pathfinder 2e, Draw Steel, Daggerheart, and dozens of alternatives</li> </ul> This is arguably the most creative and diverse moment in the hobby's post-2005 history — and also the most difficult to navigate as a new player.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key People in This Era</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Gavin Norman\">Gavin Norman</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Cordova\">Jason Cordova</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jay Dragon\">Jay Dragon</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\">Shawn Tomkin</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Francesco Nepitello\">Francesco Nepitello</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Colville\">Matt Colville</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeremy Crawford\">Jeremy Crawford</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris Perkins\">Chris Perkins</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Spenser Starke and Rowan Hall\">Starke & Hall</a>"}, "Personal/Recommended Reading and Watching": {"key": "Personal/Recommended Reading and Watching", "category": "Personal", "name": "Recommended Reading and Watching", "tags": ["personal", "reading", "resources", "blogs", "podcasts", "youtube"], "links": [], "lineage": "crossover", "summary": "> Essays, blogs, podcasts, YouTube channels, and other resources for understanding the contemporary TTRPG landscape. Organized by lineage and format.", "html": "<h1>Recommended Reading, Watching & Listening</h1>\n<p>#personal #reading #resources #blogs #podcasts #youtube</p>\n<blockquote><em>Essays, blogs, podcasts, YouTube channels, and other resources for understanding the contemporary TTRPG landscape. Organized by lineage and format.</em></blockquote>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Foundational Texts — Free to Read</h2>\n<h3>OSR Lineage</h3>\n<strong>A Quick Primer for Old School Gaming</strong> — Matt Finch (2008; updated 2024) The foundational document for understanding OSR design philosophy. Organizes old-school play around four \"Zen Moments\": Rulings not Rules; Player Skill not Character Abilities; Heroic not Super-Heroic; Forget Game Balance. The 2024 update explicitly contrasts old-school play with 5e methods using parallel examples (the pit trap comparison is especially clear). <strong>Free PDF from mythmeregames.com.</strong> You have read this; it is the right starting point.\n<strong>Principia Apocrypha</strong> — Ben Milton, Steven Lumpkin, David Perry (2018) A complementary document to the Finch Primer, written in the style of Apocalypse World's Agenda and Principles. Organizes OSR play philosophy as a list of aphorisms rather than prose explanation. Where Finch explains what old-school play is, Principia Apocrypha tells you how to do it. Translated into 9 languages; widely considered one of the two foundational OSR texts alongside the Primer. <strong>Free — search \"Principia Apocrypha PDF\" or find at osr.camp.</strong>\n<strong>\"Grand Experiments: West Marches\"</strong> — Ben Robbins (2007, ars ludi blog) A three-part series of blog posts describing Robbins' West Marches campaign — the origin of the West Marches model for open-table sandbox play. Not a manifesto but a play report that explains why the design decisions were made, which is more useful. Directly relevant to Dolmenwood's hexcrawl structure and to understanding sandbox play philosophy. <strong>Free — arsludi.lamemage.com.</strong>\n<strong>Bastionland Blog</strong> — Chris McDowall (2011–present) McDowall's design blog, which contains much of the public thinking that produced Into the Odd, Electric Bastionland, and Mythic Bastionland. Posts on encounter design, dungeon procedure, the Sites mechanic, and the philosophy behind \"no to-hit rolls\" are particularly valuable. <strong>Free — bastionland.com.</strong>\n<p>---</p>\n<h3>Story Games Lineage</h3>\n<strong>Apocalypse World (MC chapters)</strong> — Vincent Baker (2010) You own this. The MC's Agenda, Principles, and Moves sections are the most important design documents in the PbtA tradition — not because they tell you how to run AW specifically but because they articulate a theory of GMing that the entire PbtA diaspora has built on. Read these sections as design theory, not just game instructions.\n<strong>\"Powered by the Apocalypse\" (Baker's design notes)</strong> — Various blog posts Baker's public writing about AW's design process, particularly posts on bastionland.com interviews and lumpley.games, are worth seeking out. The specific post \"anyway, all those games\" describes the design logic behind Moves as a concept. <strong>Free — various blogs.</strong>\n<strong>Grant Howitt's design blog and Patreon posts</strong> — Grant Howitt (2015–present) Howitt writes about TTRPG design more accessibly and more honestly about the process than almost anyone else working. His public essays on one-page game design, on how Spire was made, and on what he's trying to accomplish with each project are excellent. <strong>Partly free, partly Patreon.</strong>\n<p>---</p>\n<h3>Mystery Design</h3>\n<strong>\"Solving the Mystery Problem\"</strong> — Jason Cordova (various podcast episodes and blog posts) Cordova has written and spoken extensively about what he was trying to solve with the Conspiracy mechanic. His Gauntlet blog posts and the +1 Forward podcast have episodes directly addressing why GUMSHOE and standard PbtA both fail the mystery genre in specific ways. <strong>Free — Gauntlet blog.</strong>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>YouTube Channels</h2>\n<strong>Questing Beast</strong> (Ben Milton) The most important OSR YouTube channel. Reviews of OSR games, interviews with designers, and design discussions. Milton's video on \"What is the OSR?\" is a useful complement to Principia Apocrypha. His newsletter is also worth subscribing to. The channel that introduced the majority of English-speaking players to the post-OSR wave of games (Cairn, Mausritter, Into the Odd, Mörk Borg) through video reviews. <strong>Free — YouTube.</strong>\n<strong>Running the Game</strong> (Matt Colville / MCDM) The series that made Colville's reputation and built the MCDM audience. The early episodes on how to run D&D are genuinely useful regardless of system. Later episodes on encounter design and faction play are directly relevant to OSR-adjacent and sandbox play. <strong>Free — YouTube.</strong>\n<strong>Dungeon Craft</strong> (Professor DM) A well-regarded channel covering OSR philosophy, game design discussion, and practical GMing advice. More mainstream-accessible than Questing Beast while still engaging seriously with design questions. <strong>Free — YouTube.</strong>\n<strong>Seth Skorkowsky</strong> (Seth Skorkowsky) The best YouTube resource for horror RPG design — specifically Call of Cthulhu, Delta Green, and adjacent games. Given your ownership of CoC and Delta Green, his series on those games is directly useful. His Delta Green \"how to run\" series is excellent. <strong>Free — YouTube.</strong>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Podcasts</h2>\n<strong>Between Two Cairns</strong> — Yochai Gal A podcast about OSR-adjacent game design hosted by the Cairn designer. Interviews with designers, discussion of specific games, and design philosophy. One of the most thoughtful ongoing podcasts in the OSR-adjacent space. <strong>Free.</strong>\n<strong>Gauntlet Podcast</strong> — Jason Cordova / Gauntlet community The podcast associated with the Gauntlet gaming community, which championed many of the PbtA and indie games in your collection. Discusses game design, actual play, and community practice. Directly relevant to Brindlewood Bay's design context. <strong>Free.</strong>\n<strong>+1 Forward</strong> — Sage LaTorra and others A podcast about PbtA design and play. The series of interviews with Belonging Outside Belonging designers is particularly good. <strong>Free.</strong>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key Blog Posts Worth Finding</h2>\n<strong>\"The Alexandrian\" blog</strong> — Justin Alexander Long-running design blog with the most thorough treatment of the Node-Based Scenario Design approach — a structured mystery/adventure design method that complements both the GUMSHOE and Conspiracy mechanic traditions. The three-clue rule post is widely cited. <strong>Free — thealexandrian.net.</strong>\n<strong>False Machine blog</strong> — Patrick Stuart Stuart's design blog, associated with Veins of the Earth, Deep Carbon Observatory, and other significant OSR adventure work. Dense but rewarding — Stuart thinks carefully and unusually about monster design, dungeon ecology, and the aesthetics of OSR adventure writing. <strong>Free — falsemachine.blogspot.com.</strong>\n<strong>Bastionland Newsletter / Substack</strong> — Chris McDowall McDowall's ongoing design writing, including extended posts on how Mythic Bastionland works and how the Sites mechanic developed. More detailed than the blog posts. <strong>Partly free — bastionland.substack.com.</strong>\n<p>---</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Graham Walmsley — Horror Design & Improv Practice</h2>\n<strong>Play Unsafe</strong> — Graham Walmsley (2007) The foundational text for applying theatre improv to TTRPG play. 74 pages. Draws on Keith Johnstone's improv theory to argue against front-loaded preparation and for holding ideas lightly, being obvious, and trusting the collaborative moment. Pairs well with Apocalypse World's MC chapters — both argue \"play to find out,\" but Walmsley arrives there from theatre rather than game design theory, and the framing is different enough to be genuinely additive. Note: if you're already deeply versed in PbtA thinking, some of this will feel familiar; it's most transformative for players coming from preparation-heavy D&D backgrounds. <strong>Available from DriveThruRPG and directly from Walmsley.</strong>\n<strong>Cthulhu Dark (Director's chapters)</strong> — Graham Walmsley (2017) You own Call of Cthulhu, Delta Green, and Night's Black Agents. Cthulhu Dark's horror GMing chapters — how to build mysteries that produce genuine horror, how to use Creeping Horrors (recurring inexplicable imagery distributed across an adventure), how to write from themes you actually find frightening rather than genre conventions — are some of the best available writing on running horror specifically at the TTRPG table. Even if you never run Cthulhu Dark itself, the Director's section is worth reading as a horror design document. <strong>Free version (4 pages, original rules only) available; full book on DriveThruRPG.</strong>\n<strong>Stealing Cthulhu</strong> — Graham Walmsley (2011) A methodology book for Lovecraftian scenario construction. The argument: break down Lovecraft's actual stories into structural components (the journey to revelation, the document that shouldn't be read, the person who knows too much) and recombine them. Produces scenarios that feel authentically Lovecraftian without being derivative. Contributors include Kenneth Hite and Jason Morningstar. Most useful if you're running horror RPGs beyond Cthulhu Dark specifically — the structural thinking applies to horror scenario design generally. <strong>Available from DriveThruRPG.</strong>\n<strong>Graham Walmsley's Substack / Patreon</strong> Walmsley writes regularly about his current design work (Cosmic Dark) and horror design thinking. Public Substack posts discuss the Changed mechanic, body horror as a design space, and the differences between Cosmic Dark and Cthulhu Dark. The Patreon ($5 tier) includes playtest scenarios for Cosmic Dark. Worth following if horror design interests you. <strong>grahamwalmsley.substack.com / patreon.com/graham.</strong>\n<h2>Books About TTRPG Culture</h2>\n<strong>\"Monsters, Aliens, and Holes in the Ground\"</strong> — Stu Horvath (2023, MIT Press) A scholarly history of tabletop RPGs from 1974 to the present, written accessibly. The most comprehensive historical account available. Covers OSR, story games, and mainstream evolution with even-handed treatment. If you want one book-length history of the hobby, this is it.\n<strong>\"Dungeons & Dragons Art & Arcana\"</strong> — Michael Witwer, Kyle Newman, Jon Peterson, Sam Witwer (2018) A visual history of D&D with extensive archival material. Less useful for design history but excellent for understanding the aesthetic evolution of the mainstream tradition and the cultural weight the brand carries.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Design Documents Worth Reading Directly</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Document</td><td>Author</td><td>Why</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Quick Primer for Old School Gaming (2024)</td><td>Matt Finch</td><td>You've read this; the 2024 update adds 5e comparisons</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Principia Apocrypha</td><td>Ben Milton et al.</td><td>OSR philosophy as aphorisms; complement to Finch</td></tr>\n<tr><td>West Marches blog posts</td><td>Ben Robbins</td><td>Origin of open-table sandbox model</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Apocalypse World MC chapters</td><td>Vincent Baker</td><td>Theory of GMing as design object</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Into the Odd Player's Guide</td><td>Chris McDowall</td><td>Most elegant statement of minimalist design</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Ironsworn free PDF</td><td>Shawn Tomkin</td><td>Best oracle system available; models solo play</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Lady Blackbird</td><td>John Harper</td><td>You own this; 16 pages; study the economy of design</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Cairn 2e SRD</td><td>Yochai Gal</td><td>You own this; contrast with Lady Blackbird's compression</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>A Note on Reading Order</h2>\n<p>If you are reading to understand the OSR tradition: 1. Quick Primer (Finch, 2024) — you've done this 2. Principia Apocrypha — complement and contrast to Finch 3. West Marches posts (Robbins) — the most influential OSR campaign model 4. Into the Odd (when acquired) — the design tradition in its purest form</p>\n<p>If you are reading to understand the story games tradition: 1. Apocalypse World MC chapters — you own this; do this now 2. Blades in the Dark \"How to Play\" chapter — you own this; compare to AW's MC guidance 3. Grant Howitt's design blog — design process made public 4. Cordova on the Conspiracy mechanic — bridges your PbtA and mystery play interests</p>\n<p>If you are reading to understand the contemporary landscape overall: 1. Monsters, Aliens, and Holes in the Ground (Horvath) — book-length history 2. Questing Beast YouTube — ongoing tastemaking and design criticism 3. Bastionland Substack (McDowall) — where cutting-edge minimalist design thinking lives now</p>"}, "Personal/My TTRPG Library": {"key": "Personal/My TTRPG Library", "category": "Personal", "name": "My TTRPG Library", "tags": ["personal", "library", "played", "owned"], "links": ["Games/Hyperborea", "Games/Dolmenwood", "Games/Spire The City Must Fall", "Games/Brindlewood Bay", "Games/Vale of the Failed and the Fallen", "Games/Monster of the Week", "Games/Old-School Essentials", "Games/Cairn", "Games/Hyperborea", "Games/Dolmenwood", "Games/Mythic Bastionland", "Games/Mausritter", "Games/Call of Cthulhu", "Games/Delta Green", "Games/Deadlands The Weird West", "Games/Cyberpunk Red", "Games/Warhammer Fantasy Roleplay", "Games/Apocalypse World", "Games/Brindlewood Bay", "Games/Monster of the Week"], "lineage": "crossover", "summary": "> A living record of games played, owned, and on the to-acquire list.", "html": "<h1>My TTRPG Library</h1>\n<p>#personal #library #played #owned</p>\n<blockquote><em>A living record of games played, owned, and on the to-acquire list.</em></blockquote>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Games I Have Played</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Role</td><td>Lineage</td><td>Notes</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Hyperborea\\</td><td>Hyperborea\">td><td>Hyperborea</a></td><td>Player</td><td>OSR</td><td>Sword & Sorcery; pulp literary sources</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dolmenwood\\</td><td>Dolmenwood\">td><td>Dolmenwood</a></td><td>Player</td><td>OSR / Neo-Trad</td><td>Folk horror; 7 factions; hexcrawl</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\\</td><td>Spire: The City Must Fall\">td><td>Spire: The City Must Fall</a></td><td>Player</td><td>FitD / Indie</td><td>Dark elf revolution; domain stress</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\\</td><td>Brindlewood Bay\">td><td>Brindlewood Bay</a></td><td>GM / Keeper</td><td>PbtA / Indie</td><td>The Conspiracy mechanic; elderly sleuth cozy horror</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Vale of the Failed and the Fallen\\</td><td>Vale of the Failed and the Fallen\">td><td>Vale of the Failed and the Fallen</a></td><td>Player</td><td>PbtA</td><td>Regret & redemption; two-timeline structure</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Monster of the Week\\</td><td>Monster of the Week\">td><td>Monster of the Week</a></td><td>Player</td><td>PbtA</td><td>Episodic monster hunting; TV-inspired</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>AD&D 2e</em></td><td>Player</td><td>Mainstream</td><td>Classic era</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>AD&D 3e</em></td><td>Player</td><td>Mainstream</td><td>d20 era</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>D&D 5e</em></td><td>Player</td><td>Mainstream</td><td>Modern mainstream</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Games I Own / Have Read</h2>\n<h3>OSR & Neo-Trad</h3>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Notes</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Old-School Essentials\\</td><td>Old-School Essentials\">td><td>Old-School Essentials</a></td><td>B/X reformed; neo-trad platform; Dolmenwood's system</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cairn\\</td><td>Cairn 1e\">td><td>Cairn 1e</a></td><td>Free; ItO distilled; gateway to minimalist OSR</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Hyperborea\\</td><td>Hyperborea\">td><td>Hyperborea</a></td><td>See above</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dolmenwood\\</td><td>Dolmenwood\">td><td>Dolmenwood</a></td><td>See above</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mythic Bastionland\\</td><td>Mythic Bastionland\">td><td>Mythic Bastionland</a></td><td>Quickstart read; Myths/Omens/Sites</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mausritter\\</td><td>Mausritter\">td><td>Mausritter</a></td><td>ItO chassis; card inventory; mice</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>OSRIC</em></td><td>AD&D 1e clone; legal/historical foundation</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Mazes Fantasy Roleplaying</em></td><td>Simple OSR-adjacent</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Kobolds Ate My Baby (Orange Book)</em></td><td>Classic comedic OSR; Brian Jelke & Steve Steinberg</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h3>Mainstream / D&D & Genre</h3>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Notes</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>AD&D 2e, 3e, 5e</em></td><td>See above</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Call of Cthulhu\\</td><td>Call of Cthulhu\">td><td>Call of Cthulhu</a></td><td>BRP percentile; Sanity track origin; foundational horror investigation</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Delta Green\\</td><td>Delta Green\">td><td>Delta Green</a></td><td>CoC-derived; Bonds system; institutional conspiracy horror</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Night's Black Agents</em></td><td>GUMSHOE spy horror; Kenneth Hite; Pelgrane</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Deadlands The Weird West\\</td><td>Deadlands: The Weird West\">td><td>Deadlands: The Weird West</a></td><td>Alternate history weird west; 9 Origins Awards; Savage Worlds</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cyberpunk Red\\</td><td>Cyberpunk Red\">td><td>Cyberpunk Red</a></td><td>Mike Pondsmith; cyberpunk; Interlock system</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Warhammer Fantasy Roleplay\\</td><td>Warhammer Fantasy Roleplay\">td><td>Warhammer Fantasy Roleplay</a></td><td>British grimdark fantasy; career system; foundational</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Castle Falkenstein</em></td><td>Steampunk; R. Talsorian; Pondsmith; historically significant</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Doctor Who RPG 2e</em></td><td>Cubicle 7 licensed adaptation</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>GI Joe RPG</em></td><td>Renegade Game Studios licensed adaptation</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Power Rangers RPG</em></td><td>Renegade Game Studios licensed adaptation</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Transformers RPG</em></td><td>Renegade Game Studios licensed adaptation</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Witcher TTRPG</em></td><td>R. Talsorian; Pondsmith team; Polish IP adaptation</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Rifts: Tomorrow Legion Player's Guide</em></td><td>Savage Worlds version of the classic Palladium setting</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Dreams and Machines</em></td><td>Modiphius; post-apocalyptic hopeful; Year Zero Engine</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Modern Age Basic Rulebook</em></td><td>Green Ronin; d6 stunt dice; modern setting platform</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Five and Infinity: A Modern Age Series</em></td><td>Modern Age setting supplement</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>King Is Dead</em></td><td>OSR-adjacent Arthurian resistance game</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h3>Story Games & Indie — PbtA</h3>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Notes</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Apocalypse World\\</td><td>Apocalypse World\">td><td>Apocalypse World</a></td><td>The source; read the MC chapters as design theory</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\\</td><td>Brindlewood Bay\">td><td>Brindlewood Bay</a></td><td>See above</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Monster of the Week\\</td><td>Monster of the Week\">td><td>Monster of the Week</a></td><td>See above</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Vale of the Failed and the Fallen\\</td><td>Vale of the Failed and the Fallen\">td><td>Vale of the Failed and the Fallen</a></td><td>See above</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Under Hollow Hills\\</td><td>Under Hollow Hills\">td><td>Under Hollow Hills</a></td><td>Baker post-AW; faerie circus; warmer register</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Masks A New Generation\\</td><td>Masks: A New Generation\">td><td>Masks: A New Generation</a></td><td>PbtA superhero; Influence/Labels system</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Rhapsody of Blood\\</td><td>Rhapsody of Blood\">td><td>Rhapsody of Blood</a></td><td>PbtA dungeon-delve; Living Palace; corruption mechanics</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Rosewood Abbey\\</td><td>Rosewood Abbey\">td><td>Rosewood Abbey</a></td><td>Carved from Brindlewood; monastic mysteries; Rumor Mill mechanic; Kalum</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Paris Gondo\\</td><td>Paris Gondo — The Life-Saving Magic of Inventorying\">td><td>Paris Gondo — The Life-Saving Magic of Inventorying</a></td><td>GM-less; Marie Kondo meets dungeon loot; GonParis Method; Kalum</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Pinebox Middle School</em></td><td>PbtA / Savage Worlds-ish; young adult supernatural</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Sentai and Sensibility</em></td><td>PbtA; Super Sentai meets Regency drama</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h3>Story Games & Indie — Other / Pre-PbtA</h3>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Notes</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Perfect Unrevised\\</td><td>Perfect, Unrevised\">td><td>Perfect, Unrevised</a></td><td>Avery Alder (published under deadname); pre-PbtA dystopian story game; free PDF</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Simple World\\</td><td>Simple World\">td><td>Simple World</a></td><td>Avery Alder; PbtA design toolkit; \"get it on the table fast\"; free</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h3>Story Games & Indie — FitD</h3>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Notes</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Blades in the Dark\\</td><td>Blades in the Dark\">td><td>Blades in the Dark</a></td><td>The source; Kickstarter backer of Blades 68 expansion</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\\</td><td>Spire: The City Must Fall\">td><td>Spire: The City Must Fall</a></td><td>See above</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Eat the Reich\\</td><td>Eat the Reich\">td><td>Eat the Reich</a></td><td>Howitt/RR&D; vampires eating Nazis; one-shot FitD-adjacent</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h3>Story Games & Indie — Cozy / Solo</h3>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Notes</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Wanderhome\\</td><td>Wanderhome\">td><td>Wanderhome</a></td><td>No combat; pastoral; token economy</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Ironsworn\\</td><td>Ironsworn\">td><td>Ironsworn</a></td><td>Definitive solo TTRPG; vow system; oracle tables; free</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Lady Blackbird\\</td><td>Lady Blackbird\">td><td>Lady Blackbird</a></td><td>Free; ultra-condensed Harper design; study the economy</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Be Like a Crow\\</td><td>Be Like a Crow\">td><td>Be Like a Crow</a></td><td>Solo journaling; you are a crow; perspective-shift design</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Journey (Lite) Solo</em></td><td>Solo journaling game</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Amazing Tales: Kids RPG</em></td><td>Family RPG; simple mechanics for young players</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h3>Grant Howitt One-Page Games</h3>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Notes</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Grant Howitt One-Page Games\\</td><td>Honey Heist\">td><td>Honey Heist</a></td><td>The viral one; bears + heist; one mechanic</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Grant Howitt One-Page Games\\</td><td>Goblin Quest\">td><td>Goblin Quest</a></td><td>Five goblins; sequential deaths; the troupe is the protagonist</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Grant Howitt One-Page Games\\</td><td>Crash Pandas\">td><td>Crash Pandas</a></td><td>Raccoons driving a car</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Grant Howitt One-Page Games\\</td><td>The Witch Is Dead\">td><td>The Witch Is Dead</a></td><td>Familiars avenge their witch; surprisingly affecting</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Grant Howitt One-Page Games\\</td><td>Pride and Extreme Prejudice\">td><td>Pride and Extreme Prejudice</a></td><td>Regency romance + paramilitary action</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Grant Howitt One-Page Games\\</td><td>One Last Job\">td><td>One Last Job</a></td><td>Retired criminals; one last heist</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Grant Howitt One-Page Games\\</td><td>Horse Around the House\">td><td>Horse Around the House</a></td><td>You are a horse in a house</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Grant Howitt One-Page Games\\</td><td>A Very Honey Heist Xmas\">td><td>A Very Honey Heist Xmas</a></td><td>Seasonal Honey Heist variant</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h3>Miscellaneous / Uncategorized</h3>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Notes</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Humble RPG Bundle</em> (contents)</td><td>Various</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>GM Resources — Misc</em></td><td>Various referee tools</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Havoc Engine SRD</em></td><td>Draft ruleset; design document</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>I'm Going To Tell My Kids This Was D&D</em></td><td>Comedy one-page</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Lexicutioners</em></td><td>Word-based RPG</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Big Goat Little Goat</em></td><td>One-page / short-form</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Bastionland Press collection</em></td><td>Various McDowall products</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Priority Acquisitions</h2>\n<p>Games identified as significant gaps, ranked by impact and learning value:</p>\n<h3>Tier 1 — High Impact / Essential</h3>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Why</td><td>Cost</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Into the Odd\\</td><td>Into the Odd\">td><td>Into the Odd</a></td><td>Source for Cairn + Mausritter; complete the ItO family</td><td>Low</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dungeon World\\</td><td>Dungeon World\">td><td>Dungeon World</a></td><td>PbtA meets D&D; most mainstream PbtA gateway; Fronts</td><td>Low</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Monsterhearts\\</td><td>Monsterhearts 2\">td><td>Monsterhearts 2</a></td><td>Alder's most significant work; Strings economy; queer design</td><td>Mid</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h3>Tier 2 — Covers Significant Gaps</h3>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Why</td><td>Cost</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Electric Bastionland\\</td><td>Electric Bastionland\">td><td>Electric Bastionland</a></td><td>Bridges ItO → Mythic Bastionland; failed careers system</td><td>Mid</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Troika\\</td><td>Troika!\">td><td>Troika!</a></td><td>Post-OSR implied-setting design; bag initiative</td><td>Low</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Thousand Year Old Vampire\\</td><td>Thousand Year Old Vampire\">td><td>Thousand Year Old Vampire</a></td><td>Forgetting mechanic; solo journaling; emotional design</td><td>Low</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The One Ring 2e\\</td><td>The One Ring 2e\">td><td>The One Ring 2e</a></td><td>Best licensed adaptation ever made; journey mechanics</td><td>Mid-High</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 2e\\</td><td>Pathfinder 2e\">td><td>Pathfinder 2e</a></td><td>Most sophisticated mainstream alternative; 3-action economy</td><td>Mid</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h3>Tier 3 — Worth Having</h3>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Why</td><td>Cost</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dream Askew\\</td><td>Dream Askew / Dream Apart\"> Dream Apart</a></td><td>BoB system origin; Lures in source form</td><td>Low</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Quiet Year\\</td><td>The Quiet Year\">td><td>The Quiet Year</a></td><td>Community-as-protagonist; map-making; GM-less</td><td>Low</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/For the Queen\\</td><td>For the Queen\">td><td>For the Queen</a></td><td>Intimate card play; short; cheap</td><td>Low</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Microscope</em></td><td>Ben Robbins; collaborative world-building; West Marches designer</td><td>Low</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Burning Wheel</em></td><td>Design landmark; demanding; worth the effort</td><td>High</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Cross-Lineage Coverage Note</h2>\n<p>Your collection spans all three lineages substantively: <ul><li><strong>OSR</strong>: OSE, Cairn, Hyperborea, Dolmenwood, Mausritter, Mythic Bastionland quickstart, OSRIC</li> <li><strong>Mainstream</strong>: AD&D 2e/3e/5e, CoC, Delta Green, Night's Black Agents, Deadlands, Cyberpunk Red, WFRP, Castle Falkenstein</li> <li><strong>Story Games</strong>: AW, Blades in the Dark, Brindlewood Bay, MotW, Ironsworn, Wanderhome, Under Hollow Hills, Spire, Rosewood Abbey, Paris Gondo, Perfect Unrevised, Simple World</li> <li><strong>Crossover</strong>: Vaesen, Masks, Dreams and Machines, Eat the Reich</li> </ul> Remaining significant gaps: Into the Odd (source for games you already own), Dungeon World (PbtA mainstream gateway), Monsterhearts (key Alder game), Electric Bastionland (completes Bastionland trilogy). Recent additions: Rosewood Abbey, Paris Gondo, Perfect Unrevised, Simple World.</p>"}, "Games/The Sprawl": {"key": "Games/The Sprawl", "category": "Games", "name": "The Sprawl", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "cyberpunk"], "links": ["People/Hamish Cameron", "People/Hamish Cameron", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Concepts/Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "A PbtA cyberpunk game specifically targeting the corporate thriller mode of William Gibson's Sprawl trilogy. Characters are operators doing jobs for megacorporations while trying to survive in a world where everyone has an agenda.", "html": "<h1>The Sprawl</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #cyberpunk</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2016 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Hamish Cameron\">Hamish Cameron</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A PbtA cyberpunk game specifically targeting the corporate thriller mode of William Gibson's Sprawl trilogy. Characters are operators doing jobs for megacorporations while trying to survive in a world where everyone has an agenda.</p>\n<h2>The Clock System</h2>\n<p>Separate clocks track the momentum of multiple corporate interests simultaneously. Corporate pressure builds independently of player action; operators navigate this pressure. The system makes systemic power mechanically visible as a constant presence rather than a backdrop.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Understood that cyberpunk is a genre defined by systemic power rather than individual heroism and designed mechanics that reflected this — one of the clearest examples of genre-specific mechanical design in PbtA. The Clock system anticipated FitD's clocks and influenced how designers approach faction and organizational mechanics.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Hamish Cameron\">Hamish Cameron</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Related concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)\">Clocks</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Deadlands The Weird West": {"key": "Games/Deadlands The Weird West", "category": "Games", "name": "Deadlands The Weird West", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "horror", "western", "owned"], "links": ["Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 1996 (original); current edition 2020 | Designer: Shane Lacy Hensley\nPublisher: Pinnacle Entertainment Group | System: Savage Worlds (current edition)", "html": "<h1>Deadlands: The Weird West</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #horror #western #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 1996 (original); current edition 2020 | <strong>Designer:</strong> Shane Lacy Hensley <strong>Publisher:</strong> Pinnacle Entertainment Group | <strong>System:</strong> Savage Worlds (current edition)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A genre-mixing alternate history RPG combining the Western and horror genres with steampunk elements. Set in an 1876 America where history diverged on July 3, 1863 — when a shamanic ritual tore open the spirit world, causing the dead to rise at Gettysburg and drawing malicious entities called Reckoners into the world. The Civil War never ended; California has partially sunk into the ocean; a mysterious mineral called ghost rock powers strange steam-powered technology; and shamans, gunslingers, mad scientists, and preachers fight the supernatural.</p>\n<h2>Historical Significance</h2>\n<p>Released at Gen Con in 1996, Deadlands heralded a renaissance in the hobby and the industry that would last until the release of D&D Third Edition. It appeared during a period when the industry was depressed by the Magic: the Gathering boom, and demonstrated that original RPG settings with strong genre identity could find large audiences. It won nine Origins Awards and became one of the most recognized non-D&D RPGs of its era.</p>\n<p>The game's use of playing cards alongside dice (for the original system) was a distinctive design choice that reinforced the Western aesthetic mechanically.</p>\n<h2>System History</h2>\n<p>Originally used a custom card-and-dice system. Later converted to d20, GURPS, and then Savage Worlds (the current platform). The current Weird West edition integrates Savage Worlds rules directly. Savage Worlds — a generic system derived from Deadlands' Great Rail Wars wargame — is now Pinnacle's flagship system used across many settings.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: Shane Lacy Hensley | Publisher: Pinnacle Entertainment Group</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/D&D Edition Wars\">D&D Edition Wars</a> (contemporary context)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005 Roots</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Basic Fantasy RPG": {"key": "Games/Basic Fantasy RPG", "category": "Games", "name": "Basic Fantasy RPG", "tags": ["game", "osr", "retroclone"], "links": ["People/Chris Gonnerman", "People/Chris Gonnerman", "Concepts/Retroclones", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2006 (ongoing) | Designer: Chris Gonnerman | System: B/X clone", "html": "<h1>Basic Fantasy RPG</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #retroclone</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2006 (ongoing) | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris Gonnerman\">Chris Gonnerman</a> | <strong>System:</strong> B/X clone\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A retroclone targeting the B/X D&D ruleset, released under Creative Commons with PDFs free and print copies at near-cost. Still actively developed with a large catalogue of community-written free supplements.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Established the radical accessibility ethos of the early OSR. Gonnerman's model — free PDF, Lulu print at cost, open community supplements — was a template for OSR publishing culture.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris Gonnerman\">Chris Gonnerman</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Retroclones\">Retroclones</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Daggerheart": {"key": "Games/Daggerheart", "category": "Games", "name": "Daggerheart", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "crossover", "actualplay", "fantasy"], "links": ["People/John Harper", "People/Jeremy Crawford", "People/Chris Perkins", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Movements/Actual Play Boom", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 2025 (Core Rulebook released May 2025) | Lead designer: Spenser Starke | Publisher: Darrington Press", "html": "<h1>Daggerheart</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #crossover #actualplay #fantasy</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2025 (Core Rulebook released May 2025) | <strong>Lead designer:</strong> Spenser Starke | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Darrington Press\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A collaborative storytelling RPG designed specifically for the Critical Role audience — players whose primary reference for TTRPG play is performative, narrative-forward, emotionally engaged play. A complete fantasy adventure game that applies PbtA and FitD design principles to d20-adjacent genre conventions, producing the play experience Critical Role's audience has been watching for a decade and trying to produce with D&D's mechanics.</p>\n<h2>The Design Team</h2>\n<p>One of the most cross-lineage design teams in the hobby's history:</p>\n<ul><li><strong>Spenser Starke</strong> — lead designer; indie design fluency; also designed Candela Obscura (FitD-adjacent)</li>\n<li><strong>Rowan Hall</strong> — co-designer; theatrical background; dramatic scene structure</li>\n<li><strong>John Harper</strong> — additional game designer (credited in core rulebook); designer of Blades in the Dark; brings FitD expertise directly</li>\n<li><strong>Jeremy Crawford</strong> — Game Director, Darrington Press (June 2025–present); 18 years as 5e's primary rules architect</li>\n<li><strong>Chris Perkins</strong> — Creative Director, Darrington Press (June 2025–present); 28 years as D&D's senior story designer</li>\n</ul>\nCrawford and Perkins joined in June 2025 after departing WotC in April 2025. Together they represent 46 combined years of D&D design experience now working on Daggerheart expansions — Crawford on a new setting, Perkins on an adventure supplement.\n<h2>Key Mechanics</h2>\n<strong>Hope and Fear dice</strong> — Two d12s rolled simultaneously. The sum (plus modifier) determines success/failure against a threshold. But the individual die values determine narrative authority: if Hope shows higher, the player gains a Hope token; if Fear shows higher, the GM gains a Fear token. Four outcome states: Success with Hope, Success with Fear, Failure with Hope, Failure with Fear.\n<strong>Hope and Fear tokens</strong> — Spendable currencies. Hope: activate class features, clear damage, boost an ally's roll (prosocial; mechanically incentivizes community). Fear: GM triggers hazards, activates adversary abilities, makes narrative moves. Makes narrative momentum visible to all players.\n<strong>Adversary system</strong> — Enemies in three categories: Minions (no individual HP; any hit kills), Standard (individual stress boxes and abilities), Solo (phase-based boss fights; new abilities and partial stress recovery when phases turn; mechanically produces cinematic arc to climactic fights).\n<strong>Two health tracks</strong> — HP (physical) and Stress (psychological, emotional, magical). Stress accumulates through non-combat challenges, difficult decisions, certain class abilities. Makes emotional and psychological content mechanically real.\n<strong>Community character layer</strong> — Where and how the character grew up (Highborne, Wanderer, Loreborn, Orderborne, Underborne, Seaborne, Wildborne, etc.). Separates biological ancestry from cultural identity in ways 5e's race/background conflated.\n<strong>Experiences advancement</strong> — End-of-session reflection (PbtA-influenced): did you face a significant challenge? Pursue a personal goal? Develop a relationship? Advancement reflects actual session content rather than combat tally.\n<strong>Card system</strong> — Class abilities presented on physical cards. Characters literally add cards as they advance. Tactile and visual; designed to look good at a table and on camera.\n<h2>Gen Con 2025 Announcements</h2>\nDaggerheart expansions announced: Crawford designing a new setting; Perkins creating an adventure supplement; Keith Baker (Eberron creator) and Jenn Ellis creating a \"new world.\"\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>The clearest example of the design conversation happening in indie TTRPG circles since 2001 reaching a mainstream audience of millions who have no idea that conversation exists. Baker's moves, Harper's position/effect, the Forge's insight that design matters — all present in Daggerheart, translated into a form that a player who has never heard of Apocalypse World can pick up and play.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Lead designer: Spenser Starke</li>\n<li>Additional designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a></li>\n<li>Game Director: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeremy Crawford\">Jeremy Crawford</a> (Darrington Press)</li>\n<li>Creative Director: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris Perkins\">Chris Perkins</a> (Darrington Press)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Actual Play Boom\">Actual Play Boom</a></li>\n<li>Influences: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Forged in the Dark Family\">FitD</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Perfect Unrevised": {"key": "Games/Perfect Unrevised", "category": "Games", "name": "Perfect Unrevised", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "indie", "dystopian", "owned"], "links": ["People/Avery Alder", "People/Avery Alder", "Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2010 (1st ed.), 2012 (revised print) | Designer: Avery Alder (published under her deadname) | Publisher: Buried Without Ceremony | Website: [buriedwithoutceremony.com/perfect](https://buriedwithoutceremony.com/perfect) | PDF: Free", "html": "<h1>Perfect, Unrevised</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #indie #dystopian #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2010 (1st ed.), 2012 (revised print) | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a> (published under her deadname) | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Buried Without Ceremony | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://buriedwithoutceremony.com/perfect\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">buriedwithoutceremony.com/perfect</a> | <strong>PDF:</strong> Free\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A game about criminals within a Dark Victorian dystopia. Set in Cadence — a steampunk-tinged authoritarian city-state where citizens are surveilled, categorized by guild, and subjected to psychological reconditioning if they deviate. Players portray the criminally different: people whose existence or desires mark them as threats to the perfect society. Playable with 2+ players; uses only d6s.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>An early, structurally rigorous pre-PbtA indie story game. Core mechanic: a <strong>bidding system</strong> in which players wager dice to determine narrative authority — who gets to narrate an outcome, and at what cost. This positions conflict as a question of <em>narrative control</em> rather than character capability, making it unusual even among its contemporaries.</p>\n<p>Published before Avery Alder's work on Monsterhearts (2012), it anticipates themes she would return to throughout her career: queerness under persecution, the violence of normalization, the cost of resistance. The PDF is now free.</p>\n<p>Malcolm Craig (Cold City): <em>\"It's like Kafka and Charlotte Bronte had children, and those children wrote Blade Runner.\"</em></p>\n<h2>Your Copy</h2>\n<p>Owned (PDF or print).</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: Buried Without Ceremony</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory\">The Forge & Indie Foundations</a> (pre-PbtA era)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Stonetop": {"key": "Games/Stonetop", "category": "Games", "name": "Stonetop", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "community", "ironage", "hearth", "dungeon"], "links": ["Games/Dungeon World", "Games/Apocalypse World", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Games/Blades in the Dark", "Games/Wanderhome", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2021 (Kickstarter); physical publication 2025 | Designer: Jeremy Strandberg\nPublisher: Lampblack & Brimstone (Jason Lutes) | Illustrator: Lucie Arnoux\nSystem: PbtA (heavily modified Dungeon World chassis) | PDFs: available via Backerkit preorder", "html": "<h1>Stonetop</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #community #ironage #hearth-fantasy #dungeon-world-family</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2021 (Kickstarter); physical publication 2025 | <strong>Designer:</strong> Jeremy Strandberg <strong>Publisher:</strong> Lampblack & Brimstone (Jason Lutes) | <strong>Illustrator:</strong> Lucie Arnoux <strong>System:</strong> PbtA (heavily modified Dungeon World chassis) | <strong>PDFs:</strong> available via Backerkit preorder\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A PbtA fantasy RPG set in the Iron Age village of Stonetop — a poor, tight-knit community of around 300 people near the edge of the known world. Players are the village's notable figures: the people everyone looks to when there's trouble. The game is about protecting and growing that community across multiple seasons of play, not about accumulating personal glory.</p>\n<p>The core concept, as Strandberg puts it: you still go on adventures, but those adventures happen to defend or improve the village. The steading of Stonetop itself has its own character sheet with stats, traits, and improvements to be unlocked through play.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Described by reviewers as a candidate for \"forever game\" and \"maybe the first candidate in the PbtA universe\" for long-term campaign play. Stonetop represents one of the most thorough attempts in the PbtA tradition to build a game for sustained campaign play rather than short-arc sessions — it is explicitly best experienced over a dozen or more sessions, with seasonal time structure carrying the campaign forward across years.</p>\n<p>Several specific design achievements stand out:</p>\n<strong>The Steading as Protagonist</strong> — Stonetop (the village) is a game character with its own stats (Fortune, Prosperity, Population, Defenses, Surplus) and an improvement track that players actively develop. The steading improvement minigame is extensive, with improvements varying in difficulty and duration — from straightforward additions like extra housing, to long projects like building a market that requires cultivating a peaceful location for four sessions. This makes community investment mechanical rather than purely narrative.\n<strong>Homefront / Expedition Structure</strong> — play alternates between Expedition (going out into the dangerous world) and Homefront (returning to the village, managing relationships, triggering steading moves). The fairly natural split ends up in a somewhat less-strict Forged in the Dark \"downtime/score\" feel, without the same level of mechanical cuts.\n<strong>Playbook Authority</strong> — each of the nine playbooks grants a character genuine authority over an aspect of the game world. The Blessed is the primary authority on the worship of Danu, the Earthmother. The Judge is the authority on ancient law and history. The Seeker handles the arcane remnants of the Makers. Players don't just play characters — they steward sections of the setting.\n<strong>The Nine Playbooks:</strong> Heavy (warrior), Marshal (leader of followers), Ranger (wilderness expert), Blessed (devotee of a god), Lightbearer (divine light priest), Would-Be Hero (hero in training), Fox (cunning and social), Judge (authority on law and truth), Seeker (scholar of the Makers' arcana).\n<strong>Seasonal Moves</strong> — the Spring Breaks Forth move opens each new season: the most hopeful character rolls and the result frames what opportunities and threats face Stonetop for the coming season. On a 10+ the season opens with opportunity; on a 7–9 an opportunity appears but a threat to the steading makes itself known; on a 6– threats abound. This makes seasonal transitions mechanically consequential rather than just narrative summaries.\n<h2>The Setting: Hearth Fantasy</h2>\n<p>Strandberg calls the tone \"hearth fantasy.\" The setting looks at first like Celtic-flavoured Iron Age — spears instead of swords, cloth instead of plate, pre-feudal society, low magic. But just below the surface sits something stranger: the Makers, four ancient advanced civilizations now long gone, left behind what looks like lost technology. The village of Stonetop is built around a massive standing stone of unknown origin, carved with faint runes, that pulls lightning from the sky during storms.</p>\n<p>Rather than offering canonical answers about the world, what you get are lists of options for the \"truth\" behind elements of your own version of the game. The anti-canon approach means each group's Stonetop is genuinely distinct.</p>\n<h2>The Books</h2>\n<p>The two books ended up at approximately 600 pages each — roughly twice the originally estimated 300 pages per book. Book I: Stonetop includes the rules and extensive actionable guidance on how to run the game. Book II: The Wider World and Other Wonders is the setting guide — a resource to exploit and pick from, with intentional blanks and tools to help each group make their version of Stonetop unique.</p>\n<p>Book I includes probably the best fantasy PbtA GMing advice available — worth the price by itself. Book II is outstanding in how easy it is to find things, read quickly, and refer to at the table.</p>\n<h2>Publication History</h2>\n<p>Strandberg has been developing Stonetop since 2013, when it began as a play setting for Dungeon World with enhanced steading management rules. The Kickstarter launched March 2021 with a target delivery of October 2021; the game spent several additional years in polishing and completion. Strandberg dramatically underestimated the work required while also holding down a demanding full-time job — and then chose not to reduce scope, because the high bar already set by existing materials meant cutting content would have left the game feeling incomplete. Strandberg also had a heart attack during development. Physical books are now entering final production.</p>\n<h2>Design Lineage</h2>\n<p>Stonetop sits in the Dungeon World branch of the PbtA family, downstream of Sage LaTorra and Adam Koebel's Dungeon World (2012), which was itself heavily influenced by Jason Lutes' The Perilous Wilds supplement. Strandberg collaborated with Lutes on The Perilous Wilds before embarking on Stonetop. The game diverges from Dungeon World substantially enough to be clearly its own system — the base moves are updated, the gear system is redesigned, the follower rules are new, and the steading mechanics are entirely Strandberg's.</p>\n<p>The game's roots go back further: Strandberg's home D&D campaign circa the late 2000s was played in 4e, and the \"Points of Light\" worldbuilding ethos of the 4e DMG is visible in Stonetop's premise — before transitioning to Dungeon World once that existed.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: Jeremy Strandberg | Publisher: Lampblack & Brimstone (Jason Lutes)</li>\n<li>Upstream: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dungeon World\">Dungeon World</a> (LaTorra & Koebel) · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Apocalypse World\">Apocalypse World</a> (Baker)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Compare: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Blades in the Dark\">Blades in the Dark</a> (Homefront/Expedition parallel to Downtime/Score) · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Wanderhome\">Wanderhome</a> (community-as-protagonist; different register)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/DD 5th Edition Supplements": {"key": "Games/DD 5th Edition Supplements", "category": "Games", "name": "DD 5th Edition Supplements", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "wotc", "5e"], "links": ["Games/DD 5th Edition", "Games/DD 5th Edition", "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "The SRD5 (2016) placed core 5e rules under OGL, enabling the DMs Guild and the massive third-party publishing ecosystem. The 2024 revision placed core rules under Creative Commons following the OGL crisis.", "html": "<h1>D&D 5e — Key Supplements & Adventures</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #wotc #5e</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Core Rules</h2>\n<ul><li><em>Player's Handbook</em> (2014) — classes, races, spells</li>\n<li><em>Dungeon Master's Guide</em> (2014) — world-building, magic items, optional rules</li>\n<li><em>Monster Manual</em> (2014) — legendary actions, lair actions, regional effects introduced here</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Notable Adventures</h2>\n<ul><li><em>Curse of Strahd</em> (2016) — gothic horror; widely considered best 5e adventure</li>\n<li><em>Tomb of Annihilation</em> (2017) — death curse; high lethality; OSR-adjacent tone</li>\n<li><em>Icewind Dale: Rime of the Frostmaiden</em> (2020) — horror survival</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Setting Books</h2>\n<ul><li><em>Eberron: Rising from the Last War</em> (2019)</li>\n<li><em>Ravenloft</em> (2021)</li>\n<li><em>Spelljammer</em> (2022)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\nThe SRD5 (2016) placed core 5e rules under OGL, enabling the DMs Guild and the massive third-party publishing ecosystem. The 2024 revision placed core rules under Creative Commons following the OGL crisis.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Core game: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 5th Edition\">D&D 5th Edition</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">OGL & Open Licensing</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Wanderhome": {"key": "Games/Wanderhome", "category": "Games", "name": "Wanderhome", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "cozy", "pastoral", "gmless", "owned"], "links": ["People/Jay Dragon", "People/Jay Dragon", "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Concepts/Cozy and Pastoral Play", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2021 | Designer: Jay Dragon | Publisher: Possum Creek Games", "html": "<h1>Wanderhome</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #cozy #pastoral #gmless #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2021 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jay Dragon\">Jay Dragon</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Possum Creek Games\n<blockquote>⭐ <strong>You own this game.</strong></blockquote>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A pastoral game about animal travellers moving through Haeth — a world recovering from a war that is over. Characters travel between settlements, share meals, rest, help people with their work, and say goodbye. No combat. No experience points. No conventional advancement.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>The most complete realization of the cozy wave's aesthetic ambitions. Demonstrated that mechanical design could serve rest and beauty as precisely as conflict. The token economy (shared pool, spending tokens to invoke moves) creates gentle pacing structure without urgency. The absence of violence doesn't make play stake-free — the stakes are relational and aesthetic, and players invest in them genuinely.</p>\n<h2>Key Mechanics</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Token economy</strong> — shared resource creating collective investment; generosity is mechanically productive</li>\n<li><strong>Moves as prompts for attention</strong> — arriving somewhere, sharing a meal, saying goodbye; each invokes specific imaginative attention rather than adjudicating success</li>\n<li><strong>Natures</strong> — character descriptors (steadfast, curious, mournful) with distinct moves attached</li>\n<li><strong>Haeths</strong> — locations as characters with detailed generation tools; place-as-participant in fiction</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Design Note</h2>\nRead Dragon's public design document about Wanderhome alongside the game — it articulates the cozy wave's philosophy more directly than the game text.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jay Dragon\">Jay Dragon</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Cozy and Pastoral Play\">Cozy & Pastoral Play</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Labyrinth Lord": {"key": "Games/Labyrinth Lord", "category": "Games", "name": "Labyrinth Lord", "tags": ["game", "osr", "retroclone"], "links": ["People/Daniel Proctor", "People/Daniel Proctor", "Concepts/Retroclones", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2007 | Designer: Daniel Proctor | Publisher: Goblinoid Games | System: B/X clone", "html": "<h1>Labyrinth Lord</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #retroclone</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2007 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Daniel Proctor\">Daniel Proctor</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Goblinoid Games | <strong>System:</strong> B/X clone\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A clean, complete retroclone of B/X D&D. Became the dominant publishing platform for early OSR adventure modules due to its clarity, completeness, and ease of writing for.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Practically the most influential first-generation clone. While OSRIC was infrastructure and Basic Fantasy was ethos, Labyrinth Lord was the game OSR publishers actually used. A huge proportion of early OSR adventures are written for or compatible with LL.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Daniel Proctor\">Daniel Proctor</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Retroclones\">Retroclones</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Lamentations of the Flame Princess": {"key": "Games/Lamentations of the Flame Princess", "category": "Games", "name": "Lamentations of the Flame Princess", "tags": ["game", "osr", "weird", "horror"], "links": ["People/James Raggi", "Publishers/Lamentations of the Flame Princess", "People/James Raggi", "Publishers/Lamentations of the Flame Princess", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "A B/X-adjacent OSR game pushing toward weird fiction, horror, and high lethality. Mechanically conservative (close to B/X) but aesthetically radical. Published lavishly produced hardcovers and adventure modules commissioning outside writers and artists.", "html": "<h1>Lamentations of the Flame Princess</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #weird #horror</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2010 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/James Raggi\">James Raggi</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Lamentations of the Flame Princess\">LotFP</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A B/X-adjacent OSR game pushing toward weird fiction, horror, and high lethality. Mechanically conservative (close to B/X) but aesthetically radical. Published lavishly produced hardcovers and adventure modules commissioning outside writers and artists.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Elevated OSR aesthetic ambition. Demonstrated that the OSR could be a vehicle for literary and artistic seriousness, not just nostalgia. Its adventure line includes genuine classics (A Red and Pleasant Land, Qelong, Veins of the Earth) alongside controversial work.</p>\n<h2>Notable Adventures</h2>\n<ul><li><em>Death Frost Doom</em> — horror dungeon; Raggi</li>\n<li><em>A Red and Pleasant Land</em> — Zak Smith; Alice-in-Wonderland horror; ENnie winner</li>\n<li><em>Qelong</em> — Kenneth Hite; Vietnam War fantasy</li>\n<li><em>Veins of the Earth</em> — Patrick Stuart & Scrap Princess; underground ecology horror</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/James Raggi\">James Raggi</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Lamentations of the Flame Princess\">Lamentations of the Flame Princess</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Never Going Home": {"key": "Games/Never Going Home", "category": "Games", "name": "Never Going Home", "tags": ["game", "horror", "wwi", "crossover", "cards", "owned"], "links": ["Publishers/Wet Ink Games", "Concepts/+One System", "Publishers/Wet Ink Games", "Concepts/+One System", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "crossover", "summary": "Year: 2019 | Designer: Irvin Jackson (writer), Brandon K. Aten (system)\nPublisher: Wet Ink Games | System: +One System\nAwards: ENNIE-nominated Best Art 2020", "html": "<h1>Never Going Home</h1>\n<p>#game #horror #wwi #crossover #cards #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2019 | <strong>Designer:</strong> Irvin Jackson (writer), Brandon K. Aten (system) <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wet Ink Games\">Wet Ink Games</a> | <strong>System:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/+One System\">+One System</a> <strong>Awards:</strong> ENNIE-nominated Best Art 2020\n<blockquote>⭐ <strong>You own this game.</strong></blockquote>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>An eldritch horror RPG set in the trenches of the First World War, 1916–1918. The Veil between worlds has been torn open by the slaughter of industrialized warfare, and alien entities called Whispers have crept through. Some soldiers have listened to the Whispers and gained arcane powers — at the cost of their humanity. Others have mutated beyond recognition. War consumes the days and monsters stalk the nights. Not even dreams are safe.</p>\n<p>Characters are soldiers in a Unit — the Unit itself is the campaign protagonist, not individual characters, who are quick to create and expected to die or go mad regularly.</p>\n<h2>Key Mechanics</h2>\n<strong>The card hand as deteriorating psychology</strong> — players manage a hand of cards representing mental and emotional resources. Cards can be played for in-game bonuses. When discarding, the player describes what part of themselves they're losing to corruption — a memory, a value, a piece of identity. As the hand depletes, the character deteriorates. The mechanic is elegant because it makes psychological erosion a player-authored process rather than something that happens to the character.\n<strong>The Unit as protagonist</strong> — individual characters depart regularly through death or madness; the Unit continues. This structure produces the feeling of WWI fiction better than any character-survival approach could — the individual is temporary; the collective struggle persists.\n<strong>d6 success-counting</strong> — 5 or 6 on each die is a success; Attributes allow manipulation of results before and after rolling.\n<strong>Magic Paths</strong> (6 core paths) — different ways of having listened to the Whispers, each with distinct powers and a distinct trajectory of corruption.\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Demonstrates that the crossover space doesn't require European folklore or D&D aesthetics — an unusual historical setting handled with genuine craft can find a real audience. The WWI setting also places the game in a conversation about what horror RPGs can actually be <em>about</em>: not just genre mood, but historical weight, systemic violence, and the cost of war on people. The ENNIE nomination for Best Art signaled the broader community's attention.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wet Ink Games\">Wet Ink Games</a></li>\n<li>System: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/+One System\">+One System</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Compare: <em>Delta Green</em> (modern horror with systemic weight) · <em>Mothership</em> (sci-fi horror; also uses real-time resource deterioration)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Be Like a Crow": {"key": "Games/Be Like a Crow", "category": "Games", "name": "Be Like a Crow", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "solo", "journaling", "nature", "owned"], "links": ["Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Movements/Solo TTRPG Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2021 | Designer: Fly Casual Games | Price: Pay-what-you-want", "html": "<h1>Be Like a Crow</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #solo #journaling #nature #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2021 | <strong>Designer:</strong> Fly Casual Games | <strong>Price:</strong> Pay-what-you-want\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A solo journaling game in which you play a crow — observing the world, collecting objects, remembering things, navigating the seasons. No conflict, no advancement, no conventional goal structure. You are a crow doing crow things across a year of seasons.</p>\n<h2>Why It's Interesting</h2>\n<p>A quiet member of the cozy/solo wave that takes the \"perspective shift\" design approach seriously — the experience of playing a non-human creature who has non-human priorities changes the texture of fictional attention in genuinely interesting ways. Related to Wanderhome's commitment to specificity of place and the pastoral wave's rejection of combat as the default mode of significance.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Solo TTRPG Design\">Solo TTRPG Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Star Crossed": {"key": "Games/Star Crossed", "category": "Games", "name": "Star Crossed", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "cozy", "twoplayer", "jenga"], "links": ["People/Alex Roberts", "People/Alex Roberts", "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2019 | Designers: Alex Roberts, Beau Jágr Sheldon | Publisher: Bully Pulpit Games", "html": "<h1>Star Crossed</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #cozy #twoplayer #jenga</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2019 | <strong>Designers:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Alex Roberts\">Alex Roberts</a>, Beau Jágr Sheldon | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Bully Pulpit Games\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A two-player game about characters who are attracted to each other but shouldn't act on it. Uses a Jenga tower as its central mechanic. Removing blocks represents the tension of maintaining appropriate distance; the tower's fall represents the moment when the characters can no longer resist.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>One of the most elegant examples of embodied mechanics — the physical tension of carefully removing Jenga blocks mirrors the fictional tension of maintaining emotional distance. Established two-player romantic play as a specific design category. The physical object makes the game's stakes viscerally present.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designers: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Alex Roberts\">Alex Roberts</a>, Beau Jágr Sheldon</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Agon": {"key": "Games/Agon", "category": "Games", "name": "Agon", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "competitive", "greek", "harper"], "links": ["People/John Harper", "People/John Harper", "Movements/Story Games & Indie", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2006 (revised 2019, with Sean Nittner) | Designer: John Harper", "html": "<h1>Agon</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #competitive #greek #harper</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2006 (revised 2019, with Sean Nittner) | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A game about Greek heroes competing for glory while serving the gods. The central innovation is a competitive structure between player characters: heroes cooperate against external threats but compete with each other for glory, and the mechanics support both simultaneously.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Part of Harper's pre-Blades catalog demonstrating his long engagement with resource management as dramatic tension. The cooperation/competition tension is built into the mechanics rather than emerging accidentally. The 2019 revision with Sean Nittner substantially refined the original.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Story Games & Indie\">Story Games</a> (pre-PbtA)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a> (revised)</li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Thousand Year Old Vampire": {"key": "Games/Thousand Year Old Vampire", "category": "Games", "name": "Thousand Year Old Vampire", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "solo", "journaling", "horror"], "links": ["People/Tim Hutchings", "People/Tim Hutchings", "Movements/Solo TTRPG Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "A solo journaling game about a vampire across centuries of existence. Characters begin their life, make connections, have experiences, and eventually forget most of what has happened to them as centuries accumulate. Prompted by cards and dice; played in a journal.", "html": "<h1>Thousand Year Old Vampire</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #solo #journaling #horror</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2019 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Tim Hutchings\">Tim Hutchings</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A solo journaling game about a vampire across centuries of existence. Characters begin their life, make connections, have experiences, and eventually forget most of what has happened to them as centuries accumulate. Prompted by cards and dice; played in a journal.</p>\n<h2>The Forgetting Mechanic</h2>\n<p>Characters have a limited number of memory slots. Gaining new memories requires erasing old ones. As the vampire accumulates centuries, they lose most of what has happened. This produces profound melancholy without any violent encounter — demonstrating that loss and grief can drive TTRPG play without combat.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Demonstrated that solo play could explore emotional registers — loss, grief, the weight of time — unavailable in most group TTRPG designs. One of the most emotionally affecting mechanics in recent TTRPG design despite extremely simple resolution.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Tim Hutchings\">Tim Hutchings</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Solo TTRPG Design\">Solo TTRPG Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Dogs in the Vineyard": {"key": "Games/Dogs in the Vineyard", "category": "Games", "name": "Dogs in the Vineyard", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "forge", "indie", "moral"], "links": ["People/Vincent Baker", "People/Vincent Baker", "Publishers/lumpley games", "Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2004 | Designer: Vincent Baker | Publisher: lumpley games", "html": "<h1>Dogs in the Vineyard</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #forge #indie #moral</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2004 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> lumpley games\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>Players are God's Watchdogs — young enforcers of religious law in a fantasy Mormon frontier. The game's conflict resolution system escalates through verbal argument → physical intimidation → fighting → shooting, with meaningful stakes at each level. About moral authority: who has it, and what it costs to use it.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>A pre-PbtA high watermark of indie design. Dogs in the Vineyard demonstrated that game mechanics could be built around a specific moral and thematic question rather than around genre trappings. Enormously influential on what became PbtA.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/lumpley games\">lumpley games</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory\">The Forge</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Apocalypse World": {"key": "Games/Apocalypse World", "category": "Games", "name": "Apocalypse World", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "origin"], "links": ["People/Vincent Baker", "People/Meguey Baker", "Publishers/lumpley games", "Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)", "People/Vincent Baker", "People/Meguey Baker", "Publishers/lumpley games", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2010 (2nd ed. 2016) | Designers: Vincent Baker, Meguey Baker | Publisher: lumpley games", "html": "<h1>Apocalypse World</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #origin</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2010 (2nd ed. 2016) | <strong>Designers:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a>, <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Meguey Baker\">Meguey Baker</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/lumpley games\">lumpley games</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A post-apocalyptic RPG and the origin of the PbtA family. Characters are archetypes (the Hardholder, the Battlebabe, the Skinner) in a violent, resource-scarce world. The MC (GM) never rolls dice — only players do. The MC's job is to \"play to find out what happens.\"</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>The most influential indie RPG of the 2010s. Apocalypse World introduced Moves as a design concept — discrete, triggered fictional actions with specific mechanical outcomes — and a GM philosophy that was reactive, improvisational, and player-forward. Every PbtA game is a conversation with this text.</p>\n<h2>Key Innovations</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Moves</strong> — triggered by fiction, produce mechanical outcomes: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)\">Moves</a></li>\n<li><strong>2d6+stat</strong> — unified resolution; 10+ strong hit, 7-9 partial hit, 6- miss</li>\n<li><strong>Playbooks</strong> — pre-structured character archetypes with move lists</li>\n<li><strong>MC Principles</strong> — explicit list of how the GM should behave</li>\n<li><strong>\"Play to find out\"</strong> — the MC does not plan outcomes</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designers: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Meguey Baker\">Meguey Baker</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/lumpley games\">lumpley games</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)\">Moves</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Cyberpunk Red": {"key": "Games/Cyberpunk Red", "category": "Games", "name": "Cyberpunk Red", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "cyberpunk", "scifi", "owned"], "links": ["Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 2020 | Designer: Mike Pondsmith | Publisher: R. Talsorian Games", "html": "<h1>Cyberpunk Red</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #cyberpunk #scifi #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2020 | <strong>Designer:</strong> Mike Pondsmith | <strong>Publisher:</strong> R. Talsorian Games\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>The fourth edition of Mike Pondsmith's Cyberpunk RPG, set in 2045 — the \"Time of the Red,\" after the collapse of the NET following catastrophic nuclear explosions triggered by Arasaka and Militech. The direct prequel era to the video game Cyberpunk 2077. Streamlined from Cyberpunk 2020 while retaining its gritty, chrome-and-neon aesthetic.</p>\n<h2>Mike Pondsmith's Significance</h2>\n<p>Pondsmith is one of the most important non-D&D designers in TTRPG history. His original Cyberpunk (1988) established the tabletop cyberpunk genre and was enormously influential on how the aesthetic translates to RPG mechanics. R. Talsorian Games — his company — also produced the original Castle Falkenstein and the Interlock system used across multiple games. The Cyberpunk IP has crossed over into mainstream gaming culture through the Cyberpunk 2077 video game, bringing significant new audiences to the TTRPG.</p>\n<h2>Design Notes</h2>\n<p>Uses the Interlock system — roll a d10 plus a relevant stat plus a skill level against a difficulty target. The system rewards specialization; characters are built around specific roles (Rockerboy, Solo, Netrunner, Tech, Medtech, Media, Exec, Lawman, Fixer, Nomad) that define their primary capabilities.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: Mike Pondsmith | Publisher: R. Talsorian Games</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Monster of the Week": {"key": "Games/Monster of the Week", "category": "Games", "name": "Monster of the Week", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "horror", "urban", "played", "owned"], "links": ["Games/Brindlewood Bay", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Games/Brindlewood Bay", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2012 (revised 2015; hardcover 2022) | Designer: Michael Sands (NZ)\nPublisher: Evil Hat Productions | System: PbtA", "html": "<h1>Monster of the Week</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #horror #urban-fantasy #played #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2012 (revised 2015; hardcover 2022) | <strong>Designer:</strong> Michael Sands (NZ) <strong>Publisher:</strong> Evil Hat Productions | <strong>System:</strong> PbtA\n<blockquote>⭐ <strong>You have played this game. You own this game.</strong></blockquote>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A PbtA game about monster hunters investigating and confronting supernatural threats — modeled on episodic television like Buffy the Vampire Slayer, Supernatural, and The X-Files. Players choose hunter playbooks (The Chosen, The Expert, The Flake, The Spooky, The Wronged, etc.) and work together to solve a new monster mystery each session. The Keeper manages the monster and its threat.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>One of the most commercially successful PbtA games ever made. Made PbtA accessible to players coming from horror and urban fantasy TV fandoms rather than game design communities. The episodic mystery structure maps cleanly onto TV pacing in a way that Apocalypse World's open structure doesn't.</p>\n<p>The Moves are calibrated specifically to monster-hunting (Investigate a Mystery, Kick Some Ass, Act Under Pressure, Help Out, Read a Bad Situation, Protect Someone). The Keeper's threats are taxonomized as Monster, Minions, Bystanders, and Locations — a structure that organizes mystery prep without scripting outcomes.</p>\n<h2>The Luck Mechanic</h2>\n<p>Each Hunter has seven Luck points spent to succeed on any roll. When Luck runs out, the Hunter is likely to die or retire. Creates natural character arcs — spending Luck means living on borrowed time — without explicit campaign planning. Produces the TV-show feeling of \"this character has survived things they shouldn't have.\"</p>\n<h2>Relationship to Brindlewood Bay</h2>\n<p>Monster of the Week establishes the Keeper-knows-the-answer mystery structure that <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\">Brindlewood Bay</a> later identified as the core problem to solve. Cordova's Conspiracy mechanic is a direct design response to MotW's predetermined-solution architecture.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: Michael Sands | Publisher: Evil Hat Productions</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Compare: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\">Brindlewood Bay</a> (solves MotW's predetermined-solution problem)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Cosmere RPG": {"key": "Games/Cosmere RPG", "category": "Games", "name": "Cosmere RPG", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "crossover", "licensed", "sanderson"], "links": ["Games/The One Ring 2e", "Games/Vaesen", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Concepts/Licensed Adaptation Design", "Games/The One Ring 2e", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 2025 (Stormlight Archive set) | Publisher: Brotherwise Games\nKickstarter: $15M+ (among the largest in TTRPG history)", "html": "<h1>Cosmere RPG</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #crossover #licensed #sanderson</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2025 (Stormlight Archive set) | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Brotherwise Games <strong>Kickstarter:</strong> $15M+ (among the largest in TTRPG history)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>Licensed adaptation of Brandon Sanderson's Cosmere universe — the interconnected worlds of Stormlight Archive, Mistborn, Elantris, and others. d20-adjacent system. First release covers Stormlight Archive; Mistborn campaign setting planned subsequently.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Primarily significant as a commercial and cultural phenomenon. The $15M+ Kickstarter is among the largest in TTRPG history, demonstrating extraordinary crossover scale when major established IP meets professional production and an author with a devoted gaming-adjacent fanbase.</p>\n<p>As a licensed adaptation case study, the Cosmere's magic systems present a genuine design challenge: each world has a distinct, rule-governed magical framework (Allomancy in Mistborn, Stormlight in Stormlight Archive, etc.). How do you make each setting's magic feel mechanically distinct while using a unified core system? The design solution to this problem is worth studying alongside <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The One Ring 2e\">The One Ring</a> and <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Vaesen\">Vaesen</a> as examples of licensed adaptation design.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Licensed Adaptation Design\">Licensed Adaptation Design</a></li>\n<li>Compare: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The One Ring 2e\">The One Ring 2e</a> (licensed adaptation with deeper design integrity)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Forbidden Lands": {"key": "Games/Forbidden Lands", "category": "Games", "name": "Forbidden Lands", "tags": ["game", "crossover", "osr", "hexcrawl", "freelague"], "links": ["Publishers/Free League Publishing", "Publishers/Free League Publishing", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "A hex-crawl survival fantasy RPG set in a world where a centuries-long Blood Mist has lifted, leaving a dangerous land full of ruins, monsters, and scattered survivors. Characters are adventurers exploring this reclaimed wilderness.", "html": "<h1>Forbidden Lands</h1>\n<p>#game #crossover #osr-adjacent #hexcrawl #freelague</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2018 | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Free League Publishing\">Free League Publishing</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A hex-crawl survival fantasy RPG set in a world where a centuries-long Blood Mist has lifted, leaving a dangerous land full of ruins, monsters, and scattered survivors. Characters are adventurers exploring this reclaimed wilderness.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Forbidden Lands occupies an interesting crossover position between OSR sensibilities (lethality, resource management, hex-crawl exploration) and Free League's production values. It demonstrates that OSR play philosophy can be packaged at mainstream production standards for a broader audience. The stronghold-building mechanics give long-term campaigns structural shape beyond dungeon-delving.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Free League Publishing\">Free League Publishing</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover Scene</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> (adjacent)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Rosewood Abbey": {"key": "Games/Rosewood Abbey", "category": "Games", "name": "Rosewood Abbey", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "mystery", "carvedfrombrindlewood", "owned"], "links": ["People/Kalum", "People/Kalum", "Games/Brindlewood Bay", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2023 | Designer: Kalum (The Rolistes) | Publisher: The Rolistes | Website: [rolistespod.itch.io/rosewood-abbey](https://rolistespod.itch.io/rosewood-abbey)", "html": "<h1>Rosewood Abbey</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #mystery #carvedfrombrindlewood #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2023 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Kalum\">Kalum</a> (The Rolistes) | <strong>Publisher:</strong> The Rolistes | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://rolistespod.itch.io/rosewood-abbey\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">rolistespod.itch.io/rosewood-abbey</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A Carved from Brindlewood (PbtA) mystery game set in a medieval European abbey. Players are Fratres Herodoti — an informal brotherhood of scholars sworn to truth — investigating mysteries at the Abbazia di Palissandro. Inspired by Umberto Eco's <em>The Name of the Rose</em>, its 1986 film adaptation, and the British TV series <em>Cadfael</em>. For 3–6 players (including the Cantor, the GM role).</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>One of the strongest entries in the Carved from Brindlewood family. Key innovations:</p>\n<ul><li><strong>Rumor Mill mechanic</strong> — tracks spreading rumors through the abbey community, simulating how small events become theological crises</li>\n<li><strong>Confabulation Move</strong> — Rosewood Abbey's version of Brindlewood Bay's Theorize move; players construct explanations from clues, and plausible theories become true</li>\n<li><strong>Replay format</strong> — the first half of the book is a Japanese TRPG-inspired play transcript of a full session, making it one of the most accessible introductions to the Carved from Brindlewood system</li>\n</ul>\nThe monastic setting is not merely aesthetic — the tension between reason (the Fratres' oath to truth) and superstition (the abbey's rumor-prone flock) is the game's central dramatic engine.\n<h2>Your Copy</h2>\n<p>Physical copy (B6 tankōbon format, 184 pages). Owned.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Kalum\">Kalum</a></li>\n<li>Parent system: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\">Brindlewood Bay</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic\">The Conspiracy Mechanic</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/The Between": {"key": "Games/The Between", "category": "Games", "name": "The Between", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "mystery", "victorian"], "links": ["People/Jason Cordova", "Publishers/Magpie Games", "Games/Brindlewood Bay", "People/Jason Cordova", "Publishers/Magpie Games", "Games/Brindlewood Bay", "Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2022 | Designer: Jason Cordova | Publisher: Magpie Games", "html": "<h1>The Between</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #mystery #victorian</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2022 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Cordova\">Jason Cordova</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Magpie Games\">Magpie Games</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>Victorian London mystery game — a spiritual successor to <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\">Brindlewood Bay</a>. Players are members of a secret society investigating supernatural threats in fog-shrouded London. Develops the Conspiracy mechanic further with more procedural mystery generation tools.</p>\n<h2>Key Developments over Brindlewood Bay</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>More explicit Conspiracy accumulation</strong> — clearer procedures for how individual session mysteries connect to campaign-level Conspiracy</li>\n<li><strong>Role + Method character system</strong> — Role defines function in the secret society; Method defines investigative approach (Consulting Detective, Hard-Boiled, Amateur Sleuth — drawn from the literary detective tradition)</li>\n<li><strong>Pressure clock</strong> — tracks how close the campaign's larger Conspiracy is to achieving something catastrophic; creates campaign-level urgency</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Cordova\">Jason Cordova</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Magpie Games\">Magpie Games</a></li>\n<li>Predecessor: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\">Brindlewood Bay</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic\">The Conspiracy Mechanic</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Cthulhu Dark": {"key": "Games/Cthulhu Dark", "category": "Games", "name": "Cthulhu Dark", "tags": ["game", "horror", "lovecraft", "minimalist", "storygames", "investigation"], "links": ["People/Graham Walmsley", "People/Graham Walmsley", "Movements/Story Games Lineage MOC", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2010 (4-page pamphlet); 2017 (full book) | Designer: Graham Walmsley\nwith Kathryn Jenkins & Helen Gould | PDF: Free (original version)", "html": "<h1>Cthulhu Dark</h1>\n<p>#game #horror #lovecraft #minimalist #storygames #investigation</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2010 (4-page pamphlet); 2017 (full book) | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Graham Walmsley\">Graham Walmsley</a> with Kathryn Jenkins & Helen Gould | <strong>PDF:</strong> Free (original version)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A rules-light Lovecraftian horror game that began as a 4-page pamphlet and expanded to a 200-page book. The extra pages are not more rules — the mechanics barely changed — but a complete horror GMing manual: how to build mysteries, how to produce horror at the table, how to use the Cthulhu Mythos's thematic structure rather than just its monsters.</p>\n<h2>Core Mechanics</h2>\n<strong>Roll only when needed:</strong> Roll one die if the task is within human capabilities. Add a die if your character concept is relevant. Add a die if you're willing to risk your mind to succeed. Higher rolls find more, but rolling a 6 means you found more than you wanted to know — and your Insight increases.\n<strong>The Insight Track:</strong> Starts at 1. Each time you roll a 6 (or witness something that creeps you out), roll against your current Insight number. Exceed it and your Insight increases by 1. At Insight 6, you lose your mind. The track doesn't just model deterioration; it models the specific Lovecraftian horror of understanding — the more you learn, the closer you are to the edge.\n<strong>Information is never gated:</strong> If you need information to proceed, you find it. The dice tell you how much you learn and at what cost, not whether you succeed. Same insight as GUMSHOE, arrived at independently through different design reasoning.\n<strong>You cannot fight the Mythos:</strong> Attempting to destroy a Mythos creature in combat means your character dies. You can run, delay, or hide. This is mechanically enforced, not advisory.\n<strong>The Failure Die:</strong> If any player thinks the story would be more interesting if the active character failed, they can describe the failure and roll against the active roll. If they beat it, the failure happens as described. This adds collaborative narrative shaping without requiring a GMless framework.\n<h2>Power and Class</h2>\n<p>A deliberate design choice: Cthulhu Dark's settings cast players as people with little social power investigating horror at the heart of power. London 1851: thieves and slum dwellers. Arkham 1692: people accused of witchcraft. Jaiwo 2017: ordinary residents of a contemporary African city. The usual Cthulhu setup — wealthy professionals investigating exotic locations — is explicitly reversed.</p>\n<h2>The Horror GMing Manual</h2>\n<p>The 2017 expansion's most valuable content isn't the additional mechanics but the design writing: how to construct mysteries that produce genuine horror, how to use Creeping Horrors (recurring inexplicable imagery distributed across an adventure to produce accumulated unease rather than punctual shocks), how to write from themes you actually find frightening rather than genre conventions.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Graham Walmsley\">Graham Walmsley</a></li>\n<li>Compare: <em>Call of Cthulhu</em> (investigation + sanity; heavier system) · <em>Delta Green</em> (modern horror; you own this) · <em>Night's Black Agents</em> (GUMSHOE spy horror; you own this)</li>\n<li>Inspired by: Ron Edwards' Sorcerer (die mechanics) · GUMSHOE (information philosophy)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Story Games Lineage MOC\">Story Games & Indie</a> (adjacent)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Pathfinder 2e": {"key": "Games/Pathfinder 2e", "category": "Games", "name": "Pathfinder 2e", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "paizo"], "links": ["Publishers/Paizo", "Publishers/Paizo", "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023", "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "A ground-up rebuild of Pathfinder's d20 system. Three-action economy, ancestry/background/class character creation, degrees of success (critical success/success/failure/critical failure), and a more modular design than PF1.", "html": "<h1>Pathfinder 2nd Edition</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #paizo</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2019 | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Paizo\">Paizo</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A ground-up rebuild of Pathfinder's d20 system. Three-action economy, ancestry/background/class character creation, degrees of success (critical success/success/failure/critical failure), and a more modular design than PF1.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Already a strong D&D alternative before the OGL crisis, PF2e saw major adoption spikes in 2023 when the crisis drove publishers and players away from WotC. Paizo also led the development of the ORC License — a genuinely system-neutral open license — making PF2e the natural home for publishers seeking a WotC-independent ecosystem.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Paizo\">Paizo</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OGL Crisis 2023\">OGL Crisis 2023</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">OGL & ORC License</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Brindlewood Bay": {"key": "Games/Brindlewood Bay", "category": "Games", "name": "Brindlewood Bay", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "mystery", "played", "keeper"], "links": ["People/Jason Cordova", "Publishers/Magpie Games", "Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic", "People/Jason Cordova", "Publishers/Magpie Games", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic", "Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)", "Games/The Between", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2020 | Designer: Jason Cordova | Publisher: Magpie Games", "html": "<h1>Brindlewood Bay</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #mystery #played #keeper</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2020 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Cordova\">Jason Cordova</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Magpie Games\">Magpie Games</a>\n<blockquote>⭐ <strong>You GM / Keeper this game.</strong></blockquote>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A PbtA mystery game in which a group of elderly women (the Maven Club) solve murders in a small coastal New England town — while slowly uncovering a deeper Lovecraftian conspiracy. Players are the mavens; the Keeper runs the town, NPCs, and Conspiracy.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Introduced the <strong>Conspiracy mechanic</strong> — the mystery's ultimate answer is not predetermined by the Keeper but generated collaboratively at the table from clues assembled during play. Solves the core tension of mystery RPGs: the GM knowing the answer creates information asymmetry that can feel like a gotcha.</p>\n<h2>Key Design Innovations</h2>\n<h3>The Conspiracy Mechanic</h3>\n<ul><li>Keeper prepares clues but not solutions</li>\n<li>Players assemble clues into theories during the Theorize move</li>\n<li>The Conspiracy is confirmed/revealed through collective interpretation</li>\n<li>Meaning: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic\">The Conspiracy Mechanic</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Maven Moves</h3>\n<ul><li>Moves built around the mavens' specific social and investigative competencies</li>\n<li>Sharp observation, social connection, community knowledge</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>The Keeper's Role</h3>\n<ul><li>Keeper plays the town as a living entity</li>\n<li>Mystery structure is loose and emergent</li>\n<li>Adjacent to PbtA MC principles but with distinct mystery-play focus</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Cordova\">Jason Cordova</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Magpie Games\">Magpie Games</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic\">The Conspiracy Mechanic</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)\">Moves</a></li>\n<li>Successor: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Between\">The Between</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Scum and Villainy": {"key": "Games/Scum and Villainy", "category": "Games", "name": "Scum and Villainy", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "fitD", "scifi", "spaceOpera"], "links": ["People/Stras Acimovic and John LeBoeuf-Little", "People/Stras Acimovic and John LeBoeuf-Little", "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family", "Games/Blades in the Dark", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "FitD applied to space opera — specifically the Firefly/Star Wars found-family outlaws mode. A crew of scoundrels navigates an empire's reach while pursuing their own goals.", "html": "<h1>Scum and Villainy</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #fitD #scifi #spaceOpera</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2018 | <strong>Designers:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Stras Acimovic and John LeBoeuf-Little\">Stras Acimovic, John LeBoeuf-Little</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>FitD applied to space opera — specifically the Firefly/Star Wars found-family outlaws mode. A crew of scoundrels navigates an empire's reach while pursuing their own goals.</p>\n<h2>Key Innovation: The Ship as Crew Member</h2>\n<p>The ship has its own mechanical sheet with stress track, abilities, and advancement. It's a crew member in game terms, not just a vehicle. The crew cares for the ship mechanically, and the ship's condition affects what the crew can do.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designers: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Stras Acimovic and John LeBoeuf-Little\">Acimovic & LeBoeuf-Little</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Forged in the Dark Family\">Forged in the Dark Family</a></li>\n<li>Origin: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Blades in the Dark\">Blades in the Dark</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/DD 5th Edition": {"key": "Games/DD 5th Edition", "category": "Games", "name": "DD 5th Edition", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "wotc", "massmarket"], "links": ["People/Mike Mearls", "People/Jeremy Crawford", "Publishers/Wizards of the Coast", "People/Mike Mearls", "People/Jeremy Crawford", "Publishers/Wizards of the Coast", "Movements/Actual Play Boom", "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 2014 | Designers: Mike Mearls, Jeremy Crawford | Publisher: WotC", "html": "<h1>D&D 5th Edition</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #wotc #massmarket</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2014 | <strong>Designers:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Mike Mearls\">Mike Mearls</a>, <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeremy Crawford\">Jeremy Crawford</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wizards of the Coast\">WotC</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>WotC's \"big tent\" edition — designed to appeal to 3e fans, 4e fans, and old-school fans simultaneously. Simplified from 3e, more narrative than 4e, with bounded accuracy math and advantage/disadvantage as a core mechanic.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>The most commercially successful TTRPG in history. Drove the mass mainstream revival of TTRPGs, amplified enormously by Critical Role and the actual play boom. The DMs Guild and OGL ecosystem around 5e created the largest third-party TTRPG publishing market ever — until the 2023 OGL crisis.</p>\n<h2>Design Notes</h2>\n<ul><li>Advantage/disadvantage replaces situational modifiers</li>\n<li>Bounded accuracy (monster AC doesn't scale as hard)</li>\n<li>Proficiency bonus as unified scaling mechanic</li>\n<li>Action economy simplified from 4e</li>\n<li>Short and long rest recovery structure</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designers: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Mike Mearls\">Mike Mearls</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeremy Crawford\">Jeremy Crawford</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wizards of the Coast\">WotC</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Actual Play Boom\">Actual Play Boom</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OGL Crisis 2023\">OGL Crisis</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/OSRIC": {"key": "Games/OSRIC", "category": "Games", "name": "OSRIC", "tags": ["game", "osr", "retroclone"], "links": ["People/Matt Finch", "People/Stuart Marshall", "People/Matt Finch", "People/Stuart Marshall", "Concepts/Retroclones", "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2006 | Designers: Matt Finch, Stuart Marshall | System: AD&D 1e clone", "html": "<h1>OSRIC</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #retroclone</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2006 | <strong>Designers:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a>, <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Stuart Marshall\">Stuart Marshall</a> | <strong>System:</strong> AD&D 1e clone\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>Old School Reference and Index Compilation. The first major retroclone — designed explicitly as a legal vehicle to allow third-party publishers to write AD&D 1e-compatible adventures without copyright risk. Dry and reference-heavy by design; it was infrastructure, not a reading experience.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>OSRIC proved the retroclone concept was legally viable. It answered the question: can you restate AD&D's mechanics in new text under the OGL? Yes. Everything else followed.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designers: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Stuart Marshall\">Stuart Marshall</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Retroclones\">Retroclones</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">OGL</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Under Hollow Hills": {"key": "Games/Under Hollow Hills", "category": "Games", "name": "Under Hollow Hills", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "fairy", "cozy", "owned"], "links": ["People/Vincent Baker", "People/Vincent Baker", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2021 | Designer: Vincent Baker | Publisher: lumpley games", "html": "<h1>Under Hollow Hills</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #fairy #cozy #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2021 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> lumpley games\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A PbtA game by Vincent Baker about a traveling faerie circus — characters are performers who wander between the mortal world and the lands of fairy, playing for human and inhuman audiences, navigating fairy politics, and making their way. Tonally warm and strange; closer to the cozy wave than to Apocalypse World's register.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Significant as Baker's own post-AW game — demonstrating how far PbtA's move structure can travel from its origins. Under Hollow Hills uses the framework for something gentle, aesthetically lush, and explicitly community-focused (the circus is the community protagonist). Shows Baker moving toward a more nurturing design register than AW's.</p>\n<p>The GM equivalent here has a more collaborative, generative function than AW's MC, reflecting the softer stakes and warmer tone. Worth reading alongside AW to see how the same designer reconfigures the same framework for a completely different emotional register.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: lumpley games</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a> (adjacent)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Mythic Bastionland": {"key": "Games/Mythic Bastionland", "category": "Games", "name": "Mythic Bastionland", "tags": ["game", "osr", "ruleslight", "arthurian", "hexcrawl", "domain", "uk"], "links": ["People/Chris McDowall", "People/Chris McDowall", "Games/Into the Odd", "Games/Electric Bastionland", "Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2024 | Designer: Chris McDowall | Publisher: Bastionland Press\nIllustrator: Alec Sorensen", "html": "<h1>Mythic Bastionland</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #ruleslight #arthurian #hexcrawl #domain #uk</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2024 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris McDowall\">Chris McDowall</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Bastionland Press <strong>Illustrator:</strong> Alec Sorensen\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>The third Bastionland game — set in the imagined past of Into the Odd and Electric Bastionland. Knights hunt Myths across a hex-mapped realm of British folklore and Arthurian legend. Uses the stripped ItO chassis but adds significant tactical texture, a Myth/Omen campaign engine, domain play, and the Glory advancement system.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Proves McDowall's minimalist chassis can support full campaign play with domain management, social advancement, and a defined arc — without becoming complicated. The most mechanically ambitious game he has designed while remaining rule-light. The Sites mechanic has propagated beyond the game as a portable location design tool used across many systems.</p>\n<p>Grant Howitt: \"a victory lap.\"</p>\n<h2>Key Mechanics</h2>\n<strong>No to-hit roll</strong> — retained from ItO. Roll straight to damage.\n<strong>Gambits</strong> — tactical combat maneuvers (push, splinter shields, drag from steed, reposition). Texture without overhead.\n<strong>Feats</strong> — Smite (extra damage), Focus (perfect maneuver), Deny (cancel strongest incoming attack).\n<strong>Three Virtues</strong> — Vigour (body), Clarity (mind), Spirit (soul). Each requires different fictional conditions to restore: Clarity needs a Seer, Spirit needs celebration or ritual, Vigour needs rest in safety.\n<strong>Myths</strong> — six per realm, placed in distant hexes. Living threats that escalate independently. Players find them through Omens, Seers, dreams.\n<strong>Omens</strong> — story beats that reveal and escalate Myths. Ignore a Myth and it deteriorates: a lost temple becomes a plague source becomes the throne of a new god.\n<strong>Glory</strong> — advancement. Doesn't make Knights more powerful; gradually opens social positions (army command, court seat, ruling a holding). Campaign arc: the City Quest.\n<strong>Sites</strong> — three points of interest, two to four challenges, one goal, one secret. Works for dungeons, city blocks, social networks, investigation challenges, battlefield layouts. Described by the community as among the most powerful portable location design tools in recent TTRPG design.\n<h2>Literary Sources</h2>\nPrince Valiant · Excalibur (1981) · Pendragon (RPG, 1985) · The Green Knight (2021) · Elden Ring (2022)\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris McDowall\">Chris McDowall</a></li>\n<li>Lineage: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Into the Odd\">Into the Odd</a> → <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Electric Bastionland\">Electric Bastionland</a> → Mythic Bastionland</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design\">Post-OSR & Minimalist Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Level Up Advanced 5e": {"key": "Games/Level Up Advanced 5e", "category": "Games", "name": "Level Up Advanced 5e", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "crossover", "5e"], "links": ["Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Games/DD 5th Edition", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "A more mechanically complex take on D&D 5e — adding depth to skills, exploration, and combat without abandoning 5e compatibility. More choices for characters; more developed wilderness and dungeon exploration procedures; more tactical combat texture.", "html": "<h1>Level Up: Advanced 5th Edition</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #crossover #5e</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2022 | <strong>Publisher:</strong> EN Publishing\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A more mechanically complex take on D&D 5e — adding depth to skills, exploration, and combat without abandoning 5e compatibility. More choices for characters; more developed wilderness and dungeon exploration procedures; more tactical combat texture.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Makes visible what 5e deliberately simplified. Comparing Level Up's design to 5e shows exactly where Mearls and Crawford made accessibility tradeoffs. Notable for OSR-adjacent exploration procedures applied to a 5e chassis — a genuine crossover hybrid.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Related: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 5th Edition\">D&D 5th Edition</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Alien RPG": {"key": "Games/Alien RPG", "category": "Games", "name": "Alien RPG", "tags": ["game", "crossover", "scifi", "horror", "licensed"], "links": ["People/Francesco Nepitello", "Publishers/Free League Publishing", "People/Francesco Nepitello", "Publishers/Free League Publishing", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "crossover", "summary": "Year: 2019 | Designer: Francesco Nepitello | Publisher: Free League Publishing", "html": "<h1>Alien RPG</h1>\n<p>#game #crossover #scifi #horror #licensed</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2019 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Francesco Nepitello\">Francesco Nepitello</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Free League Publishing\">Free League Publishing</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>The official TTRPG adaptation of the Alien franchise. Two play modes: Cinematic (tightly structured, high-lethality one-shots following the structure of Alien films) and Campaign (ongoing play for crew members navigating the frontier).</p>\n<h2>Key Mechanic: Stress</h2>\n<p>The Stress system is the game's central innovation. Characters accumulate Stress dice that add to their die pools — more stress means higher chance of success but also higher chance of triggering Panic, which has table-affecting consequences. This precisely translates the franchise's core dynamic: desperation makes characters more capable but also more likely to do something catastrophically wrong.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>The Stress mechanic is a design-from-content solution to science fiction horror. It avoids the standard horror RPG problem (competent characters aren't scared) by making stress mechanically productive rather than purely harmful.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Francesco Nepitello\">Francesco Nepitello</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Free League Publishing\">Free League Publishing</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover Scene</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Blades in the Dark": {"key": "Games/Blades in the Dark", "category": "Games", "name": "Blades in the Dark", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "fitD", "origin"], "links": ["People/John Harper", "People/John Harper", "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family", "Concepts/Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)", "Games/Spire The City Must Fall", "Games/Heart The City Beneath", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2017 | Designer: John Harper | Publisher: One Seven Design / Evil Hat", "html": "<h1>Blades in the Dark</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #fitD #origin</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2017 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> One Seven Design / Evil Hat\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A heist RPG about a crew of scoundrels in a haunted industrial city (Duskwall). Characters plan and execute scores (heists), manage their crew's reputation and territory, and deal with downtime between jobs. Resolution uses dice pools with position and effect replacing simple success/failure.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>The origin of the Forged in the Dark family. Blades introduced several genuine design innovations that spawned their own games: <ul><li><strong>Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)</strong> — replaces pass/fail with a two-axis outcome system</li> <li><strong>Flashbacks</strong> — players can declare \"I prepared for this\" mid-scene; pay stress</li> <li><strong>Clocks</strong> — progress trackers for threats and projects</li> <li><strong>Crew meta-game</strong> — faction relationships and territory at group level</li> <li><strong>Downtime</strong> — structured between-score recovery and advancement</li> </ul> The FitD license has enabled dozens of games in the family.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Forged in the Dark Family\">Forged in the Dark Family</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)\">Clocks & Position/Effect</a></li>\n<li>Influenced: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\">Spire</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Heart The City Beneath\">Heart</a> · many others</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Mork Borg": {"key": "Games/Mork Borg", "category": "Games", "name": "Mork Borg", "tags": ["game", "osr", "artgame", "aesthetic"], "links": ["Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2019 | Designers: Pelle Tøgersen, Johan Nohr | Publisher: Free League", "html": "<h1>Mörk Borg</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #artgame #aesthetic</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2019 | <strong>Designers:</strong> Pelle Tøgersen, Johan Nohr | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Free League\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A doom metal-aesthetic OSR game set in a dying fantasy world counting down to apocalypse. Mechanically simple; the production design is the statement — chaotic typography, intense color, extreme graphic design. Won ENnie Gold for Best Game and Product of the Year 2020.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Pushed art-forward OSR design to its logical extreme. The game's ORC-adjacent license (Mörk Borg Compatible) spawned a large third-party ecosystem. Demonstrated that OSR games could be objects of aesthetic interest beyond the game table.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: Free League</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing\">Zine Scene</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/DD 3e and d20 OGL": {"key": "Games/DD 3e and d20 OGL", "category": "Games", "name": "DD 3e and d20 OGL", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "wotc", "ogl"], "links": ["People/Monte Cook", "Publishers/Wizards of the Coast", "People/Monte Cook", "Publishers/Wizards of the Coast", "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing", "Concepts/Retroclones", "Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 2000 | Designers: Monte Cook, Jonathan Tweet, Skip Williams | Publisher: WotC", "html": "<h1>D&D 3rd Edition & the d20 OGL</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #wotc #ogl</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2000 | <strong>Designers:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Monte Cook\">Monte Cook</a>, Jonathan Tweet, Skip Williams | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wizards of the Coast\">WotC</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>The edition of D&D published by WotC after acquiring TSR in 1997. A complete rules redesign built around a unified d20 resolution mechanic. Accompanied by the Open Game License — which became the legal foundation for two decades of third-party publishing.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>The OGL is the hinge on which everything else turns. Without it, there are no retroclones, no Pathfinder, no OSR. D&D 3e also created the d20 boom — a wave of third-party publishers using the System Reference Document to produce compatible games and supplements.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designers: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Monte Cook\">Monte Cook</a>, Jonathan Tweet, Skip Williams</li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wizards of the Coast\">WotC</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">OGL & Open Licensing</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Retroclones\">Retroclones</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/D&D Edition Wars\">D&D Edition Wars</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Call of Cthulhu": {"key": "Games/Call of Cthulhu", "category": "Games", "name": "Call of Cthulhu", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "horror", "investigation", "lovecraft", "sanity", "owned"], "links": ["Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Games/Delta Green", "Games/Cthulhu Dark", "Concepts/The Mystery Genre Problem", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 1981 (current 7th edition 2014) | Designer: Sandy Petersen (original)\nPublisher: Chaosium | System: Basic RolePlaying (BRP) — percentile skills", "html": "<h1>Call of Cthulhu</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #horror #investigation #lovecraft #sanity #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 1981 (current 7th edition 2014) | <strong>Designer:</strong> Sandy Petersen (original) <strong>Publisher:</strong> Chaosium | <strong>System:</strong> Basic RolePlaying (BRP) — percentile skills\n<blockquote>⭐ <strong>You own this game.</strong></blockquote>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>The foundational horror investigation RPG, and one of the longest continuously published tabletop RPGs in history. Based on the fiction of H.P. Lovecraft and the Cthulhu Mythos. Players take the roles of investigators — ordinary people confronting supernatural horrors that should not exist. Success is not the expected outcome. Survival is not guaranteed. Sanity is a diminishing resource.</p>\n<h2>Historical Significance</h2>\n<p>Call of Cthulhu (1981) established the investigation genre in TTRPGs and demonstrated that horror could be a sustained campaign framework rather than just a dungeon-crawl backdrop. It predates D&D 3e by nearly two decades and has influenced almost every horror RPG that followed.</p>\n<p>Two specific design contributions that changed the field:</p>\n<strong>The Sanity track</strong> — a second resource alongside Hit Points. Encountering Mythos entities, reading forbidden tomes, and witnessing impossible things costs Sanity. When Sanity reaches zero, characters go permanently mad. This is one of the most imitated mechanics in RPG history — the idea that psychological deterioration is something you track and manage, not just narrate.\n<strong>The percentile skill system</strong> — characters have skills as percentages; roll equal to or under to succeed. No class system in the traditional sense; investigators are defined by their occupation and the skills that entails. A journalist and a professor bring different tools to the same investigation. This produces characters that feel meaningfully grounded in a specific social world.\n<h2>The Investigation Structure</h2>\n<p>CoC established a model for mystery play that proved enormously durable: investigators gather clues, consult sources, piece together what is happening, and then confront it. The problem this creates — what Robin D. Laws later identified and solved with GUMSHOE — is the failure state: if you roll poorly on a crucial investigation skill, you miss the clue and the mystery stalls. The game's answer was largely to assume competent investigators and give multiple paths to each piece of information.</p>\n<h2>Relationship to Other Games in Your Collection</h2>\n<strong>Night's Black Agents</strong> (GUMSHOE spy horror — you own it): Kenneth Hite designed NBA partly in conversation with CoC's limitations. GUMSHOE's automatic clue-finding principle directly addresses CoC's investigation failure state.\n<strong>Delta Green</strong> (you own it): The most significant licensed extension of CoC. Began as a supplement, became its own game. Takes CoC's horror investigation premise and places it in a contemporary US government context with its own full mechanical system.\n<strong>Cthulhu Dark</strong> (in vault): Graham Walmsley's radical minimalist reimagining. Where CoC is simulation-forward (skills, equipment, accurate historical settings), Cthulhu Dark is theme-forward (bleak dread, no combat vs. Mythos, social class inversion). Walmsley explicitly designed it as a different way of answering the question CoC posed.\n<h2>Current Edition</h2>\n<p>7th edition (2014) introduced some significant changes: advantage/disadvantage (\"Bonus and Penalty dice\"), pushed/rolls (retry with worse consequences), and built-in Chase rules. Some veteran players prefer earlier editions for their rawer feel; the 7th edition is more accessible to contemporary players coming from 5e.</p>\n<h2>Your Entry Points</h2>\n<p>If you're running CoC: Seth Skorkowsky's YouTube series on running CoC (especially his Delta Green episodes) is the most practical available guidance. The published Chaosium scenarios — Masks of Nyarlathotep especially — are considered among the best adventure-writing in the hobby's history.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: Chaosium | Original designer: Sandy Petersen</li>\n<li>System: Basic RolePlaying (BRP) — also powers Runequest</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Compare: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Delta Green\">Delta Green</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cthulhu Dark\">Cthulhu Dark</a> · <em>Night's Black Agents</em> (GUMSHOE)</li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The Mystery Genre Problem\">The Mystery Genre Problem</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005 Roots</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Ironsworn Sundered Isles": {"key": "Games/Ironsworn Sundered Isles", "category": "Games", "name": "Ironsworn Sundered Isles", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "solo", "seafaring", "expansion"], "links": ["People/Shawn Tomkin", "Games/Starforged", "People/Shawn Tomkin", "Games/Starforged", "Movements/Solo TTRPG Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2024 | Designer: Shawn Tomkin | Publisher: Tomkin Press\nRequires: Ironsworn: Starforged\nKickstarter: ~4,000 backers, $200k+", "html": "<h1>Ironsworn: Sundered Isles</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #solo #seafaring #expansion</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2024 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\">Shawn Tomkin</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Tomkin Press <strong>Requires:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Starforged\">Ironsworn: Starforged</a> <strong>Kickstarter:</strong> ~4,000 backers, $200k+\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A seafaring expansion for Ironsworn: Starforged — Age of Sail / fantasy nautical setting using the Starforged oracle and move system. Characters command ships and crews, chart island-filled seas, pursue sworn vows across turbulent waters. New naval combat procedure (close, engage, board), ship and crew management, wealth tracking, seafaring navigation moves.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Demonstrates that Tomkin's oracle system adapts coherently across radically different genre contexts — Norse-fantasy (Ironsworn), space opera (Starforged), Age of Sail (Sundered Isles) — without losing genre specificity. The assets are cross-compatible with Starforged: Heavy Cannons work whether you're firing cannonballs or plasma. This modularity is a design achievement.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\">Shawn Tomkin</a></li>\n<li>Requires: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Starforged\">Ironsworn: Starforged</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Solo TTRPG Design\">Solo TTRPG Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Cairn 2e": {"key": "Games/Cairn 2e", "category": "Games", "name": "Cairn 2e", "tags": ["game", "osr", "ruleslight", "free", "postOSR", "boxedset"], "links": ["People/Yochai Gal", "People/Yochai Gal", "Games/Cairn", "Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2024 | Designer: Yochai Gal | Publisher: Space Penguin Ink\nPrice: Free PDF (both books); paid boxed set", "html": "<h1>Cairn 2nd Edition (Boxed Set)</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #ruleslight #free #postOSR #boxedset</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2024 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Yochai Gal\">Yochai Gal</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Space Penguin Ink <strong>Price:</strong> Free PDF (both books); paid boxed set\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>The second edition of Cairn — a substantial expansion from the minimalist 2020 original into a fully realized boxed set. Three-book set: expanded Player's Guide, new Warden's Guide (with bestiary and referee tools), and introductory adventure Trouble in Twin Lakes. New full-color art throughout.</p>\n<h2>Key Changes from 1e</h2>\n<strong>Bonds</strong> — items or events of personal significance, established at character creation. Give players investment before the first session.\n<strong>Omens</strong> — story hooks tied to the character's background, seeding potential narrative threads from the start.\n<strong>Backgrounds</strong> — structured character histories that imply the setting through personal detail rather than sourcebook exposition.\n<strong>Warden's Guide</strong> — separate referee book with exploration procedures, faction tools, bestiary, and GMing guidance for the implied setting.\n<p>Core resolution is unchanged. The additions respond to a specific observation: Gal's players weren't primarily motivated by treasure-hunting — the traditional OSR driver. 2e gives players more reasons to care before play begins.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Demonstrates the full arc of a free minimalist game maturing into a proper publication ecosystem. Cairn 1e proved free openly licensed games could build massive communities. 2e proves those communities can sustain physical publication while preserving free PDF access — a model for sustainable indie publishing.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Yochai Gal\">Yochai Gal</a></li>\n<li>Predecessor: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cairn\\\">Cairn 1e</a> (2020)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design\">Post-OSR & Minimalist Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Into the Odd": {"key": "Games/Into the Odd", "category": "Games", "name": "Into the Odd", "tags": ["game", "osr", "ruleslight"], "links": ["Movements/OSR Movement", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2014 (Remastered 2022) | Designer: Chris McDowall | Publisher: Free League (remaster)", "html": "<h1>Into the Odd</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #ruleslight</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2014 (Remastered 2022) | <strong>Designer:</strong> Chris McDowall | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Free League (remaster)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A rules-light OSR game that eliminates to-hit rolls entirely — if you're in a position to attack, you hit. Combat is fast and lethal. Characters are fragile. Arcana (weird items) replace spell lists. The remaster (Electric Bastionland follow-up universe) updated the presentation significantly.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Influential on the \"rules-light OSR\" branch of design. Into the Odd stripped OSR design down to its core assumptions and asked which mechanics were actually load-bearing. Its influence is visible in Cairn, Knave, and many other minimalist OSR games.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n<li>Influenced: Troika!, Cairn, Knave</li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Heart The City Beneath": {"key": "Games/Heart The City Beneath", "category": "Games", "name": "Heart The City Beneath", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "fitD", "dungeon", "uk"], "links": ["People/Grant Howitt", "People/Christopher Taylor", "Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard", "Games/Spire The City Must Fall", "People/Grant Howitt", "People/Christopher Taylor", "Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard", "Games/Spire The City Must Fall", "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2021 | Designers: Grant Howitt, Christopher Taylor | Publisher: Rowan, Rook and Decard", "html": "<h1>Heart: The City Beneath</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #fitD #dungeon #uk</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2021 | <strong>Designers:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a>, <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Christopher Taylor\">Christopher Taylor</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard\">Rowan, Rook and Decard</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>The dungeon-delve companion game to <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\">Spire</a>. Players descend into the Heart — a living, psychedelic dungeon beneath the city — seeking their characters' deepest desires. The Heart reshapes itself to reflect the delvers' needs and fears. Uses the same stress-and-fallout system as Spire.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Takes the Spire engine into a very different genre space — dungeon-delve with horror and surreal fiction influences. Demonstrates how the RR&D design system adapts across genres.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designers: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Christopher Taylor\">Christopher Taylor</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard\">Rowan, Rook and Decard</a></li>\n<li>Companion: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\">Spire: The City Must Fall</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Forged in the Dark Family\">Forged in the Dark Family</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Starforged": {"key": "Games/Starforged", "category": "Games", "name": "Starforged", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "solo", "scifi"], "links": ["People/Shawn Tomkin", "Games/Ironsworn", "People/Shawn Tomkin", "Games/Ironsworn", "Movements/Solo TTRPG Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "The space opera successor to Ironsworn, applying the same Vow system and oracle design to a found-family crew navigating a hostile galaxy (Firefly/Mass Effect mode).", "html": "<h1>Ironsworn: Starforged</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #solo #scifi</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2022 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\">Shawn Tomkin</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>The space opera successor to <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Ironsworn\">Ironsworn</a>, applying the same Vow system and oracle design to a found-family crew navigating a hostile galaxy (Firefly/Mass Effect mode).</p>\n<h2>Key Additions over Ironsworn</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Sector oracle</strong> — procedural system for generating regions of space with their own character and history</li>\n<li><strong>Ship mechanics</strong> — the crew's ship has its own sheet and advancement</li>\n<li><strong>Refined oracle tables</strong> — more elaborate generation producing greater thematic coherence</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\">Shawn Tomkin</a></li>\n<li>Predecessor: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Ironsworn\">Ironsworn</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Solo TTRPG Design\">Solo TTRPG Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Mausritter": {"key": "Games/Mausritter", "category": "Games", "name": "Mausritter", "tags": ["game", "osr", "ruleslight", "free", "postOSR", "mice", "owned"], "links": ["Games/Into the Odd", "Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2019–2020 | Designer: Isaac Williams (AU) | Publisher: Games Omnivorous\nPrice: Pay-what-you-want PDF", "html": "<h1>Mausritter</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #ruleslight #free #postOSR #mice #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2019–2020 | <strong>Designer:</strong> Isaac Williams (AU) | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Games Omnivorous <strong>Price:</strong> Pay-what-you-want PDF\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A rules-light OSR game in which you play adventuring mice in a vast, dangerous world of everyday objects. Built on the Into the Odd chassis with additional mechanics from Knave and the Goblin Punch blog; layout influences from Mothership. 24 pages in the original zine; the expanded hardcover adds a starting adventure and hexcrawl setting.</p>\n<h2>Card-Based Inventory</h2>\n<p>The most distinctive innovation. Instead of writing items on a character sheet, players use physical cards placed on inventory slot grids. Conditions also take inventory slots. The physical cards make encumbrance and resource management tactile and immediately visible. Frequently cited as a mechanic worth adapting into other games.</p>\n<h2>Design Position</h2>\n<p>Demonstrates how the Into the Odd family produces new games through recombination and thematic focus. Mausritter takes the ItO chassis and applies it to a very specific genre (mouse-scale adventure) with genuine mechanical additions that serve the theme. The perspective shift — characters for whom a butter dish is a real obstacle — produces specific play behavior and rewards player cleverness over combat optimization.</p>\n<h2>Community</h2>\n<p>Over 1,000 third-party resources in the official library. The open SRD and the game's charm make it a popular platform. One of the most active third-party ecosystems in the rules-light OSR space.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: Isaac Williams | Publisher: Games Omnivorous</li>\n<li>Inspired by: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Into the Odd\">Into the Odd</a> (chassis)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design\">Post-OSR & Minimalist Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Warhammer Fantasy Roleplay": {"key": "Games/Warhammer Fantasy Roleplay", "category": "Games", "name": "Warhammer Fantasy Roleplay", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "grimdark", "british", "owned"], "links": ["Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "Games/Mork Borg", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 1986 (1e); current 4e 2018 | Publisher: Games Workshop (1e); Cubicle 7 (4e)", "html": "<h1>Warhammer Fantasy Roleplay</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #grimdark #british #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 1986 (1e); current 4e 2018 | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Games Workshop (1e); Cubicle 7 (4e)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A dark fantasy RPG set in the Old World — Games Workshop's grim, satirical pseudo-Europe of struggling Empires, rat-men under the cities, chaos gods at the borders, and ordinary people caught in events far beyond them. One of the most distinctive settings in TTRPG history: explicitly political, darkly comedic, and deeply hostile to heroic fantasy conventions.</p>\n<h2>Historical Significance</h2>\n<p>The foundational British fantasy RPG — produced by Games Workshop before they pivoted entirely to miniatures. WFRP's tone is the direct ancestor of a strain of British TTRPG sensibility that runs through OSR adjacent design (the grimdark aesthetic, the anti-heroic assumptions, the sense of history as weight rather than backdrop). Mörk Borg, Spire, and much of the UK indie scene is downstream of WFRP's aesthetic even when not consciously aware of it.</p>\n<p>The career system — characters begin as Ratcatchers and Grave Robbers before becoming Adventurers, if they survive — is one of the most influential character generation designs in TTRPG history. It produces immediate narrative context and social specificity in a way that class-based systems don't.</p>\n<h2>Current Edition</h2>\n<p>4e (Cubicle 7, 2018) is a faithful and well-produced restoration of the 1e and 2e aesthetic with modernized layout and design. One of the better examples of an edition that knows what it is and serves it well.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: Cubicle 7 (4e) | Original: Games Workshop</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Influence on: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design\">Post-OSR aesthetic</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mork Borg\">Mörk Borg</a> (indirect)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005 Roots</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Band of Blades": {"key": "Games/Band of Blades", "category": "Games", "name": "Band of Blades", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "fitD", "military", "fantasy"], "links": ["People/Stras Acimovic and John LeBoeuf-Little", "People/Stras Acimovic and John LeBoeuf-Little", "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family", "Games/Blades in the Dark", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "FitD applied to military fantasy — specifically a retreating army in a losing war against undead forces, inspired by the fantasy fiction of Django Wexler and Brian McClellan. Characters play both individual soldiers and rotating command positions that change between missions.", "html": "<h1>Band of Blades</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #fitD #military #fantasy</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2019 | <strong>Designers:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Stras Acimovic and John LeBoeuf-Little\">Stras Acimovic, John LeBoeuf-Little</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>FitD applied to military fantasy — specifically a retreating army in a losing war against undead forces, inspired by the fantasy fiction of Django Wexler and Brian McClellan. Characters play both individual soldiers and rotating command positions that change between missions.</p>\n<h2>Key Innovation: Command Positions</h2>\n<p>Players rotate through command roles (Marshal, Commander, Quartermaster) between missions. Each role has its own mechanics and decisions at the strategic level — above the tactical score level. This adds campaign-level decision-making without requiring a GM to manage it.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Demonstrated that FitD's Score/Downtime structure handles military campaign fiction precisely. Handled character death and replacement as narrative material rather than mechanical disruption — fitting for a game about a retreating army where attrition is the point.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designers: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Stras Acimovic and John LeBoeuf-Little\">Acimovic & LeBoeuf-Little</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Forged in the Dark Family\">Forged in the Dark Family</a></li>\n<li>Origin: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Blades in the Dark\">Blades in the Dark</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/The Quiet Year": {"key": "Games/The Quiet Year", "category": "Games", "name": "The Quiet Year", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "gmless", "worldbuilding", "map", "cozy"], "links": ["People/Avery Alder", "People/Avery Alder", "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Movements/GM-less Design", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2013 | Designer: Avery Alder | Publisher: Buried Without Ceremony", "html": "<h1>The Quiet Year</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #gmless #worldbuilding #map #cozy</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2013 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Buried Without Ceremony\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A map-making community worldbuilding game. Players collectively build a map of a community during one quiet year before a threat arrives. A deck of cards determines what happens each week. No GM. No individual protagonists — the community is the character. Ends when the Frost Shepherds arrive.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Established community-as-protagonist, map-making-as-play, and session-structured-around-collective-creation as recognized design tools. The Contempt token mechanic models how communities develop internal tensions — players can express disagreement by giving Contempt tokens, and Contempt limits certain actions. Widely used in design education as a model of elegant constraint-based collaborative worldbuilding.</p>\n<h2>Key Mechanics</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Card-driven weeks</strong> — each card prompts a discovery, project, or conflict</li>\n<li><strong>Contempt tokens</strong> — expressive of community friction; mechanically consequential</li>\n<li><strong>The Frost Shepherds</strong> — the threat that ends play; never fought, only anticipated</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a> (adjacent)</li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/GM-less Design\">GM-less Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Monsterhearts": {"key": "Games/Monsterhearts", "category": "Games", "name": "Monsterhearts", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "queer", "teen"], "links": ["People/Avery Alder", "People/Avery Alder", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2012 (2nd ed. 2017) | Designer: Avery Alder | Publisher: Buried Without Ceremony", "html": "<h1>Monsterhearts</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #queer #teen</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2012 (2nd ed. 2017) | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Buried Without Ceremony\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>PbtA about teenage monsters navigating high school, desire, and horror. Characters have Skins (the Vampire, the Werewolf, the Mortal) with moves built around emotional and physical entanglement. The \"Strings\" economy tracks social debt and leverage.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>One of the most played indie games of the 2010s. Monsterhearts demonstrated that PbtA could center queer experience and emotional complexity while remaining mechanically rigorous. The Strings system is an elegant solution to the problem of social conflict in TTRPGs.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Hyperborea": {"key": "Games/Hyperborea", "category": "Games", "name": "Hyperborea", "tags": ["game", "osr", "swordandsorcery", "played"], "links": ["People/Jeff Talanian", "Publishers/North Wind Adventures", "People/Jeff Talanian", "Publishers/North Wind Adventures", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2012 (3rd ed. 2022) | Designer: Jeff Talanian | Publisher: North Wind Adventures", "html": "<h1>Hyperborea</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #swordandsorcery #played</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2012 (3rd ed. 2022) | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeff Talanian\">Jeff Talanian</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/North Wind Adventures\">North Wind Adventures</a>\n<blockquote>⭐ <strong>You have played this game.</strong></blockquote>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>Astonishing Swordsmen & Sorcerers of Hyperborea — a Sword & Sorcery OSR game set in a dying, sword-and-sorcery world drawing heavily on Clark Ashton Smith, Robert E. Howard, and H.P. Lovecraft. Mechanically close to AD&D 1e with significant additions (many character classes, distinct magic systems).</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>A strong example of OSR design built around a tight literary-aesthetic identity rather than generic fantasy. Hyperborea is what happens when you take the OSR's reverence for old-school mechanics and focus it entirely on a specific literary tradition.</p>\n<h2>Literary Sources</h2>\n<ul><li>Clark Ashton Smith (Zothique, Hyperborea stories)</li>\n<li>Robert E. Howard (Conan, Kull)</li>\n<li>H.P. Lovecraft (Mythos elements, cosmic horror)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Design Notes</h2>\n<ul><li>AD&D 1e mechanical base</li>\n<li>20+ character classes with strong thematic differentiation</li>\n<li>Hexcrawl-friendly setting structure</li>\n<li>High lethality; meaningful resource management</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeff Talanian\">Jeff Talanian</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/North Wind Adventures\">North Wind Adventures</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Dolmenwood": {"key": "Games/Dolmenwood", "category": "Games", "name": "Dolmenwood", "tags": ["game", "osr", "neotrad", "setting", "played"], "links": ["People/Gavin Norman", "Publishers/Necrotic Gnome", "Games/Old-School Essentials", "People/Gavin Norman", "Publishers/Necrotic Gnome", "Games/Old-School Essentials", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2024 | Designer: Gavin Norman | Publisher: Necrotic Gnome | System: Old-School Essentials", "html": "<h1>Dolmenwood</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #neotrad #setting #played</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2024 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Gavin Norman\">Gavin Norman</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Necrotic Gnome\">Necrotic Gnome</a> | <strong>System:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Old-School Essentials\">Old-School Essentials</a>\n<blockquote>⭐ <strong>You have played this game.</strong></blockquote>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A fully realized folk horror campaign setting years in development. A woodland realm drawing on English folklore, fairy tales, and weird fiction — faerie courts, druidic cults, talking animals, and strange woodland magic. Published as a boxed set with Player's Book, Monster Book, and Referee's Book.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>The most complete realization of the neo-trad synthesis: OSR rules, modern layout and usability, rich and coherent setting, professional production. Dolmenwood shows what OSR design looks like when given time, resources, and a clear aesthetic vision.</p>\n<h2>Setting Touchstones</h2>\n<ul><li>English folklore and fairy tales</li>\n<li>Arthur Machen, Lord Dunsany (weird fiction)</li>\n<li>Mervyn Peake (Gormenghast)</li>\n<li>Poul Anderson (Three Hearts and Three Lions)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>The Seven Major Factions</h2>\nThe Drune (sorcerous druidic cult) · the Cold Prince (wicked fairy lord) · the human nobility (Duchy of Brackenwold) · the breggle nobility (goat-headed aristocracy) · the Pluritine Church · the witches · Atanuwë (chaos-godling)\n<p>Note: mosslings are a playable kindred (race), not a faction.</p>\n<h2>Design Notes</h2>\n<ul><li>Hexcrawl structure with strong pointcrawl elements</li>\n<li>Faction play central — 7 factions with distinct agendas, relationships, and NPC rosters</li>\n<li>Runs on OSE core rules; fully compatible with B/X material</li>\n<li>Seasonal play cycle built into setting structure</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Gavin Norman\">Gavin Norman</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Necrotic Gnome\">Necrotic Gnome</a></li>\n<li>System: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Old-School Essentials\">Old-School Essentials</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Masks A New Generation": {"key": "Games/Masks A New Generation", "category": "Games", "name": "Masks A New Generation", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "superhero"], "links": ["People/Brendan Conway", "Publishers/Magpie Games", "People/Brendan Conway", "Publishers/Magpie Games", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2016 | Designer: Brendan Conway | Publisher: Magpie Games", "html": "<h1>Masks: A New Generation</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #superhero</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2016 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Brendan Conway\">Brendan Conway</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Magpie Games\">Magpie Games</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A PbtA game about teenage superheroes still figuring out who they are — specifically the Young Avengers / Young Justice mode of the genre.</p>\n<h2>The Influence/Labels System</h2>\n<p>Characters have five Labels (Freak, Danger, Savior, Superior, Mundane) that affect mechanical options. NPCs and other PCs can shift your Labels through the Influence move. When someone with Influence over you tells you what you are, it mechanically affects your character.</p>\n<p>Your identity is not fixed — it's being shaped by the people around you. This is a precise mechanical translation of teen superhero fiction's actual subject matter: the negotiation between self-conception and external expectation.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<ul><li>One of the bestselling PbtA games of the era</li>\n<li>Brought PbtA to a large superhero genre audience</li>\n<li>Demonstrated that PbtA moves could do identity work as precisely as action or social work</li>\n<li>Influence/Labels is a model of genre-specific mechanical design</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Brendan Conway\">Brendan Conway</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Magpie Games\">Magpie Games</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Mothership": {"key": "Games/Mothership", "category": "Games", "name": "Mothership", "tags": ["game", "osr", "scifi", "horror", "zine"], "links": ["Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2017 (1st ed. boxed set 2022) | Designer: Sean McCoy | Publisher: Tuesday Knight Games", "html": "<h1>Mothership</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #scifi #horror #zine</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2017 (1st ed. boxed set 2022) | <strong>Designer:</strong> Sean McCoy | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Tuesday Knight Games\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A sci-fi horror RPG in zine format. Players are crew members on spacecraft in a hostile, Alien-influenced universe. High lethality, strong stress mechanics, minimalist rules. The Warden's Operations Manual is a model of GM-facing game design.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>One of the defining games of the zine-era OSR aesthetic. Mothership demonstrated that OSR design sensibilities (lethality, resource management, player skill) could be applied to genres beyond fantasy. Its production design — stark black and white, dense information layout — influenced the look of subsequent OSR zine publishing.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing\">Zine Scene</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Vaesen": {"key": "Games/Vaesen", "category": "Games", "name": "Vaesen", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "crossover", "licensed", "nordic", "horror"], "links": ["People/Nils Hintze", "Publishers/Free League Publishing", "Games/The One Ring 2e", "People/Nils Hintze", "Publishers/Free League Publishing", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Concepts/Licensed Adaptation Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 2021 | Designer: Nils Hintze | Publisher: Free League Publishing", "html": "<h1>Vaesen — Nordic Horror Roleplaying</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #crossover #licensed #nordic #horror</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2021 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Nils Hintze\">Nils Hintze</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Free League Publishing\">Free League Publishing</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A game about investigators in 19th century Scandinavia encountering the vaesen — spirits, monsters, and uncanny beings from Nordic folklore — and resolving conflicts between the vaesen's ancient rights and the modern world's encroachment.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Translates the specific moral register of Nordic folklore with design integrity. The vaesen have their own claims, histories, and grievances. The game's resolution reflects this: understanding and addressing grievances produces the most satisfying resolutions; combat is available but rarely optimal.</p>\n<p>Design sibling to <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The One Ring 2e\">The One Ring</a>: both are Free League games that design from what the source material is actually about.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Nils Hintze\">Nils Hintze</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Free League Publishing\">Free League Publishing</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Licensed Adaptation Design\">Licensed Adaptation Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Play Unsafe": {"key": "Games/Play Unsafe", "category": "Games", "name": "Play Unsafe", "tags": ["book", "design", "improv", "gm", "storygames"], "links": ["Personal/Recommended Reading and Watching", "People/Graham Walmsley", "People/Graham Walmsley", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2007 | Author: Graham Walmsley\nLength: 74 pages | Price: Low", "html": "<h1>Play Unsafe</h1>\n<p>#book #design #improv #gm-craft #storygames</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2007 | <strong>Author:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Graham Walmsley\">Graham Walmsley</a> <strong>Length:</strong> 74 pages | <strong>Price:</strong> Low\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>Not a game but a design and practice book — the first substantial application of theatre improv theory to TTRPG play. Based on threads from the Story Games forum; draws explicitly on Keith Johnstone's improv work (<em>Impro: Improvisation and the Theatre</em>, 1979).</p>\n<p>The argument: we treat games like work — buying thick books, planning detailed adventures, memorising rules — when we should treat them like play. The book explains how to apply improv's core insights to both GMing and player practice.</p>\n<h2>Core Concepts</h2>\n<strong>Hold ideas lightly</strong> — have a rough sense of direction but don't force it. If an idea isn't working, let it go rather than railroad the table toward it.\n<strong>Be obvious</strong> — when you try to be awesome, you almost always fail; when you try to be ordinary and obvious, you sometimes are inadvertently awesome. What seems obvious to you will often surprise others. Spontaneity requires not censoring your first instinct.\n<strong>Drop your guard</strong> — honesty at the table; when you censor yourself or let doubt creep in, you lose the moment.\n<strong>Status</strong> — all drama involves status change. The prince becomes a pauper; the servant girl becomes a queen. Rapid status changes are comedy; slow, sustained status changes are drama. Playing with status deliberately produces interesting scenes.\n<strong>Reincorporation</strong> — calling back to earlier details makes stories feel coherent and surprising at the same time. The dropped detail that returns becomes meaningful retroactively.\n<strong>Build on what's there</strong> — listen to other players and extend their contributions rather than redirecting to your own ideas. The \"yes, and\" principle applied specifically to TTRPG.\n<h2>Position in Design History</h2>\n<p>Play Unsafe predates most of the PbtA diaspora's articulations of \"play to find out\" and arrives at overlapping insights from a different direction — theatre improv theory rather than game design theory. Reading it alongside Apocalypse World's MC chapters is valuable: both argue against front-loaded creative decisions, but Walmsley's language is more accessible and the improv framework offers different tools.</p>\n<p>The book is notably <em>not</em> a GM guide in any traditional sense. It doesn't cover player types, mood-setting, adventure prep efficiency, or encounter building. It is entirely about changing your relationship to the game itself.</p>\n<h2>Caveat</h2>\n<p>Written in 2007, Play Unsafe's ideas are no longer novel in a field that has absorbed improv culture broadly. For players already versed in PbtA \"play to find out\" thinking, it may feel like well-trodden ground. Its value is higher for players coming from a preparation-heavy D&D background who haven't encountered this thinking elsewhere.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Author: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Graham Walmsley\">Graham Walmsley</a></li>\n<li>Influenced by: Keith Johnstone's improv theory</li>\n<li>Pair with: Apocalypse World MC chapters (different framing, overlapping conclusions)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Troika": {"key": "Games/Troika", "category": "Games", "name": "Troika", "tags": ["game", "osr", "postOSR", "scifantasy"], "links": ["Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2017 (expanded 2019) | Designer: Daniel Sell | Publisher: Melsonian Arts Council", "html": "<h1>Troika!</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #postOSR #scifantasy</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2017 (expanded 2019) | <strong>Designer:</strong> Daniel Sell | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Melsonian Arts Council\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A weird science-fantasy RPG based on the Fighting Fantasy gamebook system. Character creation is entirely through 36 varied Backgrounds (rolled randomly or chosen). Minimal fixed setting; players build the implied world from the backgrounds.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Exemplifies the post-OSR aesthetic turn: minimal rules, maximum implied setting, strong visual identity, zine/itch.io distribution culture. Its background-as-character-creation approach influenced many later games. The implied setting (a universe of crystal spheres, sky-barges, and strange philosophies) is communicated entirely through play, never stated.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing\">Zine Scene</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Shadowdark RPG": {"key": "Games/Shadowdark RPG", "category": "Games", "name": "Shadowdark RPG", "tags": ["game", "osr", "crossover", "postOGL", "dungeoncrawl"], "links": ["People/Kelsey Dionne", "People/Kelsey Dionne", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2023 | Designer: Kelsey Dionne | Publisher: The Arcane Library\nKickstarter: $1.3M (February 2023) | Awards: 4 gold ENNIEs 2024, Three Castles Award", "html": "<h1>Shadowdark RPG</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #crossover #postOGL #dungeoncrawl</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2023 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Kelsey Dionne\">Kelsey Dionne</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> The Arcane Library <strong>Kickstarter:</strong> $1.3M (February 2023) | <strong>Awards:</strong> 4 gold ENNIEs 2024, Three Castles Award\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A dungeon-crawling fantasy RPG explicitly designed to bridge the OSR and 5e audiences. d20 roll-over resolution familiar to 5e players; OSR resource management, lethality, and procedural exploration. One complete book. Launched at the height of the OGL crisis, dramatically amplifying its reach.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>The most commercially successful OSR-adjacent game of the post-OGL era. Demonstrates that OSR design insights — resource management, lethality, procedural play — can reach mainstream audiences when packaged with sufficient accessibility and production quality. The 2024 ENNIE sweep (Product of the Year, Best Game, Best Rules, Best Layout) validated the crossover design position at the highest level of recognition the hobby offers.</p>\n<h2>Key Mechanics</h2>\n<strong>Real-time torches</strong> — the most distinctive mechanic. A torch burns out in 60 actual real-world minutes. Not game turns — real time, tracked by a phone timer. Creates genuine urgency without bookkeeping overhead.\n<strong>Flat math</strong> — bounded accuracy throughout; minimal modifier inflation; the game stays dangerous at all levels.\n<strong>Talent rolls</strong> — advancement mixes choice and randomness, adding variety without full build complexity.\n<strong>Two-page core rules</strong> — distilled from Dionne's 5e adventure writing practice.\n<strong>Open third-party license</strong> — generous creator license immediately generated ecosystem of compatible content.\n<h2>Design Position</h2>\n<p>Not a pure retroclone — lacks strict B/X DNA. Not a 5e game — OSR resource management and lethality are genuine, not cosmetic. Explicitly occupies a crossover position: \"old-school gaming, new-school mechanics.\"</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Kelsey Dionne\">Kelsey Dionne</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OGL Crisis 2023\">OGL Crisis 2023</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Dream Askew": {"key": "Games/Dream Askew", "category": "Games", "name": "Dream Askew", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "gmless"], "links": ["People/Avery Alder", "People/Avery Alder", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2018 | Designer: Avery Alder | Publisher: Buried Without Ceremony", "html": "<h1>Dream Askew</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #gmless</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2018 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Buried Without Ceremony\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A GM-less PbtA game about queer communities in a post-collapse world. Uses a token economy (weak moves spend tokens, strong moves earn them) that distributes narrative authority without a central GM.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>An elegant solution to the GM-less design problem. Dream Askew's token system avoids the \"who has authority?\" uncertainty of many GM-less games without imposing a rigid turn structure.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Cairn": {"key": "Games/Cairn", "category": "Games", "name": "Cairn", "tags": ["game", "osr", "ruleslight", "free", "postOSR"], "links": ["People/Yochai Gal", "Games/Into the Odd", "People/Yochai Gal", "Games/Into the Odd", "Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2020 (2e 2024) | Designer: Yochai Gal | Price: Free (Creative Commons)", "html": "<h1>Cairn</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #ruleslight #free #postOSR</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2020 (2e 2024) | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Yochai Gal\">Yochai Gal</a> | <strong>Price:</strong> Free (Creative Commons)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A free, Creative Commons fantasy game distilling the <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Into the Odd\">Into the Odd</a> chassis into its most accessible form. Characters generate in under ten minutes. Core rules fit on a few pages. Play feels meaningfully different from D&D without requiring players to unlearn habits.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>The gateway drug to rules-light OSR for many players. Downloaded hundreds of thousands of times. Has a large community producing compatible adventures and supplements on itch.io. The clearest proof that McDowall's minimalism addresses something many players genuinely want.</p>\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\nCairn is free. Play a session before reading anything else in the minimalist OSR space.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Yochai Gal\">Yochai Gal</a></li>\n<li>Inspired by: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Into the Odd\">Into the Odd</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design\">Post-OSR & Minimalist Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Dungeon World": {"key": "Games/Dungeon World", "category": "Games", "name": "Dungeon World", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "fantasy"], "links": ["People/Sage LaTorra", "People/Adam Koebel", "People/Sage LaTorra", "People/Adam Koebel", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "PbtA applied to D&D-style dungeon fantasy. Fighters, wizards, thieves — familiar archetypes, but resolved through Moves and 2d6+stat rather than d20 systems. The GM fronts (slowly escalating threats) replace encounter planning.", "html": "<h1>Dungeon World</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #fantasy</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2012 | <strong>Designers:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Sage LaTorra\">Sage LaTorra</a>, <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Adam Koebel\">Adam Koebel</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>PbtA applied to D&D-style dungeon fantasy. Fighters, wizards, thieves — familiar archetypes, but resolved through Moves and 2d6+stat rather than d20 systems. The GM fronts (slowly escalating threats) replace encounter planning.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>The gateway drug from D&D to PbtA for thousands of players. Won multiple ENnie awards. Demonstrated that PbtA's design language could handle traditional fantasy genre conventions. LaTorra later worked on D&D 5e at WotC.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designers: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Sage LaTorra\">Sage LaTorra</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Adam Koebel\">Adam Koebel</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)\">Moves</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Dungeon Crawl Classics": {"key": "Games/Dungeon Crawl Classics", "category": "Games", "name": "Dungeon Crawl Classics", "tags": ["game", "osr", "pulp"], "links": ["Movements/OSR Movement", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence", "People/Jeff Talanian"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2012 | Designer: Joseph Goodman | Publisher: Goodman Games", "html": "<h1>Dungeon Crawl Classics</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #pulp</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2012 | <strong>Designer:</strong> Joseph Goodman | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Goodman Games\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A pulp fantasy OSR game with a distinctive dice system (the \"dice chain\"), a funnel mechanic (0-level character creation where most die), and heavy Clark Ashton Smith/Robert E. Howard influence. Known for spectacular, gonzo adventure modules.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Carved out its own aesthetic identity within the OSR — neither straight retroclone nor weird fiction, but high-energy pulp fantasy with mechanical texture. The funnel mechanic (run 4 0-level peasants, survivors become 1st level characters) is widely adopted.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n<li>Related designer influence: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeff Talanian\">Jeff Talanian</a> (shared Sword & Sorcery DNA)</li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/For the Queen": {"key": "Games/For the Queen", "category": "Games", "name": "For the Queen", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "gmless", "cozy", "cards"], "links": ["People/Alex Roberts", "People/Alex Roberts", "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Movements/GM-less Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "A card game for two to six players about companions on a journey to meet a Queen they serve. Card prompts explore relationships among companions and with the Queen. Explicitly queer and romantic. No GM.", "html": "<h1>For the Queen</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #gmless #cozy #cards</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2019 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Alex Roberts\">Alex Roberts</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A card game for two to six players about companions on a journey to meet a Queen they serve. Card prompts explore relationships among companions and with the Queen. Explicitly queer and romantic. No GM.</p>\n<h2>The Structure</h2>\n<p>Played with a deck of prompt cards drawn one at a time. Each card prompts a question about the characters' relationships, feelings, or experiences. Play ends when someone draws \"The enemy descends upon you — do you protect the Queen?\" — the only moment of conflict in the game.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Established that GM-less card-prompt play could produce genuine emotional stakes. The single conflict card at the end carries enormous weight accumulated from everything that preceded it — demonstrating that a game can have conflict as punctuation rather than as primary activity.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Alex Roberts\">Alex Roberts</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/GM-less Design\">GM-less Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Swords and Wizardry": {"key": "Games/Swords and Wizardry", "category": "Games", "name": "Swords and Wizardry", "tags": ["game", "osr", "retroclone"], "links": ["People/Matt Finch", "People/Matt Finch", "Concepts/Retroclones", "Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2008 | Designer: Matt Finch | System: OD&D clone (1974 rules)", "html": "<h1>Swords & Wizardry</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #retroclone</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2008 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a> | <strong>System:</strong> OD&D clone (1974 rules)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A retroclone targeting the original 1974 D&D rules (the \"little brown books\"), rather than any later edition. Published alongside <em>A Quick Primer for Old School Gaming</em>.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Goes back furthest of the first-wave clones. The companion Primer essay is more historically significant than the game itself as a text — it articulated OSR philosophy in a form that spread widely.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Retroclones\">Retroclones</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy\">OSR Play Philosophy</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Avatar Legends": {"key": "Games/Avatar Legends", "category": "Games", "name": "Avatar Legends", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "crossover", "pbtA", "licensed"], "links": ["Publishers/Magpie Games", "Publishers/Magpie Games", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "A PbtA game set in the Avatar: The Last Airbender and The Legend of Korra universe.", "html": "<h1>Avatar Legends: The Roleplaying Game</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #crossover #pbtA #licensed</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2022 | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Magpie Games\">Magpie Games</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A PbtA game set in the Avatar: The Last Airbender and The Legend of Korra universe.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Raised over $9 million on Kickstarter — one of the most successful tabletop RPG campaigns in history. Demonstrated that PbtA could achieve mainstream-scale commercial success. Significant proof that the indie design language had expanded far beyond its original audience.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Magpie Games\">Magpie Games</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Licensed Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Crown and Skull": {"key": "Games/Crown and Skull", "category": "Games", "name": "Crown and Skull", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "crossover", "diy", "attrition", "hexcrawl", "fantasy"], "links": ["People/Brandish Gilhelm", "People/Brandish Gilhelm", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Games/Shadowdark RPG", "Games/Mausritter", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 2023 | Designer: Brandish Gilhelm (Runehammer)\nPublisher: Runehammer Games | Free Player's Guide: 78 pages, available from runehammer.online\nVolume I: 356 pages; Volume II (Age of Dragons) in development", "html": "<h1>Crown and Skull</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #crossover #diy #attrition #hexcrawl #fantasy</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2023 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Brandish Gilhelm\">Brandish Gilhelm</a> (Runehammer) <strong>Publisher:</strong> Runehammer Games | <strong>Free Player's Guide:</strong> 78 pages, available from runehammer.online <strong>Volume I:</strong> 356 pages; Volume II (Age of Dragons) in development\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A complete fantasy RPG system and setting from the designer of Index Card RPG. Set in the North Holds — a hex-mapped northern fantasy world that emerged from three years of actual campaign play before the game was designed around it. Uses no traditional stats, no hit points, and no to-hit rolls, replacing them with a skill/equipment-based Attrition system and player-facing dice mechanics.</p>\n<h2>Core Mechanics</h2>\n<strong>Roll under on a d20</strong> — roll your skill's trained value or lower to succeed. Characters have up to 10 skills and 10 pieces of equipment.\n<strong>The Attrition System</strong> — the game's defining innovation. Hit points are replaced entirely. When a character takes damage of any kind, they cross off one skill or piece of equipment from their sheet. The GM assigns an Attrition type; the player chooses which specific item is lost. When a character has nothing left to sacrifice, a hit to the heart kills them at the round's end unless helped.\n<p>What makes this elegant: losing a sword mid-fight is mechanically identical to taking damage — both reduce capability and move you toward death — but the fiction is radically specific. The player authors their own deterioration, narrating what they lose and why. The GM is freed from tracking damage numbers.</p>\n<p>Note: Attrition applies only to player characters; enemies use standard HP. A practical GM-load decision that some find inconsistent and others find sensible.</p>\n<strong>Phase-based combat</strong> — five phases per round. Players choose their phase at the start of each round. Monsters activate in phases determined by a Tactics d6 roll, which drives enemy behavior automatically. This is the zero-prep tool at the heart of the GM design: you don't script enemy decisions; you roll a die and interpret the result.\n<strong>No classic six attributes</strong> — STR/DEX/CON/INT/WIS/CHA are entirely absent. Gilhelm's stated reason: the standard array muddies character differentiation and produces bloated modifier chains.\n<strong>Hero Points instead of gold/XP</strong> — advancement and loot acquisition use the same currency. Hero Points come from deeds of renown and from the game's central narrative choice.\n<h2>The Crown or Skull Choice</h2>\n<p>After earning enough Hero Points, each character faces a permanent binary choice: <ul><li><strong>Crown</strong> — honor-bound followers of the ruling order; 12 unique skills and equipment</li> <li><strong>Skull</strong> — masterless rogues on their own path; 12 unique skills and equipment</li> </ul> Once chosen, irreversible for that character. Opens a second tier of the build system and locks in a faction identity for the remainder of that character's arc.</p>\n<h2>Custom Magic and Equipment</h2>\n<p>Rather than fixed spell lists, players construct spells and items from component parts (effects + limitations) using Hero Points. The unified framework means a healing touch, a conjured fire, and a custom sword all follow the same construction rules.</p>\n<h2>GM Tools and Zero-Prep Design</h2>\n<p>Gilhelm is primarily known as a GM tools designer, and Crown and Skull's GM section reflects this. The game is built around the fantasy of running sessions without preparation: <ul><li>Tactics dice for automatic enemy behavior</li> <li>Hex roll tables for procedural world discovery</li> <li>Random NPC generators</li> <li>Loot tables keyed to biome and encounter type</li> <li>Dream state and esoteric scene guidance</li> </ul> The hex map of the North Holds has 60+ regions; the setting emerged from actual play rather than top-down worldbuilding.</p>\n<h2>Design Position</h2>\n<p>Crown and Skull is not OSR — Gilhelm explicitly rejects the label, preferring \"DIY.\" It shares mechanical DNA with several traditions simultaneously: roll-under and slot-based inventory from OSR; player-facing dice and zero-prep tools from story games; the ambitious hexcrawl setting from old-school sandbox play; the custom-build systems from more modern design.</p>\n<p>The Attrition system in particular is worth knowing independently of the game. It solves the \"HP as abstract number\" problem through a specific design insight: your equipped loadout <em>is</em> your buffer against death. This shares conceptual space with Mausritter's inventory-slot conditions, though the implementation is different.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Brandish Gilhelm\">Brandish Gilhelm</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Compare: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Shadowdark RPG\">Shadowdark</a> (post-OGL crossover; complete one-book design)</li>\n<li>Compare: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mausritter\">Mausritter</a> (slot-based inventory as damage replacement)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/DD 4th Edition": {"key": "Games/DD 4th Edition", "category": "Games", "name": "DD 4th Edition", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "wotc", "catalyst"], "links": ["Publishers/Wizards of the Coast", "Publishers/Wizards of the Coast", "Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Games/Pathfinder 1e", "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "WotC's 4th edition of D&D, designed around tactical miniature combat with clearly defined power structures, encounter balance, and a very different aesthetic from prior editions. Replaced the OGL with the more restrictive Game System License (GSL).", "html": "<h1>D&D 4th Edition</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #wotc #catalyst</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2008 | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wizards of the Coast\">WotC</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>WotC's 4th edition of D&D, designed around tactical miniature combat with clearly defined power structures, encounter balance, and a very different aesthetic from prior editions. Replaced the OGL with the more restrictive Game System License (GSL).</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>The single most consequential catalyst in post-2005 TTRPG history. 4e's divisive reception drove a large portion of the D&D fanbase toward retroclones (the OSR) and toward story games simultaneously. Paizo's Pathfinder emerged directly as a 4e alternative. The OSR went from niche curiosity to genuine movement largely because of 4e.</p>\n<h2>Design Character</h2>\n<ul><li>Strongly tactical; miniature-dependent</li>\n<li>Powers system (At-Will, Encounter, Daily) for all classes</li>\n<li>Clear encounter balance math</li>\n<li>MMORPG-influenced aesthetics (healing surges, roles)</li>\n<li>Abandoned many AD&D/3e conventions</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wizards of the Coast\">WotC</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/D&D Edition Wars\">D&D Edition Wars</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></li>\n<li>Caused: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 1e\">Pathfinder 1e</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">OGL</a> (replaced with GSL)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Delta Green": {"key": "Games/Delta Green", "category": "Games", "name": "Delta Green", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "horror", "investigation", "conspiracy", "modern", "owned"], "links": ["Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Games/Call of Cthulhu", "Games/Cthulhu Dark", "Concepts/The Mystery Genre Problem", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 1997 (supplement); 2017 (standalone game) | Designer: Dennis Detwiller, Adam Scott Glancy, John Tynes\nPublisher: Arc Dream Publishing | System: Proprietary (BRP-derived, heavily modified)", "html": "<h1>Delta Green</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #horror #investigation #conspiracy #modern #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 1997 (supplement); 2017 (standalone game) | <strong>Designer:</strong> Dennis Detwiller, Adam Scott Glancy, John Tynes <strong>Publisher:</strong> Arc Dream Publishing | <strong>System:</strong> Proprietary (BRP-derived, heavily modified)\n<blockquote>⭐ <strong>You own this game.</strong></blockquote>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A horror investigation RPG about clandestine US government agents confronting the Cthulhu Mythos in the contemporary world. Characters are federal agents — FBI, CDC, DEA, military intelligence — who have stumbled into the truth about what lurks behind the world's worst events and have been recruited (or dragooned) into Delta Green: an illegal, off-books conspiracy operating within the US government itself.</p>\n<p>Where Call of Cthulhu is about curious civilians investigating the unknown, Delta Green is about professionals who already know the truth and are trying to contain it — while managing their careers, their cover stories, their handlers, and their own deteriorating psychology.</p>\n<h2>Origins: Supplement to Standalone</h2>\n<p>Delta Green began in 1997 as a supplement for Call of Cthulhu, published by Pagan Publishing. It was the first serious attempt to bring the Mythos into the contemporary world with its full political and institutional weight — the government doesn't just encounter the Mythos; the government has been dealing with it since Innsmouth (1928), and the cover-up is now its own monster. The supplement won multiple Origins Awards and created a devoted following.</p>\n<p>The standalone game (Arc Dream, 2017) rebuilt the system from the ground up while preserving the tone and setting. It shares BRP's percentile DNA but is now a distinct system.</p>\n<h2>The Handler's Guide and Agent's Handbook</h2>\n<p>The game splits across two books: the Agent's Handbook (player-facing) and the Handler's Guide (GM-facing). This structure is itself a design statement — the Handler knows things the Agents don't, and the game is built around that asymmetry. The Handler's Guide contains the actual state of the Mythos, the full history of Delta Green, and mechanics the players never see.</p>\n<h2>Key Mechanics and Tone Differences from CoC</h2>\n<strong>Bonds</strong> — each Agent has a defined set of personal relationships (spouse, parent, old friend, colleague) with a numerical score. Encountering the Mythos, making terrible decisions, and failing to maintain the relationship costs Bond score. When a Bond reaches zero, it's gone — the relationship is destroyed. The Bond system makes the personal cost of the work mechanically concrete. You don't just narrate \"the job is taking a toll on your marriage\"; you watch the number go down.\n<strong>Sanity as Breaking Points</strong> — Delta Green replaces CoC's Sanity track with a Breaking Points system. Characters have a Violence score and an Helplessness score separately tracked. Witnessing extreme violence costs Violence; confronting the powerlessness of the human condition against the Mythos costs Helplessness. Breaking points produce specific Disorders and Motivations rather than the more generic madness of CoC.\n<strong>Lethality</strong> — Delta Green is significantly more lethal than CoC. Firearms are genuinely deadly; the game uses a Lethality rating system where certain weapons simply kill on a successful hit unless you make your Luck roll. The tone is that this is a world where the monsters are bad, but humans with guns are also very capable of killing each other.\n<strong>The Conspiracy Structure</strong> — the game's setting is its most distinctive feature. Delta Green operates illegally within the US government; its resources are stolen, its missions are unauthorized, its agents cover their tracks. The political and bureaucratic texture — handling your day job, maintaining your cover, managing what your superior knows — is part of the play experience. Many published scenarios are as much about navigating institutional politics as confronting supernatural horrors.\n<h2>Tone: Mundane Horror</h2>\n<p>Delta Green's specific horror register is distinct from CoC's. CoC horror is primarily about the discovery of what's out there — the moment of revelation when you realize the universe is not what you thought. Delta Green's horror is more mundane and more sustained: the Mythos has been a fact of the world for decades, and the institutions supposedly protecting you have made terrible compromises. The horror is knowing, having to act anyway, and watching what that does to you and the people you love.</p>\n<p>Arc Dream's published scenarios consistently explore this: federal agents doing something morally horrifying because the alternative is worse; cover-ups that protect careers at the cost of lives; the slow grinding of good people against a system that needs them to stay silent.</p>\n<h2>Relationship to Other Games in Your Collection</h2>\n<strong>Call of Cthulhu</strong> (you own it): Delta Green is explicitly downstream of CoC. If CoC asks \"what would you do if you discovered the Mythos?\", Delta Green asks \"what would you do if you'd known about it for thirty years and had institutional authority — and still couldn't stop it?\"\n<strong>Night's Black Agents</strong> (you own it): Both games are Mythos-adjacent espionage horror (NBA replaces Cthulhu entities with vampires, but the spy tradecraft and institutional paranoia are shared). Reading them together is illuminating — GUMSHOE's information architecture vs. Delta Green's BRP-derived skill resolution.\n<strong>Cthulhu Dark</strong> (in vault): The three games together form a useful spectrum. CoC: simulation + Sanity. Delta Green: institutional weight + Bonds + Lethality. Cthulhu Dark: minimalism + social class inversion + Insight track. Each solves a different problem with the same source material.\n<h2>Why It Matters for Horror RPG Design</h2>\n<p>Delta Green demonstrates that the horror investigation genre has room for genuine political content — not as backdrop but as mechanical weight. The Bond system makes the personal cost of doing terrible things in service of an institution a mechanical reality, not just a story beat. The conspiracy structure means the setting itself is the horror, not just the monsters within it.</p>\n<p>It also represents one of the best examples of a licensed supplement becoming more significant than its parent game in a specific audience. Among serious horror RPG players, Delta Green is often considered the definitive contemporary horror game.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: Arc Dream Publishing | Designers: Detwiller, Glancy, Tynes</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Compare: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Call of Cthulhu\">Call of Cthulhu</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cthulhu Dark\">Cthulhu Dark</a> · <em>Night's Black Agents</em> (GUMSHOE)</li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The Mystery Genre Problem\">The Mystery Genre Problem</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005 Roots</a> (1997 supplement) · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a> (standalone)</li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Electric Bastionland": {"key": "Games/Electric Bastionland", "category": "Games", "name": "Electric Bastionland", "tags": ["game", "osr", "ruleslight", "postOSR"], "links": ["People/Chris McDowall", "Games/Into the Odd", "People/Chris McDowall", "Games/Into the Odd", "Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "The follow-up to Into the Odd, developing the chassis in a new direction. Characters are Failed Careers — people who got themselves into enormous debt pursuing absurd professional dreams — navigating the Deep Country outside Bastion to find treasure. The debt mechanic is both campaign engine and tonal statement.", "html": "<h1>Electric Bastionland</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #ruleslight #postOSR</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2020 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris McDowall\">Chris McDowall</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>The follow-up to <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Into the Odd\">Into the Odd</a>, developing the chassis in a new direction. Characters are Failed Careers — people who got themselves into enormous debt pursuing absurd professional dreams — navigating the Deep Country outside Bastion to find treasure. The debt mechanic is both campaign engine and tonal statement.</p>\n<h2>Key Innovation: Failed Careers</h2>\nTables of bizarre former occupations provide starting equipment and a distinctive capability:\n<ul><li>A failed Moonshiner has a still, fermentation knowledge, and inexplicable poison immunity</li>\n<li>A failed Cryptozoologist has field notes, plaster casts, and one witness who will confirm a story</li>\n</ul>\nCareers are mechanical and tonal simultaneously — they suggest how a character behaves without constraining what they can attempt.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris McDowall\">Chris McDowall</a></li>\n<li>Predecessor: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Into the Odd\">Into the Odd</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design\">Post-OSR & Minimalist Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Dialect": {"key": "Games/Dialect", "category": "Games", "name": "Dialect", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "gmless", "collaborative", "language"], "links": ["Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Movements/GM-less Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "A game about a community developing its own language — a Dialect — over time, and eventually losing it as the community is absorbed or destroyed. Players create words and phrases, use them in play, and watch them change and disappear across three Acts.", "html": "<h1>Dialect</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #gmless #collaborative #language</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2018 | <strong>Designers:</strong> Hakan Sander, Thorny Games\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A game about a community developing its own language — a Dialect — over time, and eventually losing it as the community is absorbed or destroyed. Players create words and phrases, use them in play, and watch them change and disappear across three Acts.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Demonstrated that loss and grief could be powerful emotional drivers in TTRPG play without violence — the thing being lost is a language, an intangible cultural creation. Established language-as-mechanical-object as a viable design tool. Influenced subsequent collaborative worldbuilding games.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/GM-less Design\">GM-less Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Pathfinder 1e": {"key": "Games/Pathfinder 1e", "category": "Games", "name": "Pathfinder 1e", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "paizo", "d20"], "links": ["Publishers/Paizo", "Publishers/Paizo", "Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "Games/DD 4th Edition", "Games/Pathfinder 2e", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Built on the D&D 3.5 OGL — marketed as \"D&D 3.75.\" A more complex, feat-heavy version of 3e's d20 system. Became the #1 selling TTRPG for several years, outselling D&D itself.", "html": "<h1>Pathfinder 1st Edition</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #paizo #d20</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2009 | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Paizo\">Paizo</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>Built on the D&D 3.5 OGL — marketed as \"D&D 3.75.\" A more complex, feat-heavy version of 3e's d20 system. Became the #1 selling TTRPG for several years, outselling D&D itself.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Proved that the D&D brand was not as dominant as WotC assumed. Pathfinder's success during the 4e years validated the OGL as a vehicle for genuine competition, set up Paizo as a major long-term alternative publisher, and gave Paizo the credibility to lead the ORC license effort in 2023.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Paizo\">Paizo</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/D&D Edition Wars\">D&D Edition Wars</a></li>\n<li>Caused by: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 4th Edition\">D&D 4e</a> backlash</li>\n<li>Succeeded by: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 2e\">Pathfinder 2e</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Burning Wheel": {"key": "Games/Burning Wheel", "category": "Games", "name": "Burning Wheel", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "forge", "indie", "beliefs"], "links": ["People/Luke Crane", "People/Luke Crane", "Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2002 (revised 2011) | Designer: Luke Crane | Publisher: Burning Wheel HQ", "html": "<h1>Burning Wheel</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #forge #indie #beliefs</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2002 (revised 2011) | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Luke Crane\">Luke Crane</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Burning Wheel HQ\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>An intensely character-driven fantasy RPG organized around Beliefs, Instincts, and Traits. Characters have 2-3 Beliefs — statements about what they believe and want — and earn advancement by playing toward or against them. The mechanical weight sits on character motivation, not capability.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>The clearest mechanical argument in TTRPG design that what matters is <em>what characters want</em>, not what they can do. Hugely influential on story games designers even among those who never ran it. Torchbearer applies similar principles to dungeon-delve play.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Luke Crane\">Luke Crane</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory\">The Forge</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Spire The City Must Fall": {"key": "Games/Spire The City Must Fall", "category": "Games", "name": "Spire The City Must Fall", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "fitD", "political", "uk", "played"], "links": ["People/Grant Howitt", "People/Christopher Taylor", "Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard", "People/Grant Howitt", "People/Christopher Taylor", "Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard", "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family", "Games/Heart The City Beneath", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2018 | Designers: Grant Howitt, Christopher Taylor | Publisher: Rowan, Rook and Decard", "html": "<h1>Spire: The City Must Fall</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #fitD #political #uk #played</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2018 | <strong>Designers:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a>, <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Christopher Taylor\">Christopher Taylor</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard\">Rowan, Rook and Decard</a>\n<blockquote>⭐ <strong>You have played this game.</strong></blockquote>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>Players are dark elf (drow) revolutionaries living and working inside a vast city-spire ruled by the high elves who conquered it centuries ago. A game about oppression, resistance, and the costs of political violence. Uses a stress-and-fallout system rather than hit points — characters accumulate stress in different domains (blood, mind, shadow, reputation, resources) and suffer consequences when domains fill.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>A distinctly British take on FitD-adjacent design: literary, politically charged, with a specific aesthetic sensibility. Spire's setting is rich and implied rather than exhaustively detailed. The fallout system creates a different texture from standard FitD — consequences are varied and narratively interesting rather than purely numerical.</p>\n<h2>Design Notes</h2>\n<ul><li>Stress domains (Blood, Mind, Shadow, Silver, Reputation) replace HP</li>\n<li>Fallout table generates narrative consequences</li>\n<li>Class-based (Midwife, Masked, Vermissian Sage, etc.) with distinctive move sets</li>\n<li>FitD-adjacent but not strictly FitD licensed</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designers: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Christopher Taylor\">Christopher Taylor</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard\">Rowan, Rook and Decard</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Forged in the Dark Family\">Forged in the Dark Family</a></li>\n<li>Companion: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Heart The City Beneath\">Heart: The City Beneath</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Eat the Reich": {"key": "Games/Eat the Reich", "category": "Games", "name": "Eat the Reich", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "fitD", "horror", "comedy", "owned", "rrd"], "links": ["People/Grant Howitt", "Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard", "People/Grant Howitt", "Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard", "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2022 | Designer: Grant Howitt | Publisher: Rowan, Rook and Decard", "html": "<h1>Eat the Reich</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #fitD #horror #comedy #owned #rrd</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2022 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard\">Rowan, Rook and Decard</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A one-shot RPG about vampires parachuting into Nazi-occupied Paris during World War II to eat as many Nazis as possible. A deliberate premise study in moral clarity — every target is unambiguously evil — that allows the game to focus entirely on heist-style planning, escalating chaos, and gleeful violence. Uses a simplified FitD-adjacent chassis.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>A case study in how the one-shot game format can use a high-concept premise to eliminate entire categories of conventional RPG friction. By making the moral stakes completely unambiguous and the goal simple, Howitt removes the need for character motivation setup, moral deliberation, and world-building — the game starts immediately in action and sustains it.</p>\n<p>Also significant as Rowan, Rook and Decard's most commercially successful product alongside Spire and Heart — demonstrating that the studio can operate across tone registers from grimdark serious (Spire) to comedic high-concept (Eat the Reich).</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard\">Rowan, Rook and Decard</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Forged in the Dark Family\">FitD Family</a> (adjacent)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Precious Things": {"key": "Games/Precious Things", "category": "Games", "name": "Precious Things", "tags": ["game", "cozy", "fantasy", "dragons", "cards", "crossover"], "links": ["Publishers/Wet Ink Games", "Concepts/+One System", "Publishers/Wet Ink Games", "Concepts/+One System", "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Games/Wanderhome", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2024+ | Publisher: Wet Ink Games\nSystem: +One System | Kickstarter: Recent", "html": "<h1>Precious Things</h1>\n<p>#game #cozy #fantasy #dragons #cards #crossover</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2024+ | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wet Ink Games\">Wet Ink Games</a> <strong>System:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/+One System\">+One System</a> | <strong>Kickstarter:</strong> Recent\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A family-friendly RPG about tiny dragons who hoard mundane objects — buttons, paperclips, dried flowers, dice — and protect the home they share while keeping their existence secret from its human inhabitants. Punctuated by moments of danger but fundamentally cozy in register.</p>\n<p>The book includes a history of dragons, 52 different magic spells, threats magical and mundane, a full adventure, and notes on how to adapt the dragons and setting to different literary genres including regency drama and noir.</p>\n<h2>Design Notes</h2>\n<p>Uses the +One System's card mechanic for both individual spells and \"big magic\" — the standard playing deck doubles as a spell list and resource system simultaneously. 52 cards, 52 spells: the full deck models the full range of draconic magical capability.</p>\n<p>The game demonstrates the +One System's tonal flexibility most clearly — the same chassis that handles eldritch horror and psychological deterioration in Never Going Home here handles cozy domestic fantasy.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wet Ink Games\">Wet Ink Games</a></li>\n<li>System: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/+One System\">+One System</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a></li>\n<li>Compare: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Wanderhome\">Wanderhome</a> (pastoral cozy) · <em>Amazing Tales</em> (family RPG)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/The One Ring 2e": {"key": "Games/The One Ring 2e", "category": "Games", "name": "The One Ring 2e", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "crossover", "licensed", "tolkien"], "links": ["People/Francesco Nepitello", "Publishers/Free League Publishing", "Concepts/The Journey as Mechanical Unit", "People/Francesco Nepitello", "Publishers/Free League Publishing", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Concepts/Licensed Adaptation Design", "Concepts/The Journey as Mechanical Unit", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 2022 | Designer: Francesco Nepitello | Publisher: Free League Publishing", "html": "<h1>The One Ring 2nd Edition</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #crossover #licensed #tolkien</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2022 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Francesco Nepitello\">Francesco Nepitello</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Free League Publishing\">Free League Publishing</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>The definitive Middle-earth TTRPG. Characters are members of a Company of heroes adventuring across Tolkien's world during the period between The Hobbit and The Lord of the Rings.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>The model for licensed adaptation done right. Designed from what Tolkien's fiction is actually about rather than applying IP to an existing system.</p>\n<h2>Key Mechanics</h2>\n<strong>The Journey</strong> — the primary mechanical unit (not the encounter). Path selection, role assignment (Guide, Lookout, Scout, Hunter), hazard rolls, Fatigue accumulation. Makes travel itself narratively meaningful. See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The Journey as Mechanical Unit\">The Journey as Mechanical Unit</a>\n<strong>Fellowship Phase</strong> — structured rest and recovery between adventures. Characters return to safety, recover Shadow and Fatigue, pursue projects, deepen relationships. Encodes Tolkien's departure-and-return narrative rhythm.\n<strong>Shadow and Hope</strong> — mechanically opposed. Shadow accumulates through exposure to evil; Hope is spent to enhance dice and resist Shadow. Primary dramatic tension: will characters maintain integrity against creeping darkness?\n<strong>Fellowship Pool</strong> — shared Hope resource replenished through prosocial behavior. Mechanically incentivizes community and mutual support over personal advancement.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Francesco Nepitello\">Francesco Nepitello</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Free League Publishing\">Free League Publishing</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Licensed Adaptation Design\">Licensed Adaptation Design</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The Journey as Mechanical Unit\">Journey as Mechanical Unit</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Cosmic Dark": {"key": "Games/Cosmic Dark", "category": "Games", "name": "Cosmic Dark", "tags": ["game", "horror", "scifi", "bodhorror", "minimalist", "storygames", "forthcoming"], "links": ["People/Graham Walmsley", "People/Graham Walmsley", "Games/Cthulhu Dark", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Status: In development (on Patreon; DriveThruRPG release TBD)\nDesigner: Graham Walmsley", "html": "<h1>Cosmic Dark</h1>\n<p>#game #horror #scifi #bodhorror #minimalist #storygames #forthcoming</p>\n<strong>Status:</strong> In development (on Patreon; DriveThruRPG release TBD) <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Graham Walmsley\">Graham Walmsley</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A game of weird space horror using the Cthulhu Dark chassis with significant additions. Players are employees of Extracsa, a mining and resource conglomerate sent to the far reaches of the galaxy — a region dominated by the Glitch, an anomalous astronomical object like a golden wound. Not Lovecraftian horror in space: this is body horror, corporate horror, and the horror of life and reality going wrong in ways that don't have names.</p>\n<p>Literary influences: J.G. Ballard, Stanislaw Lem, the films Annihilation and Sunshine.</p>\n<h2>Key Departures from Cthulhu Dark</h2>\n<strong>No character creation</strong> — you start playing immediately. Characters emerge through play. This removes the barrier between sitting down and being in the story.\n<strong>The Changed Track</strong> — replaces Cthulhu Dark's Insight. Shows how much space has changed you. Rises when alien life attacks your body or mind. Reduced by erasing the change: cutting off a mutated limb, using the memory anaesthetic that Extracsa provides, accepting corporate surgery.\n<strong>Campaign play</strong> — Cthulhu Dark is a one-shot game; Cosmic Dark enables campaigns. Genre logic: in space horror, one or two people survive. They're changed, but they walk away. That makes survival across scenarios possible. Finishing a scenario gives you a Burnout score; it rises slowly over time. Your company provides surgery, adjusts your attitude, and sends you back out.\n<strong>Six-scenario mini-campaign</strong> — the book comes with a complete campaign arc from first mission to final revelation.\n<h2>Design Significance</h2>\n<p>Demonstrates that a minimalist chassis can be meaningfully extended without becoming complicated. The Changed mechanic — particularly the corporate mechanism for reducing it — encodes the game's themes directly: your employer can repair the damage, but the repair is also a form of control. The body horror and the corporate horror are mechanically entangled.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Graham Walmsley\">Graham Walmsley</a></li>\n<li>Predecessor: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cthulhu Dark\">Cthulhu Dark</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Dragonbane": {"key": "Games/Dragonbane", "category": "Games", "name": "Dragonbane", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "crossover", "swedish", "rollunder", "freeleague"], "links": ["Publishers/Free League Publishing", "Publishers/Free League Publishing", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 2023 (English) | Publisher: Free League Publishing\nOriginal: Drakar och Demoner (Sweden, 1982)", "html": "<h1>Dragonbane</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #crossover #swedish #rollunder #freeleague</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2023 (English) | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Free League Publishing\">Free League Publishing</a> <strong>Original:</strong> Drakar och Demoner (Sweden, 1982)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>Free League's English modernization of the Swedish RPG Drakar och Demoner — enormously popular in Scandinavia since 1982. Roll-under skill system: roll equal to or under your skill rating on a d20. Natural 1 is critical success; natural 20 is critical failure. No levels — characters advance by using skills. Dangerous and relatively unforgiving.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Brings a genuine European OSR-adjacent design tradition to English-speaking audiences. The roll-under system and skill-based advancement represent a distinct design lineage from both the American OSR and the D&D mainstream. Significant as evidence that the crossover space has international scope — the most important crossover games aren't all products of American or British design.</p>\n<h2>Design Notes</h2>\n<ul><li>Roll-under: intuitive (higher skill number = better odds), less flexible for difficulty modifiers</li>\n<li>Skill-based advancement: improve in what you actually do, not abstract XP</li>\n<li>Published with boxed set, bestiary, and adventure path already available at launch</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Free League Publishing\">Free League Publishing</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Ironsworn": {"key": "Games/Ironsworn", "category": "Games", "name": "Ironsworn", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "solo", "fantasy", "free"], "links": ["People/Shawn Tomkin", "Games/Starforged", "People/Shawn Tomkin", "Movements/Solo TTRPG Design", "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Movements/Solo TTRPG Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "A gritty Norse-inflected fantasy game designed specifically for solo play (also supports cooperative and traditional GM play). Characters are Ironsworn — wanderers who make and keep iron vows across a harsh frontier landscape.", "html": "<h1>Ironsworn</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #solo #fantasy #free</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2019 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\">Shawn Tomkin</a> | <strong>Price:</strong> Free\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A gritty Norse-inflected fantasy game designed specifically for solo play (also supports cooperative and traditional GM play). Characters are Ironsworn — wanderers who make and keep iron vows across a harsh frontier landscape.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Established solo TTRPG as a legitimate design category. Before Ironsworn, solo play was a fallback; after it, solo play had its own design demands and pleasures. Enormous word-of-mouth success while free; demonstrated that direct-to-audience distribution didn't require retail presence.</p>\n<h2>Core Innovations</h2>\n<strong>The Vow system</strong> — characters make formal commitments (ranked Troublesome to Epic) tracked on progress clocks. Fulfill Your Vow rolls against progress track rather than a stat; success scales with actual narrative engagement rather than character capability.\n<strong>Oracle system</strong> — extensive tables for generating world content without a GM. Designed for thematic coherence requiring interpretive judgment, not pure randomness.\n<strong>Earned accomplishment</strong> — the Vow system rewards sustained engagement with a goal, not a single fortunate roll.\n<h2>Successor</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Starforged\">Ironsworn: Starforged</a> (2022) — applied the same logic to space opera with refined oracle tables.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\">Shawn Tomkin</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Solo TTRPG Design\">Solo TTRPG Design</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Solo TTRPG Design\">Solo TTRPG Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Shadow of the Weird Wizard": {"key": "Games/Shadow of the Weird Wizard", "category": "Games", "name": "Shadow of the Weird Wizard", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "crossover", "fantasy", "paths"], "links": ["People/Robert Schwalb", "People/Robert Schwalb", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 2024 | Designer: Robert Schwalb | Publisher: Schwalb Entertainment\nMost Anticipated TTRPG of 2024 — EN World community poll", "html": "<h1>Shadow of the Weird Wizard</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #crossover #fantasy #paths</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2024 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Robert Schwalb\">Robert Schwalb</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Schwalb Entertainment <strong>Most Anticipated TTRPG of 2024</strong> — EN World community poll\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A heroic fantasy RPG using the same engine as Shadow of the Demon Lord but designed for broader appeal. Characters are refugees settling a Borderland frontier, protecting displaced people from the monsters and chaos left by the vanished Weird Wizard. Uses d20 with boons and banes (d6s added or subtracted) to mitigate swinginess.</p>\n<h2>The Paths System</h2>\n<p>The defining mechanic across both Demon Lord and Weird Wizard. Characters choose three Paths over a campaign: <ul><li><strong>Novice Path</strong> — early game; establishes core identity</li> <li><strong>Expert Path</strong> — mid game; deepens specialization</li> <li><strong>Master Path</strong> — late game; defines peak capabilities</li> </ul> Each Path is a structured package of abilities rather than individual feat choices. Early play is simple and accessible; late play is richly differentiated. Deep customization without front-loading complexity at character creation.</p>\n<h2>Design Relationship to Shadow of the Demon Lord</h2>\n<p>Demon Lord (2015) was critically acclaimed for its system; limited by its intensely grimdark register. Weird Wizard uses the same core engine with a fundamentally different emotional register — heroic rather than bleak, appropriate for broader audiences. Schwalb described it as what you get when you want the system without the \"anger and vexation.\"</p>\n<h2>Reception</h2>\n<p>Mixed relative to high expectations from the EN World poll. Some found the initial release felt incomplete at launch without the separate GM's Guide.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Robert Schwalb\">Robert Schwalb</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Simple World": {"key": "Games/Simple World", "category": "Games", "name": "Simple World", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "toolkit", "free", "owned"], "links": ["People/Avery Alder", "People/Avery Alder", "Games/Apocalypse World", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2013 | Designer: Avery Alder (published under her deadname) | Publisher: Buried Without Ceremony | Website: [buriedwithoutceremony.com/simple-world](https://buriedwithoutceremony.com/simple-world) | PDF: Free", "html": "<h1>Simple World</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #toolkit #free #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2013 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a> (published under her deadname) | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Buried Without Ceremony | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://buriedwithoutceremony.com/simple-world\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">buriedwithoutceremony.com/simple-world</a> | <strong>PDF:</strong> Free\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A lightweight, stripped-down engine for building PbtA games quickly. Not a complete game — a toolkit and design scaffold. The MC works through a structured prep document: choose what the game is about, create stats reflecting core dramatic tendencies, write character seeds (types of interesting people) with three specialties each, draft basic moves and a custom move for each type. The result is a playable PbtA framework in an evening rather than months.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Created in explicit response to a design trend Alder observed: PbtA hacks that underwent months of development before reaching the table. Simple World argues that <em>speed to table is a design virtue</em> — get mechanics in front of players fast, iterate from play rather than theory. It became an influential demonstration that a functional PbtA chassis needs very little scaffolding.</p>\n<p>Notable uses: many designers used Simple World as the starting point for one-shot convention games or early playtests of games that later became full products. Its core insight — that PbtA's essential moving parts are stats, moves, and the MC's agenda, and nothing else is required to begin — is now considered foundational design literacy in the indie community.</p>\n<h2>Your Copy</h2>\n<p>PDF (free). Owned.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a></li>\n<li>Parent system: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Apocalypse World\">Apocalypse World</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)\">Moves — PbtA Design Concept</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Sorcerer": {"key": "Games/Sorcerer", "category": "Games", "name": "Sorcerer", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "forge", "indie"], "links": ["People/Ron Edwards", "People/Ron Edwards", "Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "A Forge-era indie RPG about characters with demons — supernatural beings they've bound in exchange for power, at cost to their humanity. Uses \"bangs\" (situations demanding immediate response) and \"kickers\" (player-authored backstory hooks) as GM tools.", "html": "<h1>Sorcerer</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #forge #indie</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2001 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Ron Edwards\">Ron Edwards</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Adept Press\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A Forge-era indie RPG about characters with demons — supernatural beings they've bound in exchange for power, at cost to their humanity. Uses \"bangs\" (situations demanding immediate response) and \"kickers\" (player-authored backstory hooks) as GM tools.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>One of the foundational indie games. Sorcerer's design concepts — bangs, kickers, the centrality of character humanity — influenced the entire story games lineage. Edwards used it as the primary text for developing his design theory.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Ron Edwards\">Ron Edwards</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory\">The Forge & GNS Theory</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Rhapsody of Blood": {"key": "Games/Rhapsody of Blood", "category": "Games", "name": "Rhapsody of Blood", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "dungeon", "gothic", "horror", "owned"], "links": ["People/Minerva McJanda", "People/Minerva McJanda", "Games/Voidheart Symphony", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "A PbtA gothic dungeon-delve game. Players take on the roles of Bloodline heroes — descendants of ancient families with power over the Castle, a living supernatural structure that corrupts the land. Each investigation drives into the Castle's shifting labyrinth to strip power from the monsters within. Characters carry the weight of their lineage: gifts from their bloodline and the corruption that c", "html": "<h1>Rhapsody of Blood</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #dungeon #gothic #horror #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2019 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Minerva McJanda\">Minerva McJanda</a> <strong>Publisher:</strong> UFO Press\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A PbtA gothic dungeon-delve game. Players take on the roles of Bloodline heroes — descendants of ancient families with power over the Castle, a living supernatural structure that corrupts the land. Each investigation drives into the Castle's shifting labyrinth to strip power from the monsters within. Characters carry the weight of their lineage: gifts from their bloodline and the corruption that comes with using them.</p>\n<h2>Design Notes</h2>\n<p>Uses PbtA's move structure for dungeon-delving genre. The Castle is a meaningful antagonist with its own agenda rather than a static environment. Corruption mechanics create lasting consequences that accumulate across the campaign. A direct predecessor to Voidheart Symphony — the gothic combat engine that McJanda later adapted into that game's castle-delving phase.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Minerva McJanda\">Minerva McJanda</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: UFO Press</li>\n<li>Sequel: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Voidheart Symphony\">Voidheart Symphony</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Grant Howitt One-Page Games": {"key": "Games/Grant Howitt One-Page Games", "category": "Games", "name": "Grant Howitt One-Page Games", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "oneshot", "howitt", "owned"], "links": ["People/Grant Howitt", "People/Grant Howitt", "Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Designer: Grant Howitt | Publisher: Various (most free or pay-what-you-want)", "html": "<h1>Grant Howitt — One-Page Games Collection</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #oneshot #howitt #owned</p>\n<strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Various (most free or pay-what-you-want)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Howitt's one-page game catalog is one of the most significant bodies of short-form TTRPG design in the hobby's history. Each game is built around a single high-concept premise executed with mechanical precision, usually fit on one or two pages. The humor is structural rather than tonal — the comedy emerges from mechanic-fiction interaction, not from funny writing. As a result, these games are genuinely funny at the table rather than just amusing to read.</p>\n<p>The games in this collection that you own:</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Honey Heist</h2>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2017 | <strong>Premise:</strong> You are bears planning a heist at a honey festival.\n<p>The game that made Howitt's name beyond the British indie scene. One stat: Criminal vs. Bear. Acting like a criminal raises Criminal at the expense of Bear; acting like a bear does the reverse. When either maxes out, you either abandon the heist to pure criminal instinct or forget the plan entirely because you are a bear and there is honey. Critical Role played it. The BBC made a documentary about it. Still the clearest demonstration that a game can be complete in a single mechanic.</p>\n<h2>A Very Honey Heist Christmas</h2>\nA seasonal variant of Honey Heist. Same chassis, festive premise.\n<h2>Crash Pandas</h2>\n<strong>Premise:</strong> You are raccoons driving a car.\n<h2>Goblin Quest</h2>\n<strong>Premise:</strong> You play five goblins simultaneously, each one replacing the last when they die. Goblins die frequently. Death is the point. The game is about the journey of the troupe more than the survival of any individual.\n<h2>The Witch Is Dead</h2>\n<strong>Premise:</strong> You are the witch's familiars avenging her murder. A surprisingly affecting game dressed as a comedy — the premise creates genuine stakes through affection for the dead NPC.\n<h2>Pride and Extreme Prejudice</h2>\n<strong>Premise:</strong> Regency-era romance with extreme paramilitary action. Two genre conventions that should not coexist, coexisting.\n<h2>One Last Job</h2>\n<strong>Premise:</strong> Retired criminals dragged back for one last heist.\n<h2>Horse Around the House</h2>\n<strong>Premise:</strong> You are a horse in a house. Self-explanatory.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Design Significance</h2>\n<p>These games collectively established the one-page TTRPG as a recognized design genre rather than a proof-of-concept waiting to be expanded. They proved that:</p>\n<p>1. A complete, playable game can exist on one page 2. Constraint produces precision — the page limit forces every word to earn its place 3. High-concept premises are not gimmicks — they are design tools that resolve entire categories of setup friction 4. Comedy in TTRPG design is structural, not tonal</p>\n<p>Howitt's Patreon produces new one-page games regularly; the format he established here is now widely imitated across the indie TTRPG scene.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design\">Post-OSR & Minimalist Design</a> (crossover) · UK indie scene</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Draw Steel": {"key": "Games/Draw Steel", "category": "Games", "name": "Draw Steel", "tags": ["game", "mainstream", "postOGL", "crossover", "tactical"], "links": ["People/Matt Colville", "Publishers/MCDM Productions", "People/Matt Colville", "Publishers/MCDM Productions", "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Games/DD 4th Edition", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Year: 2024 | Designer: Matt Colville & MCDM team | Publisher: MCDM Productions", "html": "<h1>Draw Steel (MCDM RPG)</h1>\n<p>#game #mainstream #postOGL #crossover #tactical</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2024 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Colville\">Matt Colville</a> & MCDM team | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/MCDM Productions\">MCDM Productions</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A non-OGL, non-D&D-compatible fantasy RPG built from a specific diagnosis of 5e's failures in combat design. Funded at $4.7 million on Kickstarter. Extended public playtest over several years. Design team was transparent about process and influences (including 4e's tactical design) in ways mainstream publishers rarely are.</p>\n<h2>The Design Diagnosis</h2>\n<p>Colville's explicit argument: 5e is failing at its own priority (combat). <ul><li>Monsters have different stat blocks but similar tactical profiles — undistinctive</li> <li>The action economy produces flat turn-taking</li> <li>High-level play slows to a crawl</li> <li>Martial vs. caster balance remains unresolved</li> </ul> <h2>Key Departures from D&D</h2></p>\n<strong>Action economy</strong> — richer and more varied than 5e; specific actions available depend on class, positioning, and prior fight events. Closer to 4e's tactical design.\n<strong>Monster design</strong> — built around tactical identity, not stat variation. Specific things monsters do that make fights feel like distinct experiences. Developed from <em>Flee, Mortals!</em> philosophy.\n<strong>Heroes (classes)</strong> — designed around what each character uniquely does. The 4e role system (Defender/Striker/Leader/Controller) developed with more sophistication and less rigidity.\n<h2>The 4e Lineage</h2>\n<p>Draw Steel is the clearest expression of 4e's rehabilitation — recovering 4e's genuine tactical innovations while avoiding the aesthetic choices (MMORPG vocabulary, homogenized power structure) that caused 4e's commercial failure.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Colville\">Matt Colville</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/MCDM Productions\">MCDM Productions</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OGL Crisis 2023\">OGL Crisis 2023</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Licensed Design</a></li>\n<li>Related: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 4th Edition\">D&D 4th Edition</a> (design lineage)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Old-School Essentials": {"key": "Games/Old-School Essentials", "category": "Games", "name": "Old-School Essentials", "tags": ["game", "osr", "neotrad", "platform"], "links": ["People/Gavin Norman", "Publishers/Necrotic Gnome", "Games/Dolmenwood", "People/Gavin Norman", "Publishers/Necrotic Gnome", "Games/Dolmenwood", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Year: 2019 | Designer: Gavin Norman | Publisher: Necrotic Gnome", "html": "<h1>Old-School Essentials</h1>\n<p>#game #osr #neotrad #platform</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2019 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Gavin Norman\">Gavin Norman</a> | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Necrotic Gnome\">Necrotic Gnome</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A meticulous, highly formatted re-presentation of the B/X D&D ruleset. Rules are split into modular books (Core Rules, Advanced Fantasy Genre Rules, etc.) so GMs can choose their preferred complexity level. Exceptional information design — every rule is clearly stated, cross-referenced, and indexed.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Became the dominant platform for neo-trad and OSR-adjacent play in the late 2010s and 2020s. OSE is less a design innovation than a design refinement — but refinement done with exceptional care. The platform on which <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dolmenwood\">Dolmenwood</a> is built.</p>\n<h2>Design Philosophy</h2>\n<ul><li>Rules as presentation problem, not design problem</li>\n<li>Separation of rules from setting (modularity)</li>\n<li>Maximum clarity; every procedure explicitly stated</li>\n<li>Compatible with decades of B/X and OSR material</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Gavin Norman\">Gavin Norman</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Necrotic Gnome\">Necrotic Gnome</a></li>\n<li>Runs: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dolmenwood\">Dolmenwood</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Lady Blackbird": {"key": "Games/Lady Blackbird", "category": "Games", "name": "Lady Blackbird", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "free", "oneshot", "harper"], "links": ["People/John Harper", "People/John Harper", "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "A free, ~16-page complete adventure game about a noble lady escaping an arranged marriage on a sky-ship. Pre-generated characters with dice pools built from traits and secrets. Designed for one-shot play. Contains everything needed to run it.", "html": "<h1>Lady Blackbird</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #free #oneshot #harper</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2009 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a> | <strong>Price:</strong> Free\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A free, ~16-page complete adventure game about a noble lady escaping an arranged marriage on a sky-ship. Pre-generated characters with dice pools built from traits and secrets. Designed for one-shot play. Contains everything needed to run it.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Astonishing design economy — everything earns its place. Made Harper's reputation before Blades in the Dark. Showed how much could be accomplished in very few pages. The secrets system (invoke secrets for additional dice, unlock new secrets through play) anticipates Blades's approach to character capability as discovered rather than built.</p>\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\nRead Lady Blackbird before Blades in the Dark to see Harper's design sensibility in miniature form.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Forged in the Dark Family\">FitD</a> (precursor)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Voidheart Symphony": {"key": "Games/Voidheart Symphony", "category": "Games", "name": "Voidheart Symphony", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "political", "horror", "persona", "dual", "rrd"], "links": ["People/Minerva McJanda", "People/Minerva McJanda", "Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard", "Games/Rhapsody of Blood", "Games/Heart The City Beneath", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Games/Rhapsody of Blood", "Games/Spire The City Must Fall", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2021 | Designer: Minerva McJanda\nPublisher: UFO Press (original) | Rowan, Rook and Decard (Revised, in development)\nSystem: PbtA | Free quickstart: Kill or Cure (pay-what-you-want)", "html": "<h1>Voidheart Symphony</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #political #horror #persona #dual-world #rrd</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2021 | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Minerva McJanda\">Minerva McJanda</a> <strong>Publisher:</strong> UFO Press (original) | Rowan, Rook and Decard (Revised, in development) <strong>System:</strong> PbtA | <strong>Free quickstart:</strong> Kill or Cure (pay-what-you-want)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Origin</h2>\n<p>Written in late 2018 when McJanda was homeless, transitioning, and exhausted by inequality. The design question: what if the people hurting your community were supernaturally empowered — but what if the people fighting back had their own occult tools for tipping the scales? Combines the gothic combat of Rhapsody of Blood with the split-world structure of Persona 5, with Psychonauts and Inception as additional influences.</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A game of psychic rebellion in the modern city. Characters are rebels — ordinary people who have perceived the Castle: a shadow structure of supernatural corruption that gifts terrible power to the city's worst people. Corrupt landlords, predatory institutions, violent authorities are all vassals of the Castle. The rebels dive into the nightmare psychological space inside each vassal to strip them of their power, and in doing so, try to make things better.</p>\n<h2>The Dual World System</h2>\n<p>The game's defining structural innovation. Two worlds, two mechanical systems, deliberately asymmetric.</p>\n<strong>The City</strong> — investigation, mundane life, systemic pressure. Resolution uses roll-under gauges representing societal pressure. The higher the pressure on a character, the harder it is to resist. The system mechanically models how institutional weight accumulates and eventually overwhelms people who don't maintain their community bonds. City moves cover investigation, everyday actions, keeping yourself together.\n<strong>The Castle</strong> — supernatural combat in the nightmare palace inside a vassal's mind. Standard PbtA 2d6+stat resolution. Dynamic, balletic, the domain of dramatic action. Each castle is unique — built from the psychological structure of the vassal's corruption. A crooked landlord's castle is built from the fears of their tenants; a predatory institution's Perfected form embodies its worst impulses as actual monsters.\n<h2>Playbooks and Covenants — The Piecemeal Character System</h2>\n<p>Characters have two layers:</p>\n<strong>Core Playbooks</strong> define fundamental role in the crew: <ul><li>Authority (institutional power used for rebellion)</li> <li>Provider (keeping people alive and resourced)</li> <li>Watcher (surveillance and intelligence)</li> <li>Harlequin (misdirection and chaos)</li> <li>Icon (inspiration and community symbol)</li> <li>Heretic (someone who crossed over from the other side)</li> <li>Captive (constrained by circumstance)</li> <li>Inhuman (not fully human)</li> <li>Penitent (carrying guilt from past)</li> </ul> <strong>Covenants</strong> are relationships with NPCs, each keyed to a Major Arcana of the tarot (21 total: Oracle, Auteur, Chariot, Strength, and so on). Each Covenant grants three abilities: one for spending time with the contact, one for the mundane world, one for the castle. The entire rule set for a Covenant fits on a tarot card.\n<p>This is the game's most mechanically elegant achievement: advancement and community building are the same thing. You cannot grow more powerful except by cultivating relationships with people you care about. Maintained relationships grant power; neglected ones withdraw it.</p>\n<h2>The Vassal Structure</h2>\n<p>Each investigation targets a specific vassal — a real person in the city who has accepted the Castle's corruption. The Architect (GM) preps using a tarot spread to generate the castle's themes and structure. The investigation phase exposes the vassal's lies and vulnerabilities in the mundane world; the castle phase confronts their corruption directly.</p>\n<h2>Political Design</h2>\n<p>The game's political commitments are load-bearing mechanics, not set dressing: <ul><li>Stress gauges model societal pressure as mechanical reality</li> <li>Covenant advancement makes solidarity the mechanism of growth</li> <li>Vassals are always specific institutional/personal faces of corruption</li> <li>The city's roll-under system means existing pressure makes every action harder</li> <li>You can't solve the problem by yourself; the game is structurally unplayable without community</li> </ul> <h2>Connections</h2> <ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Minerva McJanda\">Minerva McJanda</a></li> <li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard\">Rowan, Rook and Decard</a> (Revised)</li> <li>Predecessor: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Rhapsody of Blood\">Rhapsody of Blood</a> (castle combat engine)</li> <li>Stress system influenced by: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Heart The City Beneath\">Heart: The City Beneath</a> (Howitt/Taylor)</li> <li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li> <li>You own: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Rhapsody of Blood\">Rhapsody of Blood</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\">Spire</a> (same publisher lineage)</li> <li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li> </ul></p>"}, "Games/Paris Gondo": {"key": "Games/Paris Gondo", "category": "Games", "name": "Paris Gondo", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "gmless", "indie", "owned"], "links": ["People/Kalum", "People/Kalum", "Movements/GM-less Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2021 (illustrated edition) | Designer: Kalum (The Rolistes) | Publisher: The Rolistes | Website: [rolistespod.itch.io/paris-gondo](https://rolistespod.itch.io/paris-gondo)", "html": "<h1>Paris Gondo — The Life-Saving Magic of Inventorying</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #gmless #indie #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2021 (illustrated edition) | <strong>Designer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Kalum\">Kalum</a> (The Rolistes) | <strong>Publisher:</strong> The Rolistes | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://rolistespod.itch.io/paris-gondo\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">rolistespod.itch.io/paris-gondo</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A GM-less storytelling game for 3–6 players about adventurers sorting through loot after defeating a dungeon boss — a tongue-in-cheek tribute to encumbrance rules and the Marie Kondo organizing philosophy. The conceit: the entire game takes place <em>after</em> the dungeon crawl. Play starts as the Party discovers loot and must decide what to carry home. Objects that \"spark joy\" may provide vital sustenance on the journey; useful-but-joyless items may be the difference between life and death.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>A precision exercise in GM-less design and structural wit. The <strong>GonParis Method</strong> — the game's six-step framework — guides players through dungeon creation (collaborative, retroactive), character selection (pre-made class card decks), loot discovery, the journey home, and the Final Inventory reckoning. Each player rolls the dice exactly three times per session.</p>\n<p>Notable design details: <ul><li><strong>Sparks Joy card</strong> — a positive safety tool (alongside the X-Card); players throw tokens onto it when something delights them, mechanically surfacing joy as a design priority alongside harm prevention</li> <li><strong>Replay format</strong> — like Rosewood Abbey, includes an actual-play transcript introducing the system</li> <li>Art by Bodie Hartley; layout by Francita Soto</li> </ul> <h2>Your Copy</h2></p>\n<p>Physical boxset (B6 rulebook + card decks). Owned.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Kalum\">Kalum</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/GM-less Design\">GM-less Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Games/Vale of the Failed and the Fallen": {"key": "Games/Vale of the Failed and the Fallen", "category": "Games", "name": "Vale of the Failed and the Fallen", "tags": ["game", "storygames", "pbtA", "redemption", "fantasy", "played", "owned"], "links": ["Movements/PbtA Family", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Year: 2025 | Designer: Robert Turk | Publisher: Wicked Clever Books & Games", "html": "<h1>Vale of the Failed and the Fallen</h1>\n<p>#game #storygames #pbtA #redemption #fantasy #played #owned</p>\n<strong>Year:</strong> 2025 | <strong>Designer:</strong> Robert Turk | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Wicked Clever Books & Games\n<blockquote>⭐ <strong>You have played this game. You own this game.</strong></blockquote>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A PbtA game about adults who, as children, traveled to a fantasy realm, failed to defeat the Great Evil, and watched a friend die. Twenty years later they are called back. A game of regret, redemption, and second chances in a ruined magical world. Thematic mash-up of The Neverending Story, Narnia, and Stephen King's IT — for adults.</p>\n<h2>Design Notes</h2>\n<p>Session Zero collaboratively creates the realm, the companions, and the first failed adventure together. Play runs in two temporal layers: present-day rebuilding through player-chosen milestones, and Around the Campfire phases exploring past adventures.</p>\n<p>Artifact-based playbooks (Blade, Heart, Mask, Quill, Shadow, Tower, Watcher). Stats built from memories, inner child aptitudes, and adult vocations. Hope tokens shared across the table; GM threat tokens limit the most devastating Keeper moves.</p>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\n<p>A 2025 PbtA game demonstrating the ongoing vitality of the diaspora — using PbtA's move structure for a distinctly non-standard premise. The two-timeline structure and failure-as-premise are unusual design choices the PbtA framework accommodates cleanly.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: Robert Turk (Wicked Clever Books & Games)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing": {"key": "Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing", "category": "Movements", "name": "Zine Scene and OSR Publishing", "tags": ["movement", "osr", "zines", "publishing", "itch"], "links": ["Publishers/Exalted Funeral", "Publishers/Exalted Funeral", "Publishers/The Merry Mushmen", "Games/Mothership", "Games/Troika", "Games/Mork Borg", "People/Gavin Norman", "People/James Raggi", "People/Sean McCoy", "People/Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "The OSR has always had a DIY publishing ethic — Basic Fantasy's \"free PDF, Lulu print at cost\" model established it early. The zine scene of the late 2010s and early 2020s represents this ethos at full maturity, enabled by itch.io distribution, Kickstarter funding, and a generation of designers for whom old-school design was a native language rather than a rediscovery.", "html": "<h1>Zine Scene & OSR Publishing</h1>\n<p>#movement #osr #zines #publishing #itch</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>The OSR has always had a DIY publishing ethic — Basic Fantasy's \"free PDF, Lulu print at cost\" model established it early. The zine scene of the late 2010s and early 2020s represents this ethos at full maturity, enabled by itch.io distribution, Kickstarter funding, and a generation of designers for whom old-school design was a native language rather than a rediscovery.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Three Enabling Platforms</h2>\n<strong>itch.io</strong> — primary distribution platform for indie and OSR zine games. Maximally favorable to small publishers: no minimum sales, no approval process, flexible pay-what-you-want pricing, direct creator-to-customer relationship. The Bundle for Racial Justice and Equality (June 2020, 1,700+ games, $8M+ raised) demonstrated itch.io's scale to the mainstream press. By 2020 the TTRPG section was a vast, if difficult to navigate, catalogue of creative work.\n<strong>Kickstarter Zine Quest</strong> — launched February 2019. Explicit Kickstarter initiative for zine-format projects. Low minimum funding requirements, short campaigns, explicit welcome for hand-stapled black-and-white productions. First iteration funded ~80 projects; by Zine Quest 3 (2021) hundreds were funding annually.\n<strong>Print-on-demand</strong> — Lulu, DriveThruRPG print service, and professional-tier fulfillment through publishers like <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Exalted Funeral\">Exalted Funeral</a>. Eliminated inventory risk. A designer could go from finished files to available physical product within days.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Zine Format and Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Saddle-stitched booklets, typically A5 or digest size, 20–64 pages, often black and white or two-color. The format imposes productive constraints — no room for padding, every page earns its place. Zine-era OSR products tended toward focused and provisional design: a single dungeon, one setting region, a specific toolkit. This focus often produced more table-useful work than comprehensive sourcebooks.</p>\n<p>The format also democratized production aesthetics. Black and white, spot color, risograph printing effects, deliberately rough layouts — all viable and often desirable. The handmade quality was a signal of authentic independent production, not a limitation to apologize for.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key Tastemakers & Curators</h2>\n<strong><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Exalted Funeral\">Exalted Funeral</a></strong> — founded 2018 by <strong>Cristin and Matt Kelley</strong>. The most important independent TTRPG retailer and publisher of the era. Curated OSR and indie games with genuine aesthetic taste; offered Kickstarter fulfillment services; co-published Old-School Essentials and Dolmenwood. An Exalted Funeral stock became a quality signal in a crowded market.\n<strong><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/The Merry Mushmen\">The Merry Mushmen</a></strong> — <strong>Éric Nieudan</strong> (editor) and <strong>Olivier Revenu</strong> (publisher/layout). Publishers of Knock! magazine — the closest thing the zine-era OSR had to a flagship anthology. Knock! issue #1 Kickstarted in December 2020 with 1,600+ backers. Each 200+ page full-colour issue collects adventures, essays, tables, and design discussions from across the OSR community. Demonstrated that the era was capable of self-reflection and critical discourse, not just production volume.\n<strong>Spear Witch</strong> and <strong>Floating Chair Club</strong> — smaller curatorial retailers stocking carefully chosen post-OSR and indie games.\n<strong>Questing Beast</strong> (Ben Milton) — YouTube reviewer whose video reviews of OSR and indie games became a primary discovery mechanism for the community.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Notable Zine-Format Games</h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mothership\">Mothership</a> — began as a zine; grew into a boxed set</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Troika\">Troika!</a> — zine aesthetic and format</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mork Borg\">Mörk Borg</a> — zine sensibility at hardcover scale</li>\n<li><em>Knock!</em> — OSR anthology; <strong>Éric Nieudan</strong> (ed.), <strong>Olivier Revenu</strong> (layout/publisher), The Merry Mushmen</li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>Connection to Neo-Trad</h2>\nThe zine scene overlaps with but is distinct from neo-trad. Neo-trad games (OSE, Dolmenwood) tend toward high production values and completeness. Zine games tend toward focused, provisional, deliberately rough design. Both flourished in the same ecosystem.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key Figures</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Gavin Norman\">Gavin Norman</a> (OSE/Dolmenwood) · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/James Raggi\">James Raggi</a> (high-production OSR model) · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Sean McCoy\">Sean McCoy</a> (Mothership) · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr\">Tøgersen & Nohr</a> (Mörk Borg Compatible license)"}, "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave": {"key": "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "category": "Movements", "name": "Cozy and Quiet Wave", "tags": ["movement", "storygames", "cozy", "solo", "gmless"], "links": ["Games/The Quiet Year", "People/Avery Alder", "Games/Wanderhome", "People/Jay Dragon", "Games/Ironsworn", "People/Shawn Tomkin", "Games/Thousand Year Old Vampire", "People/Tim Hutchings", "Games/For the Queen", "People/Alex Roberts", "People/Jay Dragon", "People/Shawn Tomkin", "People/Tim Hutchings", "People/Alex Roberts", "People/Avery Alder"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "The cozy wave made explicit a set of desires always present in TTRPG play but systematically unserved by the dominant design tradition's assumption that violent conflict was the primary driver of meaningful play. These designers demonstrated that mechanical design could support rest, beauty, and quiet pleasure as precisely as it supported dramatic conflict.", "html": "<h1>The Cozy & Quiet Wave</h1>\n<p>#movement #storygames #cozy #solo #gmless</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>The cozy wave made explicit a set of desires always present in TTRPG play but systematically unserved by the dominant design tradition's assumption that violent conflict was the primary driver of meaningful play. These designers demonstrated that mechanical design could support rest, beauty, and quiet pleasure as precisely as it supported dramatic conflict.</p>\n<h2>The Cultural Moment</h2>\n<p>The cozy wave developed in conversation with broader cultural trends responding to specific historical pressures: political turbulence, the attention economy's relentless urgency. Animal Crossing: New Horizons (March 2020) became one of the best-selling games of all time partly because it offered exactly what the pandemic moment required. The pandemic also shifted TTRPG play online, expanded the solo TTRPG market, and brought new players specifically looking for social warmth and creative pleasure.</p>\n<h2>What the Dominant Tradition Assumed</h2>\n<p>Almost every major TTRPG assumed that conflict — specifically violent conflict — was the primary driver of meaningful play. Characters had combat stats. Sessions had encounter tables. This encoded a theory of what engagement requires: risk of failure, something significant to lose, most significant things to lose are health, life, and material resources.</p>\n<p>The cozy wave rejected this theory not abstractly but by demonstrating in playable games that other things produce engagement: relational texture, small accomplishments, being in a beautiful place with interesting people.</p>\n<h2>Key Games</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Designer</td><td>Contribution</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Quiet Year\\</td><td>The Quiet Year\">td><td>The Quiet Year</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\\</td><td>Avery Alder\">td><td>Avery Alder</a></td><td>Proto-cozy; community as protagonist; map as play artifact</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Wanderhome\\</td><td>Wanderhome\">td><td>Wanderhome</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jay Dragon\\</td><td>Jay Dragon\">td><td>Jay Dragon</a></td><td>Cozy wave flagship; token economy; pastoral</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Ironsworn\\</td><td>Ironsworn\">td><td>Ironsworn</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\\</td><td>Shawn Tomkin\">td><td>Shawn Tomkin</a></td><td>Solo TTRPG as legitimate design category; Vow system</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Thousand Year Old Vampire\\</td><td>Thousand Year Old Vampire\">td><td>Thousand Year Old Vampire</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Tim Hutchings\\</td><td>Tim Hutchings\">td><td>Tim Hutchings</a></td><td>Forgetting mechanic; grief and loss without combat</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/For the Queen\\</td><td>For the Queen\">td><td>For the Queen</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Alex Roberts\\</td><td>Alex Roberts\">td><td>Alex Roberts</a></td><td>GM-less card-prompt; intimate small-group play</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Star Crossed</em></td><td>Alex Roberts & Beau Jágr Sheldon</td><td>Jenga tower as physical tension; two-player intimate play</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Dialect</em></td><td>Hakan Sander, Thorny Games</td><td>Language and loss; community as protagonist</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>What the Cozy Wave Contributed</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Legitimacy of rest as play</strong> — games for rest and quiet pleasure are legitimate design objects, not underdeveloped games needing more conflict</li>\n<li><strong>Solo play as a design target</strong> — with its own specific mechanical requirements and pleasures</li>\n<li><strong>Small-group and intimate play</strong> — two-player and three-player games as distinct categories</li>\n<li><strong>GM-less as a recognized mode</strong> — requiring specific mechanical support, not just absence of a GM</li>\n<li><strong>Procedural worldbuilding as content</strong> — building a world is itself a form of play</li>\n<li><strong>Politics of accessibility</strong> — explicit attention to who is excluded from dominant TTRPG design</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Key Designers</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jay Dragon\">Jay Dragon</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\">Shawn Tomkin</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Tim Hutchings\">Tim Hutchings</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Alex Roberts\">Alex Roberts</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a>"}, "Movements/Actual Play Boom": {"key": "Movements/Actual Play Boom", "category": "Movements", "name": "Actual Play Boom", "tags": ["movement", "mainstream", "actualplay", "criticalrole"], "links": ["People/Matthew Mercer", "People/Brennan Lee Mulligan", "People/Matthew Mercer", "People/Matt Colville"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "The explosion of streaming and podcast actual play content — TTRPGs performed for an audience — that began around 2012 and peaked from 2015 onward. The primary vector for D&D 5e's mass market adoption.", "html": "<h1>The Actual Play Boom</h1>\n<p>#movement #mainstream #actualplay #criticalrole</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>The explosion of streaming and podcast actual play content — TTRPGs performed for an audience — that began around 2012 and peaked from 2015 onward. The primary vector for D&D 5e's mass market adoption.</p>\n<h2>Critical Role (2015–present)</h2>\n<p>The dominant force. <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matthew Mercer\">Matthew Mercer</a> as GM, a cast of professional voice actors, playing D&D 5e. Launched on Geek & Sundry in 2015, moved to its own channel in 2018. The animated series Kickstarter raised $11M in 24 hours (2019).</p>\n<p>Critical Role's influence: <ul><li>Brought millions of new players to TTRPGs</li> <li>Defined public expectations of TTRPG play (performative GMing, pre-planned narrative arcs, hero fantasy)</li> <li>Made D&D 5e synonymous with TTRPG in mainstream culture</li> <li>Created Darrington Press as a publishing arm</li> </ul> <h2>Other Notable Shows</h2></p>\n<ul><li><em>The Adventure Zone</em> — McElroy family podcast; reached non-gamer audiences</li>\n<li><em>Dimension 20</em> — Dropout.tv; high production; <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Brennan Lee Mulligan\">Brennan Lee Mulligan</a> as GM</li>\n<li><em>Friends at the Table</em> — Austin Walker; story games and PbtA focus; more indie-adjacent</li>\n<li><em>Rollplay</em> — early streaming actual play; Adam Koebel as GM</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>The Tension It Created</h2>\n<p>The actual play boom created a cultural gap between: <ul><li><strong>Audience players</strong> — came in expecting Mercer-style performative GMing</li> <li><strong>Traditional players</strong> — valued improvisation, rulings, player agency over narrative coherence</li> </ul> This tension is visible in online TTRPG discourse and in the design conversation around \"game for actual play vs. game for play.\"</p>\n<h2>Post-OGL Shift</h2>\n<p>After the 2023 OGL crisis, several actual play shows moved away from D&D 5e, some visibly. This mattered because actual play had been the primary driver of 5e's mainstream growth.</p>\n<h2>Key People</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matthew Mercer\">Matthew Mercer</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Colville\">Matt Colville</a> (YouTube GM advice)"}, "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023": {"key": "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023", "category": "Movements", "name": "OGL Crisis 2023", "tags": ["movement", "mainstream", "ogl", "crisis", "history"], "links": ["Games/Pathfinder 2e", "Games/Draw Steel", "People/Mike Mearls", "People/Jeremy Crawford", "People/Matt Colville", "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "In January 2023, a draft of a new OGL — \"OGL 1.1\" — leaked before WotC announced it. The draft proposed to:\n- Revoke the original OGL (which WotC's lawyers had previously described as irrevocable)\n- Require royalty payments from publishers above a revenue threshold\n- Demand that creators report revenue to WotC\n- Claim rights for WotC to use any OGL-licensed content royalty-free\n- Shut down virtual", "html": "<h1>The OGL Crisis (2023)</h1>\n<p>#movement #mainstream #ogl #crisis #history</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What Happened</h2>\n<p>In January 2023, a draft of a new OGL — \"OGL 1.1\" — leaked before WotC announced it. The draft proposed to: <ul><li>Revoke the original OGL (which WotC's lawyers had previously described as irrevocable)</li> <li>Require royalty payments from publishers above a revenue threshold</li> <li>Demand that creators report revenue to WotC</li> <li>Claim rights for WotC to use any OGL-licensed content royalty-free</li> <li>Shut down virtual tabletop products competing with WotC's planned VTT</li> </ul> <h2>The Backlash</h2></p>\n<p>Immediate and massive. Major publishers (Kobold Press, Paizo, Green Ronin) issued public statements. An open letter gathered hundreds of thousands of signatures. Actual play shows explored alternatives. D&D Beyond subscription cancellations were publicly tracked and clearly rattled WotC.</p>\n<h2>WotC's Retreat</h2>\n<p>WotC walked back the proposed OGL over approximately two weeks of escalating community pressure. The final resolution: the core D&D SRD was placed under a <strong>Creative Commons license</strong> — genuinely irrevocable, not even WotC can revoke it.</p>\n<p>However: trust was permanently damaged. The community now knew WotC was willing to attempt this.</p>\n<h2>The ORC License</h2>\n<p>Paizo led development of the <strong>ORC License</strong> (Open RPG Creative License) — a system-neutral open license developed with input from the broader publisher community, administered by a nonprofit law firm. Multiple publishers moved to ORC as a WotC-independent alternative.</p>\n<h2>Winners and Losers</h2>\n<strong>Lost:</strong> WotC's trusted relationship with the third-party publishing community   <strong>Won:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 2e\">Pathfinder 2e</a> — major sales spike   <strong>Won:</strong> OSR and indie publishers — large wave of new players exploring alternatives   <strong>Won:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Draw Steel\">Draw Steel</a> / MCDM — post-OGL momentum   <strong>Won:</strong> The concept of genuine licensing alternatives to WotC's ecosystem\n<h2>What It Revealed</h2>\n<ul><li>The hobby was dangerously concentrated around one company</li>\n<li>The community had real leverage (subscription cancellations worked)</li>\n<li>The OGL's \"irrevocable\" language was tested and ultimately vindicated via Creative Commons</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Key People</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Mike Mearls\">Mike Mearls</a> (departed WotC) · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeremy Crawford\">Jeremy Crawford</a> (remained) · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Colville\">Matt Colville</a> (post-OGL voice)\n<h2>Key Concepts</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">The OGL & Open Licensing</a>"}, "Movements/GM-less Design": {"key": "Movements/GM-less Design", "category": "Movements", "name": "GM-less Design", "tags": ["movement", "design", "storygames", "gmless"], "links": ["Games/Ironsworn", "Games/For the Queen", "Games/The Quiet Year", "Games/Dream Askew", "Games/Wanderhome", "Games/The Quiet Year", "Games/Dream Askew", "Games/Wanderhome", "Games/For the Queen", "Games/Ironsworn", "People/Avery Alder", "People/Jay Dragon", "People/Alex Roberts", "People/Shawn Tomkin"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "GM-less design distributes narrative authority across all players rather than centralizing it in a single GM role. It's a design category rather than a design philosophy — the reasons for pursuing it vary as widely as the games that do it. It became a recognized category in the 2010s with a coherent set of mechanical approaches.", "html": "<h1>GM-less Design</h1>\n<p>#movement #design #storygames #gmless</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>GM-less design distributes narrative authority across all players rather than centralizing it in a single GM role. It's a design category rather than a design philosophy — the reasons for pursuing it vary as widely as the games that do it. It became a recognized category in the 2010s with a coherent set of mechanical approaches.</p>\n<h2>Why Go GM-less?</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Equity of creative contribution</strong> — everyone authors equally</li>\n<li><strong>Sustained solo play</strong> — no GM needed</li>\n<li><strong>Specific play experiences</strong> — some fictions are better served by distributed authority</li>\n<li><strong>Accessibility</strong> — no player has to take on the GM burden</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Key Mechanical Approaches</h2>\n<strong>Oracle systems</strong> — randomized prompts generate what would otherwise be GM-determined content (<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Ironsworn\">Ironsworn</a>)\n<strong>Card decks</strong> — structured prompts rotate creative authority (<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/For the Queen\">For the Queen</a>, <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Quiet Year\">The Quiet Year</a>)\n<strong>Token economies</strong> — tokens distribute narrative authority mechanically (<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dream Askew\">Dream Askew</a>, <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Wanderhome\">Wanderhome</a>)\n<strong>Rotating roles</strong> — players take turns as scene-framer or equivalent (<em>Polaris</em>, <em>Lovecraftesque</em>)\n<strong>Dream Askew's solution</strong> — token economy that distributes authority without rigid turn structure; each player has both a playbook and moves that trigger token generation/spending.\n<h2>Relationship to The Forge</h2>\n<p>The Forge had extensive theoretical discourse about GM authority and its problems. GM-less design is one practical answer — distributing the authority rather than designing constraints around it.</p>\n<h2>Relationship to Solo Play</h2>\n<p>Solo TTRPG play is a specific case of GM-less design — one player filling all roles simultaneously, with oracle tools providing the unpredictability a GM would normally supply.</p>\n<h2>Key Games</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Approach</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Quiet Year\\</td><td>The Quiet Year\">td><td>The Quiet Year</a></td><td>Card deck; community protagonist</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dream Askew\\</td><td>Dream Askew\">td><td>Dream Askew</a></td><td>Token economy; rotating authority</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Wanderhome\\</td><td>Wanderhome\">td><td>Wanderhome</a></td><td>Token economy; pastoral cozy</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/For the Queen\\</td><td>For the Queen\">td><td>For the Queen</a></td><td>Card prompts; intimate group</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Ironsworn\\</td><td>Ironsworn\">td><td>Ironsworn</a></td><td>Oracle system; solo play</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Lovecraftesque</em></td><td>Rotating Watcher role</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Key Designers</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jay Dragon\">Jay Dragon</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Alex Roberts\">Alex Roberts</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\">Shawn Tomkin</a>"}, "Movements/OSR Movement": {"key": "Movements/OSR Movement", "category": "Movements", "name": "OSR Movement", "tags": ["movement", "osr"], "links": ["Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years", "People/Matt Finch", "Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy", "People/Matt Finch", "People/Stuart Marshall", "People/Daniel Proctor", "People/Chris Gonnerman", "People/James Maliszewski", "People/James Raggi", "People/Gavin Norman", "People/Jeff Talanian", "Concepts/Retroclones", "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing", "Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy", "Publishers/Lamentations of the Flame Princess", "Publishers/Necrotic Gnome", "Publishers/North Wind Adventures"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "The Old School Renaissance (or Revival) is both a body of game publications and a philosophy of play. At its core: a recovery and development of design principles from D&D's early editions (1974–1983) that were abandoned or modified in later editions.", "html": "<h1>The OSR Movement</h1>\n<p>#movement #osr</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What Is the OSR?</h2>\n<p>The Old School Renaissance (or Revival) is both a body of game publications and a philosophy of play. At its core: a recovery and development of design principles from D&D's early editions (1974–1983) that were abandoned or modified in later editions.</p>\n<h2>Origin Story</h2>\n<p>The OSR emerged from the intersection of two things: 1. <strong>The OGL</strong> (2000) — which made it legally possible to restate old mechanics in new text 2. <strong>D&D 4th Edition</strong> (2008) — which gave many players strong motivation to seek alternatives</p>\n<p>See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010 Era</a> for the founding moment.</p>\n<h2>Core Philosophy</h2>\n<p>The founding philosophical text is <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a>'s <em>A Quick Primer for Old School Gaming</em> (2008). Key tenets: <ul><li><strong>Rulings over rules</strong> — the referee improvises rather than rules-looks up</li> <li><strong>Player skill over character build</strong> — clever play matters more than optimal stats</li> <li><strong>The dungeon is dangerous</strong> — death is real and meaningful</li> <li><strong>The gap in the rules is a feature</strong> — it demands creativity</li> <li><strong>Living world</strong> — the dungeon exists independently of the players</li> </ul> See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy\">OSR Play Philosophy</a></p>\n<h2>Phases</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Phase</td><td>Years</td><td>Character</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Retroclone wave</td><td>2006–2010</td><td>Legal/mechanical infrastructure</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Blog era</td><td>2008–2014</td><td>Philosophy and criticism</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Aesthetic maturation</td><td>2010–2017</td><td>LotFP, DCC, weird OSR</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Post-OSR / Neo-Trad</td><td>2017–present</td><td>Troika, OSE, Dolmenwood</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Zine explosion</td><td>2019–present</td><td>itch.io, Kickstarter Zine Quest</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Key People</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Stuart Marshall\">Stuart Marshall</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Daniel Proctor\">Daniel Proctor</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris Gonnerman\">Chris Gonnerman</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/James Maliszewski\">James Maliszewski</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/James Raggi\">James Raggi</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Gavin Norman\">Gavin Norman</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeff Talanian\">Jeff Talanian</a>\n<h2>Key Concepts</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Retroclones\">Retroclones</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">OGL</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy\">OSR Play Philosophy</a>\n<h2>Key Publishers</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Lamentations of the Flame Princess\">LotFP</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Necrotic Gnome\">Necrotic Gnome</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/North Wind Adventures\">North Wind Adventures</a>"}, "Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory": {"key": "Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory", "category": "Movements", "name": "The Forge and GNS Theory", "tags": ["movement", "storygames", "theory", "indie"], "links": ["People/Ron Edwards", "People/Ron Edwards", "People/Luke Crane", "People/Vincent Baker", "Games/Sorcerer", "Games/Burning Wheel", "Games/Dogs in the Vineyard"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "An online forum (~2001–2012) founded by Ron Edwards that became the intellectual center of indie TTRPG design in the 2000s. It was a space for analyzing why games succeed or fail at producing satisfying play, and for designing games that addressed identified failures.", "html": "<h1>The Forge & GNS Theory</h1>\n<p>#movement #storygames #theory #indie</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What Was The Forge?</h2>\n<p>An online forum (~2001–2012) founded by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Ron Edwards\">Ron Edwards</a> that became the intellectual center of indie TTRPG design in the 2000s. It was a space for analyzing why games succeed or fail at producing satisfying play, and for designing games that addressed identified failures.</p>\n<h2>GNS Theory</h2>\n<p>Edwards's framework for categorizing play priorities: <ul><li><strong>Gamist</strong> — competitive challenge; winning matters</li> <li><strong>Narrativist</strong> — story and character meaning; thematic exploration</li> <li><strong>Simulationist</strong> — internal consistency; genre emulation</li> </ul> The theory argued that games optimized for one mode often fail players seeking another, and that \"incoherent\" design (trying to serve all three equally) produces \"brain damage\" at the table.</p>\n<h2>Legacy and Criticism</h2>\n<p>GNS theory was enormously influential but also substantially criticized and revised. Later thinkers (including Baker himself) moved away from it. The Big Model (a later refinement) is more nuanced. But GNS shaped what the indie design community thought it was doing for a decade.</p>\n<strong>Key insight that survived criticism:</strong> Design choices imply a theory of play. If you don't know what theory your game embodies, you probably have an incoherent one.\n<h2>The Forge's Closure</h2>\n<p>The Forge closed in 2012. The community dispersed to Google+, blogs, and later Discord. Many consider this the end of a distinct era in indie design theory.</p>\n<h2>Key People</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Ron Edwards\">Ron Edwards</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Luke Crane\">Luke Crane</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a>\n<h2>Key Games from this era</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Sorcerer\">Sorcerer</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Burning Wheel\">Burning Wheel</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dogs in the Vineyard\">Dogs in the Vineyard</a>"}, "Movements/PbtA Family": {"key": "Movements/PbtA Family", "category": "Movements", "name": "PbtA Family", "tags": ["movement", "storygames", "pbtA", "family"], "links": ["Games/Apocalypse World", "People/Vincent Baker", "People/Meguey Baker", "Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)", "Games/Dungeon World", "Games/Monsterhearts", "Games/The Quiet Year", "Games/Dream Askew", "Games/Brindlewood Bay", "People/Vincent Baker", "People/Meguey Baker", "People/Avery Alder", "People/Sage LaTorra", "People/Adam Koebel", "People/Jason Cordova"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Apocalypse World (2010) by Vincent Baker and Meguey Baker. The PbtA name comes from the license Baker created allowing others to build on AW's design language.", "html": "<h1>Powered by the Apocalypse (PbtA)</h1>\n<p>#movement #storygames #pbtA #family</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Origin</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Apocalypse World\">Apocalypse World</a> (2010) by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a> and <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Meguey Baker\">Meguey Baker</a>. The PbtA name comes from the license Baker created allowing others to build on AW's design language.\n<h2>Core Concepts</h2>\n<strong>Moves</strong> — the central design innovation. A Move is a triggered fictional action with a specific mechanical outcome. \"When you do X, roll 2d6+stat. On 10+: full success. On 7-9: partial success. On 6-: miss, the MC makes a move.\"\n<p>See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)\">Moves — PbtA Design Concept</a></p>\n<strong>The MC/GM's role</strong> — reactive, improvisational. The MC plays to find out what happens. Never plans outcomes. Makes moves in response to player actions and misses.\n<strong>Playbooks</strong> — character archetypes with pre-built move lists. You don't build a character; you embody a playbook.\n<strong>Agenda and Principles</strong> — explicit lists of how the MC should behave. Not advice — rules.\n<h2>The Family</h2>\n<p>A partial list of notable PbtA games: <ul><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dungeon World\">Dungeon World</a> — fantasy adventure</li> <li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Monsterhearts\">Monsterhearts</a> — teen monster drama</li> <li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Quiet Year\">The Quiet Year</a> — adjacent; community worldbuilding</li> <li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dream Askew\">Dream Askew</a> — GM-less; queer post-collapse</li> <li><em>Masks</em> — superhero; Magpie Games</li> <li><em>Urban Shadows</em> — urban fantasy politics</li> <li><em>The Sprawl</em> — cyberpunk</li> <li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\">Brindlewood Bay</a> — elderly mystery ⭐ <em>you GM this</em></li> </ul> <h2>Key People</h2> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Meguey Baker\">Meguey Baker</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Sage LaTorra\">Sage LaTorra</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Adam Koebel\">Adam Koebel</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Cordova\">Jason Cordova</a></p>"}, "Movements/D&D Edition Wars": {"key": "Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "category": "Movements", "name": "D&D Edition Wars", "tags": ["movement", "mainstream", "wotc", "history"], "links": ["Games/Pathfinder 1e", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory", "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023", "People/Monte Cook", "People/Mike Mearls", "People/Jeremy Crawford"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "The repeated conflicts within the D&D player community over edition transitions — each of which produced winners, losers, and refugees who shaped the broader TTRPG landscape.", "html": "<h1>D&D Edition Wars</h1>\n<p>#movement #mainstream #wotc #history</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>The repeated conflicts within the D&D player community over edition transitions — each of which produced winners, losers, and refugees who shaped the broader TTRPG landscape.</p>\n<h2>3e to 4e (2008) — The Great Fracture</h2>\n<p>The most consequential transition. D&D 4th Edition's radical redesign alienated a large portion of the player base: <ul><li>Players seeking 3e continuity went to <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 1e\">Pathfinder</a></li> <li>Players seeking old-school play went to the <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR</a></li> <li>Players seeking narrative design found <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory\">story games</a></li> </ul> The OGL was also replaced with the more restrictive GSL, cutting off a large third-party publishing ecosystem.</p>\n<h2>4e to 5e (2014) — The Reconciliation</h2>\n<p>D&D 5th Edition was designed explicitly to reunite the fractured playerbase. The \"D&D Next\" playtest (2012–2014) was the largest in TTRPG history. 5e succeeded — it became the most commercially successful edition ever.</p>\n<h2>5e and the OGL Crisis (2023)</h2>\n<p>WotC's attempted OGL revision in January 2023 reopened edition-war-like fractures, this time along licensing rather than design lines.</p>\n<p>See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OGL Crisis 2023\">OGL Crisis 2023</a></p>\n<h2>Timeline</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Year</td><td>Event</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2000</td><td>D&D 3e + OGL published</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2008</td><td>D&D 4e + GSL; fracture begins</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2009</td><td>Pathfinder 1e; OSR accelerates</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2012</td><td>D&D Next playtest begins</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2014</td><td>D&D 5e; reconciliation</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2023</td><td>OGL crisis; new fracture</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2024</td><td>D&D 2024 (revised 5e)</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Key People</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Monte Cook\">Monte Cook</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Mike Mearls\">Mike Mearls</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeremy Crawford\">Jeremy Crawford</a>"}, "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family": {"key": "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family", "category": "Movements", "name": "Forged in the Dark Family", "tags": ["movement", "storygames", "fitD", "family"], "links": ["Games/Blades in the Dark", "People/John Harper", "Concepts/Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)", "Games/Spire The City Must Fall", "Games/Heart The City Beneath", "People/John Harper", "People/Grant Howitt", "People/Christopher Taylor"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Blades in the Dark (2017) by John Harper. The FitD name comes from Harper's license allowing others to build on BitD's design framework.", "html": "<h1>Forged in the Dark (FitD)</h1>\n<p>#movement #storygames #fitD #family</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Origin</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Blades in the Dark\">Blades in the Dark</a> (2017) by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a>. The FitD name comes from Harper's license allowing others to build on BitD's design framework.\n<h2>Core Innovations</h2>\n<strong>Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)</strong> — instead of simple success/failure, every action has two axes: <ul><li><em>Position</em>: how risky is the situation? (Controlled / Risky / Desperate)</li> <li><em>Effect</em>: how much impact will success have? (Limited / Standard / Great)</li> </ul> <strong>Flashbacks</strong> — players can declare mid-scene that they prepared for this situation. Pay stress, narrate the preparation, gain the benefit. Eliminates \"but we didn't plan for this!\" paralysis.\n<strong>Clocks</strong> — circular progress trackers (4/6/8/10 segments) for threats, projects, and goals. When a clock fills, something happens.\n<strong>Crew meta-game</strong> — the group has its own sheet tracking rep, heat, coin, and faction relationships. Between-score play is structured.\n<strong>Stress and Trauma</strong> — characters have a stress track. At zero, they take Trauma (permanent character changes).\n<p>See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)\">Clocks & Position/Effect</a></p>\n<h2>The Family</h2>\n<p>Notable FitD and FitD-adjacent games: <ul><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\">Spire: The City Must Fall</a> ⭐ <em>you play this</em></li> <li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Heart The City Beneath\">Heart: The City Beneath</a></li> <li><em>Scum and Villainy</em> — sci-fi space opera</li> <li><em>Band of Blades</em> — military fantasy</li> <li><em>Beam Saber</em> — giant robot war</li> <li><em>Candela Obscura</em> — Darrington Press; horror</li> </ul> <h2>Key People</h2> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Christopher Taylor\">Christopher Taylor</a></p>"}, "Movements/Solo TTRPG Design": {"key": "Movements/Solo TTRPG Design", "category": "Movements", "name": "Solo TTRPG Design", "tags": ["movement", "solo", "design", "storygames", "oracles"], "links": ["Movements/GM-less Design", "Games/Ironsworn", "People/Shawn Tomkin", "Games/Starforged", "People/Shawn Tomkin", "Games/Ironsworn Sundered Isles", "People/Shawn Tomkin", "Games/Thousand Year Old Vampire", "People/Tim Hutchings", "Games/For the Queen", "People/Alex Roberts", "People/Shawn Tomkin", "People/Tim Hutchings", "People/Alex Roberts"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Before Ironsworn and the solo wave it helped produce, solo TTRPG play was a marginal category — games you played alone when you couldn't find a group, adaptations of group games rather than games designed for the form. Ironsworn (2019) established solo play as its own design category with specific mechanical requirements and pleasures. The pandemic (2020–2022) dramatically expanded the audience: I", "html": "<h1>Solo TTRPG Design</h1>\n<p>#movement #solo #design #storygames #oracles</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Before Ironsworn and the solo wave it helped produce, solo TTRPG play was a marginal category — games you played alone when you couldn't find a group, adaptations of group games rather than games designed for the form. Ironsworn (2019) established solo play as its own design category with specific mechanical requirements and pleasures. The pandemic (2020–2022) dramatically expanded the audience: Ironsworn was free and well-reviewed when the demand spike hit.</p>\n<h2>What Solo Design Requires</h2>\n<strong>Oracle systems</strong> — tables and procedures for generating world responses in the absence of a GM. Must produce thematic coherence requiring interpretive judgment, not just random results. Quality oracle design is the hardest part: bad oracles produce random assemblages; good oracles produce content that feels like it came from a GM who understood the fiction.\n<strong>Progress mechanics</strong> — ways to track sustained engagement with a goal across multiple sessions without external accountability. Ironsworn's key innovation: rolling against a progress track (filled by narrative work) rather than a stat means success scales with work done, not character capability.\n<strong>Journaling structures</strong> — formats for recording and reflecting on play. Serve as both record and creative act.\n<strong>Pacing tools</strong> — structures that create urgency and momentum without another player to provide them.\n<h2>Oracle Design — Key Types</h2>\n<strong>Tables</strong> — d6/d10/d100 results for specific categories (NPC names, locations, complications). Ironsworn's tables are organized around the genres and situations the game creates, and designed for combination — multiple rolls together produce nuanced results.\n<strong>Cards</strong> — shuffle and draw for randomness with memorable physical results. Thousand Year Old Vampire, For the Queen.\n<strong>Tarot / oracle decks</strong> — full deck of prompts with symbolic associations supporting interpretation.\n<strong>The Mythic GME</strong> — meta-system for GM emulation over any game; probability-weighted yes/no oracle plus scene alteration.\n<h2>Relationship to the Cozy Wave</h2>\n<p>Solo TTRPG design and the cozy wave overlap significantly. Both reject the assumption that TTRPGs require a group organized around conflict. Both were amplified by the pandemic. Many cozy games support solo play; many solo games have a cozy or pastoral register.</p>\n<h2>Relationship to GM-less Design</h2>\n<p>Solo play is a specific case of <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/GM-less Design\">GM-less design</a> — one player filling all roles simultaneously, with oracle tools providing the unpredictability a GM would normally supply.</p>\n<h2>Key Games</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Designer</td><td>Innovation</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Ironsworn\\</td><td>Ironsworn\">td><td>Ironsworn</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\\</td><td>Shawn Tomkin\">td><td>Shawn Tomkin</a></td><td>Vow/progress system; benchmark oracle tables</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Starforged\\</td><td>Starforged\">td><td>Starforged</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\\</td><td>Shawn Tomkin\">td><td>Shawn Tomkin</a></td><td>Space opera expansion; Sector generation</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Ironsworn Sundered Isles\\</td><td>Sundered Isles\">td><td>Sundered Isles</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\\</td><td>Shawn Tomkin\">td><td>Shawn Tomkin</a></td><td>Age of Sail; naval procedures</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Thousand Year Old Vampire\\</td><td>Thousand Year Old Vampire\">td><td>Thousand Year Old Vampire</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Tim Hutchings\\</td><td>Tim Hutchings\">td><td>Tim Hutchings</a></td><td>Forgetting mechanic; grief as play</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/For the Queen\\</td><td>For the Queen\">td><td>For the Queen</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Alex Roberts\\</td><td>Alex Roberts\">td><td>Alex Roberts</a></td><td>Card prompts; intimate group or solo</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Key Designers</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\">Shawn Tomkin</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Tim Hutchings\">Tim Hutchings</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Alex Roberts\">Alex Roberts</a>"}, "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design": {"key": "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "category": "Movements", "name": "Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "tags": ["movement", "crossover", "mainstream", "contemporary"], "links": ["Games/The One Ring 2e", "People/Francesco Nepitello", "Games/Vaesen", "People/Nils Hintze", "Games/Draw Steel", "People/Matt Colville", "Games/Daggerheart", "Games/Pathfinder 2e", "People/Logan Bonner", "Games/Level Up Advanced 5e", "Games/Starforged", "People/Shawn Tomkin", "Concepts/Licensed Adaptation Design", "Publishers/Free League Publishing", "People/Francesco Nepitello", "People/Nils Hintze", "People/Matt Colville", "People/Spenser Starke and Rowan Hall", "People/Logan Bonner"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Games occupying the productive space between the mass-market D&D audience and the indie scene. Too mechanically ambitious or aesthetically distinctive for the mainstream; too well-produced and genre-legible for the pure indie market. Not defined by a design lineage — defined by audience position.", "html": "<h1>Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</h1>\n<p>#movement #crossover #mainstream #contemporary</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Games occupying the productive space between the mass-market D&D audience and the indie scene. Too mechanically ambitious or aesthetically distinctive for the mainstream; too well-produced and genre-legible for the pure indie market. Not defined by a design lineage — defined by <strong>audience position</strong>.</p>\n<h2>What Created This Space</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Growing design literacy</strong> across all audiences — Critical Role viewers 5–10 years later care about design questions</li>\n<li><strong>Production value democratization</strong> — the distinction between indie aesthetic and mainstream production has blurred</li>\n<li><strong>Kickstarter</strong> — indie-spirited designers reach mainstream-scale audiences without publisher compromise</li>\n<li><strong>OGL crisis (2023)</strong> — compressed a five-year transition into one year; dramatically expanded interest in non-D&D alternatives</li>\n<li><strong>Genre legibility</strong> — successful crossover games are legible to mainstream players (Tolkien, space opera) with design sophistication available through familiar entry points</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Key Games</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Designer</td><td>Core Approach</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The One Ring 2e\\</td><td>The One Ring 2e\">td><td>The One Ring 2e</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Francesco Nepitello\\</td><td>Nepitello\">td><td>Nepitello</a></td><td>Licensed adaptation from source content; journey mechanics</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Vaesen\\</td><td>Vaesen\">td><td>Vaesen</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Nils Hintze\\</td><td>Hintze\">td><td>Hintze</a></td><td>Nordic folkloric adaptation; grievance-based resolution</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Draw Steel\\</td><td>Draw Steel\">td><td>Draw Steel</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Colville\\</td><td>Colville\">td><td>Colville</a></td><td>Mainstream combat rebuilt from scratch</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Daggerheart\\</td><td>Daggerheart\">td><td>Daggerheart</a></td><td>Starke & Hall</td><td>Actual play tradition's own mechanics</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 2e\\</td><td>Pathfinder 2e\">td><td>Pathfinder 2e</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Logan Bonner\\</td><td>Bonner\">td><td>Bonner</a></td><td>Mainstream scale; indie-influenced mechanics</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Level Up Advanced 5e\\</td><td>Level Up: A5e\">td><td>Level Up: A5e</a></td><td>EN Publishing</td><td>5e with added depth; OSR-adjacent exploration</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Starforged\\</td><td>Ironsworn: Starforged\">td><td>Ironsworn: Starforged</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\\</td><td>Tomkin\">td><td>Tomkin</a></td><td>Solo; $1.4M Kickstarter; genre-legible</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>The Licensed Adaptation Problem</h2>\n<p>The crossover space includes many licensed adaptations. The central design problem: most TTRPG adaptations apply IP as a setting to an existing system. The best crossover games identify what the source material is actually about and design mechanics for that content.</p>\n<p>See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Licensed Adaptation Design\">Licensed Adaptation Design</a></p>\n<h2>Free League as Crossover Publisher</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Free League Publishing\">Free League Publishing</a> is the most significant publisher operating specifically in this space.\n<h2>Key People</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Francesco Nepitello\">Francesco Nepitello</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Nils Hintze\">Nils Hintze</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Colville\">Matt Colville</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Spenser Starke and Rowan Hall\">Starke & Hall</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Logan Bonner\">Logan Bonner</a>\n<h2>What It Tells Us</h2>\nThe crossover space reveals that the TTRPG ecosystem is not cleanly divided into \"mainstream D&D\" and \"indie alternatives.\" The most commercially interesting space is the middle ground: games that bring design sophistication to genres and production values that mainstream audiences can access. The OGL crisis accelerated this space's growth by motivating audiences to look for alternatives and validating the idea that non-WotC games could achieve mainstream scale."}, "Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design": {"key": "Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "category": "Movements", "name": "Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "tags": ["movement", "osr", "postOSR", "minimalist", "secondwave"], "links": ["Games/Dungeon Crawl Classics", "People/Joseph Goodman", "Games/Troika", "People/Daniel Sell", "Games/Mothership", "People/Sean McCoy", "Games/Mork Borg", "People/Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr", "Games/Into the Odd", "People/Chris McDowall", "Games/Cairn", "People/Yochai Gal", "People/Joseph Goodman", "People/Daniel Sell", "People/Sean McCoy", "People/Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr", "People/Chris McDowall", "People/Yochai Gal"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "By 2015–2019, a generation of designers had grown up with the OSR's output as a native language rather than a rediscovered one. They didn't need to recover anything because they'd never lost it. What they built was visually radical, mechanically confident, and often deliberately difficult to categorize. The conversation with TSR's legacy became optional rather than mandatory.", "html": "<h1>Post-OSR & Minimalist Design</h1>\n<p>#movement #osr #postOSR #minimalist #secondwave</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>By 2015–2019, a generation of designers had grown up with the OSR's output as a native language rather than a rediscovered one. They didn't need to recover anything because they'd never lost it. What they built was visually radical, mechanically confident, and often deliberately difficult to categorize. The conversation with TSR's legacy became optional rather than mandatory.</p>\n<h2>The Two Design Poles</h2>\n<p>The second wave produced two opposed design philosophies, best understood as a spectrum:</p>\n<strong>Maximalist (DCC end):</strong> More dice, more spectacle, more gonzo energy. The problem with later D&D was that it became too safe and too balanced. Add the dice chain, corruption tables, Mighty Deeds. Amplify.\n<strong>Minimalist (Into the Odd end):</strong> Most of what we add to RPG systems doesn't make play better — it makes it more comfortable through the illusion of control. Remove the to-hit roll. Remove skill lists. Test every element.\n<p>Both positions are legitimate. Both produced lasting, influential games.</p>\n<h2>What Changed from the First Wave</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Genre expanded</strong> beyond fantasy — Mothership (sci-fi horror), Troika! (uncategorizable)</li>\n<li><strong>Production design became a primary design tool</strong> — Mothership's operational aesthetic, Mörk Borg's hostile typography</li>\n<li><strong>Setting implied rather than stated</strong> — backgrounds, tables, and visual language replace sourcebooks</li>\n<li><strong>OSR principles became portable</strong> — lethality, rulings, player agency applied to any genre</li>\n<li><strong>Commercial model matured</strong> — itch.io + Kickstarter + zine format = viable micro-publishing</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Key Games</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Designer</td><td>Position on Spectrum</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dungeon Crawl Classics\\</td><td>DCC\">td><td>DCC</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Joseph Goodman\\</td><td>Goodman\">td><td>Goodman</a></td><td>Maximalist</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Troika\\</td><td>Troika!\">td><td>Troika!</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Daniel Sell\\</td><td>Sell\">td><td>Sell</a></td><td>Post-OSR aesthetic</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mothership\\</td><td>Mothership\">td><td>Mothership</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Sean McCoy\\</td><td>McCoy\">td><td>McCoy</a></td><td>Genre expansion</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mork Borg\\</td><td>Mörk Borg\">td><td>Mörk Borg</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr\\</td><td>Tøgersen & Nohr\">td><td>Tøgersen & Nohr</a></td><td>Art-forward</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Into the Odd\\</td><td>Into the Odd\">td><td>Into the Odd</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris McDowall\\</td><td>McDowall\">td><td>McDowall</a></td><td>Minimalist</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cairn\\</td><td>Cairn\">td><td>Cairn</a></td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Yochai Gal\\</td><td>Gal\">td><td>Gal</a></td><td>Minimalist, accessible</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Key People</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Joseph Goodman\">Joseph Goodman</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Daniel Sell\">Daniel Sell</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Sean McCoy\">Sean McCoy</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr\">Tøgersen & Nohr</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris McDowall\">Chris McDowall</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Yochai Gal\">Yochai Gal</a>"}, "Publishers/Lamentations of the Flame Princess": {"key": "Publishers/Lamentations of the Flame Princess", "category": "Publishers", "name": "Lamentations of the Flame Princess", "tags": ["publisher", "osr", "weird"], "links": ["People/James Raggi", "Games/Lamentations of the Flame Princess"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Publisher of the LotFP game line and an influential range of adventure modules. Known for high production values, weird fiction aesthetics, and commissioning notable outside designers. Controversial for some published content.", "html": "<h1>Lamentations of the Flame Princess</h1>\n<p>#publisher #osr #weird</p>\n<strong>Founded:</strong> 2010 | <strong>Owner:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/James Raggi\">James Raggi</a> | <strong>Location:</strong> Finland\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Publisher of the LotFP game line and an influential range of adventure modules. Known for high production values, weird fiction aesthetics, and commissioning notable outside designers. Controversial for some published content.</p>\n<h2>Key Publications</h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Lamentations of the Flame Princess\">LotFP core rules</a></li>\n<li><em>A Red and Pleasant Land</em> (Zak Smith)</li>\n<li><em>Qelong</em> (Kenneth Hite)</li>\n<li><em>Veins of the Earth</em> (Patrick Stuart & Scrap Princess)</li>\n<li><em>The Seclusium of Orphone</em> (Vincent Baker)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\nRaised aesthetic standards across the OSR. Demonstrated that the retroclone market could support lavishly produced, literarily ambitious work."}, "Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard": {"key": "Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard", "category": "Publishers", "name": "Rowan Rook and Decard", "tags": ["publisher", "storygames", "fitD", "uk"], "links": ["People/Grant Howitt", "People/Christopher Taylor", "Games/Spire The City Must Fall", "Games/Heart The City Beneath"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Founded: ~2016 | Owners: Grant Howitt, Christopher Taylor | Website: [rowanrookanddecard.com](https://rowanrookanddecard.com)", "html": "<h1>Rowan, Rook and Decard</h1>\n<p>#publisher #storygames #fitD #uk</p>\n<strong>Founded:</strong> ~2016 | <strong>Owners:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a>, <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Christopher Taylor\">Christopher Taylor</a> | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://rowanrookanddecard.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">rowanrookanddecard.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key Publications</h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\">Spire: The City Must Fall</a> (2018)</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Heart The City Beneath\">Heart: The City Beneath</a> (2021)</li>\n<li><em>Honey Heist</em> (free one-page game)</li>\n<li>Various short-form games</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\n<p>The leading voice of British indie TTRPG design. RR&D's games are characterized by literary quality, political consciousness, and a willingness to make the setting do significant design work. Their Patreon model for short-form games has been influential on indie publishing economics.</p>"}, "Publishers/Magpie Games": {"key": "Publishers/Magpie Games", "category": "Publishers", "name": "Magpie Games", "tags": ["publisher", "storygames", "pbtA"], "links": ["Games/Brindlewood Bay", "Games/The Between", "People/Jason Cordova"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "One of the leading PbtA publishers. Home to Jason Cordova's mystery games and several other significant PbtA titles.", "html": "<h1>Magpie Games</h1>\n<p>#publisher #storygames #pbtA</p>\n<strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://magpiegames.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">magpiegames.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key Publications</h2>\n<ul><li><em>Masks: A New Generation</em> (PbtA superhero)</li>\n<li><em>Urban Shadows</em></li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\">Brindlewood Bay</a> (2020)</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Between\">The Between</a> (2022)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\n<p>One of the leading PbtA publishers. Home to <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Cordova\">Jason Cordova</a>'s mystery games and several other significant PbtA titles.</p>"}, "Publishers/The Merry Mushmen": {"key": "Publishers/The Merry Mushmen", "category": "Publishers", "name": "The Merry Mushmen", "tags": ["publisher", "osr", "zines", "anthology"], "links": ["Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Founded: ~2018 | Members: Éric Nieudan (editor), Olivier Revenu (publisher/layout) | Website: [themerrymushmen.com](https://themerrymushmen.com)", "html": "<h1>The Merry Mushmen</h1>\n<p>#publisher #osr #zines #anthology</p>\n<strong>Founded:</strong> ~2018 | <strong>Members:</strong> Éric Nieudan (editor), Olivier Revenu (publisher/layout) | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://themerrymushmen.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">themerrymushmen.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Publishers of Knock! magazine — the closest thing the zine-era OSR had to a flagship anthology. The Merry Mushmen was formed by Éric Nieudan (Dublin-based game designer and writer; also designed Macchiato Monsters) and Olivier Revenu (graphic designer and publisher in the Basque country; also publishes Battles wargaming magazine). Revenu conceived the idea for a print compendium of OSR blog material in winter 2018; Nieudan came aboard as editor.</p>\n<h2>Key Publications</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Knock!</em> issue 1</td><td>2021</td><td>Kickstarted December 2020 (1,600+ backers); 200+ pages</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Knock!</em> issues 2–4</td><td>2021–present</td><td>Each issue larger and more widely backed than the last</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Knock! Magazine</h2>\n<ul><li>200+ full-colour pages per issue</li>\n<li>Collects adventures, essays, random tables, house rules, design discussions</li>\n<li>Layout evocative of Mörk Borg — demonstrates OSR anthology can match second-wave aesthetic ambitions</li>\n<li>Demonstrated that the zine-era OSR was capable of critical discourse, not just production</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing\">Zine Scene & OSR Publishing</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Publishers/Wizards of the Coast": {"key": "Publishers/Wizards of the Coast", "category": "Publishers", "name": "Wizards of the Coast", "tags": ["publisher", "mainstream", "wotc"], "links": ["Games/DD 3e and d20 OGL", "Games/DD 4th Edition", "Games/DD 5th Edition", "People/Monte Cook", "People/Mike Mearls", "People/Jeremy Crawford", "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing", "Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Founded: 1990 | Acquired TSR: 1997 | Acquired by Hasbro: 1999 | Website: [dnd.wizards.com](https://dnd.wizards.com)", "html": "<h1>Wizards of the Coast</h1>\n<p>#publisher #mainstream #wotc</p>\n<strong>Founded:</strong> 1990 | <strong>Acquired TSR:</strong> 1997 | <strong>Acquired by Hasbro:</strong> 1999 | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://dnd.wizards.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">dnd.wizards.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>The publisher of D&D since 1997. WotC's decisions — OGL, edition transitions, OGL crisis — have shaped the entire TTRPG landscape, often by catalyzing reactions against them.</p>\n<h2>Key Publications</h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 3e and d20 OGL\">D&D 3e</a> (2000) + OGL</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 4th Edition\">D&D 4e</a> (2008) + GSL</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 5th Edition\">D&D 5e</a> (2014)</li>\n<li>D&D 2024 (One D&D)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Key People</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Monte Cook\">Monte Cook</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Mike Mearls\">Mike Mearls</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeremy Crawford\">Jeremy Crawford</a>\n<h2>Key Events</h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">OGL publication (2000)</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/D&D Edition Wars\">Edition Wars</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OGL Crisis 2023\">OGL Crisis 2023</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Publishers/Paizo": {"key": "Publishers/Paizo", "category": "Publishers", "name": "Paizo", "tags": ["publisher", "mainstream", "pathfinder"], "links": ["Games/Pathfinder 1e", "Games/Pathfinder 2e"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Founded: 2002 (as WotC magazine publisher) | Independent: 2004 | Website: [paizo.com](https://paizo.com)", "html": "<h1>Paizo</h1>\n<p>#publisher #mainstream #pathfinder</p>\n<strong>Founded:</strong> 2002 (as WotC magazine publisher) | <strong>Independent:</strong> 2004 | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://paizo.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">paizo.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Originally published Dragon and Dungeon magazines under WotC license. When WotC ended that arrangement (2007), Paizo pivoted to publishing Pathfinder — a D&D 3.5-compatible game that became WotC's primary competitor. Led the ORC License effort in 2023.</p>\n<h2>Key Publications</h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 1e\">Pathfinder 1e</a> (2009)</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 2e\">Pathfinder 2e</a> (2019)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Key Events</h2>\n<ul><li>Created ORC License (2023) in response to OGL crisis</li>\n<li>Pathfinder outsold D&D during the 4e era</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\nPaizo has twice positioned itself as a refuge when WotC alienated its playerbase (4e era; OGL crisis). The ORC License is their most lasting contribution to the broader TTRPG ecosystem."}, "Publishers/Necrotic Gnome": {"key": "Publishers/Necrotic Gnome", "category": "Publishers", "name": "Necrotic Gnome", "tags": ["publisher", "osr", "neotrad"], "links": ["People/Gavin Norman", "Games/Old-School Essentials", "Games/Dolmenwood"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Founded: ~2010 | Owner: Gavin Norman | Website: [necroticgnome.com](https://necroticgnome.com)", "html": "<h1>Necrotic Gnome</h1>\n<p>#publisher #osr #neotrad</p>\n<strong>Founded:</strong> ~2010 | <strong>Owner:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Gavin Norman\">Gavin Norman</a> | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://necroticgnome.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">necroticgnome.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key Publications</h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Old-School Essentials\">Old-School Essentials</a> (2019)</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dolmenwood\">Dolmenwood</a> (2024)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\n<p>Responsible for the two most important neo-trad publications: OSE (the platform) and Dolmenwood (the setting). Norman's design philosophy — clarity, modularity, separation of rules from setting — defines the neo-trad approach.</p>"}, "Publishers/North Wind Adventures": {"key": "Publishers/North Wind Adventures", "category": "Publishers", "name": "North Wind Adventures", "tags": ["publisher", "osr", "swordandsorcery"], "links": ["People/Jeff Talanian", "Games/Hyperborea"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Sole publisher of Hyperborea. Represents the OSR's Sword & Sorcery tradition — pulp literary influence, high lethality, deep genre fidelity to Clark Ashton Smith and Robert E. Howard.", "html": "<h1>North Wind Adventures</h1>\n<p>#publisher #osr #swordandsorcery</p>\n<strong>Owner:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeff Talanian\">Jeff Talanian</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key Publications</h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Hyperborea\">Hyperborea</a> (2012, 3rd ed. 2022)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\n<p>Sole publisher of Hyperborea. Represents the OSR's Sword & Sorcery tradition — pulp literary influence, high lethality, deep genre fidelity to Clark Ashton Smith and Robert E. Howard.</p>"}, "Publishers/Exalted Funeral": {"key": "Publishers/Exalted Funeral", "category": "Publishers", "name": "Exalted Funeral", "tags": ["publisher", "osr", "zines", "retailer", "curator"], "links": ["Games/Dolmenwood", "Publishers/Necrotic Gnome", "Publishers/Necrotic Gnome", "Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Founded: 2018 | Founders: Cristin and Matt Kelley | Location: Idaho, US | Website: [exaltedfuneral.com](https://www.exaltedfuneral.com)", "html": "<h1>Exalted Funeral</h1>\n<p>#publisher #osr #zines #retailer #curator</p>\n<strong>Founded:</strong> 2018 | <strong>Founders:</strong> Cristin and Matt Kelley | <strong>Location:</strong> Idaho, US | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://www.exaltedfuneral.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">exaltedfuneral.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>The most important independent TTRPG retailer and publisher of the zine era. Founded in 2018 by Cristin and Matt Kelley, Exalted Funeral curated OSR and indie games with genuine aesthetic and editorial taste, offered Kickstarter fulfillment services, and became a destination for players who trusted their judgment. A stock listing at Exalted Funeral became a meaningful quality signal in a market producing enormous volume.</p>\n<p>Also a publisher and co-publisher in their own right — co-publishing Old-School Essentials box sets and co-publishing the Dolmenwood Kickstarter campaign with Necrotic Gnome.</p>\n<h2>Key Publications & Co-Publications</h2>\n<ul><li>Old-School Essentials Fantasy RPG Box Sets (co-publisher)</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dolmenwood\">Dolmenwood</a> Kickstarter (co-publisher with <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Necrotic Gnome\">Necrotic Gnome</a>)</li>\n<li>Various indie and OSR titles</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\nExalted Funeral's curation function — selecting what to stock and publish — is as significant as any individual game it carried. In a market where discoverability was a serious challenge, a trusted curatorial voice shaped what the community discovered.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Co-publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Necrotic Gnome\">Necrotic Gnome</a> (OSE, Dolmenwood)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing\">Zine Scene & OSR Publishing</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Publishers/Wet Ink Games": {"key": "Publishers/Wet Ink Games", "category": "Publishers", "name": "Wet Ink Games", "tags": ["publisher", "indie", "horror", "crossover", "louisville"], "links": ["Concepts/+One System", "Games/Never Going Home", "Games/Precious Things", "Concepts/+One System", "Concepts/+One System", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Founded: 2015 | Location: Louisville, KY\nFounders: Brandon K. Aten & Matthew Orr\nHouse system: +One System", "html": "<h1>Wet Ink Games</h1>\n<p>#publisher #indie #horror #crossover #louisville</p>\n<strong>Founded:</strong> 2015 | <strong>Location:</strong> Louisville, KY <strong>Founders:</strong> Brandon K. Aten & Matthew Orr <strong>House system:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/+One System\">+One System</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A Louisville-based indie TTRPG publisher founded by Brandon K. Aten and Matthew Orr — long-time gaming partners who had previously worked as freelance writers for Palladium Books, Third Eye Games, and others. Their stated goals as a company are two: to make games that fill voids in the market (unusual settings, underrepresented histories, diverse creators) and to make physically beautiful products through offset print runs rather than print-on-demand.</p>\n<h2>Design Philosophy</h2>\n<p>Wet Ink describes itself as making \"fresh, indie games before the ink dries\" — a commitment to original settings and underrepresented stories. Every major release occupies a genre corner few others inhabit: WWI horror, Roman collapse, Prohibition-era Chinatown, psychic kids on the run.</p>\n<h2>Key Releases</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Year</td><td>Notes</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Wild Skies</td><td>2017</td><td>Diesel-punk 1930s; anthropomorphic animal pilots</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Never Going Home\\</td><td>Never Going Home\">td><td>Never Going Home</a></td><td>2019</td><td>WWI eldritch horror; ENNIE-nominated Best Art 2020</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Tenebria: Remnant of Rome</td><td>2020</td><td>Surviving the collapse of empire</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Jiangshi: Blood in the Banquet Hall</td><td>2021</td><td>Co-published with Game and a Curry; Chinese-American family restaurant 1920s Chinatown</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Psychic Kids</td><td>2022</td><td>Kids with psychic powers fleeing a mysterious Facility</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Precious Things\\</td><td>Precious Things\">td><td>Precious Things</a></td><td>2024+</td><td>Tiny dragons hoarding mundane objects; cozy</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Heckin' Good Doggos</td><td>Recent</td><td>You are beloved family dogs saving your humans</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>System</h2>\nAll major releases use the <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/+One System\">+One System</a>, designed primarily by Brandon K. Aten. The system travels across the full tonal range of Wet Ink's catalog — from eldritch horror to cozy fantasy — demonstrating genuine flexibility.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>People: Brandon K. Aten (system designer), Matthew Orr (co-founder)</li>\n<li>System: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/+One System\">+One System</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Publishers/lumpley games": {"key": "Publishers/lumpley games", "category": "Publishers", "name": "lumpley games", "tags": ["publisher", "storygames", "pbtA", "forge"], "links": ["People/Vincent Baker", "People/Meguey Baker", "Games/Dogs in the Vineyard", "Games/Apocalypse World"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Owner: Vincent Baker & Meguey Baker | Website: [lumpley.games](https://lumpley.games)", "html": "<h1>lumpley games</h1>\n<p>#publisher #storygames #pbtA #forge</p>\n<strong>Owner:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a> & <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Meguey Baker\">Meguey Baker</a> | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://lumpley.games\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">lumpley.games</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key Publications</h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dogs in the Vineyard\">Dogs in the Vineyard</a> (2004)</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Apocalypse World\">Apocalypse World</a> (2010)</li>\n<li><em>Murderous Ghosts</em></li>\n<li><em>Apocalypse Keys</em></li>\n<li>Various Baker short games</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\n<p>The most historically important indie TTRPG publisher. lumpley games published two of the most influential indie games ever written and originated the PbtA design language.</p>"}, "Publishers/Monte Cook Games": {"key": "Publishers/Monte Cook Games", "category": "Publishers", "name": "Monte Cook Games", "tags": ["publisher", "mainstream", "indie"], "links": ["People/Monte Cook"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Founded: 2012 | Owner: Monte Cook | Website: [montecookgames.com](https://www.montecookgames.com)", "html": "<h1>Monte Cook Games</h1>\n<p>#publisher #mainstream #indie</p>\n<strong>Founded:</strong> 2012 | <strong>Owner:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Monte Cook\">Monte Cook</a> | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://www.montecookgames.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">montecookgames.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key Publications</h2>\n<ul><li><em>Numenera</em> (2013)</li>\n<li><em>Cypher System</em> (2015)</li>\n<li><em>The Strange</em></li>\n<li><em>Invisible Sun</em></li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\n<p>Demonstrated that a D&D 3e pedigree designer could successfully build a non-D&D game via Kickstarter. The Cypher System is a streamlined universal system with a large following.</p>"}, "Publishers/Free League Publishing": {"key": "Publishers/Free League Publishing", "category": "Publishers", "name": "Free League Publishing", "tags": ["publisher", "crossover", "mainstream", "swedish"], "links": ["Games/Vaesen", "People/Nils Hintze", "Games/The One Ring 2e", "People/Francesco Nepitello", "Games/Mork Borg", "People/Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Founded: 2011 | Location: Sweden | Website: [freeleaguepublishing.com](https://freeleaguepublishing.com)", "html": "<h1>Free League Publishing</h1>\n<p>#publisher #crossover #mainstream #swedish</p>\n<strong>Founded:</strong> 2011 | <strong>Location:</strong> Sweden | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://freeleaguepublishing.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">freeleaguepublishing.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Swedish publisher occupying a specific market position: more expensive and more designed than mass-market d20 products, more accessible and more conventionally beautiful than most indie games. High-quality physical objects; significant artwork budgets; consistent Kickstarter success.</p>\n<p>The unifying thread across their catalog: each game attempts to identify what the source material or genre is actually about and design mechanics for that content. The indie tradition's design insight applied at mainstream-adjacent production scale.</p>\n<h2>Key Publications</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Year</td><td>Designer</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Vaesen\\</td><td>Vaesen\">td><td>Vaesen</a></td><td>2021</td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Nils Hintze\\</td><td>Nils Hintze\">td><td>Nils Hintze</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The One Ring 2e\\</td><td>The One Ring 2e\">td><td>The One Ring 2e</a></td><td>2022</td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Francesco Nepitello\\</td><td>Francesco Nepitello\">td><td>Francesco Nepitello</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mork Borg\\</td><td>Mörk Borg\">td><td>Mörk Borg</a></td><td>2019</td><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr\\</td><td>Tøgersen & Nohr\">td><td>Tøgersen & Nohr</a></td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Alien RPG</em></td><td>2019</td><td>Andrew E.C. Gaska</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Blade Runner RPG</em></td><td>2022</td><td>Tomas Härenstam</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Forbidden Lands</em></td><td>2018</td><td>Tomas Härenstam et al.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Dragonbane</em></td><td>2023</td><td>—</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>The Year Zero Engine</h2>\n<p>Most Free League games use variants of the Year Zero Engine — a dice pool system adapted for each game's specific genre requirements.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Publishers/MCDM Productions": {"key": "Publishers/MCDM Productions", "category": "Publishers", "name": "MCDM Productions", "tags": ["publisher", "mainstream", "postOGL", "crossover"], "links": ["People/Matt Colville", "Games/Draw Steel", "People/Matt Colville", "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Founded: ~2019 | Owner: Matt Colville | Design team: Colville, James Introcaso, et al. | Website: [mcdmproductions.com](https://www.mcdmproductions.com)", "html": "<h1>MCDM Productions</h1>\n<p>#publisher #mainstream #postOGL #crossover</p>\n<strong>Founded:</strong> ~2019 | <strong>Owner:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Colville\">Matt Colville</a> | <strong>Design team:</strong> Colville, James Introcaso, et al. | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://www.mcdmproductions.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">mcdmproductions.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Founded on Matt Colville's YouTube audience, MCDM represents a crossover position: a mainstream-audience publisher with genuine design sophistication, approaching TTRPG design from a diagnosis of what D&D gets wrong rather than from indie theory. Built audience through 5e supplemental content, then pivoted to their own game system.</p>\n<h2>Key Publications</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Kingdoms & Warfare</em></td><td>2021</td><td>5e mass combat and domain supplement</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Flee, Mortals!</em></td><td>2023</td><td>5e monster book; distinctive tactical monster design</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Draw Steel\\</td><td>Draw Steel\">td><td>Draw Steel</a></td><td>2024</td><td>Non-OGL fantasy RPG; $4.7M Kickstarter</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Draw Steel's Design Position</h2>\n<p>Draw Steel's diagnosis: 5e's combat less interesting than it should be; monsters tactically indistinct; action economy flat. Response: richer action economy from 4e's tactical depth; monster design around tactical identity; heroes designed around what specific things they uniquely do. Explicitly a 4e rehabilitation without 4e's aesthetic failures.</p>\n<h2>The Crossover Tension</h2>\n<p>MCDM built its audience through 5e content, then asked that audience to follow them to an incompatible system. Conversion rate lower than anticipated — many follow MCDM for YouTube content and 5e supplements without moving to Draw Steel. Characteristic of the crossover space: creator loyalty doesn't automatically equal system loyalty.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Key person: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Colville\">Matt Colville</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OGL Crisis 2023\">OGL Crisis 2023</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Licensed Design</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Concepts/2d6 Bell Curve and PbtA Reward Cycles": {"key": "Concepts/2d6 Bell Curve and PbtA Reward Cycles", "category": "Concepts", "name": "2d6 Bell Curve and PbtA Reward Cycles", "tags": ["concept", "pbtA", "design", "storygames", "resolution"], "links": ["Concepts/Lures (Belonging Outside Belonging)", "Games/Apocalypse World", "People/Vincent Baker", "Games/Dream Askew", "People/Avery Alder", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)", "Concepts/Lures (Belonging Outside Belonging)"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "The fundamental resolution mechanic of Powered by the Apocalypse games: roll 2d6, add a relevant stat modifier, compare to a threshold.", "html": "<h1>2d6 Bell Curve, PbtA Reward Cycles & Playbook Design</h1>\n<p>#concept #pbtA #design #storygames #resolution</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The 2d6 Bell Curve</h2>\n<p>The fundamental resolution mechanic of Powered by the Apocalypse games: roll 2d6, add a relevant stat modifier, compare to a threshold.</p>\n<ul><li><strong>10+:</strong> Full success</li>\n<li><strong>7-9:</strong> Partial success / success with complication</li>\n<li><strong>6-:</strong> Miss — the MC makes a move</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>Why 2d6 instead of d20:</strong> The d20 produces a flat distribution — every result from 1 to 20 is equally likely. The 2d6 produces a bell curve — results cluster toward the middle (7 is the most common single result). With a +1 stat modifier:\n<ul><li>6- (miss): ~28%</li>\n<li>7-9 (partial): ~42%</li>\n<li>10+ (full success): ~30%</li>\n</ul>\nThe statistical consequence: <strong>partial success (7-9) is the most common outcome.</strong> Not full success, not failure — the complicated middle. This is not accidental. Baker designed the resolution system to make complication the statistical norm rather than the exception. Every session, most rolls land in the messy middle where something good happens <em>and</em> something bad happens or a hard choice must be made.\n<strong>The design argument:</strong> partial success is more dramatically interesting than clean success or clean failure. It generates situations rather than resolving them. A roll that produces \"you get what you want, but at a cost\" is a scene-generator; a roll that produces \"you succeed\" is a scene-ender. PbtA games are calibrated to produce scene-generators most of the time.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Keys and Reward Cycles</h2>\n<strong>Origin:</strong> Clinton R. Nixon's <em>The Shadow of Yesterday</em> (2004) — <strong>Keys</strong> as a precursor mechanic.\n<p>A Key is a specific behavior or situation tied to a character's core motivations, values, or drives. When a character acts on their Key — when the Key \"fires\" — they earn XP. Examples: \"Hit the Key of the Berserker when you attack someone in a blind rage.\" \"Hit the Key of Conscience when you compromise your mission to help someone in need.\"</p>\n<p>Keys encode a specific theory of advancement: <strong>characters should grow by doing what they do, not by accumulating abstract experience.</strong> A thief earns XP by stealing. A warrior earns XP by fighting. A diplomat earns XP by negotiating. The advancement is tied to the fiction the character actually inhabits.</p>\n<strong>PbtA's end-of-session move</strong> (from Dungeon World) is a descendant of this thinking. At session's end, players ask questions — \"Did we learn something new and important?\" \"Did we loot a treasure?\" \"Did someone grow closer to you?\" — and mark XP for yes answers. The XP system reflects on what kind of session was played rather than on individual mechanical outcomes.\n<strong>The Monsterhearts advance</strong> goes further: characters can advance by marking XP when they act on their Darkest Self or their Strings — their most problematic drives. The reward system incentivizes the behavior that is most dramatically interesting and genre-appropriate.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Playbook Design</h2>\n<p>A Playbook is Dream Askew / Apocalypse World's term for the character sheet — a folded document presenting a character archetype with their moves, stats, and advancement options.</p>\n<strong>What the Playbook format does:</strong>\n<strong>Archetypes, not builds.</strong> In d20 games, characters are built from components (class, feats, skills, equipment). In PbtA, characters are archetypes — the Hardholder, the Battlebabe, the Gunlugger. The Playbook is the archetype made tangible: you are <em>the</em> Hardholder, not <em>a</em> fighter who chose certain options. This produces immediate character identity before a single session has been played.\n<strong>The moves list as implied genre fiction.</strong> A Playbook's moves are not merely mechanical options — they're a description of what this archetype does in fiction. The Battlebabe's moves tell you that Battlebabes are beautiful, dangerous, provocative, and manipulative — not through flavor text but through the specific fiction-triggering-mechanics on their sheet. The moves <em>are</em> the character description.\n<strong>Unique occupancy.</strong> Most PbtA games allow only one player per Playbook per table. This ensures the archetypes remain distinctive — there is only one Hardholder in the settlement, one Maelstrom user in the group. Niche protection through structural scarcity.\n<strong>Advancement as character evolution.</strong> Playbooks have advancement options that represent how an archetype develops over time. Taking an advance from another playbook represents the character growing beyond their original archetype. The advancement system tells a story about how characters change rather than just getting more capable.\n<strong>The Playbook as design pitch.</strong> From a designer's perspective, each Playbook is a concentrated design document: this is what this character does, what they care about, how they interact with the world, and how they grow. Writing a Playbook forces a designer to answer all of those questions precisely. It's one of the most useful design tools in the PbtA tradition.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Weak Moves, Strong Moves, and Token Economies</h2>\n<p>In Belonging Outside Belonging (Dream Askew, Dream Apart), the 2d6 resolution is replaced with a token economy:</p>\n<ul><li><strong>Weak moves</strong> — available anytime; grant a token; involve vulnerability, setback, or exposure</li>\n<li><strong>Regular moves</strong> — available anytime; neither grant nor cost tokens; produce outcomes without mechanical stakes</li>\n<li><strong>Strong moves</strong> — require spending a token; allow significant narrative action or resolution</li>\n</ul>\nThe token economy replaces random resolution with a pacing system: you must accumulate vulnerability (weak moves) before you can act with power (strong moves). The rhythm of play is built into the economy rather than generated by probability.\n<strong>The Lure</strong> sits alongside this: see <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Lures (Belonging Outside Belonging)\">Lures</a> for how the BoB system creates pull between characters through a fourth move type that rewards others for engaging with your character.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Origin: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Apocalypse World\">Apocalypse World</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a></li>\n<li>Keys precursor: Clinton R. Nixon (<em>The Shadow of Yesterday</em>)</li>\n<li>BoB token economy: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dream Askew\">Dream Askew</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Related: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)\">Moves</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Lures (Belonging Outside Belonging)\">Lures</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Concepts/The Mystery Genre Problem": {"key": "Concepts/The Mystery Genre Problem", "category": "Concepts", "name": "The Mystery Genre Problem", "tags": ["concept", "mystery", "design", "storygames"], "links": ["People/Robin D. Laws", "People/Jason Cordova", "Games/Brindlewood Bay", "Games/The Between"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Mystery fiction and TTRPGs have an uncomfortable relationship. The problem is structural:", "html": "<h1>The Mystery Genre Problem</h1>\n<p>#concept #mystery #design #storygames</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Structural Problem</h2>\n<p>Mystery fiction and TTRPGs have an uncomfortable relationship. The problem is structural:</p>\n<p>A mystery has a specific shape — crime, clues, solution. In fiction, the author controls both clues and solution, ensuring they're sufficient and that the revelation lands correctly. In a TTRPG, the GM knows the solution and the players don't. This creates several failure modes:</p>\n<ul><li><strong>The gotcha problem</strong> — players pursue logical lines of inquiry that don't lead to the GM's predetermined answer; feel punished for not guessing correctly</li>\n<li><strong>The railroad problem</strong> — to ensure players find the solution, the GM steers toward relevant clues; players experience loss of agency</li>\n<li><strong>The Schrodinger's culprit problem</strong> — some GMs don't decide until accusation; requires extraordinary improvisation; produces variable coherence</li>\n<li><strong>The failure state problem</strong> — failed investigation checks often mean nothing happens; dramatically inert</li>\n<li><strong>The information asymmetry problem</strong> — GM has complete knowledge; asymmetry feels adversarial in mysteries specifically</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Two Solutions</h2>\n<strong>GUMSHOE</strong> (<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Robin D. Laws\">Robin D. Laws</a>, 2007) — separate clue discovery from clue interpretation. Clue discovery is automatic if you have the relevant ability; skills are spent for additional information. Solves the failure state problem; leaves gotcha and railroad partially in place.\n<strong>The Conspiracy Mechanic</strong> (<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Cordova\">Jason Cordova</a>, 2020) — eliminate the predetermined solution entirely. Keeper prepares elements (suspects, clues, Conspiracy themes) but not a solution. Players assemble theory from evidence; if plausible and consistent with the Conspiracy, it becomes true. Solves all five failure modes simultaneously at the cost of requiring a different conception of what the Keeper does.\n<h2>Why the Conspiracy Mechanic Is a Breakthrough</h2>\n<ul><li>No predetermined answer to miss → gotcha problem disappears</li>\n<li>Any plausible theory can be correct → railroad problem disappears</li>\n<li>Keeper discovers solution alongside players → adversarial dynamic becomes collaborative</li>\n<li>Any theory fitting the evidence works → pressure to find every clue reduced</li>\n<li>Players author the solution → genuine ownership of the mystery</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Key Games</h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\">Brindlewood Bay</a> — Conspiracy mechanic origin</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Between\">The Between</a> — Conspiracy mechanic developed</li>\n<li><em>Trail of Cthulhu</em> — GUMSHOE implementation</li>\n</ul>"}, "Concepts/Lures (Belonging Outside Belonging)": {"key": "Concepts/Lures (Belonging Outside Belonging)", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Lures (Belonging Outside Belonging)", "tags": ["concept", "storygames", "BoB", "design", "token", "gmless"], "links": ["Games/Dream Askew", "Games/Wanderhome", "People/Avery Alder", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Movements/GM-less Design", "Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)", "Concepts/Cozy and Pastoral Play", "Games/Dream Askew"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "A Lure is a per-character mechanic in the Belonging Outside Belonging system (Dream Askew, Dream Apart, Begin Again, Wanderhome-adjacent games) that defines the specific kind of interaction a character invites from others — and that mechanically rewards the other player for engaging with it.", "html": "<h1>Lures — Belonging Outside Belonging</h1>\n<p>#concept #storygames #BoB #design #token #gmless</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A Lure is a per-character mechanic in the Belonging Outside Belonging system (Dream Askew, Dream Apart, Begin Again, Wanderhome-adjacent games) that defines the specific kind of interaction a character <em>invites from others</em> — and that mechanically rewards the <em>other player</em> for engaging with it.</p>\n<p>Structure: <strong>\"When [another character does X with/to/for your character], they gain a token.\"</strong></p>\n<p>Examples from Dream Askew: <ul><li>The Hawker's Lure: <em>\"When a character offers you a new gig, or gets hooked on your supply\"</em> — the player who initiates that interaction gains a token</li> <li>The Midwife's Lure: <em>\"Whenever someone places themselves in your care, or follows your advice\"</em></li> <li>The Iris's Lure: <em>\"Whenever someone invites you to use your psychic gifts on them\"</em></li> </ul> ---</p>\n<h2>What Makes It Distinctive</h2>\n<p>In most RPGs — including PbtA — the primary reward economy runs through your <em>own</em> actions. You roll your moves, you spend your resources, you earn your advancement. The Lure inverts this for a specific mechanic: the character defines what kind of attention they <em>attract</em>, and another player is rewarded for delivering it.</p>\n<p>This creates <strong>pull between characters</strong> without requiring a GM to engineer encounters. In a GM-less system, something must motivate players to engage with each other's characters rather than playing in parallel. The Lure is that mechanism.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters Mechanically</h2>\n<strong>Niche protection through invitation.</strong> Each Lure defines a character's social niche not in terms of what they can do but in terms of what they draw from others. The Midwife doesn't just have healing moves — she has a Lure that makes other characters want to place themselves in her care, because doing so earns them a token.\n<strong>Replaces the GM's encounter-engineering role.</strong> In a GMed game, the GM can create situations that force characters into meaningful interaction. In a GM-less game, the Lure does this work: it gives players a mechanical incentive to seek out specific characters and engage with them in specific ways.\n<strong>Creates character interdependence.</strong> A table where every character has a Lure that other characters want to trigger produces a web of mutual interest and pull. Characters need each other — not just fictionally but mechanically.\n<strong>As noted in community design discussion:</strong> \"Not having lures for characters can mean that they're less motivated to approach one another\" — the Lure is not decorative, it is structurally load-bearing in GM-less play.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Relationship to Other Mechanics</h2>\n<strong>vs. PbtA Moves:</strong> PbtA Moves are triggered by your own actions in the fiction; they generate outcomes for you. Lures are triggered by <em>others'</em> actions toward you; they generate outcomes for <em>them</em>. Complementary but distinct logics.\n<strong>vs. Monsterhearts Strings:</strong> Strings track accumulated social leverage between characters. Lures define standing invitations — a permanent condition rather than an accumulated resource.\n<strong>vs. Blades in the Dark's Devil's Bargain:</strong> Both offer tokens in exchange for accepting complications. But a Lure is character-specific and relationally directed; it defines <em>this character's</em> gravitational field in the social space of the game.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Belonging Outside Belonging System Context</h2>\n<p>Lures are one of three move types in BoB: <ul><li><strong>Weak moves</strong> — available anytime; grant a token; involve vulnerability or setback</li> <li><strong>Strong moves</strong> — require a token; allow significant narrative action</li> <li><strong>Lures</strong> — passive conditions that reward <em>other</em> players for specific interactions with your character</li> </ul> The Lure sits alongside the token economy as the mechanism that makes BoB's GM-less system produce genuine character interconnection rather than parallel solo play.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Games Using Lures</h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dream Askew\">Dream Askew</a> — origin; queer post-apocalyptic community</li>\n<li><em>Dream Apart</em> — Benjamin Rosenbaum; Jewish shtetl fantasy</li>\n<li><em>Begin Again</em> — Lures in a different community context</li>\n<li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Wanderhome\">Wanderhome</a> — Lure-adjacent mechanics via Natures and token economy</li>\n<li><em>Sleepaway</em> — Jay Dragon; summer camp horror</li>\n<li>200+ BoB-tagged games on itch.io as of 2024</li>\n</ul>\n---\n<h2>Designer</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a> — Dream Askew / Dream Apart (2018, with Benjamin Rosenbaum)\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a></li>\n<li>Related concepts: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/GM-less Design\">GM-less Design</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)\">Moves</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Cozy and Pastoral Play\">Cozy & Pastoral Play</a></li>\n<li>Game: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dream Askew\">Dream Askew</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Concepts/Position and Effect": {"key": "Concepts/Position and Effect", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Position and Effect", "tags": ["concept", "fitD", "design", "storygames"], "links": ["Games/Blades in the Dark", "People/John Harper", "Games/Blades in the Dark", "Games/Band of Blades", "Games/Scum and Villainy", "Games/Spire The City Must Fall"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "The core resolution framework of Forged in the Dark games, replacing the pass/fail binary with a two-axis system evaluated before rolling.", "html": "<h1>Position and Effect</h1>\n<p>#concept #fitD #design #storygames</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>The core resolution framework of Forged in the Dark games, replacing the pass/fail binary with a two-axis system evaluated before rolling.</p>\n<strong>Position</strong> — how risky is the situation? <ul><li><em>Controlled</em> — in command; a miss has minor consequences</li> <li><em>Risky</em> — standard danger; a miss has serious consequences</li> <li><em>Desperate</em> — in trouble; a miss has severe consequences</li> </ul> <strong>Effect</strong> — how much impact will success have? <ul><li><em>Limited</em> — partial progress; even full success moves things forward minimally</li> <li><em>Standard</em> — normal impact</li> <li><em>Great</em> — exceptional impact</li> </ul> <h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Both axes are set by the GM before the roll and are visible to players. This means:</p>\n<p>1. <strong>Informed decisions</strong> — players know what they're risking before they risk it 2. <strong>Richer outcome space</strong> — rolling well in Desperate/Great is very different from rolling the same number in Controlled/Limited 3. <strong>Negotiable</strong> — players can accept worse position for better effect, or vice versa 4. <strong>Failure is always interesting</strong> — failing in Desperate/Great means something serious went wrong AND the attempt had the potential to matter enormously</p>\n<h2>The Devil's Bargain</h2>\n<p>Before rolling, the GM or another player can offer a Devil's Bargain: one extra die in exchange for a complication regardless of the outcome. Creates dramatic material from the resolution process itself, not just its outcome. Players always have agency over their risk profile.</p>\n<h2>Origin</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Blades in the Dark\">Blades in the Dark</a> (2017) — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a>\n<h2>Key Games Using Position/Effect</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Blades in the Dark\">Blades in the Dark</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Band of Blades\">Band of Blades</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Scum and Villainy\">Scum and Villainy</a>\n(Note: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\">Spire</a> uses a similar but distinct approach — stress/difficulty rather than position/effect)"}, "Concepts/Licensed Adaptation Design": {"key": "Concepts/Licensed Adaptation Design", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Licensed Adaptation Design", "tags": ["concept", "crossover", "design", "licensed"], "links": ["People/Francesco Nepitello", "People/Nils Hintze", "Games/The One Ring 2e", "Games/Vaesen"], "lineage": "crossover", "summary": "Most TTRPG adaptations apply IP as a setting to an existing system (usually d20). This produces games that look like the source material from outside but play like generic D&D — because the mechanics assume D&D's priorities rather than the source material's.", "html": "<h1>Licensed Adaptation Design</h1>\n<p>#concept #crossover #design #licensed</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Central Problem</h2>\n<p>Most TTRPG adaptations apply IP as a setting to an existing system (usually d20). This produces games that look like the source material from outside but play like generic D&D — because the mechanics assume D&D's priorities rather than the source material's.</p>\n<p>The problem: <strong>mechanical structure shapes what play is easy and what is hard.</strong> Apply Tolkien's setting to D&D's mechanics and players optimize combat encounters in Middle-earth, because that's what D&D's mechanics make central.</p>\n<h2>The Design Question</h2>\n<p>Not \"what system should we use for this IP?\" but <strong>\"what is this property actually about, and what mechanics would make that the primary experience?\"</strong></p>\n<h2>Two Models</h2>\n<strong>The One Ring</strong> (<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Francesco Nepitello\">Nepitello</a>) — Middle-earth is about: long journeys, accumulated experience, maintaining hope and integrity against creeping darkness, the value of community. Mechanics: Journey system, Shadow/Hope opposition, Fellowship Pool.\n<strong>Vaesen</strong> (<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Nils Hintze\">Hintze</a>) — Nordic folklore is about: beings with ancient claims meeting modernity; resolution through understanding. Mechanics: grievance-based vaesen, investigation-forward play, combat as suboptimal.\n<h2>What Good Licensed Adaptation Does</h2>\n<p>1. Identifies what the source material is actually about (not just its genre) 2. Designs mechanical weight around that content 3. Makes suboptimal behavior (combat in TOR; killing vaesen in Vaesen) available but not mechanically rewarded 4. Encodes the source material's moral sensibility in incentive structures</p>\n<h2>Key Games</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The One Ring 2e\">The One Ring 2e</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Vaesen\">Vaesen</a> · <em>Avatar Legends</em> (Magpie Games)"}, "Concepts/Cozy and Pastoral Play": {"key": "Concepts/Cozy and Pastoral Play", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Cozy and Pastoral Play", "tags": ["concept", "cozy", "design", "storygames"], "links": ["Games/Wanderhome", "Games/The Quiet Year", "Games/For the Queen", "Games/Dialect", "Games/Star Crossed", "Games/Ironsworn"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "A design category organizing play around rest, relationship, aesthetic pleasure, and small accomplishments rather than violent conflict and advancement. Not the absence of mechanics — cozy games are mechanically designed — but a different theory of what mechanics should serve.", "html": "<h1>Cozy & Pastoral Play</h1>\n<p>#concept #cozy #design #storygames</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A design category organizing play around rest, relationship, aesthetic pleasure, and small accomplishments rather than violent conflict and advancement. Not the absence of mechanics — cozy games are mechanically designed — but a different theory of what mechanics should serve.</p>\n<h2>The Design Argument</h2>\n<p>The dominant TTRPG tradition assumed that meaningful play requires: 1. Risk of failure 2. Stakes involving significant loss (health, life, resources) 3. Resolution through violent conflict</p>\n<p>Cozy and pastoral design argues that meaningful play can instead be organized around: 1. Relational investment (relationships with characters and places) 2. Aesthetic stakes (will this journey be beautiful? will these relationships deepen?) 3. Resolution through attention, generosity, and presence</p>\n<p>Both positions are legitimate theories of what engagement requires. The cozy wave proved empirically that cozy stakes produce genuine engagement — players invest in them, care about outcomes, and find the play meaningful.</p>\n<h2>Key Mechanical Innovations</h2>\n<strong>Token economies</strong> — shared pools creating collective investment; generosity mechanically productive (Wanderhome)\n<strong>Moves as prompts for attention</strong> — mechanics that invoke specific imaginative attention to details of the fictional world rather than adjudicating success or failure\n<strong>Community as protagonist</strong> — the group rather than individuals as the primary mechanical entity (The Quiet Year)\n<strong>Progress without advancement</strong> — play that feels purposeful without character sheets getting more powerful\n<strong>Embodied mechanics</strong> — physical objects (Jenga towers, token pools) whose physical state mirrors fictional state (Star Crossed)\n<h2>What Cozy Play Is Not</h2>\n<ul><li>Conflict-free: cozy games have tension, difficult choices, and real stakes</li>\n<li>Mechanically absent: cozy games are as mechanically intentional as action games</li>\n<li>Without emotional depth: the cozy wave produced some of the most emotionally affecting TTRPG experiences of the era</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Key Games</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Wanderhome\">Wanderhome</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Quiet Year\">The Quiet Year</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/For the Queen\">For the Queen</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dialect\">Dialect</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Star Crossed\">Star Crossed</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Ironsworn\">Ironsworn</a>"}, "Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)": {"key": "Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Moves (PbtA Design)", "tags": ["concept", "pbtA", "design", "storygames"], "links": ["Games/Apocalypse World", "People/Vincent Baker", "People/Meguey Baker", "Games/Apocalypse World", "Games/Dungeon World", "Games/Monsterhearts", "Games/Brindlewood Bay"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "A Move is the fundamental mechanical unit of PbtA design. A Move is triggered by fiction and produces a mechanical outcome.", "html": "<h1>Moves — PbtA Design Concept</h1>\n<p>#concept #pbtA #design #storygames</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What Is a Move?</h2>\n<p>A Move is the fundamental mechanical unit of PbtA design. A Move is triggered by fiction and produces a mechanical outcome.</p>\n<p>Basic structure: <blockquote><em>When you [do X in the fiction], roll 2d6+[stat].</em></blockquote> <blockquote><em>On a 10+: [full success outcome]</em></blockquote> <blockquote><em>On a 7–9: [partial success / complication]</em></blockquote> <blockquote><em>On a 6-: [miss — the MC makes a move]</em></blockquote></p>\n<h2>Why Moves Matter</h2>\n<p>Before PbtA, most RPGs resolved actions through a single resolution mechanic (roll d20, compare to DC) applied to any situation. Moves replace this with <strong>specific, designed fictional triggers</strong> that produce <strong>specific, designed outcomes</strong>.</p>\n<p>This means: <ul><li>The game's design attention is focused on what matters in play</li> <li>Partial success (7-9) creates interesting decisions without pure failure</li> <li>Miss (6-) gives the MC/GM narrative authority rather than just blocking action</li> <li>Every Move is a miniature design statement about what the game is about</li> </ul> <h2>Types of Moves</h2></p>\n<strong>Basic moves</strong> — available to all characters (Act Under Fire, Help, etc.)   <strong>Playbook moves</strong> — specific to a character archetype   <strong>MC moves</strong> — what the GM does; also explicitly listed as \"moves\" (announce future badness, put someone in a spot, etc.)   <strong>Peripheral moves</strong> — end of session, leveling, etc.\n<h2>The MC's Moves</h2>\n<p>Crucially, the MC/GM also has Moves — explicit, named actions they can take. This means the GM's behavior is as designed as the players'. The GM is not improvising freely; they're choosing from a palette of moves.</p>\n<h2>Origin</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Apocalypse World\">Apocalypse World</a> (2010) — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a> & <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Meguey Baker\">Meguey Baker</a>\n<h2>Key Games Using Moves</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Apocalypse World\">Apocalypse World</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dungeon World\">Dungeon World</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Monsterhearts\">Monsterhearts</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\">Brindlewood Bay</a>"}, "Concepts/Safety Tools": {"key": "Concepts/Safety Tools", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Safety Tools", "tags": ["concept", "design", "community", "practice", "safeplay"], "links": ["People/Jason Cordova", "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Movements/GM-less Design"], "lineage": "crossover", "summary": "Safety tools are explicit, agreed-upon mechanisms that allow players to modify, pause, or stop play when content becomes unwanted or harmful. They operate outside the fiction — they're real-world social technology applied to the TTRPG table.", "html": "<h1>Safety Tools</h1>\n<p>#concept #design #community #practice #safeplay</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What They Are</h2>\n<p>Safety tools are explicit, agreed-upon mechanisms that allow players to modify, pause, or stop play when content becomes unwanted or harmful. They operate outside the fiction — they're real-world social technology applied to the TTRPG table.</p>\n<p>The modern safety tool tradition developed primarily in the story games and indie TTRPG community from roughly 2012 onward, though some tools have older roots. They became broadly adopted through the Gauntlet community (Jason Cordova), convention gaming culture, and their inclusion in published game texts.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key Tools</h2>\n<h3>The X-Card</h3>\n<strong>Designer:</strong> John Stavropoulos (2012)\n<p>A physical card (or digital equivalent) that any player can tap, hold up, or point to at any time. When the X-Card is invoked, play pauses and the most recent content is edited out — no questions asked, no explanation required. The scene is modified or skipped; play continues.</p>\n<p>The X-Card's key design principle: <em>no questions asked</em>. Requiring explanation for why content is unwanted recreates the social pressure the card is designed to relieve. The power of the tool is its unconditional nature.</p>\n<p>Now included in dozens of published games as a recommended practice. The most widely adopted safety tool in the hobby.</p>\n<h3>Lines and Veils</h3>\n<strong>Origin:</strong> attributed to Ron Edwards (The Forge era), popularized in wider practice\n<ul><li><strong>Lines</strong> — content that will not appear in the game at all. Hard stops, established before play begins. \"No sexual violence\" is a Line. Lines are not crossed.</li>\n<li><strong>Veils</strong> — content that can occur in the game but is not depicted in detail. It happens \"off-screen.\" \"Violence against children can happen in the fiction but we won't play through it\" is a Veil.</li>\n</ul>\nLines and Veils are established during Session Zero through discussion. They're social contracts rather than in-game mechanics — explicit articulations of the group's shared creative limits.\n<h3>Script Change</h3>\n<strong>Designer:</strong> Brie Beau Sheldon\n<p>A more granular set of tools using media terminology: <ul><li><strong>Fast Forward</strong> — skip ahead past the current content</li> <li><strong>Rewind</strong> — go back and replay a scene differently</li> <li><strong>Pause</strong> — stop and check in with the table out-of-character</li> <li><strong>Frame</strong> — establish what a scene will and won't contain before it begins</li> </ul> Script Change gives players more options than the binary X-Card and more in-the-moment flexibility than Lines and Veils.</p>\n<h3>Open Door Policy</h3>\nA simple standing agreement: any player may leave the game at any time, for any reason, without explanation or social penalty. Not a mechanic but an explicit social norm that removes the pressure of feeling obligated to stay through uncomfortable content.\n<h3>Check-In / Consent Forms</h3>\nPre-session questionnaires asking players about their comfort with various content categories. Used primarily in convention gaming and organized play where the GM doesn't know the players in advance.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Session Zero</h2>\n<p>Session Zero is a dedicated pre-campaign session (or extended conversation) in which the group establishes: <ul><li>Safety tools to be used</li> <li>Lines and Veils</li> <li>Campaign tone, themes, and content expectations</li> <li>Character relationships and backstory</li> <li>Practical logistics (scheduling, absences, platform)</li> </ul> Session Zero is not itself a safety tool but is the primary context in which safety tools are established. It represents a design philosophy: <strong>explicitly negotiating the social contract of play produces better play than assuming everyone has the same expectations.</strong></p>\n<p>Session Zero practice was promoted heavily by the Gauntlet community (Jason Cordova), incorporated into many indie games as a recommended first step, and subsequently adopted in varying forms by mainstream game design.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Design Argument for Safety Tools</h2>\n<p>Safety tools encode a specific theory of what the table is:</p>\n<strong>Traditional implicit model:</strong> the GM has authority over content; players trust the GM to handle sensitive material appropriately; discomfort is raised through social channels (talking after the session, declining to continue).\n<strong>Safety tool model:</strong> content is a shared responsibility; every player has explicit authority to modify or stop play; discomfort is addressed as it arises through explicit mechanisms that remove the social cost of speaking up.\n<p>The tools work best when they're normalized — introduced before play, used casually when needed, not treated as emergency measures. A table that uses the X-Card once in ten sessions has a healthier safety culture than a table that has never needed to use it because no one felt they could.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Community History</h2>\n<p>Safety tools developed primarily in the story games and convention TTRPG community, not in mainstream or OSR contexts. Their adoption was and remains uneven across the hobby — broadly accepted in indie and convention spaces, more contested in some traditional and OSR communities where they're sometimes perceived as unnecessary or as limiting creative freedom.</p>\n<p>The counterarguments (that safety tools break immersion, that good players don't need them, that they signal distrust) are well-known. The design tradition's response: safety tools don't prevent difficult content, they enable it — groups can explore harder material when everyone knows there's a reliable mechanism for adjusting course.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key People</h2>\nJohn Stavropoulos (X-Card) · Brie Beau Sheldon (Script Change) · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Cordova\">Jason Cordova</a> (Gauntlet community adoption and propagation) · Kienna Shaw & Lauren Bryant-Monk (TTRPG Safety Toolkit compilation)\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a> (strong adoption overlap) · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Related concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/GM-less Design\">GM-less Design</a> (safety tools are especially important without a GM managing content)</li>\n</ul>"}, "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing": {"key": "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing", "category": "Concepts", "name": "The OGL and Open Licensing", "tags": ["concept", "ogl", "legal", "publishing"], "links": ["Concepts/Retroclones", "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023", "Publishers/Paizo", "People/Matt Finch", "People/Stuart Marshall", "People/Monte Cook"], "lineage": "crossover", "summary": "Published alongside D&D 3rd Edition by WotC. A legal instrument allowing third parties to publish material using D&D's mechanics without license fees or permission, provided they:\n- Included the OGL text\n- Identified \"product identity\" (WotC's IP) vs. \"open content\" (the mechanics)\n- Did not use WotC's product identity without separate permission", "html": "<h1>The OGL & Open Licensing</h1>\n<p>#concept #ogl #legal #publishing</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Original OGL (2000)</h2>\n<p>Published alongside D&D 3rd Edition by WotC. A legal instrument allowing third parties to publish material using D&D's mechanics without license fees or permission, provided they: <ul><li>Included the OGL text</li> <li>Identified \"product identity\" (WotC's IP) vs. \"open content\" (the mechanics)</li> <li>Did not use WotC's product identity without separate permission</li> </ul> The OGL covered <strong>mechanics</strong> (which copyright law cannot protect) but not <strong>expression</strong> (specific text, artwork). This distinction is the legal foundation of every retroclone.</p>\n<p>Key phrase: <em>\"perpetual, worldwide, royalty-free, and irrevocable.\"</em> The community took \"irrevocable\" seriously — it was the bedrock of a publishing ecosystem.</p>\n<h2>The System Reference Document (SRD)</h2>\n<p>WotC published an SRD — a version of D&D's rules text stripped of product identity — that publishers could legally reference and reprint. The 5e SRD (2016) enabled the DMs Guild and the 5e third-party boom.</p>\n<h2>The Retroclone Insight</h2>\n<p>If mechanics can't be copyrighted, you can write <em>new text</em> expressing <em>old mechanics</em> and release it under the OGL. This is what OSRIC, Labyrinth Lord, and the first retroclones did.</p>\n<p>See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Retroclones\">Retroclones</a></p>\n<h2>The GSL (2008)</h2>\n<p>When D&D 4e launched, WotC replaced the OGL with the Game System License — more restrictive, not covering the same ground. This cut off a large third-party publishing ecosystem and directly accelerated OSR growth.</p>\n<h2>The OGL Crisis (2023)</h2>\n<p>WotC attempted to revoke and replace the OGL in January 2023. After massive community backlash, they retreated and placed the 5e SRD under Creative Commons — genuinely irrevocable.</p>\n<p>See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OGL Crisis 2023\">OGL Crisis 2023</a></p>\n<h2>The ORC License</h2>\n<p>Developed by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Paizo\">Paizo</a> with community input after the 2023 crisis. A system-neutral open license administered by a nonprofit law firm — designed so no single company can revoke or weaponize it.</p>\n<h2>Key People</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Stuart Marshall\">Stuart Marshall</a> (OGL application to retroclones)  \n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Monte Cook\">Monte Cook</a> (3e OGL designer)"}, "Concepts/Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)": {"key": "Concepts/Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)", "tags": ["concept", "fitD", "design", "storygames"], "links": ["Games/Blades in the Dark", "People/John Harper", "Games/Blades in the Dark", "Games/Band of Blades", "Games/Scum and Villainy", "Games/Spire The City Must Fall", "Games/Heart The City Beneath"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "The core resolution framework of Forged in the Dark games. Instead of a simple pass/fail roll, every action has two axes evaluated before rolling:", "html": "<h1>Clocks & Position/Effect — FitD Design Concepts</h1>\n<p>#concept #fitD #design #storygames</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Position and Effect</h2>\n<p>The core resolution framework of Forged in the Dark games. Instead of a simple pass/fail roll, every action has two axes evaluated before rolling:</p>\n<strong>Position</strong> — how risky is the situation? <ul><li><em>Controlled</em> — you're in command; a miss has minor consequences</li> <li><em>Risky</em> — standard danger; a miss has serious consequences</li> <li><em>Desperate</em> — you're in trouble; a miss has severe consequences</li> </ul> <strong>Effect</strong> — how much impact will success have? <ul><li><em>Limited</em> — partial progress; even full success moves things forward minimally</li> <li><em>Standard</em> — normal impact</li> <li><em>Great</em> — exceptional impact</li> </ul> Both axes are set by the GM before the roll and are visible to players. This means informed decisions, a richer outcome space, and outcomes that are always interesting — failing in Desperate/Great means something serious went wrong and the attempt had the potential to matter enormously.\n<p>Players can negotiate: accepting worse position for better effect, or vice versa.</p>\n<h2>The Devil's Bargain</h2>\n<p>Before rolling, the GM or another player can offer a Devil's Bargain: one extra die in exchange for a complication regardless of the outcome. Creates dramatic material from the resolution process itself, not just its outcome. Players always have agency over their risk profile.</p>\n<h2>Clocks</h2>\n<p>Circular progress trackers divided into segments (4, 6, 8, or 10). When a clock fills, something happens.</p>\n<p>Uses: <ul><li><strong>Threat clocks</strong> — the enemies' plan progresses; fill it and bad things happen</li> <li><strong>Project clocks</strong> — the players work toward a goal; fill it and they succeed</li> <li><strong>Tug-of-war clocks</strong> — players fill from one end, enemies from the other</li> <li><strong>Tick clocks</strong> — countdowns to immediate events</li> </ul> Clocks externalize narrative tension. Players can see how close the alarm is to being raised, how near the target is to escaping.</p>\n<h2>Flashbacks</h2>\n<p>Players may call for a flashback at any point during a scene: 1. Declare what you prepared or arranged before the current moment 2. Pay stress (1–2 depending on complexity) 3. Narrate the preparation scene 4. Gain the established benefit in the current scene</p>\n<p>Flashbacks eliminate \"but we didn't plan for this!\" paralysis. They reward creative thinking in the moment rather than pre-session planning.</p>\n<h2>Origin</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Blades in the Dark\">Blades in the Dark</a> (2017) — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a>\n<h2>Key Games Using These Concepts</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Blades in the Dark\">Blades in the Dark</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Band of Blades\">Band of Blades</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Scum and Villainy\">Scum and Villainy</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\">Spire</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Heart The City Beneath\">Heart</a>\n(Note: Spire uses a similar but distinct approach — stress/difficulty rather than position/effect)"}, "Concepts/Implied Setting Design": {"key": "Concepts/Implied Setting Design", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Implied Setting Design", "tags": ["concept", "osr", "postOSR", "design", "worldbuilding"], "links": ["Games/Troika", "Games/Into the Odd", "Games/Mork Borg", "Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy", "People/Daniel Sell", "People/Chris McDowall", "People/Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "A design approach in which the game's world is communicated through play materials — character backgrounds, random tables, art direction, equipment lists — rather than through explicit sourcebook description. The setting exists in suggestion rather than statement.", "html": "<h1>Implied Setting Design</h1>\n<p>#concept #osr #postOSR #design #worldbuilding</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A design approach in which the game's world is communicated through play materials — character backgrounds, random tables, art direction, equipment lists — rather than through explicit sourcebook description. The setting exists in suggestion rather than statement.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<p>Conventional RPG settings are described in sourcebooks: here is the world, here are its factions, here is its history. This approach makes the setting authoritative but also finite — once you've read the sourcebook, the world is fixed.</p>\n<p>Implied setting design inverts this. The setting is generated through play, built from the table's interpretation of suggestive materials. Because it's never fully stated, it can never be wrong. Every table's version is slightly different.</p>\n<h2>Examples in Practice</h2>\n<strong><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Troika\\\">Troika!</a></strong> — 36 character Backgrounds imply a complete space-fantasy multiverse without ever describing it. The Lonesome Monarch tells you that lonely monarchs exist in this universe. The Befouled Fisherman tells you about tides and philosophy. Together they build a world.\n<strong><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Into the Odd\\\">Into the Odd</a></strong> — Bastion is described in a few paragraphs and a map that raises more questions than it answers. The Arcana system implies what magic is through the specific items characters find, not through a description of how magic works.\n<strong><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mork Borg\\\">Mörk Borg</a></strong> — Art direction communicates setting more efficiently than any amount of flavor text. The color scheme, typography, and images tell you exactly what kind of world this is before you've read a word.\n<h2>Relationship to OSR Philosophy</h2>\nImplied setting design is consistent with <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy\">OSR play philosophy</a>'s preference for rulings over rules — just as the referee improvises mechanical rulings from principles rather than looking up tables, the table generates the world from suggestive materials rather than consuming pre-built description.\n<h2>Key Designers</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Daniel Sell\">Daniel Sell</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris McDowall\">Chris McDowall</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr\">Johan Nohr</a>"}, "Concepts/The Funnel": {"key": "Concepts/The Funnel", "category": "Concepts", "name": "The Funnel", "tags": ["concept", "osr", "dcc", "charactercreation", "design"], "links": ["Games/Dungeon Crawl Classics", "People/Joseph Goodman", "Games/Dungeon Crawl Classics", "People/Joseph Goodman"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "A character creation mechanic introduced in Dungeon Crawl Classics (2012) by Joseph Goodman. At the start of a campaign, each player generates 3–4 zero-level characters — ordinary peasants, farmers, cobblers, ratcatchers — with 1d4 HP, random equipment, and nothing special about them. These characters are run through a lethal introductory adventure. Most die. Survivors become 1st-level characters ", "html": "<h1>The Funnel</h1>\n<p>#concept #osr #dcc #charactercreation #design</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A character creation mechanic introduced in <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dungeon Crawl Classics\">Dungeon Crawl Classics</a> (2012) by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Joseph Goodman\">Joseph Goodman</a>. At the start of a campaign, each player generates 3–4 zero-level characters — ordinary peasants, farmers, cobblers, ratcatchers — with 1d4 HP, random equipment, and nothing special about them. These characters are run through a lethal introductory adventure. Most die. Survivors become 1st-level characters in their chosen class.</p>\n<h2>Why It Works</h2>\n<strong>Stakes are real from session one.</strong> Characters die randomly and the world doesn't care about them. This is the OSR's lethality principle at its most concentrated.\n<strong>Survivors have stories before they have character sheets.</strong> The ratcatcher who survived by hiding behind a barrel has a narrative identity before any mechanical choices were made.\n<strong>It solves new-player class-selection paralysis.</strong> You play several characters simultaneously, discover what you enjoy, and your 1st-level choice reflects actual play experience.\n<strong>Generates immediate campaign hooks.</strong> Who were these people? How does the ratcatcher becoming a warrior change their relationship to their surviving companions?\n<h2>Adoption</h2>\n<p>The funnel has been adopted across many OSR and OSR-adjacent games that share nothing else with DCC. It's one of the movement's most portable design innovations.</p>\n<h2>Origin</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dungeon Crawl Classics\">Dungeon Crawl Classics</a> (2012) — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Joseph Goodman\">Joseph Goodman</a>"}, "Concepts/The Journey as Mechanical Unit": {"key": "Concepts/The Journey as Mechanical Unit", "category": "Concepts", "name": "The Journey as Mechanical Unit", "tags": ["concept", "crossover", "design", "tolkien", "onering"], "links": ["Games/The One Ring 2e", "Games/The One Ring 2e", "People/Francesco Nepitello", "Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy"], "lineage": "crossover", "summary": "A design approach in The One Ring where travel itself is the primary mechanical unit rather than the encounter.", "html": "<h1>The Journey as Mechanical Unit</h1>\n<p>#concept #crossover #design #tolkien #onering</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A design approach in <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The One Ring 2e\">The One Ring</a> where <strong>travel itself</strong> is the primary mechanical unit rather than the encounter.</p>\n<h2>Why Conventional Design Fails Here</h2>\n<p>In most RPGs, travel is a transition between meaningful events — resolved quickly so play can reach the \"real\" scenes. This fails for Middle-earth because the journey <em>is</em> the real scene in Tolkien. The walk to Mordor is the plot, not the vehicle for the plot.</p>\n<h2>How The One Ring Implements It</h2>\n<p>When the Company travels: 1. <strong>Path selection</strong> — route choice affects terrain, hazards, time 2. <strong>Role assignment</strong> — Guide, Lookout, Scout, Hunter each contribute 3. <strong>Hazard rolls</strong> — terrain and weather resolved through roles 4. <strong>Fatigue accumulation</strong> — travel costs Endurance; arrival is significant because of what the journey cost 5. <strong>Miserable and Wounded states</strong> — conditions persisting into subsequent scenes</p>\n<p>Result: arriving somewhere is mechanically and fictionally significant. The Company paid a price together.</p>\n<h2>Broader Influence</h2>\n<p>The journey-as-mechanical-unit concept has influenced how designers think about travel where movement is thematically important. OSR hexcrawl design engages similar questions through different mechanics (resource management, random encounter tables, navigation). The One Ring's approach is narratively structured; OSR hexcrawl is procedurally emergent. Both are more interesting than \"roll for random encounters.\"</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Origin: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The One Ring 2e\">The One Ring 2e</a></li>\n<li>Designer: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Francesco Nepitello\">Francesco Nepitello</a></li>\n<li>Related: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy\">OSR Play Philosophy</a> (overlapping travel concerns)</li>\n</ul>"}, "Concepts/Retroclones": {"key": "Concepts/Retroclones", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Retroclones", "tags": ["concept", "osr", "retroclone", "publishing"], "links": ["Games/OSRIC", "Games/Basic Fantasy RPG", "Games/Labyrinth Lord", "Games/Swords and Wizardry", "Games/Lamentations of the Flame Princess", "Games/Dungeon Crawl Classics", "Games/Old-School Essentials", "People/Matt Finch", "People/Stuart Marshall", "People/Daniel Proctor", "People/Chris Gonnerman"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "A game that restates the mechanics of an older edition of D&D in new text, released under the OGL, to achieve legal compatibility with that edition's adventure and supplement material.", "html": "<h1>Retroclones</h1>\n<p>#concept #osr #retroclone #publishing</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What Is a Retroclone?</h2>\n<p>A game that restates the mechanics of an older edition of D&D in new text, released under the OGL, to achieve legal compatibility with that edition's adventure and supplement material.</p>\n<p>The key legal insight: <strong>mechanics cannot be copyrighted, but expression can.</strong> You can write new text expressing B/X D&D's mechanics. You cannot reprint TSR's actual rulebook text.</p>\n<h2>Why They Exist</h2>\n<p>Two reasons: 1. Older D&D editions are out of print and legally grey to reprint 2. Third-party publishers need a legal reference document to write \"compatible with AD&D\" adventures</p>\n<p>Retroclones solve both: they provide a freely available rules reference that publishers can use without legal risk.</p>\n<h2>First Generation (2006–2009)</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Game</td><td>Target Edition</td><td>Designer</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/OSRIC\\</td><td>OSRIC\">td><td>OSRIC</a></td><td>AD&D 1e</td><td>Finch, Marshall</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Basic Fantasy RPG\\</td><td>Basic Fantasy RPG\">td><td>Basic Fantasy RPG</a></td><td>B/X</td><td>Gonnerman</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Labyrinth Lord\\</td><td>Labyrinth Lord\">td><td>Labyrinth Lord</a></td><td>B/X</td><td>Proctor</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Swords and Wizardry\\</td><td>Swords & Wizardry\">td><td>Swords & Wizardry</a></td><td>OD&D (1974)</td><td>Finch</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Second Generation (2010–present)</h2>\n<p>Later retroclones began diverging from pure mechanical fidelity: <ul><li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Lamentations of the Flame Princess\">LotFP</a> — B/X base with horror aesthetic</li> <li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dungeon Crawl Classics\">DCC</a> — AD&D-adjacent with pulp fantasy additions</li> <li><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Old-School Essentials\">Old-School Essentials</a> — B/X re-presented for clarity</li> </ul> <h2>Key People</h2> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Stuart Marshall\">Stuart Marshall</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Daniel Proctor\">Daniel Proctor</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris Gonnerman\">Chris Gonnerman</a></p>"}, "Concepts/Production Design as Content": {"key": "Concepts/Production Design as Content", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Production Design as Content", "tags": ["concept", "osr", "postOSR", "design", "aesthetic"], "links": ["Games/Mork Borg", "Games/Mothership", "Games/Troika", "People/Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr", "People/Sean McCoy", "People/Daniel Sell"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "A design philosophy, most fully developed in the second-wave OSR, in which a game's physical and visual form is treated as a primary meaning-making tool — not packaging for rules, but content in its own right.", "html": "<h1>Production Design as Content</h1>\n<p>#concept #osr #postOSR #design #aesthetic</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A design philosophy, most fully developed in the second-wave OSR, in which a game's physical and visual form is treated as a primary meaning-making tool — not packaging for rules, but content in its own right.</p>\n<h2>The Argument</h2>\n<p>Standard RPG layout prioritizes information retrieval: rules should be findable, procedures clear, tables scannable. This is a neutral-professional aesthetic that signals the book is a tool.</p>\n<p>Production-design-as-content uses layout, typography, color, and visual language to transmit the game's emotional and tonal argument before the reader has processed a single rule. The medium carries meaning.</p>\n<h2>Key Examples</h2>\n<strong><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mork Borg\\\">Mörk Borg</a></strong> — the most extreme case. Chaotic typography (text at angles, multiple fonts competing on one page), hostile color schemes (bile yellow, blood orange, deep black). Every visual choice is an argument about the game's nihilist tone. Johan Nohr's art direction is the game's primary content.\n<strong><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mothership\\\">Mothership</a></strong> — early editions designed to look like technical documentation from within the game's world. A Mothership supplement that resembles a corporate HR manual from a megacorporation communicates tone no flavor text could match.\n<strong><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Troika\\\">Troika!</a></strong> — handmade zine aesthetic signals independence from professional RPG production values. The look says \"this was made by someone\" before you've read a word.\n<h2>Influence</h2>\nThe production-design-as-content philosophy propagated rapidly through the itch.io OSR community. The Mörk Borg Compatible ecosystem in particular produced hundreds of products that understood aesthetic coherence as part of their design brief.\n<h2>Key Designers</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr\">Johan Nohr</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Sean McCoy\">Sean McCoy</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Daniel Sell\">Daniel Sell</a>"}, "Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy": {"key": "Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy", "category": "Concepts", "name": "OSR Play Philosophy", "tags": ["concept", "osr", "philosophy", "playstyle"], "links": ["People/Matt Finch", "People/Matt Finch", "People/James Maliszewski"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Old-school play treats the rules as a referee's toolkit for a living world, not a balanced system for producing fair encounters. These are fundamentally different orientations to what a TTRPG is.", "html": "<h1>OSR Play Philosophy</h1>\n<p>#concept #osr #philosophy #playstyle</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Core Argument</h2>\n<p>Old-school play treats the rules as a <strong>referee's toolkit for a living world</strong>, not a <strong>balanced system for producing fair encounters</strong>. These are fundamentally different orientations to what a TTRPG is.</p>\n<p>The foundational text: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a>'s <em>A Quick Primer for Old School Gaming</em> (2008, free).</p>\n<h2>Key Tenets</h2>\n<strong>Rulings over rules</strong> — When the rules don't cover a situation, the referee improvises a ruling rather than looking it up. The rules are incomplete by design; the gap is a feature.\n<strong>Player skill over character build</strong> — A clever 1st-level character can achieve things a well-built 10th-level character cannot, through creative use of the fiction. The character sheet is not the primary resource.\n<strong>Death is real</strong> — Characters die, and that's meaningful. Danger requires real stakes.\n<strong>The dungeon is a living place</strong> — The dungeon exists independently of the players. Factions pursue their own goals. The environment changes whether or not the players are there.\n<strong>Exploration is the core activity</strong> — Mapping, resource management, and decision-making under uncertainty are primary pleasures, not just scaffolding for combat.\n<strong>Naturalistic encounter design</strong> — Monsters and NPCs have their own motivations and can be negotiated with, fled from, or avoided. Not everything is a combat encounter.\n<h2>What This Opposes</h2>\n<p>The OSR philosophy defines itself partly against what it sees as later D&D's assumptions: <ul><li>Balanced encounters scaled to party level</li> <li>Character optimization as primary skill expression</li> <li>The GM as entertainer/narrator rather than referee</li> <li>Rules covering every situation</li> </ul> <h2>Key Texts</h2> <ul><li><em>A Quick Primer for Old School Gaming</em> — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Finch</a> (free)</li> <li>Grognardia blog archives — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/James Maliszewski\">Maliszewski</a></li> <li><em>Principia Apocrypha</em> — various OSR bloggers (free)</li> </ul></p>"}, "Concepts/DD Edition History": {"key": "Concepts/DD Edition History", "category": "Concepts", "name": "DD Edition History", "tags": ["concept", "mainstream", "dnd", "editions", "history"], "links": ["Games/Labyrinth Lord", "Games/Old-School Essentials", "Games/Dolmenwood", "Games/OSRIC", "Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Games/Pathfinder 1e", "Games/Daggerheart", "People/Jeremy Crawford", "People/Chris Perkins", "Games/Daggerheart", "People/Jeremy Crawford", "People/Mike Mearls", "People/Rob Heinsoo", "People/Monte Cook", "People/Peter Adkison", "People/Chris Perkins"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "D&D's edition history is the trunk of the whole tree. Every lineage in this vault exists in relationship to it. The editions divide into three eras: the TSR era (1974–1999), the WotC d20 era (2000–2013), and the 5e era (2014–present).", "html": "<h1>D&D Edition History</h1>\n<p>#concept #mainstream #dnd #editions #history</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>D&D's edition history is the trunk of the whole tree. Every lineage in this vault exists in relationship to it. The editions divide into three eras: the TSR era (1974–1999), the WotC d20 era (2000–2013), and the 5e era (2014–present).</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The TSR Era (1974–1999)</h2>\n<h3>Original D&D (1974)</h3>\nThree \"little brown books\" by Gary Gygax and Dave Arneson. Famously incomplete and inconsistent; assumed wargaming background. The gaps demanded creative interpretation and produced extraordinary play diversity. The OSR's philosophical foundations lie here.\n<p>Key supplements: Greyhawk, Blackmoor, Eldritch Wizardry, Gods Demigods & Heroes.</p>\n<h3>Basic D&D: Three versions</h3>\n<strong>Holmes Basic Set (1977)</strong> — First introductory rulebook; covered only 1st–3rd level; directed players to AD&D for higher levels.\n<strong>B/X: Moldvay/Cook (1981)</strong> — The OSR's primary reference. Tom Moldvay's Basic Set and David Cook's Expert Set cover levels 1–14 with clarity and playability earlier versions lacked. Fast character creation. Implied hexcrawl structure. The edition that <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Labyrinth Lord\">Labyrinth Lord</a>, <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Old-School Essentials\">Old-School Essentials</a>, and <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dolmenwood\">Dolmenwood</a> build on.\n<strong>Mentzer BECMI (1983)</strong> — Basic, Expert, Companion, Master, Immortal. Expanded level range; the Rules Cyclopedia (1991) consolidated it into one of the most complete RPG rulebooks ever produced.\n<h3>AD&D 1st Edition (1977–1979)</h3>\nPrimarily Gygax: Player's Handbook (1978), Dungeon Master's Guide (1979), Monster Manual (1977). More comprehensive than B/X; the DMG is a sprawling, idiosyncratic record of how Gygax's Lake Geneva circle actually played. <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/OSRIC\">OSRIC</a> clones this edition.\n<strong>The Gygax departure (1985)</strong> — Corporate maneuvers involving the Blume brothers pushed Gygax out of TSR. D&D continued without its primary architect.\n<h3>AD&D 2nd Edition (1989)</h3>\nDesigned by David Cook (also designer of B/X Expert). Cleaner presentation than 1e; sanitized for the Satanic Panic era (demons renamed, assassin class removed). The era of campaign settings: Forgotten Realms, Planescape, Dark Sun, Ravenloft, Spelljammer. Creative high point and commercial overextension that contributed to TSR's near-bankruptcy. WotC acquired TSR in 1997 for approximately $30M in debt.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The WotC d20 Era (2000–2013)</h2>\n<h3>D&D 3rd Edition (2000)</h3>\nCook, Tweet, Williams. Complete mechanical reinvention: unified d20 resolution, ascending AC, skills and feats. Published with the OGL — the hinge on which everything else turns. The d20 boom followed immediately; dozens of third-party publishers entered the market.\n<h3>D&D 3.5 (2003)</h3>\nAddressed 3e's mechanical inconsistencies but couldn't repair the fundamental architecture of a game accumulating sourcebook complexity. By 2007: severe martial/caster power disparity, hours-long combat, unreliable CR system.\n<h3>D&D 4th Edition (2008)</h3>\nHeinsoo, Collins, Wyatt. Solved 3.5's real problems by reconceptualizing D&D as a tactical miniatures game: unified power structures (At-Will/Encounter/Daily), explicit combat roles (Defender/Striker/Leader/Controller), healing surges, minion rules. The game worked as designed. A large portion of the playerbase experienced the reconceptualization as a betrayal. <strong>The single biggest catalyst in the post-2005 landscape</strong>: drove players toward Pathfinder, the OSR, and story games simultaneously. The GSL replaced the OGL, cutting off third-party publishers.\n<p>See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/D&D Edition Wars\">D&D Edition Wars</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></p>\n<h3>Pathfinder 1e (2009)</h3>\nBulmahn/Paizo. Built on 3.5 OGL. Conservative design: fix what's broken, keep what works. Outsold D&D during the 4e era. See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 1e\">Pathfinder 1e</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The 5e Era (2014–present)</h2>\n<h3>D&D 5th Edition (2014)</h3>\nMearls and Crawford. The 'big tent' edition: reunite the fractured playerbase. Open playtest with 175,000+ participants. Core innovations: <strong>bounded accuracy</strong> (world doesn't scale to party level), <strong>advantage/disadvantage</strong> (collapses situational modifiers into a binary), <strong>proficiency bonus</strong> (single scaling mechanic), <strong>short/long rest resource recovery</strong>. Conservative publication model avoided the sourcebook arms race. Amplified by Critical Role into mainstream cultural visibility from 2015 onward.\n<h3>5e's design gap</h3>\nThe rules as written support faster, more procedural play than the game is commonly played. Players arriving through actual play often bring expectations (performative roleplay, narrative continuity) that the mechanics don't specifically support. This gap produced <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Daggerheart\">Daggerheart</a> (designed to close it mechanically) and waves of supplements trying to address it within 5e.\n<h3>D&D 2024 revision (One D&D)</h3>\nSpecies replaces race (Tasha's flexible ability scores as standard). Backgrounds provide a 1st-level feat. Classes reorganized; ranger substantially revised. Arrived post-OGL crisis into a community whose trust had been damaged.\n<h3>Crawford and Perkins depart / join Darrington (2025)</h3>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeremy Crawford\">Crawford</a> and <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris Perkins\">Perkins</a> — 46 combined years of WotC experience — departed April 2025, joined Darrington Press as Game Director and Creative Director respectively in June 2025. Now working on <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Daggerheart\">Daggerheart</a> expansions. The most significant talent shift in mainstream TTRPG in years.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Edition Summary Table</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Edition</td><td>Year</td><td>Key Designers</td><td>OSR Relationship</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Original D&D</td><td>1974</td><td>Gygax, Arneson</td><td>Philosophical foundation</td></tr>\n<tr><td>B/X</td><td>1981</td><td>Moldvay, Cook</td><td>Primary OSR target</td></tr>\n<tr><td>AD&D 1e</td><td>1977–79</td><td>Gygax</td><td>OSRIC clones this</td></tr>\n<tr><td>AD&D 2e</td><td>1989</td><td>D. Cook</td><td>2e-adjacent OSR games</td></tr>\n<tr><td>D&D 3e</td><td>2000</td><td>Cook, Tweet, Williams</td><td>OGL created; d20 boom</td></tr>\n<tr><td>D&D 3.5</td><td>2003</td><td>WotC team</td><td>Pathfinder heir</td></tr>\n<tr><td>D&D 4e</td><td>2008</td><td>Heinsoo et al.</td><td>Largest OSR catalyst</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Pathfinder 1e</td><td>2009</td><td>Bulmahn/Paizo</td><td>3.5 continuation</td></tr>\n<tr><td>D&D 5e</td><td>2014</td><td>Mearls, Crawford</td><td>Mainstream revival</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Pathfinder 2e</td><td>2019</td><td>Bonner/Paizo</td><td>Post-OGL alternative</td></tr>\n<tr><td>D&D 2024</td><td>2024</td><td>Crawford et al.</td><td>Revised 5e</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Key People</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeremy Crawford\">Jeremy Crawford</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Mike Mearls\">Mike Mearls</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Rob Heinsoo\">Rob Heinsoo</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Monte Cook\">Monte Cook</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Peter Adkison\">Peter Adkison</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris Perkins\">Chris Perkins</a>"}, "Concepts/Hexcrawl and Dungeon Procedure": {"key": "Concepts/Hexcrawl and Dungeon Procedure", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Hexcrawl and Dungeon Procedure", "tags": ["concept", "osr", "procedure", "exploration", "design"], "links": ["People/Matt Finch", "People/Gavin Norman", "Games/Dolmenwood", "Games/Hyperborea", "Games/Into the Odd", "Games/Cairn", "Games/Old-School Essentials"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Two of the OSR's foundational procedural frameworks, both rooted in the original D&D design: the hexcrawl (wilderness exploration) and the dungeon turn (structured dungeon exploration). Both treat exploration as the primary activity and resource management as the primary mechanical tension.", "html": "<h1>Hexcrawl & Dungeon Procedure</h1>\n<p>#concept #osr #procedure #exploration #design</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Two of the OSR's foundational procedural frameworks, both rooted in the original D&D design: the hexcrawl (wilderness exploration) and the dungeon turn (structured dungeon exploration). Both treat exploration as the primary activity and resource management as the primary mechanical tension.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Hexcrawl</h2>\n<p>A hexcrawl is a wilderness exploration structure where the map is divided into hexagons, each containing (or possibly containing) points of interest, terrain features, and encounter possibilities. Players navigate by declaring movement directions; the referee tracks their position on a master map; players build their own map as they explore.</p>\n<strong>Core procedures:</strong> <ul><li><strong>Movement</strong> — how many hexes can be traveled per day? Terrain modifies this</li> <li><strong>Navigation</strong> — players can become lost; skill or landmark checks determine orientation</li> <li><strong>Encounter rolls</strong> — each hex traversed, each watch kept, triggers a random encounter check</li> <li><strong>Resource tracking</strong> — food, water, light, rations are tracked explicitly; wilderness survival is a real problem</li> <li><strong>Revealed vs. unrevealed</strong> — players only know what they've seen; the GM's map contains secrets</li> </ul> <strong>The key design insight:</strong> the hexcrawl makes the <em>space between dungeons</em> as mechanically meaningful as the dungeons themselves. Travel is not a transition — it's a system of resource expenditure, risk management, and discovery.\n<strong>Notable hexcrawl designs:</strong> <ul><li>Original D&D wilderness procedures</li> <li>Judges Guild's Wilderlands of High Fantasy (1977) — definitive early hexcrawl setting</li> <li>Dolmenwood — modern neo-trad hexcrawl</li> <li>Forbidden Lands (Free League) — hexcrawl revival in mainstream-adjacent design</li> </ul> ---\n<h2>The Pointcrawl</h2>\n<p>A pointcrawl is an alternative to the hexcrawl that maps a region as a network of notable points connected by paths rather than a uniform hex grid. Characters move between points along established paths; the interesting decisions are <em>which path to take</em> rather than <em>which direction to go</em>.</p>\n<strong>When pointcrawl works better than hexcrawl:</strong> <ul><li>Regions with strong landmark structure (river valleys, mountain passes, forest roads)</li> <li>Settings where wilderness travel follows established routes</li> <li>Groups who find hexcrawl navigation bookkeeping excessive</li> </ul> Patrick Stuart's essay \"Pointcrawl\" (2012) is the foundational text. Many neo-trad and second-wave OSR games use hybrid approaches — a hex map for overview, pointcrawl structure for actual travel.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Dungeon Turn</h2>\n<p>The dungeon turn is a time-keeping structure that makes dungeon exploration procedurally meaningful. A turn is ten minutes of in-game time. Each turn, the referee:</p>\n<p>1. <strong>Checks for wandering monsters</strong> — typically 1-in-6 chance per turn; noise, light, and delay increase the risk 2. <strong>Tracks light</strong> — torches last 6 turns; lanterns longer; darkness is lethal 3. <strong>Tracks player resources</strong> — spells, hit points, rations, equipment 4. <strong>Advances time</strong> — resting takes turns; searching takes turns; everything has a time cost</p>\n<strong>What the dungeon turn accomplishes:</strong> <ul><li>Makes the dungeon feel like a living place with its own rhythms</li> <li>Creates resource pressure that makes every decision meaningful</li> <li>Transforms \"do we look for secret doors?\" into a real cost-benefit analysis</li> <li>Generates the OSR's characteristic sense of creeping danger even without active conflict</li> </ul> <strong>The wandering monster</strong> is not primarily a combat encounter — it's a time tax. The reason players avoid wandering monsters is that fighting takes turns, burns resources, and makes noise that attracts more monsters. The incentive structure produces careful, quiet, efficient play.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Reaction Rolls and Encounter Negotiation</h2>\n<p>One of the OSR's most misunderstood mechanics. When characters encounter a monster or NPC, the referee rolls 2d6 on a reaction table: <ul><li>2: Hostile — immediate attack</li> <li>3-5: Unfriendly — wary, may attack</li> <li>6-8: Uncertain — neutral, watching</li> <li>9-11: Indifferent — no immediate action</li> <li>12: Friendly — actively positive</li> </ul> <strong>The design argument:</strong> most encounters are not fights. They're negotiations, standoffs, opportunities for parley, or mutual avoidance. The reaction roll operationalizes this — it forces referees to play monsters as beings with their own agendas rather than combat encounters waiting to happen.</p>\n<p>Characters with high Charisma get modifiers to reaction rolls. This makes Charisma genuinely useful rather than a dump stat — it affects whether the orc chief wants to bargain before fighting.</p>\n<strong>The downstream effect:</strong> OSR play produces a very different encounter culture from d20 play. Players learn to consider whether they can avoid, negotiate, bribe, or trick their way past a problem before committing to violence. This isn't just a playstyle preference — it's engineered by the mechanics.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Save or Die</h2>\n<p>High-lethality design at its most concentrated. Certain spells, traps, and conditions require a saving throw — fail it and the character dies immediately, regardless of hit points remaining. No lingering wound, no dramatic death scene: death, now.</p>\n<strong>The design argument:</strong> save-or-die mechanics communicate that the world is genuinely dangerous in a way that hit point attrition alone cannot. A medusa's gaze, a poisoned needle, a pit trap — these should feel categorically different from a goblin's sword. The binary outcome makes that difference mechanical rather than just tonal.\n<strong>The counterargument:</strong> save-or-die feels arbitrary when characters die to a single unlucky roll regardless of player skill or fictional positioning. It's the mechanic that most divides old-school enthusiasts from those who came to TTRPGs through later design.\n<strong>Modern OSR approaches:</strong> many second-wave OSR games have modified this — Cairn and Into the Odd have death tables that produce interesting consequences short of death, while retaining lethality at the high end.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key People</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a> (articulated OSR procedure philosophy) · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Gavin Norman\">Gavin Norman</a> (neo-trad procedural refinement in OSE/Dolmenwood) · Patrick Stuart (pointcrawl theory)\n<h2>Key Games</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dolmenwood\">Dolmenwood</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Hyperborea\">Hyperborea</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Into the Odd\">Into the Odd</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cairn\">Cairn</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Old-School Essentials\">Old-School Essentials</a>"}, "Concepts/Solo TTRPG Design": {"key": "Concepts/Solo TTRPG Design", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Solo TTRPG Design", "tags": ["concept", "solo", "design", "storygames"], "links": ["Games/Ironsworn", "Games/Starforged", "Games/Thousand Year Old Vampire", "People/Shawn Tomkin", "People/Tim Hutchings"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Solo TTRPG design is a recognized design category with its own specific mechanical requirements, distinct from adapting group games for solo play.", "html": "<h1>Solo TTRPG Design</h1>\n<p>#concept #solo #design #storygames</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Solo TTRPG design is a recognized design category with its own specific mechanical requirements, distinct from adapting group games for solo play.</p>\n<h2>The Design Challenge</h2>\n<p>Solo play requires solving problems that a GM and other players usually solve: <ul><li><strong>World response</strong> — what happens when characters act? (→ oracle systems)</li> <li><strong>Accountability</strong> — motivation to keep pursuing goals across sessions (→ vow/progress systems)</li> <li><strong>Pacing</strong> — urgency and momentum (→ clock systems, card structures)</li> <li><strong>Reflection</strong> — processing what has happened (→ journaling)</li> </ul> <h2>Key Innovations</h2></p>\n<strong>Oracle systems</strong> — randomized tables that generate thematically coherent content requiring interpretive judgment. Quality oracle design is the hardest part of solo game design. Bad oracles: produce random assemblage. Good oracles: produce content that feels like it came from a GM who understood the fiction.\n<strong>Progress tracks</strong> — visible, quantifiable advancement toward goals that rewards sustained engagement. Ironsworn's innovation: rolling against progress rather than a stat means success scales with narrative work done, not character capability.\n<strong>Journaling</strong> — the act of writing play as it happens serves both as record and as creative act, producing reflection that group play usually handles through conversation.\n<h2>Relationship to the Cozy Wave</h2>\n<p>Solo TTRPG design and the cozy wave overlap significantly. Both reject the assumption that TTRPGs require a group organized around combat. Both were amplified by the pandemic. Many cozy games support solo play; many solo games have a cozy register.</p>\n<h2>Key Games</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Ironsworn\">Ironsworn</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Starforged\">Starforged</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Thousand Year Old Vampire\">Thousand Year Old Vampire</a>\n<h2>Key Designers</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Shawn Tomkin\">Shawn Tomkin</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Tim Hutchings\">Tim Hutchings</a>"}, "Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic": {"key": "Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic", "category": "Concepts", "name": "The Conspiracy Mechanic", "tags": ["concept", "pbtA", "mystery", "design", "brindlewood"], "links": ["Games/Brindlewood Bay", "People/Jason Cordova", "People/Jason Cordova", "Games/Brindlewood Bay", "Games/The Between"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Traditional mystery RPGs have a structural problem: the GM knows the answer, the players don't. This creates:\n- Information asymmetry that can feel adversarial\n- \"Gotcha\" moments if players miss key clues\n- The GM steering play toward their predetermined solution\n- Players feeling like they're solving the GM's puzzle rather than creating a story", "html": "<h1>The Conspiracy Mechanic</h1>\n<p>#concept #pbtA #mystery #design #brindlewood</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Problem It Solves</h2>\n<p>Traditional mystery RPGs have a structural problem: <strong>the GM knows the answer, the players don't.</strong> This creates: <ul><li>Information asymmetry that can feel adversarial</li> <li>\"Gotcha\" moments if players miss key clues</li> <li>The GM steering play toward their predetermined solution</li> <li>Players feeling like they're solving the GM's puzzle rather than creating a story</li> </ul> <h2>The Conspiracy Mechanic</h2></p>\n<p>Introduced in <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\">Brindlewood Bay</a> by <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Cordova\">Jason Cordova</a>.</p>\n<strong>The Keeper does not predetermine the mystery's solution.</strong> Instead: 1. The Keeper prepares clues — details, inconsistencies, suspicious elements 2. Players investigate and collect clues through play 3. When ready, players trigger the <strong>Theorize Move</strong>: they assemble clues into an explanation 4. If the theory is plausible (fits the clues, fits the setting), it becomes true 5. The Conspiracy is confirmed through collective interpretation\n<h2>Why It Works</h2>\n<ul><li>The Keeper plays to find out what happened, same as the players</li>\n<li>There is no \"right answer\" to miss — the story is being authored at the table</li>\n<li>Player agency is genuine: they are making meaning, not decoding it</li>\n<li>The Keeper's job shifts from information gatekeeper to scene-setter and clue-provider</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>The Deeper Conspiracy</h2>\n<p>Brindlewood Bay adds a second layer: beneath each individual mystery is a larger <strong>Conspiracy</strong> — an ongoing supernatural threat accumulating across sessions. The same mechanic operates at campaign scale.</p>\n<h2>Designer</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Cordova\">Jason Cordova</a> | <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\">Brindlewood Bay</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Between\">The Between</a>"}, "Concepts/Three-Action Economy": {"key": "Concepts/Three-Action Economy", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Three-Action Economy", "tags": ["concept", "mainstream", "pathfinder", "design"], "links": ["Games/Pathfinder 2e", "People/Logan Bonner"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "The core resolution framework of Pathfinder 2nd Edition. Every character gets three actions per turn. Almost every activity costs one, two, or three of them:\n- Strike (attack) — 1 action\n- Move — 1 action\n- Cast a cantrip — 1–2 actions\n- Cast a complex spell — 3 actions\n- Raise a shield — 1 action", "html": "<h1>Three-Action Economy</h1>\n<p>#concept #mainstream #pathfinder #design</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>The core resolution framework of Pathfinder 2nd Edition. Every character gets three actions per turn. Almost every activity costs one, two, or three of them: <ul><li>Strike (attack) — 1 action</li> <li>Move — 1 action</li> <li>Cast a cantrip — 1–2 actions</li> <li>Cast a complex spell — 3 actions</li> <li>Raise a shield — 1 action</li> </ul> This replaces 3e/PF1e's standard action / move action / swift action / free action taxonomy.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<strong>More flexible than the old taxonomy.</strong> Want to move twice and attack once? Three moves? Two attacks? All are possible within the same framework.\n<strong>Creates meaningful tactical math.</strong> Is it worth spending two actions to cast this spell vs. one action to Strike twice? This decision is genuinely interesting and varies by situation.\n<strong>Scales elegantly.</strong> Works for single combatants and large battles alike without special-case rules.\n<h2>Propagation</h2>\nThe three-action economy has been adopted or adapted in several games following PF2e's release. It's likely to continue propagating — it solves real problems in action economy design cleanly.\n<h2>Origin</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 2e\">Pathfinder 2nd Edition</a> (2019) — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Logan Bonner\">Logan Bonner</a>"}, "Concepts/Bounded Accuracy": {"key": "Concepts/Bounded Accuracy", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Bounded Accuracy", "tags": ["concept", "mainstream", "5e", "design"], "links": ["Games/DD 5th Edition", "People/Mike Mearls", "People/Jeremy Crawford"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "A core design principle of D&D 5th Edition. In 3e and 4e, bonuses to attack rolls, AC, and skill checks scaled dramatically with level — a 20th-level fighter's attack bonus was so much higher than a 1st-level character's that low-level monsters became trivially easy. Bounded accuracy caps this scaling. A 20th-level fighter has roughly +11 to hit, not +25.", "html": "<h1>Bounded Accuracy</h1>\n<p>#concept #mainstream #5e #design</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A core design principle of D&D 5th Edition. In 3e and 4e, bonuses to attack rolls, AC, and skill checks scaled dramatically with level — a 20th-level fighter's attack bonus was so much higher than a 1st-level character's that low-level monsters became trivially easy. Bounded accuracy caps this scaling. A 20th-level fighter has roughly +11 to hit, not +25.</p>\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\n<strong>The world doesn't have to scale to the party.</strong> A goblin remains a credible threat at 10th level if there are enough of them. A dragon is dangerous at 1st level. This is directly compatible with OSR sensibilities about a living world that doesn't care about the party's power level.\n<strong>Encounter math becomes more reliable.</strong> GMs can mix creature levels more freely. A 1st-level character can contribute meaningfully alongside higher-level allies.\n<strong>Easier for new GMs.</strong> No need to carefully calibrate encounters to a narrow power band.\n<h2>Origin</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 5th Edition\">D&D 5th Edition</a> (2014) — <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Mike Mearls\">Mike Mearls</a> & <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeremy Crawford\">Jeremy Crawford</a>\n<h2>Relationship to OSR</h2>\nBounded accuracy is the 5e design decision most explicitly aligned with OSR philosophy. Whether intentional or not, it addressed one of the OSR's primary critiques of 3e: that a scaling world broke the referee's ability to use the environment as a living, dangerous place."}, "Concepts/Sandbox vs Railroad and the West Marches": {"key": "Concepts/Sandbox vs Railroad and the West Marches", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Sandbox vs Railroad and the West Marches", "tags": ["concept", "design", "osr", "gm", "campaigndesign"], "links": ["People/Matt Finch", "People/James Maliszewski", "People/Vincent Baker", "Games/Dolmenwood", "Games/Hyperborea", "Games/Apocalypse World", "Games/Ironsworn"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Two poles of campaign design philosophy, representing different theories of where narrative agency should live in TTRPG play.", "html": "<h1>Sandbox vs. Railroad & the West Marches Model</h1>\n<p>#concept #design #osr #gm #campaigndesign</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Spectrum</h2>\n<p>Two poles of campaign design philosophy, representing different theories of where narrative agency should live in TTRPG play.</p>\n<h3>The Railroad</h3>\n<p>A campaign structured around a predetermined narrative path. The GM has a story in mind; player choices are accommodated where possible but the major plot beats occur regardless. Named for the metaphor: players are passengers on a train — they can look out different windows, but the destination is fixed.</p>\n<strong>At its best:</strong> coherent, dramatically satisfying narratives with strong characterization and emotional payoff. Some players actively prefer this.\n<strong>At its worst:</strong> player choices feel meaningless because outcomes are predetermined; the GM \"fudges\" dice and overrides player decisions to protect the plot; players feel like an audience rather than participants.\n<strong>The illusionism critique</strong> (from the Forge tradition): a GM who gives players the <em>appearance</em> of choice while covertly steering toward predetermined outcomes is practicing \"illusionism\" — a form of bad faith that the Forge considered a design failure rather than a style preference.\n<h3>The Sandbox</h3>\n<p>A campaign structured around a living world with its own factions, agendas, and momentum. Players set their own goals; the world responds to their choices; there is no predetermined destination. Named for the playground metaphor: the sand is there, the tools are there, the players decide what to build.</p>\n<strong>At its best:</strong> genuine player agency; emergent stories that feel owned by the whole table; a world that feels alive and consequential.\n<strong>At its worst:</strong> directionless play where nothing feels urgent; players paralyzed by infinite options; GMs overwhelmed by maintaining a complex living world.\n<strong>The OSR's position:</strong> strongly pro-sandbox. The OSR play philosophy's insistence on rulings over rules, the living dungeon, and referee-as-referee rather than referee-as-storyteller are all expressions of sandbox values. The dungeon exists independently of the players; it doesn't await them.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The West Marches Model</h2>\n<strong>Designer:</strong> Ben Robbins | <strong>Published:</strong> 2007 (blog posts, \"ars ludi\")\n<p>The West Marches is a specific campaign model that solved a common real-world play problem: how to run a sandbox campaign for a large, irregularly available group of players.</p>\n<strong>The core structure:</strong> <ul><li>There is a safe home base (the town). The wilderness beyond is dangerous.</li> <li>The players — not the GM — organize each session. They decide who attends, where they're going, and what they're trying to accomplish.</li> <li>Sessions are self-contained expeditions that begin and end at home base.</li> <li>There is no fixed group. Any combination of willing players can form a party for any session.</li> <li>The world is persistent and shared — what one group discovers or changes is real for all groups.</li> </ul> <strong>Why it works:</strong> <ul><li>Scheduling problems are solved structurally. Missing a session doesn't derail a campaign.</li> <li>Player agency is maximized — they literally organize the session.</li> <li>The GM prepares the <em>world</em>, not the <em>plot</em>. Dungeons, factions, and geography are prepared once; they're used whenever players choose to engage with them.</li> <li>Player investment is high because they're choosing their own objectives rather than following a predetermined questline.</li> </ul> <strong>Influence:</strong> The West Marches model is one of the most cited campaign design documents in the OSR. It influenced how neo-trad and OSR games think about open-table play, session structure, and the GM's preparation practice. Dolmenwood's hexcrawl structure and its 200 prepared hexes reflect West Marches thinking: prepare the world thoroughly, let players navigate it freely.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The OSR's Design Resolution</h2>\n<p>The OSR doesn't treat the sandbox/railroad spectrum as a matter of preference — it treats it as a question with a defensible answer. The founding philosophical texts (Finch's Quick Primer, Maliszewski's Grognardia essays) argue that the original D&D design was sandbox in intent and that later editions' drift toward narrative scripting was a design failure.</p>\n<p>The specific mechanisms that enable sandbox play in OSR design: <ul><li><strong>Reaction rolls</strong> — monsters have their own agendas; encounters are negotiated, not scripted</li> <li><strong>Random tables</strong> — the world generates content independently of GM intention</li> <li><strong>The dungeon turn</strong> — time pressure exists independent of narrative needs</li> <li><strong>Faction systems</strong> — (Dolmenwood, Scarlet Heroes, etc.) — the world's factions pursue goals regardless of player involvement</li> </ul> All of these produce a world that feels like it exists independently of the players — the defining quality of sandbox play.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The PbtA Response</h2>\n<p>Apocalypse World's \"play to find out what happens\" is a story games answer to the railroad/sandbox spectrum. It is neither a railroad (the GM has no predetermined outcome) nor a conventional sandbox (the GM isn't maintaining a fully realized independent world). Instead, the GM prepares <em>situation</em> — pressures, characters, and problems — and plays to discover what the characters do with them.</p>\n<p>This represents a third position on the spectrum that the binary railroad/sandbox framing doesn't capture: <strong>the GM as situation-generator who discovers the story alongside the players</strong>.</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Key People</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/James Maliszewski\">James Maliszewski</a> (OSR sandbox philosophy) · Ben Robbins (West Marches model) · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a> (\"play to find out\" as third position)\n<h2>Key Games</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dolmenwood\">Dolmenwood</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Hyperborea\">Hyperborea</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Apocalypse World\">Apocalypse World</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Ironsworn\">Ironsworn</a> (oracles as sandbox tools)"}, "Concepts/Stress vs Hit Points": {"key": "Concepts/Stress vs Hit Points", "category": "Concepts", "name": "Stress vs Hit Points", "tags": ["concept", "design", "storygames", "osr", "consequence"], "links": ["Games/DD 5th Edition", "Games/Pathfinder 2e", "Games/Blades in the Dark", "People/John Harper", "Games/Spire The City Must Fall", "People/Grant Howitt", "People/Christopher Taylor", "Games/Mothership", "People/Sean McCoy", "Games/Monsterhearts", "People/Avery Alder", "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family", "Movements/PbtA Family"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Hit points are a numerical abstraction of a character's capacity to keep functioning. Losing HP represents accumulated damage, exhaustion, close calls, and deteriorating condition. Reaching 0 HP means the character cannot continue — death, unconsciousness, or incapacitation depending on the game.", "html": "<h1>Stress vs. Hit Points — Two Theories of Consequence</h1>\n<p>#concept #design #storygames #osr #consequence</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Hit Points Model</h2>\n<p>Hit points are a numerical abstraction of a character's capacity to keep functioning. Losing HP represents accumulated damage, exhaustion, close calls, and deteriorating condition. Reaching 0 HP means the character cannot continue — death, unconsciousness, or incapacitation depending on the game.</p>\n<strong>What HP communicates:</strong> <ul><li>Capability is the primary resource. Characters are resources to be managed.</li> <li>Consequences are graduated but undifferentiated — 3 HP of damage from a goblin's sword and 3 HP of damage from a pitfall are mechanically identical.</li> <li>Death (or incapacitation) is the only significant threshold.</li> </ul> <strong>HP's design strengths:</strong> Simple. Universal. Produces clear resource management decisions. Works for any level of lethality just by adjusting numbers.\n<strong>HP's design weaknesses:</strong> Produces a specific psychology at the table — characters are \"alive\" until they're suddenly \"dead.\" The gradient between \"fully functional\" and \"gone\" is largely invisible unless the GM describes it fictionally. The mechanic doesn't differentiate <em>how</em> characters are damaged.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>The Stress Model</h2>\n<p>Stress replaces or supplements HP with a track that represents accumulated psychological, physical, and social harm. Characters take Stress in response to danger; when Stress fills, consequences occur — but those consequences are varied, specific, and narratively interesting.</p>\n<strong>Origin in TTRPG design:</strong> Call of Cthulhu's Sanity system (1981) is an early implementation — a separate track for psychological harm that produces specific behavioral consequences. Modern stress systems develop this into a full alternative to HP.\n<strong>Blades in the Dark's implementation:</strong> <ul><li>Stress is a resource characters <em>spend</em> (to resist consequences, fuel flashbacks, push for extra effect) as well as a track that fills from harm</li> <li>When Stress fills, the character takes Trauma — a permanent change to who they are: Cold, Haunted, Obsessed, Paranoid, Reckless, Soft, Unstable, Vicious</li> <li>Trauma is not \"worse HP damage\" — it's a change in character identity</li> </ul> <strong>Spire's domain stress:</strong> <ul><li>Multiple separate stress tracks: Blood (physical), Mind (psychological), Shadow (social/professional), Silver (financial), Reputation (standing within the resistance network)</li> <li>Harm is allocated to the most appropriate domain rather than to a single pool</li> <li>Fallout tables generate varied, narratively specific consequences for each domain</li> </ul> <strong>Mothership's implementation:</strong> <ul><li>Stress accumulates through frightening events, not physical damage</li> <li>Stress triggers Panic rolls with escalating consequences (freeze, flee, catatonia, cardiac arrest)</li> <li>Mechanizes the horror genre's core dynamic: accumulated dread makes each new threat feel worse</li> </ul> ---\n<h2>What Stress Does That HP Doesn't</h2>\n<strong>Consequences are varied.</strong> \"You take 3 HP\" produces one outcome. \"You take Mind stress, roll Fallout\" produces one of a range of specific, narratively meaningful consequences. The character's state after the same numeric threshold is always different.\n<strong>Characters have a history.</strong> HP damage heals between sessions; a character who took 30 HP in the last session is fully functional in the next. Trauma and Fallout conditions persist — they become part of the character's story. A character who has taken Haunted Trauma is permanently different from one who hasn't.\n<strong>Spending stress is meaningful.</strong> In Blades, spending Stress is a real decision because Stress is also a harm track. You can push yourself for extra effect, but doing so moves you closer to Trauma. This creates genuine tension in the spending decision that spending HP doesn't produce.\n<strong>The fiction and the mechanic align.</strong> \"You're at 3 HP but feeling great\" is a common absurdity in HP systems. Stress systems produce states that feel more continuous with the fiction — a character with high Stress <em>should</em> be acting differently than one with low Stress, and the mechanics support this.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Hard Moves and Soft Moves (PbtA)</h2>\n<p>Closely related to the question of consequences: how does the GM deliver narrative harm?</p>\n<strong>Soft move:</strong> announces impending badness without fully delivering it. Foreshadows consequences. Creates tension. \"The building shudders — the ceiling is going to come down.\" A soft move gives players a chance to react before the consequence lands.\n<strong>Hard move:</strong> delivers the consequence immediately and fully. \"The ceiling comes down. You're buried.\" No opportunity to react. Hard moves follow missed rolls (6-) directly, or follow up on soft moves that players ignored.\n<strong>The design argument:</strong> mixing soft and hard moves produces a specific narrative rhythm. Soft moves create suspense and give players warning; hard moves make clear that the world is real and consequences are actual. A GM who only makes soft moves produces a consequence-free game; one who only makes hard moves produces a punishing one. The taxonomy gives the GM a precise vocabulary for where they are in the consequence sequence.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Conditions (Monsterhearts and beyond)</h2>\n<p>A third approach to consequence: Conditions replace both HP damage and Stress tracking with specific named states. Examples from Monsterhearts: Afraid, Angry, Guilty, Hopeless, Insecure.</p>\n<strong>What Conditions do:</strong> <ul><li>Each Condition specifically limits or modifies what a character can do</li> <li>Conditions describe the character's state in dramatically useful terms rather than numerical ones</li> <li>Conditions must be fictionally addressed to be cleared — you don't rest off \"Guilty,\" you do something about what you're guilty for</li> </ul> Conditions have propagated widely across PbtA and FitD games because they produce narratively interesting states while remaining mechanically functional.\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>HP: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 5th Edition\">D&D 5e</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 2e\">PF2e</a> · all d20 games</li>\n<li>Stress (Blades): <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Blades in the Dark\">Blades in the Dark</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a></li>\n<li>Domain stress (Spire): <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\">Spire</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Christopher Taylor\">Christopher Taylor</a></li>\n<li>Stress/Panic (Mothership): <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mothership\">Mothership</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Sean McCoy\">Sean McCoy</a></li>\n<li>Conditions: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Monsterhearts\">Monsterhearts</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Avery Alder\">Avery Alder</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Forged in the Dark Family\">FitD</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Concepts/+One System": {"key": "Concepts/+One System", "category": "Concepts", "name": "+One System", "tags": ["concept", "system", "mechanics", "wetink", "d6", "cards"], "links": ["Publishers/Wet Ink Games", "Publishers/Wet Ink Games", "Games/Never Going Home", "Games/Precious Things"], "lineage": "crossover", "summary": "A proprietary RPG system designed by Brandon K. Aten for Wet Ink Games, used across their catalog from WWI eldritch horror to cozy tiny dragon games. Uses d6 dice pools and a standard deck of playing cards, with the card mechanic doing different narrative work in each game.", "html": "<h1>+One System</h1>\n<p>#concept #system #mechanics #wetink #d6 #cards</p>\n<strong>Designer:</strong> Brandon K. Aten | <strong>Publisher:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wet Ink Games\">Wet Ink Games</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>What It Is</h2>\n<p>A proprietary RPG system designed by Brandon K. Aten for Wet Ink Games, used across their catalog from WWI eldritch horror to cozy tiny dragon games. Uses d6 dice pools and a standard deck of playing cards, with the card mechanic doing different narrative work in each game.</p>\n<h2>Core Resolution</h2>\n<p>Players roll a number of d6 equal to their skill proficiency. Successes are 5 or 6 on each die. Characters use their Attributes to manipulate results — adding dice before a roll, adding a pip to a die after a roll (e.g. changing a 4 to a 5), rerolling dice, or keeping a result. The modifier system makes Attributes feel meaningfully different from skills: skills tell you how many dice you roll, Attributes tell you how you can shape the outcome.</p>\n<h2>The Playing Card Layer</h2>\n<p>Cards serve different narrative functions in each +One game:</p>\n<strong>Never Going Home</strong> — cards represent mental and emotional resources. Players manage a hand of cards; each discard requires describing what part of yourself you're losing to eldritch corruption. Cards can be played for in-game bonuses. As the hand depletes, the character deteriorates. The mechanic makes corruption tangible and player-directed — <em>you</em> choose what to sacrifice.\n<strong>Precious Things</strong> — cards represent magical capability. Individual spells and \"big magic\" are both card-driven, with the deck providing 52 different spells. The card system makes magic feel finite, special, and distinct from the d6 skill system.\n<strong>Psychic Kids</strong> — cards represent psychic powers, creating a separate economy for extraordinary abilities distinct from mundane skill rolls.\n<h2>Design Significance</h2>\n<p>The +One System is notable for how cleanly the same chassis serves radically different tonal registers. Wet Ink's catalog ranges from survival horror to family-friendly cozy play, and the system adapts without requiring complete redesign. The card mechanic is the key variable: what the cards <em>mean</em> — what they represent narratively and what using them costs — is redesigned per game while the underlying d6 resolution stays consistent.</p>\n<p>This is a different approach from PbtA's genre translation (which rewrites Moves per game) or FitD's adaptation (which rewrites the crew/faction layer per game). +One translates by reassigning the card layer's meaning while keeping the dice stable.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Designer: Brandon K. Aten</li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wet Ink Games\">Wet Ink Games</a></li>\n<li>Games: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Never Going Home\">Never Going Home</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Precious Things\">Precious Things</a> · Psychic Kids · Tenebria: Remnant of Rome</li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Francesco Nepitello": {"key": "People/Francesco Nepitello", "category": "People", "name": "Francesco Nepitello", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "crossover", "designer", "licensed"], "links": ["Games/The One Ring 2e", "Concepts/The Journey as Mechanical Unit", "Publishers/Free League Publishing", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Concepts/Licensed Adaptation Design", "Concepts/The Journey as Mechanical Unit", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Designer of The One Ring — the model for licensed adaptation done right. His fundamental insight: Tolkien's fiction is not a D&D setting. D&D's mechanical assumptions produce play antithetical to what Tolkien's fiction contains. The One Ring designs from source material content rather than applying IP to an existing system.", "html": "<h1>Francesco Nepitello</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #crossover #designer #licensed</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2011 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer (The One Ring)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of The One Ring — the model for licensed adaptation done right. His fundamental insight: Tolkien's fiction is not a D&D setting. D&D's mechanical assumptions produce play antithetical to what Tolkien's fiction contains. The One Ring designs from source material content rather than applying IP to an existing system.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td>The One Ring 1e</td><td>2011</td><td>First design (Cubicle 7)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The One Ring 2e\\</td><td>The One Ring 2e\">td><td>The One Ring 2e</a></td><td>2022</td><td>Refined; Free League; definitive version</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Innovations</h2>\n<strong>Journey as primary mechanical unit</strong> — not the encounter. Travel is a full system: path choice, role assignment, hazard rolls, Fatigue accumulation. Makes travel itself narratively meaningful. See: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The Journey as Mechanical Unit\">The Journey as Mechanical Unit</a>\n<strong>Fellowship Phase</strong> — structured rest and recovery. Encodes Tolkien's departure-and-return narrative rhythm.\n<strong>Shadow and Hope</strong> — mechanically opposed. Primary dramatic tension: will characters maintain integrity against creeping darkness?\n<strong>Fellowship pool</strong> — shared Hope resource replenished through prosocial behavior. Makes community support mechanically optimal.\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\nRead The One Ring before running any licensed adaptation — the clearest demonstration of what \"designing from source material\" means in practice.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Free League Publishing\">Free League Publishing</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Licensed Adaptation Design\">Licensed Adaptation Design</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The Journey as Mechanical Unit\">Journey as Mechanical Unit</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Shawn Tomkin": {"key": "People/Shawn Tomkin", "category": "People", "name": "Shawn Tomkin", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "solo", "designer"], "links": ["Games/Ironsworn", "Games/Starforged", "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Movements/Solo TTRPG Design", "Movements/Solo TTRPG Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2019 – present | Role: Designer; software designer by profession | Website: [ironswornrpg.com](https://www.ironswornrpg.com)", "html": "<h1>Shawn Tomkin</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #solo #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2019 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer; software designer by profession | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://www.ironswornrpg.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">ironswornrpg.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Ironsworn — the game that established solo TTRPG as a legitimate design category rather than a fallback for players without a group. The Vow system and oracle tables are his primary contributions to the design vocabulary. Ironsworn was released free and grew through word of mouth into one of the most played indie games of its era.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Ironsworn\\</td><td>Ironsworn\">td><td>Ironsworn</a></td><td>2019</td><td>Free; established solo TTRPG as a design category</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Starforged\\</td><td>Ironsworn: Starforged\">td><td>Ironsworn: Starforged</a></td><td>2022</td><td>Space opera; refined oracle system</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Innovations</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Vow system</strong> — formal commitments tracked on progress clocks; Fulfill Your Vow rolls against progress rather than a stat, so success scales with narrative engagement</li>\n<li><strong>Oracle system</strong> — tables designed for thematic coherence, not randomness; require interpretive judgment</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Solo TTRPG Design\">Solo TTRPG Design</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Solo TTRPG Design\">Solo TTRPG Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Kelsey Dionne": {"key": "People/Kelsey Dionne", "category": "People", "name": "Kelsey Dionne", "tags": ["person", "osr", "crossover", "designer", "mainstream"], "links": ["Games/Shadowdark RPG", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023", "Games/Shadowdark RPG", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Active: 2017 – present | Role: Designer, publisher (The Arcane Library, Las Vegas) | Website: [thearcanelibrary.com](https://www.thearcanelibrary.com)", "html": "<h1>Kelsey Dionne</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #crossover #designer #mainstream</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2017 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, publisher (The Arcane Library, Las Vegas) | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://www.thearcanelibrary.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">thearcanelibrary.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why She Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Shadowdark RPG — the most commercially successful OSR-adjacent game of the post-OGL era and the clearest example of design that successfully bridges the 5e mainstream audience and the OSR tradition. Dionne came up through 5e adventure writing before designing her own system; the craft of efficient, table-ready adventure presentation translates directly into Shadowdark's clean design.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>The Secrets of Skyhorn Lighthouse</em></td><td>2017</td><td>One of the highest-rated 5e adventures; established The Arcane Library</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Shadowdark RPG\\</td><td>Shadowdark RPG\">td><td>Shadowdark RPG</a></td><td>2023</td><td>$1.3M Kickstarter; 4 gold ENNIEs 2024; OSR-to-5e bridge</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Philosophy</h2>\n<p>\"D&D without all the stuff that makes it less fun.\" Shadowdark strips 5e's bloat while retaining its legibility for mainstream players. Her background writing ultra-efficient 5e adventures — dense with exactly the information a DM needs, nothing more — translates directly into Shadowdark's two-page core rules and clean presentation.</p>\n<p>Key design decisions: real-time torches (a torch burns out in 60 actual minutes, not game turns), flat math with minimal modifier inflation, talent rolls mixing choice and randomness, open third-party license.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: The Arcane Library</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OGL Crisis 2023\">OGL Crisis 2023</a></li>\n<li>Game: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Shadowdark RPG\\\">Shadowdark RPG</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Robert Schwalb": {"key": "People/Robert Schwalb", "category": "People", "name": "Robert Schwalb", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "designer", "veteran"], "links": ["Games/Shadow of the Weird Wizard", "Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Active: 2000s – present | Role: Designer, publisher (Schwalb Entertainment)", "html": "<h1>Robert Schwalb</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #designer #veteran</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2000s – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, publisher (Schwalb Entertainment)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Veteran designer with broad mainstream credentials who founded his own company and designed two significant independent games. His career arc — Green Ronin staff, WotC 5e lead designer, indie publisher — is a model for how mainstream design expertise translates to independent work. His Paths system is one of the more distinctive character development frameworks in recent fantasy game design.</p>\n<h2>Career Background</h2>\n<p>Green Ronin (A Song of Ice and Fire RPG, Freeport) → Wizards of the Coast (5e lead designer, 2012–2014) → founded Schwalb Entertainment.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td>D&D 5e (co-designer)</td><td>2014</td><td>Lead design credit on PHB</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Shadow of the Demon Lord</em></td><td>2015</td><td>Critically acclaimed; grimdark; Paths system</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Shadow of the Weird Wizard\\</td><td>Shadow of the Weird Wizard\">td><td>Shadow of the Weird Wizard</a></td><td>2024</td><td>Same engine, heroic register; most anticipated TTRPG of 2024 (EN World)</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>The Paths System</h2>\nCharacters choose three Paths across a campaign — Novice, Expert, Master — each a structured package of abilities taken at a different developmental stage. Early play is simple; late play is richly differentiated. Deep customization without front-loaded complexity.\n<h2>SotDL vs. Weird Wizard</h2>\nDemon Lord was his \"catharsis\" — intensely grimdark, critically acclaimed system, limited by register. Weird Wizard uses the same engine with a heroic, accessible register, designed for players who loved the mechanics but couldn't play in Demon Lord's bleak world.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/D&D Edition Wars\">D&D Edition Wars</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Christopher Taylor": {"key": "People/Christopher Taylor", "category": "People", "name": "Christopher Taylor", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "fitD", "designer", "uk"], "links": ["People/Grant Howitt", "Games/Spire The City Must Fall", "Games/Heart The City Beneath", "People/Grant Howitt", "Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard", "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2018 – present | Role: Designer (Rowan, Rook and Decard)", "html": "<h1>Christopher Taylor</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #fitD #designer #uk</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2018 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer (Rowan, Rook and Decard)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Co-designer with <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a> at Rowan, Rook and Decard. Taylor's contributions include much of the mechanical architecture of Spire and Heart, including the stress-and-fallout system that distinguishes RR&D games from standard FitD. A quieter public presence than Howitt but central to the design.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\\</td><td>Spire: The City Must Fall\">td><td>Spire: The City Must Fall</a></td><td>2018</td><td>Co-designed ⭐ <em>you play this</em></td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Heart The City Beneath\\</td><td>Heart: The City Beneath\">td><td>Heart: The City Beneath</a></td><td>2021</td><td>Co-designed</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Collaborator: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Grant Howitt\">Grant Howitt</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard\">Rowan, Rook and Decard</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Forged in the Dark Family\">Forged in the Dark Family</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Stuart Marshall": {"key": "People/Stuart Marshall", "category": "People", "name": "Stuart Marshall", "tags": ["person", "osr", "designer"], "links": ["People/Matt Finch", "Games/OSRIC", "People/Matt Finch", "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing", "Concepts/Retroclones", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Co-author of OSRIC alongside Matt Finch. Did the painstaking legal and mechanical work of demonstrating that AD&D's mechanics could be expressed in new text under the OGL without infringing WotC's copyrights. Less prominent as a public voice than Finch but foundational to the movement's infrastructure.", "html": "<h1>Stuart Marshall</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2006 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, legal architect\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Co-author of OSRIC alongside <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a>. Did the painstaking legal and mechanical work of demonstrating that AD&D's mechanics could be expressed in new text under the OGL without infringing WotC's copyrights. Less prominent as a public voice than Finch but foundational to the movement's infrastructure.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/OSRIC\\</td><td>OSRIC\">td><td>OSRIC</a></td><td>2006</td><td>Legal vehicle enabling AD&D-compatible publishing</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Collaborator: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Matt Finch\">Matt Finch</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">OGL & Open Licensing</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Retroclones\">Retroclones</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Hamish Cameron": {"key": "People/Hamish Cameron", "category": "People", "name": "Hamish Cameron", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "pbtA", "designer"], "links": ["Games/The Sprawl", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Concepts/Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Designer of The Sprawl — a PbtA cyberpunk game that understood the genre's actual subject matter (systemic corporate power rather than individual heroism) and designed mechanics to reflect it. The Clock system anticipated FitD's clocks and influenced how PbtA designers approach faction mechanics.", "html": "<h1>Hamish Cameron</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #pbtA #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2016 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of The Sprawl — a PbtA cyberpunk game that understood the genre's actual subject matter (systemic corporate power rather than individual heroism) and designed mechanics to reflect it. The Clock system anticipated FitD's clocks and influenced how PbtA designers approach faction mechanics.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Sprawl\\</td><td>The Sprawl\">td><td>The Sprawl</a></td><td>2016</td><td>PbtA cyberpunk; Clock system; corporate power as mechanic</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Related concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)\">Clocks</a> (anticipated by The Sprawl's Clock system)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Spenser Starke and Rowan Hall": {"key": "People/Spenser Starke and Rowan Hall", "category": "People", "name": "Spenser Starke and Rowan Hall", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "crossover", "designer", "actualplay"], "links": ["Games/Daggerheart", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Movements/Actual Play Boom", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Co-designed Daggerheart (2024) — Critical Role's own RPG system. The most significant example of the actual play tradition creating its own mechanical vocabulary. Explicitly acknowledged indie design influences (Baker, Harper) in a way mainstream publishers rarely do. Developed through extensive public playtest.", "html": "<h1>Spenser Starke & Rowan Hall</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #crossover #designer #actualplay</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2024 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designers (Darrington Press)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why They Matter</h2>\n<p>Co-designed Daggerheart (2024) — Critical Role's own RPG system. The most significant example of the actual play tradition creating its own mechanical vocabulary. Explicitly acknowledged indie design influences (Baker, Harper) in a way mainstream publishers rarely do. Developed through extensive public playtest.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Daggerheart\\</td><td>Daggerheart\">td><td>Daggerheart</a></td><td>2024</td><td>Actual play's own mechanics; Hope/Fear dice system</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design: Hope and Fear Dice</h2>\n<p>Resolution uses two d12s — one Hope, one Fear. Their relationship determines not just success/failure but narrative authority flow: high Fear with success gives the GM narrative fodder; high Hope gives the player narrative fodder. Constant bidirectional narrative momentum reflecting PbtA/FitD influence.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: Darrington Press (Critical Role)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Actual Play Boom\">Actual Play Boom</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Luke Crane": {"key": "People/Luke Crane", "category": "People", "name": "Luke Crane", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "designer", "publisher"], "links": ["Games/Burning Wheel", "Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2002 – present | Role: Designer, publisher (Burning Wheel HQ)", "html": "<h1>Luke Crane</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #designer #publisher</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2002 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, publisher (Burning Wheel HQ)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Burning Wheel — an intensely character-driven fantasy RPG with a highly mechanical approach to belief, instinct, and trait systems. Its core philosophy: mechanical weight should sit on what characters <em>believe and want</em>, not what they can <em>do</em>. Hugely influential on story games design even among people who never played it. Also designed Mouse Guard RPG and Torchbearer. Later worked at Kickstarter.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Burning Wheel\\</td><td>Burning Wheel\">td><td>Burning Wheel</a></td><td>2002 (rev. 2011)</td><td>Belief/instinct system; deeply influential</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Mouse Guard RPG</em></td><td>2008</td><td>Burning Wheel adapted for David Petersen's comic</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Torchbearer</em></td><td>2013</td><td>Dungeon-delve with resource management; OSR-adjacent</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\nBurning Wheel is demanding to learn and demanding to run, but rewards close reading as a design object. The \"Hub and Spokes\" system and the Beliefs mechanic are genuinely novel approaches to the problem of character motivation.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory\">The Forge & GNS Theory</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Peter Adkison": {"key": "People/Peter Adkison", "category": "People", "name": "Peter Adkison", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "publisher", "wotc", "ogl"], "links": ["Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing", "Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Active: 1990 – 2001 at WotC | Role: CEO, Wizards of the Coast", "html": "<h1>Peter Adkison</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #publisher #wotc #ogl</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 1990 – 2001 at WotC | <strong>Role:</strong> CEO, Wizards of the Coast\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Founded WotC in 1990, grew it through Magic: The Gathering, and led the acquisition of TSR in 1997. As CEO during D&D 3e's development, made the decision to publish the game under the Open Game License — influenced by open source software culture and a belief that a thriving third-party ecosystem would grow the core game. The OGL is his most lasting legacy, both in the market it created and in the 2023 crisis it survived.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Open Game License</td><td>2000</td><td>The most consequential publishing act in post-1990 TTRPG history</td></tr>\n<tr><td>D&D 3rd Edition</td><td>2000</td><td>Publisher; transformed D&D into an open ecosystem</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\nAdkison left WotC after Hasbro's acquisition and has not been a major industry figure since 2001. His significance is entirely in this one decision. The OGL outlasted him, outlasted WotC's own attempts to revoke it, and remains the legal foundation of the open gaming commons.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">OGL & Open Licensing</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/D&D Edition Wars\">D&D Edition Wars</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Sage LaTorra": {"key": "People/Sage LaTorra", "category": "People", "name": "Sage LaTorra", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "pbtA", "designer"], "links": ["People/Adam Koebel", "Games/Dungeon World", "People/Adam Koebel", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2012 – present | Role: Designer; later game designer at WotC", "html": "<h1>Sage LaTorra</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #pbtA #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2012 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer; later game designer at WotC\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Co-designer (with <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Adam Koebel\">Adam Koebel</a>) of Dungeon World — the game that translated PbtA's design language into D&D-style dungeon fantasy and introduced PbtA ideas to the mainstream D&D audience. Later went to work at WotC on D&D 5e, a career arc that illustrates PbtA's influence crossing into the mainstream.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dungeon World\\</td><td>Dungeon World\">td><td>Dungeon World</a></td><td>2012</td><td>PbtA meets D&D; major ENnie winner</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Collaborator: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Adam Koebel\">Adam Koebel</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Meguey Baker": {"key": "People/Meguey Baker", "category": "People", "name": "Meguey Baker", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "pbtA", "designer"], "links": ["People/Vincent Baker", "Games/Apocalypse World", "People/Vincent Baker", "Publishers/lumpley games", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Co-designer of Apocalypse World alongside Vincent Baker. Her contributions to AW — particularly around the game's social and intimate fiction, its approach to player agency, and its design of specific playbooks — are significant and often underacknowledged in histories that attribute the game solely to Vincent. Also an independent designer of games exploring history, intimacy, and social dynamics.", "html": "<h1>Meguey Baker</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #pbtA #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2010 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer (lumpley games)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why She Matters</h2>\n<p>Co-designer of Apocalypse World alongside <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a>. Her contributions to AW — particularly around the game's social and intimate fiction, its approach to player agency, and its design of specific playbooks — are significant and often underacknowledged in histories that attribute the game solely to Vincent. Also an independent designer of games exploring history, intimacy, and social dynamics.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Apocalypse World\\</td><td>Apocalypse World\">td><td>Apocalypse World</a></td><td>2010</td><td>Co-designed; PbtA origin</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>1001 Nights</em></td><td>2006</td><td>Pre-AW; story game about telling stories</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Psi</em>Run</td><td>2012</td><td>Amnesia and psychic powers; innovative dice mechanic</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Collaborator: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Vincent Baker\">Vincent Baker</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/lumpley games\">lumpley games</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Avery Alder": {"key": "People/Avery Alder", "category": "People", "name": "Avery Alder", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "pbtA", "designer"], "links": ["Games/Perfect Unrevised", "Games/Simple World", "Games/Monsterhearts", "Games/The Quiet Year", "Games/Dream Askew", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Movements/GM-less Design", "Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)", "Concepts/Lures (Belonging Outside Belonging)", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2010 – present | Role: Designer (Buried Without Ceremony) | Website: [buriedwithoutceremony.com](https://buriedwithoutceremony.com)", "html": "<h1>Avery Alder</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #pbtA #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2010 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer (Buried Without Ceremony) | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://buriedwithoutceremony.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">buriedwithoutceremony.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why She Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Monsterhearts (one of the most played indie games of the 2010s) and The Quiet Year (which established a new genre of collaborative fiction game). Alder's work is notable for centering queer experience and emotional complexity, and for finding elegant mechanical solutions to difficult design problems. Also the originator of the Belonging Outside Belonging framework (Dream Askew).</p>\n<p>Her earlier works were published under a deadname — Perfect, Unrevised (2010) and Simple World (2013) — and are credited to Buried Without Ceremony.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Perfect Unrevised\\</td><td>Perfect, Unrevised\">td><td>Perfect, Unrevised</a></td><td>2010</td><td>Pre-PbtA dystopian story game; bidding mechanic; free PDF</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Simple World\\</td><td>Simple World\">td><td>Simple World</a></td><td>2013</td><td>PbtA design toolkit; \"get it on the table fast\" philosophy; free</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Monsterhearts\\</td><td>Monsterhearts\">td><td>Monsterhearts</a></td><td>2012</td><td>PbtA; teen monsters; queer themes; Strings economy</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Quiet Year\\</td><td>The Quiet Year\">td><td>The Quiet Year</a></td><td>2013</td><td>Map-making community game; no GM; widely used in design education</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dream Askew\\</td><td>Dream Askew\">td><td>Dream Askew</a></td><td>2018</td><td>GM-less PbtA; Belonging Outside Belonging; innovative token economy</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\n<em>The Quiet Year</em> is worth playing or reading for its approach to constraint-based collaborative worldbuilding. <em>Simple World</em> is essential reading for anyone designing a PbtA game — it demonstrates the minimal viable chassis in under 10 pages.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: Buried Without Ceremony</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/GM-less Design\">GM-less Design</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)\">Moves</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Lures (Belonging Outside Belonging)\">Lures — Belonging Outside Belonging</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Adam Koebel": {"key": "People/Adam Koebel", "category": "People", "name": "Adam Koebel", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "pbtA", "designer"], "links": ["People/Sage LaTorra", "Games/Dungeon World", "People/Sage LaTorra", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2012 – present (with significant controversy in 2020) | Role: Designer, actual play GM", "html": "<h1>Adam Koebel</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #pbtA #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2012 – present (with significant controversy in 2020) | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, actual play GM\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Co-designer of Dungeon World alongside <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Sage LaTorra\">Sage LaTorra</a>. Also became a prominent actual play GM with the <em>Rollplay</em> and <em>Friends at the Table</em>-adjacent scene. His design work is significant; his public standing was severely damaged by a 2020 incident involving a live actual play session.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dungeon World\\</td><td>Dungeon World\">td><td>Dungeon World</a></td><td>2012</td><td>Co-designed; PbtA's entry point for D&D players</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Collaborator: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Sage LaTorra\">Sage LaTorra</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Jason Cordova": {"key": "People/Jason Cordova", "category": "People", "name": "Jason Cordova", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "pbtA", "designer", "podcaster"], "links": ["Games/Brindlewood Bay", "Games/The Between", "Publishers/Magpie Games", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic", "Conventions/Gauntlet Codex", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2018 – present | Role: Designer, podcaster (The Gauntlet community) | Website: [magpiegames.com](https://magpiegames.com)", "html": "<h1>Jason Cordova</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #pbtA #designer #podcaster</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2018 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, podcaster (The Gauntlet community) | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://magpiegames.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">magpiegames.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Brindlewood Bay — a PbtA mystery game in which elderly women solve Lovecraftian murders — and its successor The Between. Cordova's design innovations include the <strong>Conspiracy mechanic</strong> (mystery answers are generated collaboratively at the table, not predetermined) and a deeply considered approach to the Keeper/GM role in mystery play. Also runs The Gauntlet, an influential online TTRPG community and podcast.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\\</td><td>Brindlewood Bay\">td><td>Brindlewood Bay</a></td><td>2020</td><td>PbtA mystery; Conspiracy mechanic ⭐ <em>you GM this</em></td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/The Between\\</td><td>The Between\">td><td>The Between</a></td><td>2022</td><td>Victorian mystery; Brindlewood successor</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\nThe Conspiracy mechanic is a genuine design breakthrough for mystery play — it solves the \"the GM knows the answer\" problem that makes mysteries awkward at the table. Worth understanding even if you modify how you use it.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Magpie Games\">Magpie Games</a></li>\n<li>Community: The Gauntlet (podcast and convention)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic\">The Conspiracy Mechanic</a></li>\n<li>Conventions: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Conventions/Gauntlet Codex\">Gauntlet Gatherings</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Chris McDowall": {"key": "People/Chris McDowall", "category": "People", "name": "Chris McDowall", "tags": ["person", "osr", "designer", "minimalist", "ruleslight", "uk"], "links": ["Games/Into the Odd", "Games/Electric Bastionland", "Games/Mythic Bastionland", "Games/Cairn", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "People/Yochai Gal", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Active: 2014 – present | Role: Designer, blogger (Bastionland Press) | Website: [bastionlandpress.com](https://www.bastionlandpress.com)", "html": "<h1>Chris McDowall</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #designer #minimalist #ruleslight #uk</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2014 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, blogger (Bastionland Press) | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://www.bastionlandpress.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">bastionlandpress.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>The most rigorous application of design minimalism to OSR premises. McDowall began by publicly asking: what happens if you remove each element of the OSR chassis and test whether play improves? The answers were consistent — removing the to-hit roll, removing skill lists, replacing spell lists with discovered items all produced play that was faster and more focused on interesting decisions. Into the Odd is the accumulated result of that testing. Mythic Bastionland proves the chassis can support full campaign play with domain management, social advancement, and a defined narrative arc — without becoming complicated.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Into the Odd\\</td><td>Into the Odd\">td><td>Into the Odd</a></td><td>2014 (remastered 2022)</td><td>OSR minimalism; no to-hit rolls; Arcana</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Electric Bastionland\\</td><td>Electric Bastionland\">td><td>Electric Bastionland</a></td><td>2020</td><td>Failed careers; debt as campaign engine</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mythic Bastionland\\</td><td>Mythic Bastionland\">td><td>Mythic Bastionland</a></td><td>2024</td><td>Arthurian; Myths/Omens; Sites mechanic; Glory</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Core Design Positions</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>No to-hit roll</strong> — roll straight to damage; interesting decisions are about what you trade</li>\n<li><strong>No skill lists</strong> — fictional positioning and equipment replace numerical modifiers</li>\n<li><strong>Arcana</strong> — magic as improvisation with discovered weird items, not spell lists</li>\n<li><strong>Three stats</strong> (STR, DEX, WIL) — HP is a buffer before real ability damage begins</li>\n<li><strong>Setting implied</strong> through art and tables, never stated in a sourcebook</li>\n<li><strong>Distillation as method</strong> — each design decision tested against whether removal improves play</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Legacy</h2>\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cairn\\\">Cairn</a> (Yochai Gal, 2020) distilled the ItO chassis into its most accessible form. The Into the Odd family now includes dozens of games across genres. The Sites mechanic from Mythic Bastionland has been adopted as a portable location design tool across the broader TTRPG community.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design\">Post-OSR & Minimalist Design</a></li>\n<li>Influenced: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Yochai Gal\">Yochai Gal</a> (Cairn)</li>\n<li>Grant Howitt on Mythic Bastionland: \"a victory lap\"</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Jeremy Crawford": {"key": "People/Jeremy Crawford", "category": "People", "name": "Jeremy Crawford", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "designer", "wotc", "darrington"], "links": ["Games/DD 5th Edition", "People/Chris Perkins", "People/Mike Mearls", "People/Chris Perkins", "Publishers/Wizards of the Coast", "Games/DD 5th Edition", "Games/Daggerheart", "Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Active: 2007–2025 at WotC; 2025–present at Darrington Press\nRole: Lead rules designer, D&D 5e (WotC) \n---", "html": "<h1>Jeremy Crawford</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #designer #wotc #darrington</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2007–2025 at WotC; 2025–present at Darrington Press <strong>Role:</strong> Lead rules designer, D&D 5e (WotC) → Game Director, Darrington Press\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Co-primary architect of D&D 5th Edition alongside Mike Mearls, and the sole primary public voice for D&D's rules across its entire 5e lifespan. His departure from WotC and arrival at Darrington Press in June 2025 is the most significant personnel shift in mainstream TTRPG in years — the person most responsible for how 5e's mechanics work is now directing the game development of 5e's most prominent competitor.</p>\n<h2>Timeline</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Period</td><td>Role</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2007–2014</td><td>Designer, WotC</td><td>Co-designed D&D 5e</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2014–2025</td><td>Lead rules designer & public face</td><td>Primary rules authority across 5e's full run</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2024</td><td>Led D&D 2024 revision</td><td>Final major WotC project</td></tr>\n<tr><td>April 2025</td><td>Departed WotC</td><td>Framed as retirement after D&D's 50th anniversary</td></tr>\n<tr><td>June 2025</td><td>Joined Darrington Press</td><td>Game Director; working on Daggerheart expansions</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 5th Edition\\</td><td>D&D 5th Edition\">td><td>D&D 5th Edition</a></td><td>2014</td><td>Co-lead designer</td></tr>\n<tr><td>D&D 2024 revision</td><td>2024</td><td>Led final WotC project</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Daggerheart expansions</td><td>2025–present</td><td>New setting in development at Darrington</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>The Move to Darrington</h2>\n<p>Crawford and <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris Perkins\">Chris Perkins</a> together represent 46 combined years of WotC experience. Both departed WotC in April 2025 and were announced as Darrington Press hires in June 2025 — Crawford as Game Director, Perkins as Creative Director. The announcement coincided with significant other departures from WotC, suggesting a broader talent transition at the company.</p>\n<p>Crawford has stated the Darrington team is \"passionate, wildly creative, and committed to building welcoming, connected, amazing story-driven experiences.\"</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Collaborator: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Mike Mearls\">Mike Mearls</a> (5e) · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris Perkins\">Chris Perkins</a> (Darrington)</li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wizards of the Coast\">WotC</a> (2007–2025) · Darrington Press (2025–present)</li>\n<li>Games: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 5th Edition\">D&D 5th Edition</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Daggerheart\">Daggerheart</a> (expansions)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/D&D Edition Wars\">D&D Edition Wars</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Daniel Proctor": {"key": "People/Daniel Proctor", "category": "People", "name": "Daniel Proctor", "tags": ["person", "osr", "designer", "publisher"], "links": ["Games/Labyrinth Lord", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Concepts/Retroclones", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Active: 2007 – present | Role: Designer, publisher (Goblinoid Games)", "html": "<h1>Daniel Proctor</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #designer #publisher</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2007 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, publisher (Goblinoid Games)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Author of Labyrinth Lord — the most practically influential first-generation retroclone. Clean, complete, and easy to write for, it became the default publishing platform for a huge wave of OSR adventure modules. The Advanced Edition Companion bridged B/X and AD&D sensibilities. Proctor's work is less about aesthetic vision than about creating reliable infrastructure.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Labyrinth Lord\\</td><td>Labyrinth Lord\">td><td>Labyrinth Lord</a></td><td>2007</td><td>B/X clone; dominant OSR publishing platform</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Advanced Edition Companion</em></td><td>2010</td><td>Bridges B/X and AD&D for Labyrinth Lord</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: Goblinoid Games</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Retroclones\">Retroclones</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/James Maliszewski": {"key": "People/James Maliszewski", "category": "People", "name": "James Maliszewski", "tags": ["person", "osr", "critic", "historian", "blogger"], "links": ["Movements/OSR Movement", "Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Active: 2008 – present (with hiatus ~2012–2014) | Role: Critic, historian, blogger", "html": "<h1>James Maliszewski</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #critic #historian #blogger</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2008 – present (with hiatus ~2012–2014) | <strong>Role:</strong> Critic, historian, blogger\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Author of <em>Grognardia</em> (launched 2008) — arguably the OSR's most important early critical and historical voice. Deeply researched, thoughtful, historically grounded posts on old-school games, designers, and play culture. Shaped what the OSR thought it <em>was</em> before anyone had clearly named it. The Grognardia archives are primary source material for OSR intellectual history.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Grognardia</em> blog</td><td>2008–2012, resumed</td><td>Cultural center of gravity for early OSR</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Dwimmermount</em></td><td>2012 (troubled Kickstarter)</td><td>Megadungeon; cautionary tale about crowdfunding</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\nThe Grognardia archives (available via Wayback Machine) reward reading even now. Maliszewski's treatment of TSR-era designers and games is often more nuanced than anything written since.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy\">OSR Play Philosophy</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Chris Perkins": {"key": "People/Chris Perkins", "category": "People", "name": "Chris Perkins", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "designer", "wotc", "darrington"], "links": ["People/Jeremy Crawford", "Publishers/Wizards of the Coast", "Games/Daggerheart", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Active: 1997–2025 at WotC; 2025–present at Darrington Press\nRole: Senior story designer, D&D (WotC) \n---", "html": "<h1>Chris Perkins</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #designer #wotc #darrington</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 1997–2025 at WotC; 2025–present at Darrington Press <strong>Role:</strong> Senior story designer, D&D (WotC) → Creative Director, Darrington Press\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>The longest-serving senior creative figure at WotC — 28 years from 1997 to 2025 — responsible for the editorial and narrative direction of D&D's most significant published adventures across multiple editions. His departure and move to Darrington Press in 2025 alongside Jeremy Crawford signals that D&D's primary creative architects have chosen to build its most prominent competitor rather than continue at WotC.</p>\n<h2>Timeline</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Period</td><td>Role</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td>1997–2014</td><td>Designer, editor, story designer</td><td>Adventures across 3e and 4e eras</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2014–2025</td><td>Senior story designer</td><td>Editorial and narrative direction of 5e adventure line</td></tr>\n<tr><td>April 2025</td><td>Departed WotC</td><td>After 28 years; framed as retirement</td></tr>\n<tr><td>June 2025</td><td>Joined Darrington Press</td><td>Creative Director; working on Daggerheart adventure supplement</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td>D&D adventures (multiple eras)</td><td>1997–2025</td><td>Editorial voice behind 5e's best-regarded adventures</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Daggerheart adventure supplement</td><td>forthcoming</td><td>First Darrington Press project</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Perkins on the Move</h2>\n<p>Perkins told the LA Times: \"I was committed to staying with Wizards until after D&D's 50th anniversary, which gave me lots of time to work on succession planning and exit strategies.\" At Darrington: \"Storytelling has always been at the heart of everything I do, and joining Darrington Press feels a bit like coming home.\"</p>\n<p>His involvement in Daggerheart expansions brings the editorial craft behind D&D's best published adventures to a different system. Alongside Crawford, he gives Daggerheart institutional depth no indie or crossover publisher has previously had.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Collaborator: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeremy Crawford\">Jeremy Crawford</a> (Darrington)</li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wizards of the Coast\">WotC</a> (1997–2025) · Darrington Press (2025–present)</li>\n<li>Game: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Daggerheart\">Daggerheart</a> (expansions)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Brendan Conway": {"key": "People/Brendan Conway", "category": "People", "name": "Brendan Conway", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "pbtA", "designer"], "links": ["Games/Masks A New Generation", "Publishers/Magpie Games", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Lead designer of Masks: A New Generation — one of the bestselling PbtA games of the era, which brought PbtA to the superhero genre and introduced the Influence/Labels system as a model of genre-specific mechanical design.", "html": "<h1>Brendan Conway</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #pbtA #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2016 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer (Magpie Games)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Lead designer of Masks: A New Generation — one of the bestselling PbtA games of the era, which brought PbtA to the superhero genre and introduced the Influence/Labels system as a model of genre-specific mechanical design.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Masks A New Generation\\</td><td>Masks: A New Generation\">td><td>Masks: A New Generation</a></td><td>2016</td><td>PbtA superheroes; Influence/Labels system</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>The Influence/Labels System</h2>\nCharacters have five Labels (Freak, Danger, Savior, Superior, Mundane) that affect mechanical options. NPCs and other PCs can shift your Labels through the Influence move. Your identity is not fixed — it's being shaped by the people around you. This is a precise mechanical translation of teen superhero fiction's actual subject matter: the negotiation between self-conception and external expectation.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Magpie Games\">Magpie Games</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/James Raggi": {"key": "People/James Raggi", "category": "People", "name": "James Raggi", "tags": ["person", "osr", "designer", "publisher"], "links": ["Games/Lamentations of the Flame Princess", "Publishers/Lamentations of the Flame Princess", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Active: 2010 – present | Role: Designer, publisher (Lamentations of the Flame Princess) | Website: [lotfp.com](https://www.lotfp.com)", "html": "<h1>James Raggi</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #designer #publisher</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2010 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, publisher (Lamentations of the Flame Princess) | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://www.lotfp.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">lotfp.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Finnish-American designer who pushed the OSR in a deliberately weird, transgressive, and literary direction. LotFP emphasizes horror, nihilism, and high lethality. Raggi commissioned some of the most distinctive adventure writing in the scene from outside designers. His lavishly produced hardcovers raised aesthetic standards across the OSR. Controversial figure — some of his commissions attracted significant criticism.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Lamentations of the Flame Princess\\</td><td>LotFP Core Rules\">td><td>LotFP Core Rules</a></td><td>2010</td><td>Weird horror OSR; high production values</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Death Frost Doom</em></td><td>2009</td><td>Early defining LotFP adventure</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>A Red and Pleasant Land</em></td><td>2014</td><td>Zak Smith; ENnie winner; Alice in Wonderland horror</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Qelong</em></td><td>2013</td><td>Kenneth Hite; Vietnam War fantasy</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Lamentations of the Flame Princess\">Lamentations of the Flame Princess</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing\">Zine Scene</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Grant Howitt": {"key": "People/Grant Howitt", "category": "People", "name": "Grant Howitt", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "fitD", "designer", "uk"], "links": ["Games/Spire The City Must Fall", "Games/Heart The City Beneath", "People/Christopher Taylor", "Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard", "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2016 – present | Role: Designer (Rowan, Rook and Decard) | Website: [rowanrookanddecard.com](https://www.rowanrookanddecard.com)", "html": "<h1>Grant Howitt</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #fitD #designer #uk</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2016 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer (Rowan, Rook and Decard) | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://www.rowanrookanddecard.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">rowanrookanddecard.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Half of the UK design duo behind Spire and Heart — FitD-adjacent games with highly literary, politically-charged writing and a distinctive aesthetic sensibility. Spire is explicitly about revolutionary politics (dark elves oppressed by high elves). Also prolific creator of short-form games, especially Honey Heist (you play bears trying to rob a honey convention), which circulated virally and introduced many people to one-page game design.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Spire The City Must Fall\\</td><td>Spire: The City Must Fall\">td><td>Spire: The City Must Fall</a></td><td>2018</td><td>FitD-adjacent; political; ⭐ <em>you play this</em></td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Heart The City Beneath\\</td><td>Heart: The City Beneath\">td><td>Heart: The City Beneath</a></td><td>2021</td><td>Dungeon-delve companion to Spire</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Honey Heist</em></td><td>2017</td><td>Free one-page game; viral; intro to one-page design</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Collaborator: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Christopher Taylor\">Christopher Taylor</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard\">Rowan, Rook and Decard</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Forged in the Dark Family\">Forged in the Dark Family</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Ron Edwards": {"key": "People/Ron Edwards", "category": "People", "name": "Ron Edwards", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "theorist", "designer", "publisher"], "links": ["Games/Sorcerer", "Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2001 – present | Role: Theorist, designer, publisher (Adept Press)", "html": "<h1>Ron Edwards</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #theorist #designer #publisher</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2001 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Theorist, designer, publisher (Adept Press)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Founded The Forge forum (~2001) — the central hub for indie TTRPG design theory in the 2000s. Developed the GNS framework (Gamist / Narrativist / Simulationist), a contested but enormously influential attempt to categorize different modes of play and design. Also designed Sorcerer — an influential indie game about characters with dangerous supernatural power.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Sorcerer\\</td><td>Sorcerer\">td><td>Sorcerer</a></td><td>2001</td><td>Forge-era indie; \"bangs\" and \"kickers\" as design concepts</td></tr>\n<tr><td>GNS Theory essays</td><td>~2001–2005</td><td>Foundational story games design theory</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Trollbabe</em></td><td>2002</td><td>Feminist adventure game; innovative protagonist design</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\nGNS theory is controversial — later thinkers have substantially revised or rejected it — but understanding it is essential context for everything PbtA and FitD do differently. Read Edwards's essays with a critical eye.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory\">The Forge & GNS Theory</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: Adept Press</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Monte Cook": {"key": "People/Monte Cook", "category": "People", "name": "Monte Cook", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "designer", "publisher"], "links": ["Games/DD 3e and d20 OGL", "Publishers/Monte Cook Games", "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing", "Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Active: 2000 – present | Role: Designer, publisher (Monte Cook Games)", "html": "<h1>Monte Cook</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #designer #publisher</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2000 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, publisher (Monte Cook Games)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>One of the primary designers of D&D 3rd edition (with Jonathan Tweet and Skip Williams) — the game that created the OGL and enabled everything that followed. After leaving WotC, founded Malhavoc Press. Co-designed D&D 4e briefly before departing (his departure was itself a news event). Founded Monte Cook Games and created Numenera via a landmark Kickstarter in 2012.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 3e and d20 OGL\\</td><td>D&D 3rd Edition\">td><td>D&D 3rd Edition</a></td><td>2000</td><td>Co-designed; OGL created here</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Ptolus</em></td><td>2006</td><td>Massive city-based campaign setting</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Numenera</em></td><td>2013</td><td>Science-fantasy; streamlined Cypher System</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Cypher System</em></td><td>2015</td><td>System behind Numenera; now standalone</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Monte Cook Games\">Monte Cook Games</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">OGL & Open Licensing</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/D&D Edition Wars\">D&D Edition Wars</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Vincent Baker": {"key": "People/Vincent Baker", "category": "People", "name": "Vincent Baker", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "pbtA", "designer"], "links": ["People/Meguey Baker", "Games/Dogs in the Vineyard", "Games/Apocalypse World", "People/Meguey Baker", "Publishers/lumpley games", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory", "Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2004 – present | Role: Designer (lumpley games) | Website: [lumpley.games](https://lumpley.games)", "html": "<h1>Vincent Baker</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #pbtA #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2004 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer (lumpley games) | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://lumpley.games\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">lumpley.games</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>The most influential indie TTRPG designer of the 2000s–2010s. Dogs in the Vineyard (2004) was a pre-PbtA masterpiece of moral design. Apocalypse World (2010, co-designed with <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Meguey Baker\">Meguey Baker</a>) introduced Moves as a design concept, the 2d6+stat resolution system, and a GM philosophy of \"playing to find out what happens.\" The entire PbtA family — dozens of games — descends from this work.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dogs in the Vineyard\\</td><td>Dogs in the Vineyard\">td><td>Dogs in the Vineyard</a></td><td>2004</td><td>Pre-PbtA touchstone; moral authority mechanics</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Apocalypse World\\</td><td>Apocalypse World\">td><td>Apocalypse World</a></td><td>2010 (2nd ed 2016)</td><td><strong>PbtA origin</strong>; Moves, 2d6+stat, play to find out</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Murderous Ghosts</em></td><td>2012</td><td>Two-player horror; innovative format</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Apocalypse Keys</em></td><td>—</td><td>Further PbtA development</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\nRead Apocalypse World's GM chapter (\"The Meditations\") even if you never run it. It's the clearest articulation of a particular GM philosophy — reactive, improvisational, player-forward — in the TTRPG canon.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Collaborator: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Meguey Baker\">Meguey Baker</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/lumpley games\">lumpley games</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory\">The Forge</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Moves (PbtA Design)\">Moves</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Matt Finch": {"key": "People/Matt Finch", "category": "People", "name": "Matt Finch", "tags": ["person", "osr", "designer", "essayist"], "links": ["Games/OSRIC", "Games/Swords and Wizardry", "People/Stuart Marshall", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy", "Concepts/Retroclones", "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Active: 2006 – present | Role: Designer, legal architect, essayist (Mythmere Games)", "html": "<h1>Matt Finch</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #designer #essayist</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2006 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, legal architect, essayist (Mythmere Games)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>The single most important figure in the OSR's founding infrastructure. Co-wrote the legal vehicle that made retroclones possible (OSRIC), designed Swords & Wizardry, and wrote <em>A Quick Primer for Old School Gaming</em> — the philosophical text that articulated <em>why</em> old-school play felt different. He built the roads the OSR traveled on.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/OSRIC\\</td><td>OSRIC\">td><td>OSRIC</a></td><td>2006</td><td>Co-authored; legal infrastructure for the movement</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Swords and Wizardry\\</td><td>Swords & Wizardry\">td><td>Swords & Wizardry</a></td><td>2008</td><td>Targets original 1974 D&D rules</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>A Quick Primer for Old School Gaming</em></td><td>2008</td><td>Founding OSR philosophical text; <strong>free; read this first</strong></td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\nThe <em>Quick Primer</em> is ~10 pages and free. Its core argument: old-school rules are a referee's toolkit for a living world, not a balanced encounter system. The gap in the rules is a feature. Best single entry into OSR philosophy.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Collaborator: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Stuart Marshall\">Stuart Marshall</a> (OSRIC)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></li>\n<li>Concepts: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy\">OSR Play Philosophy</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Retroclones\">Retroclones</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">OGL</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Nils Hintze": {"key": "People/Nils Hintze", "category": "People", "name": "Nils Hintze", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "crossover", "designer", "licensed"], "links": ["Games/Vaesen", "Publishers/Free League Publishing", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Concepts/Licensed Adaptation Design", "People/Francesco Nepitello", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Designer of Vaesen — Nordic Horror Roleplaying. Translates the specific moral register of Nordic folklore: the vaesen are not simply enemies to be defeated but beings with their own claims and histories, usually acting from pain or grievance. The game makes understanding and addressing the vaesen's grievance the most satisfying resolution — combat is available but rarely optimal.", "html": "<h1>Nils Hintze</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #crossover #designer #licensed</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2021 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer (Vaesen)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Vaesen — Nordic Horror Roleplaying. Translates the specific moral register of Nordic folklore: the vaesen are not simply enemies to be defeated but beings with their own claims and histories, usually acting from pain or grievance. The game makes understanding and addressing the vaesen's grievance the most satisfying resolution — combat is available but rarely optimal.</p>\n<p>Close design sibling to The One Ring in its commitment to designing from what the source material is actually about.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Vaesen\\</td><td>Vaesen — Nordic Horror Roleplaying\">td><td>Vaesen — Nordic Horror Roleplaying</a></td><td>2021</td><td>Folkloric adaptation; grievance-based monster design</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Free League Publishing\">Free League Publishing</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Licensed Adaptation Design\">Licensed Adaptation Design</a></li>\n<li>Related: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Francesco Nepitello\">Francesco Nepitello</a> (parallel design approach)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Sean McCoy": {"key": "People/Sean McCoy", "category": "People", "name": "Sean McCoy", "tags": ["person", "osr", "scifi", "designer", "publisher", "secondwave"], "links": ["Games/Mothership", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing", "Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Active: 2017 – present | Role: Designer, publisher (Tuesday Knight Games) | Website: [tuesdayknightgames.com](https://www.tuesdayknightgames.com)", "html": "<h1>Sean McCoy</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #scifi #designer #publisher #secondwave</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2017 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, publisher (Tuesday Knight Games) | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://www.tuesdayknightgames.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">tuesdayknightgames.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Mothership — which applied OSR principles to science fiction horror and demonstrated that old-school mechanical philosophy (lethality, resource management, player agency) works in any genre. The stress and panic system mechanizes horror's core dynamic. The Warden's Operations Manual is one of the best pieces of GM-facing design documentation in the OSR era.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mothership\\</td><td>Mothership RPG\">td><td>Mothership RPG</a></td><td>2017 (boxed set 2022)</td><td>Sci-fi horror OSR; stress/panic system; ENnie winner</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Dead Planet</td><td>2018</td><td>With Donn Stroud & Fiona Geist; defining Mothership adventure</td></tr>\n<tr><td>A Pound of Flesh</td><td>2019</td><td>Space station pointcrawl</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Gradient Descent</td><td>2021</td><td>Megadungeon in space</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Innovations</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Stress and Panic</strong> — accumulated stress increases Panic check frequency; Panic results escalate from freezing to cardiac arrest</li>\n<li><strong>Warden's Operations Manual</strong> — concrete procedures over abstract advice; templates for scenario types</li>\n<li><strong>Production design as content</strong> — early editions looked like technical documentation from within the game world</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing\">Zine Scene</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design\">Post-OSR</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Robin D. Laws": {"key": "People/Robin D. Laws", "category": "People", "name": "Robin D. Laws", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "designer", "gumshoe", "mystery"], "links": ["Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic", "Movements/PbtA Family", "People/Jason Cordova", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2007 – present | Role: Designer (Pelgrane Press); creator of GUMSHOE", "html": "<h1>Robin D. Laws</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #designer #gumshoe #mystery</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2007 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer (Pelgrane Press); creator of GUMSHOE\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of the GUMSHOE investigative system, which addressed the mystery genre's failure state problem before Brindlewood Bay tackled the deeper structural issue. GUMSHOE's principle: if you have the relevant investigative ability and look in the right place, you automatically find the clue. Skills are spent for additional information, not clue discovery. This eliminated stalled investigation as a failure mode while leaving the predetermined-solution problem in place. Underpins Trail of Cthulhu, Night's Black Agents, Dracula Dossier, and many Pelgrane Press games.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td>GUMSHOE system</td><td>2007</td><td>Automatic clue-finding; eliminated investigation failure states</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Trail of Cthulhu</em></td><td>2008</td><td>GUMSHOE applied to Lovecraftian horror</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Night's Black Agents</em></td><td>2012</td><td>GUMSHOE applied to spy thriller</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Dracula Dossier</em></td><td>2016</td><td>Major GUMSHOE campaign; Dracula as historical document</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>GUMSHOE vs. The Conspiracy Mechanic</h2>\nGUMSHOE solves: clues going unfound (stalled investigation)\nGUMSHOE does NOT solve: predetermined solution (gotcha), information asymmetry, railroad\n<a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic\">The Conspiracy Mechanic</a> (Brindlewood Bay): solves all three by eliminating the predetermined solution\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">Story Games</a> (adjacent — investigation design)</li>\n<li>Contrast: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Cordova\">Jason Cordova</a> (solved the deeper mystery problem)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Tim Hutchings": {"key": "People/Tim Hutchings", "category": "People", "name": "Tim Hutchings", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "solo", "designer"], "links": ["Games/Thousand Year Old Vampire", "Movements/Solo TTRPG Design", "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Designer of Thousand Year Old Vampire — a solo journaling game about a vampire across centuries, with one of the most emotionally affecting mechanics in recent TTRPG design. The forgetting mechanic demonstrated that solo play could explore emotional registers unavailable in most group TTRPG designs.", "html": "<h1>Tim Hutchings</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #solo #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2019 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Thousand Year Old Vampire — a solo journaling game about a vampire across centuries, with one of the most emotionally affecting mechanics in recent TTRPG design. The forgetting mechanic demonstrated that solo play could explore emotional registers unavailable in most group TTRPG designs.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Thousand Year Old Vampire\\</td><td>Thousand Year Old Vampire\">td><td>Thousand Year Old Vampire</a></td><td>2019</td><td>Forgetting mechanic; grief and loss as solo play</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>The Forgetting Mechanic</h2>\nCharacters have limited memory slots. Gaining new memories requires erasing old ones. As the vampire accumulates centuries, they lose most of what has happened to them. This produces profound melancholy without any violent encounter — demonstrating that loss and grief can drive TTRPG play without combat.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Solo TTRPG Design\">Solo TTRPG Design</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr": {"key": "People/Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr", "category": "People", "name": "Pelle Togersen and Johan Nohr", "tags": ["person", "osr", "artgame", "designer", "secondwave"], "links": ["Games/Mork Borg", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing", "Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Active: 2019 – present | Roles: Designer (Tøgersen), Art Director (Nohr) | Publisher: Free League", "html": "<h1>Pelle Tøgersen & Johan Nohr</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #artgame #designer #secondwave</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2019 – present | <strong>Roles:</strong> Designer (Tøgersen), Art Director (Nohr) | <strong>Publisher:</strong> Free League\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why They Matter</h2>\n<p>Created Mörk Borg — a doom metal-aesthetic OSR game that won ENnie Gold for Best Game and Product of the Year 2020. A Swedish art-game that beat every mainstream release. The primary content is art direction, not rules. The Mörk Borg Compatible license produced hundreds of compatible products within a year.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Mork Borg\\</td><td>Mörk Borg\">td><td>Mörk Borg</a></td><td>2019</td><td>Art-forward OSR; hostile design; nihilist premise; ENnie winner</td></tr>\n<tr><td>CYBER//MÖRK BORG</td><td>2022</td><td>Official cyberpunk fork</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Pirate Borg</td><td>2022</td><td>Official nautical fork</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Philosophy</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Art direction as primary argument</strong> — chaotic typography, hostile color (bile yellow, blood orange, deep black), angles and bleeds; you <em>feel</em> the game before you understand it</li>\n<li><strong>Nihilism as load-bearing mechanic</strong> — the world is ending (the Psalms of the Dying); the Miseries system tracks approaching apocalypse; rules are minimal because nothing the characters do changes the fundamental trajectory</li>\n<li><strong>Free compatible license</strong> — Mörk Borg Compatible license requires no royalties, no approval; produced enormous ecosystem rapidly</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: Free League</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing\">Zine Scene</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design\">Post-OSR</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Mike Mearls": {"key": "People/Mike Mearls", "category": "People", "name": "Mike Mearls", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "designer", "wotc"], "links": ["Games/DD 5th Edition", "People/Jeremy Crawford", "Publishers/Wizards of the Coast", "Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Active: ~2005–2023 at WotC | Role: Lead designer, D&D 5th Edition", "html": "<h1>Mike Mearls</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #designer #wotc</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> ~2005–2023 at WotC | <strong>Role:</strong> Lead designer, D&D 5th Edition\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Led the design of D&D 5th Edition and its landmark open playtest process. Shaped 5e's design philosophy of broad accessibility and \"big tent\" appeal across edition preferences. His departure from WotC in the OGL crisis aftermath marked the end of his era there.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 5th Edition\\</td><td>D&D 5th Edition\">td><td>D&D 5th Edition</a></td><td>2014</td><td>Co-led; mass market revival</td></tr>\n<tr><td>D&D Next open playtest</td><td>2012–2014</td><td>Largest TTRPG playtest in history</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Collaborator: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jeremy Crawford\">Jeremy Crawford</a></li>\n<li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Wizards of the Coast\">WotC</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/D&D Edition Wars\">D&D Edition Wars</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OGL Crisis 2023\">OGL Crisis</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/John Harper": {"key": "People/John Harper", "category": "People", "name": "John Harper", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "fitD", "designer"], "links": ["Games/Lady Blackbird", "Games/Blades in the Dark", "Games/Agon", "Games/Daggerheart", "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family", "Concepts/Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)", "Games/Daggerheart", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2006 – present | Role: Designer (One Seven Design); additional designer, Daggerheart | Website: [onesevendesign.com](https://www.onesevendesign.com)", "html": "<h1>John Harper</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #fitD #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2006 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer (One Seven Design); additional designer, Daggerheart | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://www.onesevendesign.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">onesevendesign.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Blades in the Dark — the game that introduced the Forged in the Dark framework and spawned a large family of games. FitD's innovations (position and effect, flashbacks, clocks, crew-level meta-game, stress and trauma) represent the most significant structural departure from PbtA in the indie design space. Also designed Lady Blackbird — a free, ultra-condensed adventure game that made his reputation before Blades — and Agon.</p>\n<p>Harper is also a credited additional game designer on the Daggerheart core rulebook, connecting the game directly to the FitD tradition in a way that goes beyond aesthetic borrowing.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Lady Blackbird\\</td><td>Lady Blackbird\">td><td>Lady Blackbird</a></td><td>2009</td><td>Free; ultra-condensed; read for design efficiency</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Blades in the Dark\\</td><td>Blades in the Dark\">td><td>Blades in the Dark</a></td><td>2017</td><td><strong>FitD origin</strong>; position/effect, flashbacks, clocks</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Agon\\</td><td>Agon\">td><td>Agon</a></td><td>2019</td><td>Greek heroes; cooperation/competition tension</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Daggerheart\\</td><td>Daggerheart\">td><td>Daggerheart</a></td><td>2025</td><td>Additional game designer credit</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Philosophy</h2>\n<p>Harper is always asking what can be removed without loss, what the essential load-bearing elements of a play experience are. Lady Blackbird (16 pages) is the most compressed expression of this. Blades in the Dark represents a deliberate expansion — adding what a specific play experience (heists) required — but every element earns its place.</p>\n<p>Position and effect, flashbacks, and clocks each solve a specific design problem that heist fiction requires solving. Read Blades asking \"what problem does this mechanic solve?\" and the answers illuminate how to design for any genre.</p>\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\nRead Lady Blackbird (free) before Blades in the Dark to see the design sensibility in miniature.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: One Seven Design</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Forged in the Dark Family\">Forged in the Dark Family</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Clocks and Position-Effect (FitD)\">Clocks & Position/Effect</a></li>\n<li>Connected to: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Daggerheart\">Daggerheart</a> (additional designer)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Joseph Goodman": {"key": "People/Joseph Goodman", "category": "People", "name": "Joseph Goodman", "tags": ["person", "osr", "designer", "publisher", "secondwave"], "links": ["Games/Dungeon Crawl Classics", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing", "Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence", "People/Chris McDowall"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Active: 2003 – present | Role: Designer, publisher (Goodman Games)", "html": "<h1>Joseph Goodman</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #designer #publisher #secondwave</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2003 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, publisher (Goodman Games)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Founded Goodman Games in 2003 to publish d20-era dungeon crawl adventures in the style of 1970s TSR modules. When the OSR demonstrated that non-3e games were viable, pivoted to Dungeon Crawl Classics RPG — a maximalist OSR game that amplified old-school energy rather than merely recovering it. DCC represents the \"more, louder, stranger\" pole of OSR design philosophy, in direct contrast to the minimalism of Into the Odd.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dungeon Crawl Classics\\</td><td>Dungeon Crawl Classics RPG\">td><td>Dungeon Crawl Classics RPG</a></td><td>2012</td><td>Maximalist OSR; dice chain, funnel, Mighty Deeds, catastrophic magic</td></tr>\n<tr><td>DCC adventure module line</td><td>2012–present</td><td>Consistently excellent gonzo pulp fantasy adventures</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>DCC's Design Innovations</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Dice chain</strong> — d3 through d30; moving up/down expresses advantage/disadvantage</li>\n<li><strong>The funnel</strong> — run 4 zero-level peasants; survivors become 1st level; widely adopted</li>\n<li><strong>Mighty Deeds</strong> — warriors declare combat stunts adjudicated by a Deed Die</li>\n<li><strong>Catastrophic magic</strong> — corruption tables, misfire results, patron relationships</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Literary Sources (explicitly named)</h2>\nRobert E. Howard · Fritz Leiber · Michael Moorcock · Jack Vance · Clark Ashton Smith\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing\">Zine Scene</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/OSR Play Philosophy\">OSR Play Philosophy</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a></li>\n<li>Contrast with: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris McDowall\">Chris McDowall</a> (opposite design pole)</li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Becky Annison and Josh Fox": {"key": "People/Becky Annison and Josh Fox", "category": "People", "name": "Becky Annison and Josh Fox", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "gmless", "designer", "uk"], "links": ["Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "Movements/GM-less Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Co-designers of Lovecraftesque — a GM-less horror investigation game structured around the specific narrative logic of Lovecraftian fiction. Each player takes turns as the Watcher for a single scene, then passes the role. Lovecraftesque demonstrated that GM-less design could handle genre fiction precisely, and that distributing narrative authority was a specific design tool for producing particula", "html": "<h1>Becky Annison & Josh Fox</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #gmless #designer #uk</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2016 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designers (Just Critting)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why They Matter</h2>\n<p>Co-designers of Lovecraftesque — a GM-less horror investigation game structured around the specific narrative logic of Lovecraftian fiction. Each player takes turns as the Watcher for a single scene, then passes the role. Lovecraftesque demonstrated that GM-less design could handle genre fiction precisely, and that distributing narrative authority was a specific design tool for producing particular kinds of fiction — not just a political statement about table equality.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Lovecraftesque</em></td><td>2016</td><td>GM-less Lovecraftian horror; rotating Watcher role</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design\">Post-OSR</a> · UK indie scene</li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/GM-less Design\">GM-less Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Yochai Gal": {"key": "People/Yochai Gal", "category": "People", "name": "Yochai Gal", "tags": ["person", "osr", "designer", "ruleslight", "free"], "links": ["Games/Cairn", "Games/Cairn 2e", "People/Chris McDowall", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "Games/Cairn", "Games/Cairn 2e", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Active: 2020 – present | Role: Designer, publisher (Cairn Press)", "html": "<h1>Yochai Gal</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #designer #ruleslight #free</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2020 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, publisher (Cairn Press)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Cairn — a free, Creative Commons fantasy game distilling the Into the Odd chassis into its most accessible form. Downloaded hundreds of thousands of times. Cairn became the gateway for many players into rules-light OSR design and demonstrated that free, openly licensed games could build substantial communities and commercial ecosystems. The 2024 second edition boxed set represented significant maturation: from minimalist pamphlet to fully realized game with its own setting and expanding publication catalog.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cairn\\</td><td>Cairn 1e\">td><td>Cairn 1e</a></td><td>2020</td><td>Free; CC-licensed; ItO distilled; massive download numbers</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cairn 2e\\</td><td>Cairn 2e Boxed Set\">td><td>Cairn 2e Boxed Set</a></td><td>2024</td><td>Player's Guide, Warden's Guide, Bonds, color art</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Evolution: 1e to 2e</h2>\n<p>A key observation drove the 2e design: his players weren't primarily motivated by treasure-hunting — the traditional OSR driver. Cairn 2e adds Bonds (items or events of personal significance), Omens (story hooks), and Backgrounds (implied setting through character history) to create investment at the table's start. The additions preserve 1e's minimalism while giving players more reasons to care about their characters before a die is rolled.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Influenced by: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Chris McDowall\">Chris McDowall</a> (Into the Odd chassis)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design\">Post-OSR & Minimalist Design</a></li>\n<li>Games: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cairn\\\">Cairn 1e</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cairn 2e\\\">Cairn 2e</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Erik Mona": {"key": "People/Erik Mona", "category": "People", "name": "Erik Mona", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "paizo", "publisher", "editor"], "links": ["Publishers/Paizo", "People/James Jacobs", "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing", "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Active: 2002 – present | Role: Publisher, Paizo; former editor Dragon & Dungeon", "html": "<h1>Erik Mona</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #paizo #publisher #editor</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2002 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Publisher, Paizo; former editor Dragon & Dungeon\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>As editor of Dragon and Dungeon under WotC license, oversaw some of the best adventure writing of the 3e era. When WotC ended the license, was central to Paizo's pivot to Pathfinder. As publisher shaped Paizo's notably progressive approach to representation and led ORC License development — positioning Paizo as a steward of the open gaming commons.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Dragon & Dungeon magazines</td><td>2002–2007</td><td>Best 3e adventure writing; Age of Worms, Savage Tide</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Pathfinder product line</td><td>2007–present</td><td>Publisher and creative direction</td></tr>\n<tr><td>ORC License</td><td>2023</td><td>System-neutral open license; nonprofit administration</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Paizo\">Paizo</a></li>\n<li>Collaborator: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/James Jacobs\">James Jacobs</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">OGL & ORC License</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OGL Crisis 2023\">OGL Crisis 2023</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Clinton R. Nixon": {"key": "People/Clinton R. Nixon", "category": "People", "name": "Clinton R. Nixon", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "forge", "designer"], "links": ["People/Ron Edwards", "People/Ron Edwards", "Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory", "Eras/Pre-2005 Roots", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2001 – 2012 (Forge era) | Role: Co-founder, The Forge; designer, developer", "html": "<h1>Clinton R. Nixon</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #forge #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2001 – 2012 (Forge era) | <strong>Role:</strong> Co-founder, The Forge; designer, developer\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Co-founded The Forge forum alongside <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Ron Edwards\">Ron Edwards</a>, providing the technical infrastructure and community organizing that made it function. Also a designer in his own right — Donjon and other Forge-era games. Less prominent as a public theorist than Edwards but essential to the institution.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Co-founder: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Ron Edwards\">Ron Edwards</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/The Forge and GNS Theory\">The Forge & GNS Theory</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/Pre-2005 Roots\">Pre-2005</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Kalum": {"key": "People/Kalum", "category": "People", "name": "Kalum", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "pbtA", "designer", "indie"], "links": ["Games/Paris Gondo", "Games/Rosewood Abbey", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Games/Brindlewood Bay", "Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2021 – present | Role: Designer, podcaster (The Rolistes) | Website: [rolistespod.com](https://rolistespod.com) | Itch: [rolistespod.itch.io](https://rolistespod.itch.io)", "html": "<h1>Kalum</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #pbtA #designer #indie</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2021 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, podcaster (The Rolistes) | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://rolistespod.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">rolistespod.com</a> | <strong>Itch:</strong> <a href=\"https://rolistespod.itch.io\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">rolistespod.itch.io</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why They Matter</h2>\n<p>UK-based designer and host of The Rolistes podcast, Kalum has built two distinctive games within the Carved from Brindlewood design space and developed a recognizable house aesthetic: manga-inspired B6 format, actual-play replay transcripts as teaching tools, and a commitment to games that punch above their production weight.</p>\n<p>Both of Kalum's games were self-published through The Rolistes and distributed internationally via itch.io and The Rolistes Big Cartel store, making them a notable example of successful micro-publishing without a traditional distributor.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Paris Gondo\\</td><td>Paris Gondo — The Life-Saving Magic of Inventorying\">td><td>Paris Gondo — The Life-Saving Magic of Inventorying</a></td><td>2021</td><td>GM-less; Marie Kondo meets dungeon loot; GonParis Method</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Rosewood Abbey\\</td><td>Rosewood Abbey\">td><td>Rosewood Abbey</a></td><td>2023</td><td>Carved from Brindlewood; monastic mysteries; Rumor Mill mechanic</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Notes</h2>\n<strong>Paris Gondo</strong> demonstrates design wit applied to a traditionally mechanical problem (encumbrance) and strips it down to pure narrative and emotional consequence. The GonParis Method's six-step structure makes the game nearly foolproof to run.\n<strong>Rosewood Abbey</strong> is the more substantive design statement: a full Carved from Brindlewood adaptation with a purpose-built setting, the Rumor Mill mechanic adding a layer of community dynamics absent from Brindlewood Bay itself, and the replay format as a genuine accessibility innovation.\n<p>The replay format — drawn from Japanese TRPG (TRPG) tradition — is Kalum's most portable design contribution: a complete play transcript at the front of the book that teaches the game better than any rules summary.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Key game: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Brindlewood Bay\">Brindlewood Bay</a> (design lineage)</li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The Conspiracy Mechanic\">The Conspiracy Mechanic</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Matthew Mercer": {"key": "People/Matthew Mercer", "category": "People", "name": "Matthew Mercer", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "gm", "actualplay", "publisher"], "links": ["Movements/Actual Play Boom", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Active: 2015 – present | Role: GM, voice actor, publisher (Darrington Press)", "html": "<h1>Matthew Mercer</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #gm #actualplay #publisher</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2015 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> GM, voice actor, publisher (Darrington Press)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>GM of Critical Role — the actual play web series that became the single most powerful force in mainstreaming D&D 5e. A voice actor by profession, Mercer's performative GM style (detailed world-building, character voices, emotional storytelling) defined public expectations of TTRPG play for a generation of new players. Critical Role's animated series Kickstarter raised $11M in 24 hours (2019). The company now publishes games and settings through Darrington Press.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Critical Role</em></td><td>2015–present</td><td>The most-watched actual play; mainstreamed D&D</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Tal'Dorei Campaign Setting</em></td><td>2017 (rev. 2021)</td><td>Critical Role's home setting</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Candela Obscura RPG</em></td><td>2023</td><td>FitD-adjacent horror game (Darrington Press)</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\nCritical Role's influence on player expectations — for better and worse — is impossible to overstate. Many new players arrived at the table expecting GM performance, pre-planned narratives, and hero fantasy. Understanding Mercer's style helps explain the cultural tensions between actual play audiences and traditional play communities.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: Darrington Press</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Actual Play Boom\">Actual Play Boom</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Matt Colville": {"key": "People/Matt Colville", "category": "People", "name": "Matt Colville", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "designer", "youtuber", "publisher"], "links": ["Games/Draw Steel", "Publishers/MCDM Productions", "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Active: 2016 – present | Role: Designer, YouTuber, publisher (MCDM Productions) | Website: [mcdmproductions.com](https://www.mcdmproductions.com)", "html": "<h1>Matt Colville</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #designer #youtuber #publisher</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2016 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, YouTuber, publisher (MCDM Productions) | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://www.mcdmproductions.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">mcdmproductions.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Game designer and YouTuber whose <em>Running the Game</em> series became essential viewing for new D&D GMs. Founded MCDM Productions, which developed Draw Steel — a non-OGL fantasy RPG with a strong focus on combat as the primary design challenge. A prominent post-OGL voice arguing for building genuine alternatives to D&D rather than rebuilding on its foundation.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Running the Game</em> (YouTube)</td><td>2016–present</td><td>GM advice; widely watched</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Flee, Mortals!</em></td><td>2023</td><td>5e monster book; MCDM's flagship 5e product</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Draw Steel\\</td><td>Draw Steel / MCDM RPG\"> MCDM RPG</a></td><td>2024</td><td>Non-OGL mainstream alternative; Kickstarter funded</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/MCDM Productions\">MCDM Productions</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OGL Crisis 2023\">OGL Crisis 2023</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/James Jacobs": {"key": "People/James Jacobs", "category": "People", "name": "James Jacobs", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "paizo", "designer", "worldbuilder"], "links": ["Publishers/Paizo", "People/Erik Mona", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Creative director of the Pathfinder RPG line and primary architect of the Golarion setting. Developed Golarion's foundational lore, major factions and deities, and the maximalist 'every fantasy genre in one world' approach. Golarion contains a region for every fantasy genre — this maximalism was commercial strategy as much as creative vision: every region is a potential adventure path.", "html": "<h1>James Jacobs</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #paizo #designer #worldbuilder</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2002 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Creative director, Paizo\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Creative director of the Pathfinder RPG line and primary architect of the Golarion setting. Developed Golarion's foundational lore, major factions and deities, and the maximalist 'every fantasy genre in one world' approach. Golarion contains a region for every fantasy genre — this maximalism was commercial strategy as much as creative vision: every region is a potential adventure path.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Golarion setting</td><td>2007–present</td><td>Primary architect; one continent, every genre</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Curse of the Crimson Throne</td><td>2008</td><td>Defining early Pathfinder adventure path</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Return of the Runelords</td><td>2018</td><td>Major anniversary adventure path</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Golarion's Design Strategy</h2>\nThe 'every genre in one continent' approach means: Mediterranean sword-and-sandal, Scandinavian viking, Egyptian tomb-raiding, East Asian samurai/ninja, post-apocalyptic wasteland, gothic horror, undead-ruled nation, magocracy, theocracy. Each region generates content indefinitely.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Paizo\">Paizo</a></li>\n<li>Collaborator: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Erik Mona\">Erik Mona</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Graham Walmsley": {"key": "People/Graham Walmsley", "category": "People", "name": "Graham Walmsley", "tags": ["person", "designer", "horror", "improv", "storygames", "uk"], "links": ["Games/Cthulhu Dark", "Games/Cosmic Dark", "Movements/Story Games Lineage MOC", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2007 – present | Role: Designer, writer (UK)\nPatreon: patreon.com/graham | Substack: grahamwalmsley.substack.com", "html": "<h1>Graham Walmsley</h1>\n<p>#person #designer #horror #improv #storygames #uk</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2007 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, writer (UK) <strong>Patreon:</strong> patreon.com/graham | <strong>Substack:</strong> grahamwalmsley.substack.com\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>An English designer whose work sits at an unusual intersection: rigorous minimalist mechanics, horror design theory, and improvisation practice. He has written extensively for Pelgrane's Trail of Cthulhu, designed Cthulhu Dark (2010/2017) and the forthcoming Cosmic Dark, and wrote <em>Play Unsafe</em> (2007) — the foundational text on applying theatre improv to TTRPG practice. He has also contributed to Blades in the Dark and Doctor Who: Adventures in Time and Space.</p>\n<p>His design philosophy is precise minimalism — not minimalism for its own sake but the specific removal of everything that doesn't serve the intended effect. His framing: what excites him about Cthulhu Dark is not how simple it is but how <em>precise</em> it is.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Type</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Play Unsafe</em></td><td>2007</td><td>Design book</td><td>Improv theory applied to TTRPGs; 74 pages; foundational</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Trail of Cthulhu scenarios</td><td>2008–present</td><td>Adventures</td><td>Best-in-class Purist horror for the Pelgrane system</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Stealing Cthulhu</em></td><td>2011</td><td>Design book</td><td>Methodology for Lovecraftian scenario construction</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cthulhu Dark\\</td><td>Cthulhu Dark\">td><td>Cthulhu Dark</a></td><td>2010/2017</td><td>Game</td><td>Rules-light horror; Insight mechanic; horror GMing manual</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Cosmic Dark\\</td><td>Cosmic Dark\">td><td>Cosmic Dark</a></td><td>In development</td><td>Game</td><td>Space body horror; Changed mechanic; no character creation</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Positions</h2>\n<strong>Minimalism as precision</strong> — every mechanic should do exactly the work it needs to do, no more. The Insight track in Cthulhu Dark doesn't just track sanity; it mechanises the specific Lovecraftian horror of learning too much, with 6s giving you more than you wanted to know.\n<strong>Horror is thematic, not cosmetic</strong> — the goal is lingering unease, not shock. The Creeping Horrors concept (recurring, often inexplicable imagery and motifs distributed across an adventure) produces sustained dread rather than punctual scares.\n<strong>Power dynamics matter</strong> — Cthulhu Dark deliberately inverts the usual Lovecraftian game premise by having players portray people with little power investigating horror at the heart of power — thieves and slum dwellers rather than wealthy antiquarians.\n<strong>Improv over preparation</strong> — Play Unsafe argues that front-loaded preparation works against the kind of spontaneous, collaborative play that makes games memorable. Hold ideas lightly.\n<strong>You can't fight the Mythos</strong> — a design rule enforced mechanically. In Cthulhu Dark, characters cannot defeat Mythos creatures in combat. They can run, hide, or watch helplessly. This isn't a flavour note; it's built into the resolution system.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Story Games Lineage MOC\">Story Games & Indie</a> (adjacent, independent tradition)</li>\n<li>Influenced by: Keith Johnstone (improv), Ron Edwards' Sorcerer (die mechanics), Robin D. Laws' GUMSHOE (information always found if needed)</li>\n<li>Works for: Pelgrane Press, Evil Hat Productions, Cubicle 7</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Stras Acimovic and John LeBoeuf-Little": {"key": "People/Stras Acimovic and John LeBoeuf-Little", "category": "People", "name": "Stras Acimovic and John LeBoeuf-Little", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "fitD", "designer"], "links": ["Games/Scum and Villainy", "Games/Band of Blades", "Movements/Forged in the Dark Family", "People/John Harper", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2018 – present | Role: Designers; Acimovic also at Magpie Games", "html": "<h1>Stras Acimovic & John LeBoeuf-Little</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #fitD #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2018 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designers; Acimovic also at Magpie Games\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why They Matter</h2>\n<p>Designers of Band of Blades and Scum and Villainy — the most significant FitD games after Blades in the Dark itself, demonstrating that the FitD framework could handle military campaign fiction and space opera respectively.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Scum and Villainy\\</td><td>Scum and Villainy\">td><td>Scum and Villainy</a></td><td>2018</td><td>FitD space opera; ship as mechanical crew member</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Band of Blades\\</td><td>Band of Blades\">td><td>Band of Blades</a></td><td>2019</td><td>FitD military fantasy; command positions as rotating roles</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Contributions</h2>\n<strong>Band of Blades</strong> — added command positions (Marshal, Commander, Quartermaster) that rotate between players between missions, creating strategic-level decision-making above the tactical score level. Handled character death and replacement as narrative material rather than mechanical disruption.\n<strong>Scum and Villainy</strong> — the ship becomes a mechanical entity with its own sheet and advancement, extending FitD's crew mechanics spatially.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Forged in the Dark Family\">Forged in the Dark Family</a></li>\n<li>Origin: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/John Harper\">John Harper</a> (Blades in the Dark)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Brandish Gilhelm": {"key": "People/Brandish Gilhelm", "category": "People", "name": "Brandish Gilhelm", "tags": ["person", "designer", "mainstream", "crossover", "youtube", "diy"], "links": ["Games/Crown and Skull", "Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Active: 2016 – present | Role: Designer, YouTuber, artist (Runehammer Games)\nAlso known as: Hankerin Ferinale, Ingrid Burnall", "html": "<h1>Brandish Gilhelm</h1>\n<p>#person #designer #mainstream #crossover #youtube #diy</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2016 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, YouTuber, artist (Runehammer Games) <strong>Also known as:</strong> Hankerin Ferinale, Ingrid Burnall\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Index Card RPG (ICRPG) and Crown and Skull — two games that built a devoted community around practical, GM-focused design and DIY play culture. Gilhelm came up through the YouTube GM advice space and carries that ethos directly into his game design: everything is built to actually work at a table, not just read well on a page. Deliberately positions himself outside the OSR label, preferring \"DIY.\"</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Index Card RPG (ICRPG)</td><td>2016</td><td>Bestseller on DriveThruRPG; GM tools focus; large community</td></tr>\n<tr><td>EZD6</td><td>2021</td><td>Ultra-lite d6 system</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Crown and Skull\\</td><td>Crown and Skull\">td><td>Crown and Skull</a></td><td>2023</td><td>No stats/HP; Attrition system; North Holds setting</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Philosophy</h2>\n<p>Gilhelm's games are built from actual play — the North Holds setting for Crown and Skull emerged from three years of actual campaign play before the game was designed around it. His design process is table-first: if it doesn't work in practice, it doesn't go in the book.</p>\n<p>His strongest contribution is probably GM tools: Crown and Skull's Tactics dice for enemy behavior, hex roll tables, zero-prep frameworks. He's described himself as making tools for \"chronically overloaded\" GMs. The YouTube community he built around Runehammer is unusually collaborative, with community members contributing to world development.</p>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: Runehammer Games</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Crossover and Mainstream-Adjacent Design\">Crossover & Mainstream-Adjacent Design</a></li>\n<li>YouTube: Runehammer channel</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Alex Roberts": {"key": "People/Alex Roberts", "category": "People", "name": "Alex Roberts", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "designer", "gmless"], "links": ["Games/For the Queen", "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Movements/GM-less Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Designer of For the Queen and co-designer of Star Crossed — two games that established intimate two-player and small-group play as distinct design categories with their own mechanical requirements. Both games are explicitly queer and romantic without combat or conflict.", "html": "<h1>Alex Roberts</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #designer #gmless</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2019 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why She Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of For the Queen and co-designer of Star Crossed — two games that established intimate two-player and small-group play as distinct design categories with their own mechanical requirements. Both games are explicitly queer and romantic without combat or conflict.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/For the Queen\\</td><td>For the Queen\">td><td>For the Queen</a></td><td>2019</td><td>Card game; companions and a Queen; no conflict until the final card</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>Star Crossed</em></td><td>2019</td><td>Co-designed with Beau Jágr Sheldon; Jenga tower as tension mechanic</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Contributions</h2>\n<strong>For the Queen</strong> — ends when someone draws the card asking \"do you protect the Queen?\" The only moment of conflict carries enormous weight from everything preceding it. Establishes that GM-less card-prompt play can produce genuine emotional stakes.\n<strong>Star Crossed</strong> — two players navigate attraction they shouldn't act on, removing Jenga blocks to represent maintaining appropriate distance. Physical tension of the tower mirrors fictional tension. Established embodied mechanics as emotionally effective.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/GM-less Design\">GM-less Design</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Jay Dragon": {"key": "People/Jay Dragon", "category": "People", "name": "Jay Dragon", "tags": ["person", "storygames", "cozy", "designer"], "links": ["Games/Wanderhome", "Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave", "Movements/GM-less Design", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2019 – present | Role: Designer (Possum Creek Games) | Website: [possumcreekgames.com](https://possumcreekgames.com)", "html": "<h1>Jay Dragon</h1>\n<p>#person #storygames #cozy #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2019 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer (Possum Creek Games) | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://possumcreekgames.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">possumcreekgames.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why They Matter</h2>\n<p>Designer of Wanderhome — the game that most completely realized the cozy wave's aesthetic ambitions. Dragon's design philosophy starts from questions about what play is for and who it serves. Their background in queer community-making and disability advocacy inflects their work explicitly. Wanderhome demonstrated that mechanical design could serve rest, beauty, and quiet pleasure as precisely as dramatic conflict.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Wanderhome\\</td><td>Wanderhome\">td><td>Wanderhome</a></td><td>2021</td><td>Cozy wave flagship; token economy; no combat; animal travelers</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Philosophy</h2>\n<ul><li>Play as rest, as community, as practice of attention</li>\n<li>Token economy makes generosity mechanically visible</li>\n<li>Moves organized around activities, not character capabilities</li>\n<li>Stakes without violent conflict are genuine stakes</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\nWanderhome's public design document is worth reading as a philosophy statement, not just game reference.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: Possum Creek Games</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Cozy and Quiet Wave\">Cozy & Quiet Wave</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/GM-less Design\">GM-less Design</a> (adjacent)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Minerva McJanda": {"key": "People/Minerva McJanda", "category": "People", "name": "Minerva McJanda", "tags": ["person", "designer", "storygames", "pbtA", "queer", "uk"], "links": ["Games/Rhapsody of Blood", "Games/Voidheart Symphony", "Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard", "Movements/PbtA Family", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Active: 2019 – present | Role: Designer, artist (UFO Press; Rowan, Rook and Decard)", "html": "<h1>Minerva McJanda</h1>\n<p>#person #designer #storygames #pbtA #queer #uk</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2019 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, artist (UFO Press; Rowan, Rook and Decard)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why She Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Voidheart Symphony — a PbtA game of psychic rebellion in the modern city that integrates explicit political commitment into its core mechanical architecture rather than treating it as aesthetic framing. One of the clearest examples of a designer for whom the game's thematic content and its mechanical structure are genuinely inseparable.</p>\n<p>McJanda began writing Voidheart Symphony in late 2018 while homeless and transitioning. The game emerged directly from that experience: a need to tell stories about ordinary people under systemic pressure who push back using whatever extraordinary means they can find. The revised edition, now in development with Rowan, Rook and Decard, marks a significant expansion of the game's reach and production quality.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Rhapsody of Blood\\</td><td>Rhapsody of Blood\">td><td>Rhapsody of Blood</a></td><td>2019</td><td>Gothic PbtA dungeon-delve; precursor to Voidheart</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Voidheart Symphony\\</td><td>Voidheart Symphony\">td><td>Voidheart Symphony</a></td><td>2021</td><td>Dual-world PbtA; Covenants; political horror</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Voidheart Symphony Revised</td><td>In development</td><td>With RR&D; new layout, writing, art</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Philosophy</h2>\n<strong>Politics as mechanical architecture</strong> — in Voidheart, the stress gauges model societal pressure as a mechanical reality; the covenant advancement system makes community solidarity the mechanism of power growth; the vassal structure means enemies are always specific faces of systemic corruption. The political commitments aren't themes painted over a generic system — they're what the mechanics are built to do.\n<strong>Dual mechanical registers</strong> — Voidheart's split city/castle system uses genuinely different mechanics for each world. The city uses roll-under gauges representing societal pressure; the castle uses standard PbtA 2d6+stat. This isn't just flavour variety — each system is precisely calibrated to the different kinds of stakes in each domain.\n<strong>Advancement through community</strong> — characters in Voidheart grow more powerful by cultivating relationships (Covenants), not by accumulating XP. You cannot get stronger except by caring about people. This is the most structurally elegant expression of the game's values.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: UFO Press · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Rowan Rook and Decard\">Rowan, Rook and Decard</a> (Revised)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/PbtA Family\">PbtA Family</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Chris Gonnerman": {"key": "People/Chris Gonnerman", "category": "People", "name": "Chris Gonnerman", "tags": ["person", "osr", "designer", "publisher"], "links": ["Games/Basic Fantasy RPG", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing", "Concepts/Retroclones", "Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Author of Basic Fantasy RPG and establisher of the OSR's radical accessibility ethos: PDFs free, print at near-cost on Lulu. Basic Fantasy remains actively developed and community-supported, with a large catalogue of free supplements. A model for open, community-driven game development.", "html": "<h1>Chris Gonnerman</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #designer #publisher</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2006 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, publisher\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Author of Basic Fantasy RPG and establisher of the OSR's radical accessibility ethos: PDFs free, print at near-cost on Lulu. Basic Fantasy remains actively developed and community-supported, with a large catalogue of free supplements. A model for open, community-driven game development.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Basic Fantasy RPG\\</td><td>Basic Fantasy RPG\">td><td>Basic Fantasy RPG</a></td><td>2006</td><td>B/X clone; free/open access model</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing\">Zine Scene</a></li>\n<li>Concept: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/Retroclones\">Retroclones</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Concepts/The OGL and Open Licensing\">OGL</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Jason Bulmahn": {"key": "People/Jason Bulmahn", "category": "People", "name": "Jason Bulmahn", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "paizo", "designer"], "links": ["Games/Pathfinder 1e", "Publishers/Paizo", "Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "People/Logan Bonner", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Active: 2007 – present | Role: Lead designer, Pathfinder 1st Edition", "html": "<h1>Jason Bulmahn</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #paizo #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2007 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Lead designer, Pathfinder 1st Edition\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Primary mechanical designer of Pathfinder 1e. His brief was conservative by design: take D&D 3.5, fix what was demonstrably broken, do not break what worked. The Pathfinder open playtest (2007–2009) was the first major TTRPG open playtest, predating D&D Next by three years and establishing a model WotC would later adopt.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 1e\\</td><td>Pathfinder 1st Edition\">td><td>Pathfinder 1st Edition</a></td><td>2009</td><td>Conservative 3.5 refinement; outsold D&D during 4e era</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Pathfinder open playtest</td><td>2007–2009</td><td>First major TTRPG open playtest</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Approach</h2>\n<ul><li>Skill consolidation (45 → 35 skills)</li>\n<li>Eliminated dead levels across all classes</li>\n<li>Unified Combat Maneuver mechanics (replacing tangle of special cases)</li>\n<li>Sorcerer bloodlines (gave class distinct identity)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Paizo\">Paizo</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/D&D Edition Wars\">D&D Edition Wars</a></li>\n<li>Succeeded by: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Logan Bonner\">Logan Bonner</a> (PF2e)</li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Rob Heinsoo": {"key": "People/Rob Heinsoo", "category": "People", "name": "Rob Heinsoo", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "designer"], "links": ["Games/DD 4th Edition", "Movements/D&D Edition Wars", "Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Active: 2008 – present | Role: Lead designer, D&D 4e; co-designer, 13th Age", "html": "<h1>Rob Heinsoo</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2008 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Lead designer, D&D 4e; co-designer, 13th Age\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Led the D&D 4th Edition design team. 4e's unified power structure, explicit combat roles, healing surges, and minion rules were coherent solutions to real 3.5 problems — the controversy was about whether those were the right problems. After 4e, co-designed 13th Age (2013, with Jonathan Tweet) — widely considered the most thoughtful synthesis of 3e, 4e, and OSR design lessons in a single mainstream-adjacent game.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/DD 4th Edition\\</td><td>D&D 4th Edition\">td><td>D&D 4th Edition</a></td><td>2008</td><td>Lead designer; the great divisive edition</td></tr>\n<tr><td><em>13th Age</em></td><td>2013</td><td>Co-designed with Jonathan Tweet; 3e+4e+OSR synthesis</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>13th Age</h2>\n13th Age is worth knowing. It kept 3e's class identity and level-based advancement, adopted 4e's encounter design philosophy without its power structure, introduced the One Unique Thing (a narrative hook distinguishing each character), and Icon Relationships (ongoing ties to powerful factions). A game that learned from 4e's commercial failure while preserving its design insight.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Collaborator: Jonathan Tweet (13th Age)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/D&D Edition Wars\">D&D Edition Wars</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2005-2010 The Catalyst Years\">2005–2010</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Daniel Sell": {"key": "People/Daniel Sell", "category": "People", "name": "Daniel Sell", "tags": ["person", "osr", "postOSR", "designer", "publisher", "secondwave"], "links": ["Games/Troika", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing", "Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Active: 2015 – present | Role: Designer, publisher (Melsonian Arts Council)", "html": "<h1>Daniel Sell</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #postOSR #designer #publisher #secondwave</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2015 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, publisher (Melsonian Arts Council)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Troika! — a game that redefined what an OSR game could look like aesthetically and structurally. Built on the Fighting Fantasy gamebook system rather than any edition of D&D, Troika! communicates its entire setting through 36 character Backgrounds, eliminating the need for a sourcebook. The bag-based initiative system produces genuinely chaotic, unpredictable combat. Sell's zine aesthetic influenced a generation of subsequent OSR designers.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Troika\\</td><td>Troika!\">td><td>Troika!</a></td><td>2015 (expanded 2019)</td><td>Post-OSR; implied setting through backgrounds; bag initiative</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Design Philosophy</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Setting through backgrounds</strong> — 36 strange character options imply a complete world without ever stating it</li>\n<li><strong>Bag initiative</strong> — tokens drawn from a bag; genuinely chaotic, scales elegantly to large combats</li>\n<li><strong>Fighting Fantasy chassis</strong> — mechanical choice signals aesthetic independence from D&D entirely</li>\n<li><strong>Zine aesthetic</strong> — handmade visual language influenced subsequent OSR design</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing\">Zine Scene</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Post-OSR and Minimalist Design\">Post-OSR</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Gavin Norman": {"key": "People/Gavin Norman", "category": "People", "name": "Gavin Norman", "tags": ["person", "osr", "neotrad", "designer", "publisher"], "links": ["Games/Old-School Essentials", "Games/Dolmenwood", "Publishers/Necrotic Gnome", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing", "Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Active: 2010 – present | Role: Designer, publisher (Necrotic Gnome) | Website: [necroticgnome.com](https://necroticgnome.com)", "html": "<h1>Gavin Norman</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #neotrad #designer #publisher</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2010 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, publisher (Necrotic Gnome) | <strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"https://necroticgnome.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">necroticgnome.com</a>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Old-School Essentials — a meticulous, highly formatted re-presentation of the B/X ruleset that became the dominant platform for neo-trad and OSR-adjacent play. OSE is less a design innovation than a design refinement done with exceptional care for clarity, usability, and modularity. Also the primary designer of Dolmenwood — a fully realized folk horror campaign setting years in development.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Old-School Essentials\\</td><td>Old-School Essentials\">td><td>Old-School Essentials</a></td><td>2019</td><td>B/X reformed; dominant neo-trad platform</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Dolmenwood\\</td><td>Dolmenwood\">td><td>Dolmenwood</a></td><td>2024</td><td>Folk horror setting; OSE platform ⭐ <em>you play this</em></td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Study Note</h2>\nOSE's design philosophy — separate rules from setting, maximize clarity, enable modularity — is worth studying as a document design approach, not just a game design approach.\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Necrotic Gnome\">Necrotic Gnome</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/Zine Scene and OSR Publishing\">Zine Scene</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2017-2020 Synthesis and Maturity\">2017–2020</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Jeff Talanian": {"key": "People/Jeff Talanian", "category": "People", "name": "Jeff Talanian", "tags": ["person", "osr", "designer", "publisher"], "links": ["Games/Hyperborea", "Publishers/North Wind Adventures", "Movements/OSR Movement", "Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Active: 2009 – present | Role: Designer, publisher (North Wind Adventures)", "html": "<h1>Jeff Talanian</h1>\n<p>#person #osr #designer #publisher</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2009 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Designer, publisher (North Wind Adventures)\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Designer of Hyperborea — a Sword & Sorcery take on OSR design drawing heavily on Clark Ashton Smith, Robert E. Howard, and H.P. Lovecraft. Talanian's work represents the OSR's deep engagement with pulp fantasy literature as source material. Hyperborea has a tight literary-aesthetic identity that distinguishes it from more generic fantasy retroclones.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Hyperborea\\</td><td>Hyperborea\">td><td>Hyperborea</a> (ASSH)</td><td>2012</td><td>Sword & Sorcery OSR; Clark Ashton Smith influence ⭐ <em>you play this</em></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Hyperborea 3rd Edition</td><td>2022</td><td>Revised and expanded</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/North Wind Adventures\">North Wind Adventures</a></li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OSR Movement\">OSR Movement</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2011-2016 Explosion and Divergence\">2011–2016</a> · <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "People/Logan Bonner": {"key": "People/Logan Bonner", "category": "People", "name": "Logan Bonner", "tags": ["person", "mainstream", "paizo", "designer"], "links": ["Games/Pathfinder 2e", "Publishers/Paizo", "People/Jason Bulmahn", "Movements/OGL Crisis 2023", "Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape"], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Active: 2019 – present | Role: Lead designer, Pathfinder 2nd Edition", "html": "<h1>Logan Bonner</h1>\n<p>#person #mainstream #paizo #designer</p>\n<strong>Active:</strong> 2019 – present | <strong>Role:</strong> Lead designer, Pathfinder 2nd Edition\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Why He Matters</h2>\n<p>Led the ground-up rebuild of Pathfinder for its 2nd edition. Where Bulmahn's PF1e was conservative, Bonner's PF2e was genuinely innovative — the three-action economy, four-outcome degree-of-success, and layered character creation are all departures from d20 convention. PF2e occupies a specific market position: more accessible than PF1e, more mechanically deep than 5e.</p>\n<h2>Key Works</h2>\n<table class=\"md-table\">\n<tr><td>Work</td><td>Year</td><td>Significance</td></tr>\n<tr><td><a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Games/Pathfinder 2e\\</td><td>Pathfinder 2nd Edition\">td><td>Pathfinder 2nd Edition</a></td><td>2019</td><td>Ground-up rebuild; three-action economy; four outcomes</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Pathfinder 2e Remaster</td><td>2023</td><td>Post-OGL revision; fully ORC-licensed</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h2>PF2e's Core Innovations</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Three-action economy</strong> — every character gets 3 actions; activities cost 1, 2, or 3; replaces standard/move/swift taxonomy</li>\n<li><strong>Four-outcome resolution</strong> — critical success (beat DC by 10+) / success / failure / critical failure (miss DC by 10+) on every roll</li>\n<li><strong>Proficiency tiers</strong> — Untrained / Trained / Expert / Master / Legendary with level-scaling bonuses</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Connections</h2>\n<ul><li>Publisher: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Publishers/Paizo\">Paizo</a></li>\n<li>Predecessor: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Bulmahn\">Jason Bulmahn</a> (PF1e)</li>\n<li>Movement: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Movements/OGL Crisis 2023\">OGL Crisis 2023</a></li>\n<li>Era: <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"Eras/2021-Present The Post-OGL Landscape\">2021–Present</a></li>\n</ul>"}, "Conventions/PAX Unplugged": {"key": "Conventions/PAX Unplugged", "category": "Conventions", "name": "PAX Unplugged", "tags": ["convention", "mainstream", "tabletop", "indie"], "links": [], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Location: Philadelphia, Pennsylvania | Timing: December | Scale: ~25,000 attendees", "html": "<h1>PAX Unplugged</h1>\n<p>#convention #mainstream #tabletop #indie</p>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Philadelphia, Pennsylvania | <strong>Timing:</strong> December | <strong>Scale:</strong> ~25,000 attendees\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>The tabletop-focused PAX event (part of the Penny Arcade Expo series). Grew significantly during the actual play boom as tabletop gaming entered mainstream pop culture. More indie-friendly than Gen Con's industry-focus, with a strong open gaming hall and publisher presence across all categories.</p>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\nPAX Unplugged's growth tracks the actual play boom — it's where the new wave of D&D 5e players intersects with indie and OSR publishers. Good venue for observing cross-lineage audience overlap."}, "Conventions/Gen Con": {"key": "Conventions/Gen Con", "category": "Conventions", "name": "Gen Con", "tags": ["convention", "mainstream", "osr", "industry"], "links": [], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Location: Indianapolis, Indiana | Timing: August | Scale: ~70,000 attendees", "html": "<h1>Gen Con</h1>\n<p>#convention #mainstream #osr #industry</p>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Indianapolis, Indiana | <strong>Timing:</strong> August | <strong>Scale:</strong> ~70,000 attendees\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>The largest tabletop gaming convention in North America, and the most important industry event in TTRPGs. Major publishers debut products, WotC makes announcements, and ENnie Awards are presented. Relevant to all three lineages.</p>\n<h2>OSR Presence</h2>\nMajor OSR publishers (Goodman Games, North Wind Adventures, Necrotic Gnome) debut and sell at Gen Con. The OSR scene has a visible presence despite Gen Con's mainstream-skewing demographics.\n<h2>Mainstream Significance</h2>\nWotC's primary convention venue for major announcements. New edition reveals, film/TV tie-in announcements, and Designer panels happen here.\n<h2>History</h2>\nFounded 1968 by Gary Gygax (as Lake Geneva Wargames Convention). Moved to Indianapolis in 2003. Named after Gygax's home town of Geneva, Wisconsin."}, "Conventions/Origins Game Fair": {"key": "Conventions/Origins Game Fair", "category": "Conventions", "name": "Origins Game Fair", "tags": ["convention", "mainstream", "ennies"], "links": [], "lineage": "mainstream", "summary": "Location: Columbus, Ohio | Timing: June | Scale: ~15,000 attendees", "html": "<h1>Origins Game Fair</h1>\n<p>#convention #mainstream #ennies</p>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Columbus, Ohio | <strong>Timing:</strong> June | <strong>Scale:</strong> ~15,000 attendees\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Major mid-year TTRPG and tabletop gaming convention. Home of the <strong>ENnie Awards</strong> — the most prominent peer-recognition awards in the TTRPG industry, voted on by the public from a judge-selected nominee slate.</p>\n<h2>ENnie Awards</h2>\nThe ENnies cover categories including Best Game, Best Writing, Best Adventure, Best Setting, and many others. OSR games have won (Mörk Borg won Gold Best Game 2020; A Red and Pleasant Land won multiple ENnies). The awards are a useful gauge of what the TTRPG community values in any given year.\n<h2>Local Note</h2>\nColumbus, Ohio — your home city."}, "Conventions/Metatopia": {"key": "Conventions/Metatopia", "category": "Conventions", "name": "Metatopia", "tags": ["convention", "storygames", "indie", "design", "playtest"], "links": [], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Location: Morristown, New Jersey | Timing: November | Organizer: Double Exposure", "html": "<h1>Metatopia</h1>\n<p>#convention #storygames #indie #design #playtest</p>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Morristown, New Jersey | <strong>Timing:</strong> November | <strong>Organizer:</strong> Double Exposure\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>A design-focused convention explicitly built around playtesting games in development. Designers bring works-in-progress; attendees play them and provide structured feedback. The most important convention for indie TTRPG design community.</p>\n<h2>Significance for Story Games Lineage</h2>\nMany significant PbtA and indie games were playtested at Metatopia before publication. The convention is where the story games design community physically convenes and where new designs are stress-tested.\n<h2>Culture</h2>\nMetatopia has a strong commitment to inclusive and safe play practices. Its culture of structured feedback and designer accountability has influenced how the broader indie community thinks about design iteration."}, "Conventions/OSRCon": {"key": "Conventions/OSRCon", "category": "Conventions", "name": "OSRCon", "tags": ["convention", "osr"], "links": [], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "A dedicated OSR convention, focused specifically on old-school TTRPG play. Smaller and more focused than Gen Con; attended primarily by OSR community members. Location has varied.", "html": "<h1>OSRCon</h1>\n<p>#convention #osr</p>\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>A dedicated OSR convention, focused specifically on old-school TTRPG play. Smaller and more focused than Gen Con; attended primarily by OSR community members. Location has varied.</p>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\nRepresents the OSR community's desire for dedicated space apart from mainstream conventions. Programming focuses on actual old-school play (running published OSR modules, playtesting new OSR games) rather than industry events."}, "Conventions/Gary Con": {"key": "Conventions/Gary Con", "category": "Conventions", "name": "Gary Con", "tags": ["convention", "osr", "oldschool"], "links": [], "lineage": "osr", "summary": "Location: Lake Geneva, Wisconsin | Timing: March | Scale: ~3,000 attendees", "html": "<h1>Gary Con</h1>\n<p>#convention #osr #oldschool</p>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Lake Geneva, Wisconsin | <strong>Timing:</strong> March | <strong>Scale:</strong> ~3,000 attendees\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Named in honor of Gary Gygax, held in his home town. The spiritual home of old-school TTRPG play. Strongly OSR-focused, with significant presence of grognards (players who played in the original D&D era) and old-school designers.</p>\n<h2>Significance for OSR Study</h2>\nGary Con is where living history happens. Original D&D players, first-generation OSR designers, and TSR-era material all converge. If you want to understand the OSR's relationship to the original game, Gary Con is the place.\n<h2>Notable Events</h2>\n<ul><li>Games run by original TSR designers (when living)</li>\n<li>OSR publisher presence</li>\n<li>Original D&D modules run as written</li>\n</ul>"}, "Conventions/Big Bad Con": {"key": "Conventions/Big Bad Con", "category": "Conventions", "name": "Big Bad Con", "tags": ["convention", "storygames", "indie", "inclusive"], "links": [], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "An inclusive, indie-focused TTRPG convention with a strong commitment to safety, accessibility, and diverse voices. Strongly represents PbtA, FitD, and indie design communities. Known for thoughtful programming and a welcoming culture.", "html": "<h1>Big Bad Con</h1>\n<p>#convention #storygames #indie #inclusive</p>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Oakland, California | <strong>Timing:</strong> October\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>An inclusive, indie-focused TTRPG convention with a strong commitment to safety, accessibility, and diverse voices. Strongly represents PbtA, FitD, and indie design communities. Known for thoughtful programming and a welcoming culture.</p>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\nBig Bad Con represents the indie TTRPG scene's values made physical — safety tools, diverse game design, accessible play. A contrast to Gen Con's industry-scale culture. Many story games designers attend and run events."}, "Conventions/Gauntlet Codex": {"key": "Conventions/Gauntlet Codex", "category": "Conventions", "name": "Gauntlet Codex", "tags": ["convention", "storygames", "pbtA", "community"], "links": ["People/Jason Cordova", "People/Jason Cordova"], "lineage": "storygames", "summary": "Organizer: Jason Cordova | Format: Primarily online; some in-person", "html": "<h1>Gauntlet Gatherings</h1>\n<p>#convention #storygames #pbtA #community</p>\n<strong>Organizer:</strong> <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Cordova\">Jason Cordova</a> | <strong>Format:</strong> Primarily online; some in-person\n<p>---</p>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>The convention and community events organized by or affiliated with The Gauntlet — Jason Cordova's online TTRPG community and podcast. Focused on story games, PbtA, FitD, and indie design. Strong commitment to inclusive play practices.</p>\n<h2>Significance</h2>\nThe Gauntlet has been one of the most important online communities for story games in the 2010s-2020s. Its gatherings are where PbtA and indie designers and players physically (and virtually) meet. <a href=\"#\" class=\"wikilink\" data-key=\"People/Jason Cordova\">Cordova</a>'s community-building work is as significant as his design work.\n<h2>The Gauntlet Podcast</h2>\nA long-running actual play and discussion podcast covering indie and story games. Archive is a useful resource for understanding the story games community's values and conversations."}};
